Location_desc: Pt is located on slight hill, with mature forest of large trees. Immediately surrounding point is mossy boulder field w/ some hefty, angular boulders. Also, large snags around. Image DSC01993 is site showing boulders.

Travel_notes: Difficult travel to pt. WW03--you're traversing some steep slopes so watch your footing. The first 150m are fairly open and steadily uphill. As you pass a small shoulder in a ridge, look beyond for mossy rock face 50m in the distance on hillside, visable above canopy. From this ridge drop down and traverse through thick saplings.
Location_desc: Point is in dense thicket of sideways-growing vine maple and yew saplings on very steep slope. Point is just downhill from a cliffband that runs N-S parallel to transect. This cliffband contains the rockface mentioned in the travel features as well as a secondary, smaller mossy rockface seen uphill from point.

Travel_notes: Another tough transect section, but richly rewarded. The first 60m is steep and tough, but it soon levels out. If you have time, stop by the beautiful filled-in forest pond just west of the point.
Location_desc: Point is under a clearing in the canopy near some large deadfalls, approx 20m SW from marshy clearing (w/ skunk cabbage). Point is next to new blowdown-open  canopy.

Travel_notes: Again, a tough section to walk. The first 100m are a stroll through glorious elk habitat. Be prepared, however, for some thickets and big blowdowns to climb over on the descent to NN05. Take your time and keep at it.
Location_desc: The point is located on a hill between some large blowdowns. Moss, blueberries, vanilla-leaf and Oregon grape groundcover. A small seep runs downhill approx 25m N (you can probably hear it).

Travel_notes: Head N (360) along downward sloping hill, past small stream and many large blowdowns. Proceed downhill 15m (NE) to point just around  rocky outcrop.
Location_desc: Point is just below (NE) small rocky outcrop between rock and large, long fallen tree with many saplings growing on it. There are yews all around and several silver firs.

Travel_notes: Travel straight down trail 100 m from TO.
Location_desc: Located on trail on straightaway section 100 m down trail from TO.  Forest dominated by Doug-fir. Both Doug-fir and white pine feature are on uphill side of trail.

Travel_notes: Travel down trail straight away section.  Point located at first major switchback curve beyond the double switchback located at 115 m (see description below).
Location_desc: Point located on trail at first switchback beyond the double switchback located at 115 m.  Point located exactly on a hairpin curve.  No other distinctive features present.  Doug-fir/Western hemlock forest dense, beargrass abundant in area.

Travel_notes: Pass 3 switchback hairpin curves from point 2 (not including SB point 2 is located on).  Point 3 is on straight away section 150 m beyond 3rd hairpin switchback (pace from this SB to point).
Location_desc: Located on trail in fairly straight section.  Look for doug-fir described above.  Trail striaght for approx 10 m, below point trail is steeper w/ several meandering curves.  Look for exposed doug-fir roots.

Travel_notes: From pt 3, pass 4 hairpin switchback curves, 50 m beyond the fourth sb curve look for a dog leg in trail with a log following it (described below) and well portrayed on map.
Location_desc: Located on trail where it dog-legs coming down slope just before a 9 m flat and straight section.  Look for log paralelling trail on the right side of trail as you come down hill.  Point is located just where trail becomes flat after dog leg.

Travel_notes: Travel down trail, meandering curves down steep slope,  located at bottom of section w/ steeply cut sidewalls into banks of trail.  Just downhill cuts not apparent.  No other distinctive features present.
Location_desc: Located on trail just as surrounding woods begin to flatten out. Surrounding woods are primarily Western Hemlock and Douglas Fir with little to no understory and lots of deadfall.

Travel_notes: Travel due East through dense forest, varied terrain, mostly downhill. Open understory and easy travel the first 100m, as you descend to point, doghair silver fir abound.  Pass small stream in steep ravine--30 m beyond slope goes steeply downhill. Travel down to base of steep slope for pt 6.
Location_desc: Point located at foot of steep slope just beyond large downed log in mid- to late-decay stages, bisecting transect at a 90 degree angle. GPS ~30m off.

Travel_notes: travel down slight slope and flat terrain through Western hemlock then Doug-fir/Western hemlock forest, undergrowth dense, downed wood abundant.  Look for 1st huge doug-fir 107 m beyond pt 6.
Location_desc: Dense Doug-fir/western hemlock forest w/ doug-fir trees being very large.  There is a lot of downed wood at the point but it occurs throughout the forest as well.

Travel_notes: fairly easy, crossing downed logs, understory very short. Creek becomes audible near point, which is on SE facing slope down to creek, roughly 50 m away.
Location_desc: On slope going down to creek (approx. 50 m). Lots of rotting wood and stumps. Pacific silver fir, Douglas-fir, cedar, and hemlock present (mixed conifer).

Travel_notes: Travel through hemlock saplings and some downed logs. Lots of huckleberry the entire way. Walk downhill to a creek and then travel levels out.
Location_desc: Point is nearish to loud creek, creek cannot be seen at point. It is downslope of 2 close together, short decaying snags and upslope of a leaning ~25cm DBH snag (that leans over point). Point located in gully area before you reach the creek. Lots of vaccinium.

Travel_notes:
In 2011, camped near top of slope that contains WW arm. Not that comfortable, but only about 5-minute slide down slope to TO.
If coming from Longmire, allow hour and 20 minutes or so to get to T.O. (~10 minute drive to Kautz Creek Trailhead, hike to TO is just over an hour). Beware HEWA/TOWA/hybrid situation. It is about an hour hike from the TO without a pack on. Bring an extra shirt to change into after the sweaty hike to the TO. Thick canopy for hike to TO. Turn on your GPS early to acquire satellites.
Location_desc: Point located 25 m South (down trail) from South end of bridge crossing over creek that intersects the trail near origination point.  We camped in a cross country zone in a meadow N of the TO in the headwaters of a Kautz Ck. tributary- excellent camping with 15-min. walk to TO.

Travel_notes: Travel is uphill through open forest. Continue past marker a few meters to edge of canopy opening.
Location_desc: Point is on moderate slope on the edge of a small canopy opening.  Understory consists primarily of vaccinium; herb layer is beargrass, with some oregon grape and fern. Point has you standing basically under tall leaning slide alder.

Travel_notes: Travel upslope through open forest.
Location_desc: Point is on steep slope under moderately open mixed conifer canopy.  Understory is open except for conifer seedlings, herb layer is populated by beargrass. Just downhill of a ~35cm DBH hemlock.

Travel_notes: Traverse undulating terrain for 300m.  Stop 10 m before drop-off.
Location_desc: Point is 10 m from significant drop-off, under closed-canopy mixed conifer forest.  Understory is relatively open except for conifer seedlings.

Travel_notes: Traverse across extremely steep slope, cross gully at approx 100 m.
Location_desc: Point is on shoulder of hill 20 m above significant drop-off.  Habitat is primarily closed-canopy mixed conifer forest though point is on edge of small clearing w/ conifer saplings and false azalea.  Sapling species: white pine, Doug-fir, hemlock. ~10m upslope of point is less shrubby, more open forest.

Travel_notes: The first 140 or so m are a gradual uphill traverse through open understory/closed canopy mixed conifer forest. Halfway-ish you will hit large patches of false azalea and bushwack through that until you get to the point. The point is difficult to find--no reliable features. Fortunately, it's open and GPS signal is strong.   Bearing to point should be 32 instead of 23 degrees.
Location_desc: Point is under open mixed conifer canopy (fir and western white pine) amid a lot of dense false azalea shrubs approx 1 m tall, on gentle slope. Point is ~12m past where slope levels off.

Travel_notes: Continue through meadow with scattered trees, then climb small ridge. On the crest of the ridge, alders grow conspicuously, curving out and up from central point. Then down through open forest to azalea opening.
Location_desc: Point is on moderate slope under mixed conifer canopy.

Travel_notes: Travel through open forest and sections of false azalea.
Location_desc: Point is approx 40 m into mixed conifer forest w/ shrubby alder understory. About 1m to the N of cluster of yellow cedar saplings.

Travel_notes: Once you hit trail, it's probably easiest to walk up trail ~100m to get to where you're at approximate Northing (use GPS). Walk off-trail through beargrass and other vegetation. Slippery when wet.
Location_desc: Point is ~8m W of a cliff/ rock face. Steep slope. There is a large (~80cm DBH), silver fir downslope (and to "right" [w] ),of point.

Travel_notes: Follow Eastside Trail 200 m from T.O.  Stop 23 m before stream crosses trail.
Location_desc: On Eastside Trail, 23 m before small stream crossing.  Many large standing snags in area. There is a cut log on both sides of trail ~6m past (N of) point.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is in the middle of a small log bridge spanning creek draining seasonal (?) marsh E. into Ohanapecosh Creek.

Travel_notes: Follow trail 200 m.
Location_desc: Point is on Eastside Trail.  Trail surves slightly N. around 108 cm Western redcedar on W. side.

Travel_notes: Follow trail.  Olallie Creek is too far.
Location_desc: On Eastside Trail, 37 m before Olallie Creek.

Travel_notes: Follow trail over Olallie Ck. bridge.  Pass over small wooden bridge at 83 m.  Pace to the point - no other prominent features until curve in trail after point.
Location_desc: On Eastside Trail 14 m before curve, 3 m past sawed butt of fallen 32 cm DBH tree on N. side of trail.  River audible but not visible.

Reason_for_change: First chance to turn off trail.
Travel_notes: Travel at 270 degrees upslope from trail, reaching top of ridge at 44 m.  Drop into bowl and traverse N. slope, reaching base of steep slope at 143 m.  Proceed to top of steep slope.
Location_desc: At crest of steep slope, dropping off to the E. and SE.  Gentle upward slope to W and NW.  Forest type is large Doug-fir (ca. 100 cm DBH) mixed with smaller Western redcedar and Western hemlock.

Reason_for_change: Unscalable rock face 150m from last point on previous bearing.
Travel_notes: Head N over relatively level terrain. There are many downed trees of various sizes to be crossed along the way.
Location_desc: Point is in mossy patch encircled by sizeable downed trees. At the bottom of a hill.

Travel_notes: Moderate travel over a fair number of downed trees.
Location_desc: In area relatively free of understory, on a bit of a flat spot to stand. Small yew tree extends to point from S. Hemlock saplings upslope. On steepish slope.

Travel_notes: Travel moderate over some downed trees and saplings/shrubs. Travel not bad.
Location_desc: Point is right under the branches of a ~15cm DBH silver fir (upslope of point). There is also a vine maple whose leaves/branches extend almost to point (from upslope). Three massive Doug-firs are visible from point- point is in the middle of all 3.

Reason_for_change: River on one side and steep slope on the other prevented off-trail point establishment
Travel_notes: Walk southerly on Eastside Trail for 100m from the transect origin.
Location_desc: Point is on trail above river.

Travel_notes: Walk 200m southerly on trail.
Location_desc: Point on trail where canopy opens over river, among ample vine maple and scattered deciduous cover.

Travel_notes: Walk southerly on trail for 200m.
Location_desc: On trail 14m south of turnoff to "Grove of the Patriarchs".  Ohanapecosh River is broadly visible (40 m at the closest), and there is a stand of narrow alders on slope below stretch of trail to the immediate north of point.

Travel_notes: Walk 200m southerly on trail.
Location_desc: Point on trail, about 5m S of interpretive sign "Western Redcedar - Thuja plicata".  Ohanapecosh River is 20 m at closest.

Travel_notes: This point requires some travel off bearing to reach.  Climb up steep slope from trail, skirting north around cliff, then jog back about 10m and reset bearing.  From there travel 180m over small ridges and depressions to point.
Location_desc: Point is in low area at the base of a steep hill to the west, near park water supply buildings.  Boulder situated between a medium Silver fir with a twisted fir sapling at its base, a >100cm dbh cedar, and an ~100cm dbh hemlock snag.

Reason_for_change: Cliff and falls creek intercedes westward travel
Travel_notes: Travel north uphill among yews, cedars, and snags.  At around 130m, you may have to skirt around steep slope, but aim for prominent Doug-fir at top.  Proceed 60m north from there.
Location_desc: Point on ridgetop with aspects to the SE and SW, on an almost totally decayed log between a 9m tall silvery snag and a medium yellow cedar.

Travel_notes: Travel due north over rolling terrain.
Location_desc: Point is on moderate slope amongst mixed old-growth conifer forest, with younger Silver fir between older trees.

Travel_notes: Travel due North accross the side of the the hill through mostly open understory with a few log crossings.
Location_desc: Point is located on the side of a hill in an open area with salal in a mature mixed conifer forest. The point is between a giant Doug-fir and a large hemlock (features mentioned above).

Travel_notes: Camp at Ohanapecosh. Drive 5 min to 'Grove of the Patriachs' parking area. Follow Eastside Trail past grove of the partriachs to T.O. About a 10-15 minute walk up Eastside Trail.
Location_desc: On Eastside Trail between 116 cm DBH Doug-fir and cut end of downed tree.  Ohanapecosh Creek is visible. Look for large Doug-fir on downhill side of trail.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: 15 m E of small drainage; stop right before slope gets very steep; n 30 m from edge of Subalpine fir stand. 2014: Unable to locate ground stake among dense lupine. Conducted survey near sapling subalpine fir.

Travel_notes: Travel 200 m S across meadow above treeline.
Location_desc: Large, flat area of parklands, dominated by white heather.  Point 19 m from nearest Subalpine fir patch

Travel_notes: After crossing trail head up rocky slope into Subalpine fir patch, point in the middle of the patch.
Location_desc: Point is on a mostly flat hilltop in a stand of Subalpine fir.  Point on a sandy  spot, 3 m wide, surrounded by Subalpine fir.

Travel_notes: Pass through a few patches of Subalpine fir, and then climb a moderately steep rocky slope for the last 20 + meters.
Location_desc: pt is in last substantial clump of krumholzed Subalpine fir before you reach huge talus slope (heading south). There is a wire ~2m downslope of point.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: Rocky plateau dotted with forbs and heather. On a flat 5-sided rock.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: E side of rocky ridge overlooking 'parkland' to the E.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: Pt. is on rocky knoll with low Subalpine fir overlooking 'parklands' habitat to the NE, and talus to the SE. On edge of Subalpine firs.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: Jumble of meadow, Heather, and Subalpine fir.  Pt is at small hill with lots of good rocks for sitting on; approx 50 m N of trail. Terrain slopes steeply to the NW beginning about 100 m to the NW.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m at 360 degrees, entering thick Krummholz stand at 50m, crossing trail to Berkeley Park after exiting Krummholz.  Open, rocky dirt gives way to lush meadow accross trail.  Point is just 6m after first stream crossing.
Location_desc: On 2x2x2m lichen covered rock, 6m past tributary brook on E. slope of main creek drainage.  Forgot to write down bearings for seen from features, but rock is unmistakable (do this next visit!).

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point is in a white heather open area up from Wonderland trail to glacier peak.  Pt next to a dry wide drainage area.  Rocks are numerous(more so than surrounding approx. 50 m) at head of dry drainage fir clumps approx 70 m to the south

Travel_notes: Follow fir edge up to ridge then go slightly down the other side, look for medium whitebark pines in a clump.  Whitebark pines approx 10-12m tall; see image for perspective.
Location_desc: Point is on a steep rocky slope dominated by shrubby subalpine fir and a few whitebark pines.  Pt is near top of ridge though definitely on the West facing slope.  Point is on perimeter of whitebark clump (a few small subalpine firs present in clump).

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: Point on edge of small non-running drainage.  Area is meadow with numerous forbs.  Pt is where small drainage turns to meet up with a medium running drainage which flows into granite creek. Point just outside area thick with shrubby subalpine firs.

Travel_notes: Travel across meadow bottom and cross numerous drainages. Begin climbing the gravel / talus slope on the far side of basin, but stop before you get to the band of subalpine-fir krummholz.
Location_desc: Point on rocky talus slope.  Heather and forbs grow in patches.  Drainage/water falls to the west, 3-4 drainages in meadow below pt within plot.  Short firs grow upslope to s/sw.

Travel_notes: Continue up talus slope, through band of trees (convenient at square rock) and climb next hill, over subterranean rivulet gurgle to where slope mellows. Continue on bearing to where large car-sized boulders are strewn on small ridge.
Location_desc: Point is in white heather/rock sparsely vegetated area.  On small ridge over granite creek, drainage below.  Many large, grey boulders nearby.

Travel_notes: Continue travelling uphill toward serrated ridge of 3rd Burroughs mountain. point is on moderately steep talus of large soccer-ball sized grey boulders.
Location_desc: Point is on talus slope leading up to large impressive moraine at base of north face Burroughs Mountain (back cliffs).

Travel_notes: Climb the rest of the way up the scree field and onto a milder incline covered mostly in pumice stones.  Cross two dry drainages and then hit a slightly steeper slope, but stop before a bunching of krummholz and heather.
Location_desc: Point on a flattish scree of pumice stones on the slope up towards Mt. Burrough's most western extent.  Imemediately above is a patch of krummholz and heather among small boulders.

Travel_notes: Continue due west for 200m, traversing the medium talus.  Once boulders thin out to smaller rocks, look for biggest rock in immediate area (2m width).
Location_desc: On side of talus slope between the cliffs of Mt. Burroughs and a protected area below with krummholz and heather, and what looks like a seasonal lakebed.  50m further west the slope drops off into steep scree and down into the granite creek watershed.
Location_notes: It was deemed too steep to access, so it was replaced by SW08a.

Reason_for_change: SW is too steep, W is sketchy talus slope.
Travel_notes: Travel downslope at NW bearing into a wide, flat bowl between ridges.
Location_desc: Point located on sparsely vegetated meadow with thicker vegetation to the west; on flat ground with ridges to south, west, and east and more flat ground continuing north.

Travel_notes: Berkeley Camp is (allegedly) further North than the maps indicate, about an hour from the TO, and kind of steep in places. Best camping option is Skyscraper Mountain X-Country zone (limit 2 parties per night), just make sure you're out of view of trail where you camp; beautiful area.  Good camping ~300m N of SW02, can access by hiking down the ridge line. Incredible views. ~10 minute hike to trail off ridge. Water is ~300m past TO just at the base of the hill. ~20 minute hike to TO from Skyscraper x-country zone camp spot!
Location_desc: Sunrise Camp / Shadow lake -- 1hr hike in morning to TO. Points on SW arm are further than 200m apart.

Travel_notes: Travel up trail for 100m. Cross two small brooks and continue up a gradual sloping contour.
Location_desc: Point is on trail with huckleberry understory and Needle Ck downhill to left.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m up trail.
Location_desc: Mixed forest with several large Y cedars nearby. Kotsuck creek can be seen downhill approx 50m away. Point on trail between two small brooks. Just downhill is a leaning double-cedar. 213 bearing to the metal-marked tree, but it is just downhill from point, barely 2m away.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: At corner of hair-pin curve; several big Pac-silver firs surround.
Location_notes: Location retired in 2008, field observer installed a new point because this point was too far oof-trail (was supposed to be on trail).

Travel_notes: 5m after 8th switchback up from NW02.  I paced 472m on trail.
Location_desc: S facing slope in medium age Pacific silver fir/Alaska yellow cedar woods.  Point is opposite rotting stump and just before Alaska yellow cedar described in features - roots extened into trail. 2021: GPS 20m off here - use features.

Travel_notes: From point 03A, travel up 4 switchbacks.  Point is 15m before small bridge with 9 board slats.
Location_desc: Point is on trail above the Kotsuck river among switchbacks. Uphill 15m is a small wooden slat-bridge that crosses small brook. just uphill from point is characteristic dbl-Pacific silver-fir (see image).

Travel_notes: Switchbacks make the walk much longer than 200 m.  Travel 680m uphill, across many small creeks and bridges, with two large switchbacks (first right-turning, then left).
Location_desc: Point is on trail above all the switchbacks near a very large Y cedar and a few sawed blowdowns (see image). 40m NW on trail (uphill) is a wooden slat-bridge over spring-fed brook.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m up trail. Cross two small brooks and into a younger, more closed and tight forest.
Location_desc: Point is on trail uphill and slightly NW of spring-fed brook; you can hear the brook bubbling forth from the earth. You can see deciduous trees in canopy opening (~90m down trail).

Travel_notes: Travel 200m up gradual trail to second canopy opening.
Location_desc: In 2007, I may have been a little short, on trail, from past years. I paced exactly 200m up trail. Point in canopy opening on trail, 5m before a very small wash crosses trail. To the left across valley you can see the Cowlitz Chimneys. Through trees, Double Peak barely visible. 2018: unable to find point based on description-cloudy day so I couldn't use the mountains as features. I surveyed in the open area-nondescript. No photos given to me either. Aim for survey on sunny day next visit to get an exact location and add better features. Surveyed where a pacific silver fir was at 200 degrees but was only 1m away.

Travel_notes: Pace 210m on trail through Alaska yellow cedar/Pacific silver fir, open, stunted woods.  Woods opens into Slide alder shrubs and Alaska yellow cedar 15m before point.
Location_desc: Point is on E edge of 8m wide avalanche shoot, in open Alaska yellow cedar/slide alder habitat with thicker Pacific silver fir/Alaska yellow cedar about 20m E on trail. Chute is currently filled with snow, but a pile of split wood planks at point suggests that it may raun as a creek when melted out.

Travel_notes: Pace 230m from previous point through open, shrubby Alaska yellow cedar, Slide alder and avalanche runs.  Enter patch of Pacific silver fir woods at 193m.  Point is in middle of this patch - you can't miss the boulder.
Location_desc: Point is in 65m wide finger of woods between two avalanche shoots.  On trail between large mossy boulder to N and 70 cm DBH Pacific silver fir that has fallen and been cut into sections on S side of trail.

Travel_notes: Travel across first oepn slide area into brief stretch of Pacific silver fir forest. Exit to second open meadow area.
Location_desc: In open meadow stretch of about 80m. Many young Alaska yellow cedars and scattered rocks.

Travel_notes: Go up first switchback, step over small stream and go up second switchback. Trail curves briefly through forest and back to meadow with wooden steps.
Location_desc: Point in open meadow, 1m before last wooden "step." Ahead is very open meadow; behind is small forested area. Beargrass around pt with Subalpine fir and Alaska yellow cedar saplings.

Travel_notes: Travel on trail 100m to a large vaccinium patch.
Location_desc: Gap in forest created by downed trees.  Shrubby understory--mtn ash, vaccinium. Doug-fir overstory with smaller silver fir. Another large downled log on the N side of trail is more visible but not the feature log, the feature log is rotting and covered in vaccinium, on same side as silver fir feature.

Travel_notes: on trail to E
Location_desc: Doug-fir w/ west. Hemlock and medium aged silver fir. Small stream thru E side of plot.  Vaccinium understory. Hemlock feature on your right on approach.

Travel_notes: On trail, GPS is off and thinks point is ~20m past the actual point.
Location_desc: Point just before gap in forest.  Can hear the falls and see the grassy/shrubby slope at 200 deg.

Travel_notes: 300 m travel on trail to get 200 m from SE03. GPS off, actual point is ~15m before what the GPS says, right after sharp snag - photos help.
Location_desc: Mixed doug-fir w/ w. hemlock; vaccinium , devils club, false azalea understory.  Point is between 2 large snags with falling bark.

Travel_notes: Because of ravine you need to travel 280 m on trail between SE04 and SE05.  The creek is midway in ravine. Point after sharp curve on trail, ~45m past where GPS tells you the point is.
Location_desc: Small drainage w/ several downed logs, doug-fir/w. hemlock mix.  Understory vaccinium w/ small trees. Point just after sharp curve in trail.  On the north side there is a downed tree with a cut section in the middle, probably an old trail going through it. (2014: previous bearings/distances to features didn't make any sense, ie. would have put you well off the trail, down a cliff, etc. so I reset bearings and distances as close as I could get to what I thought was probably the point and added a third feature)

Travel_notes: On trail - GPS ~35-40m off and thinks point is off trail but it is not.
Location_desc: Point is in small drainage with minor stream. Mixed cedar, W hemlock, Silver fir, devil's club, salmonberry understory.

Travel_notes: On trail, pass Boundary Creek Bridge.
Location_desc: Mixed doug-fir, W Hemlock, silver fir forest.  Several trees > 100cm dbh.  False Azalea/blackberry understory.

Travel_notes: on trail
Location_desc: Mixed doug-fir, w. hemlock, p silver fir forest w/ several large (80+ cm dbh) trees.  Huckleberry and false azalea understory.

Travel_notes: Walk 200m southeasterly on trail.
Location_desc: On trail just past a small mossy rill, in a mixed Doug-fir/western hemlock forest with vaccinium, vine maple, and sapling understory.

Travel_notes: Travel southeasterly on trail.
Location_desc: On trail over gentle slope leading down to Kotsuck Creek, between a 92cm dbh Doug-fir sawed off across trail and a 42cm dbh Doug-fir sawed off across trail, 20m between the two.  There is a 40cm dbh Western redcedar right south of point and two runoff reliefs crossing trail.

Travel_notes: Travel 225m down trail to reach point
Location_desc: Point in open fir/hemlock forest with falls (smallish, ~4m tall) just audible/visible to WSW. Point surrounded by second-grwoth Pacific Silver-Fir, false azalea, and vaccinium spp. Several rotten logs around point, including feature log.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Several snags in area, look for shorter orange one on right hand side after passing the trail sign. Huckleberry and sapling undergrowth. 2-3 large Doug firs seen from point. Mostly Western Hemlock.

Reason_for_change: Didn't want to run into raod
Travel_notes: Pass Deer Creek Camp sign. Go down Eastside Trail. Go past open area on E side of river that looks like decommissioned CG.
Location_desc: Huckleberry, primarily Western hemlock habitat. Some vanilla leaf by point on left side of trail.

Travel_notes: Travel down trail. Barkless snag feature will be on your left on approach, GPS says point is ~15-20m farther down trail than it actually is.
Location_desc: Lots of Western hemlocks. River audible less than 18m away. Vaccinium groundcover with hemlock saplings.

Travel_notes: From Deer Creek CG, it takes 40min to hike to TO. Deer Creek CG not well-marked; hang a left at first junction (before crossing creek) if coming from HWY 123. Can also x-country camp in Lower Ohanapecosh Cross Country Zone near Needle/Kotsuck Creek junction about 2 miles from Deerk Creek CG, 5 min walk to TO in morning. Marker visible from approach (2013: Not really, kind of crushed up against tree, but still easy to find). 2021: We packed up before surveying: SE arm did surveys in backpacking gear, NW arm stashed pack to grab on the way out.
Location_desc: West. hemlockPac. Silver-fir forest canopy gap to SE w/ large, leaning P silver-fir, vaccinium understory.  On SE arm some of the GPS coordinates are way off (especially SE05) but features are unmistakable.  Follow the nav report rather than GPS.

Travel_notes: Do not come this way again, steep and dengerous.
very steep; somewhat dengerous; should not be repeated.
Location_desc: N/A Point should not be conducted here in future.

Travel_notes: left point 2 heading SE.  Turned to avoid cliffs to the east.  Extremely steep, tough going.  After approx 120 m (45 min of bush wacking) encountered trail and stayeed on it.
Location_desc: At sharp bend in trail (one of many).  Tahoma creek in view far below.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: Small clump of young Mtn. hemlock in matrix of Subalpine fir woodland.  Smalll creek approx 15 m east.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: Point is at NE edge of small meadow.  Large patch of tall white snags to the east.

Travel_notes: Travel 100m downhill on trail, cross a few waterbars. Point located before the first switchback.
Location_desc: Point NW01 is on trail with conifer sapling & huckleberry understory; open hemlock forest above. Downhill is very conspicuous leaning firs that form a triangle--the trees are lined up in a row and the two outer ones are leaning in and resting on the middle tree, almost like an arrow pointing upward.
on trail

Travel_notes: Travel about 425m downhill on trail from NW01. Descend 8 switchbacks on loosely switchbacked trail. At the beginning of the 7th switchback, note large roots from big Doug-fir and grey exposed slabby bedrock in trail. Point is 10m beyond the 8th switchback.
Location_desc: Point is on trail in section of switchbacks. Uphill is downed and cut wood. Rainier can be seen through the trees and river is loud below.
on trail

Travel_notes: Travel downhill 270m from point NW03. After 20m, the trail switchbacks to the right and continues a downhill contour. Around 200m from point NW03 the trail follows a larger, loud creek downhill. Cross creek on log bridge and point NW04a is just beyond, on far shore.
Location_desc: Point NW04a is on trail on a bank above convergence of two unknown creeks, about 20m from the creeks in open forest understory. To the east and north is huckleberry understory. Small round cobbles in trail directly at point--see image. To the SE 100m is a riparian canopy opening, just visible from point.
Near a patch of small short mountain hemlock. Very green due to low hemlock.

Travel_notes: Travel downtrail about 380 m. From NW04a at creek, travel downhill into open, dry, Mtn. hemlock sapling forest with view to river valley and mountains beyond. As the forest gets taller downhill, travel down 7 switchbacks and stop before the 8th.
Location_desc: On trail, rocky, small Mtn. hemlock, no understory.  Point is on trail just uphill from river and suspension bridge. Point is directly beside large gray boulder and waterbar downhill. See image.
Point is just after crossing bridge

Travel_notes: No distinctive features, stay on Wonderland Trail and proceed up hill on trail.  Travel 415 m on trail. The first 130 m arer downhill across 3 switchbacks to bridge. Cross bridge and proceed uphill. Shortly, you are to a trail junction where you bear right (on Wonderland Trail). Continue 50 m past your first view of the river (where bank has eroded close to trail) up into the forest where you'll spot a large (3/4 m) cut deadfall uphill and nearly parallel to trail and a large backpacking backpack sized boulder in trail.
Location_desc: The point overlooks the river and bridge from Wonderland Trail. There is an open area 20 m wide with no trees blocking view.

Travel_notes: travel 210 m uphill on gradual upward contour.
Location_desc: Point is uphill from river on gradual ascending trail. Just uphill on trail is an opening in canopy where alder and wildflowers are growing. Point is next to large Doug-fir growing almost in trail.

Travel_notes: Walk 220m up trail to a break in downslope canopy where a few slide alders grow downslope and a view across the valley opens up.
Location_desc: Point on trail at far side of slide-opening, where Pacific silver firs start to fill in again at sides of trail.

Travel_notes: Travel uphill on trail 455m.  Point is on east-bearing stretch of trail after second switchback up.
Location_desc: On trail, 20m short of left-turning switchback, where an outcropping of rocks studs the left side of trail.  Forest is Mtn. hemlock, mixed fir and Alaska yellow cedar, with slide alders stretching where they can.

Travel_notes: travel ~410 meters on trail. The distances given for the travel features are distances paced on the trail.
Location_desc: Point is on trail in very open area with clear view to Mount Rainier. Point 1m before opening of alders. Trail very wet this year (2012). There may be a stream flowing on the trail for 10-20m.

Travel_notes: On trail, very rocky most of the way and shrubby
Location_desc: Fairly open canopy, dirt rock/pebble trail. Some moss and handful huckleberry vegetation. Mostly Alaksa yellow cedar, Subalpine fir, and Mtn. hemlock habitat. There are two snags and two skinny (<10cm DBH) Pacific silver firs near the pair of Mtn. hemlocks (feature) as well.

Travel_notes: Trail more rocky to sparse vegetation at end. This is where point is.
Location_desc: Very birdy here! Rocks w/ meadow, small trees, flowers, vegetation on left. On the right, you can see the summit of Rainier. Subalpine fir and cedars dominate. Mostly cedars on left. Very pretty here.

Travel_notes: Rocky trail travel.
Location_desc: To right of trail can see down ravine of Rock/sparsely vegetated habitat and saplings.

Travel_notes: on trail, just after little open area
Location_desc: The point is next to a clump of mountain hemlocks and silver firs, just after some wooden steps

Travel_notes: Uphill on the Wonderland Trail over 4 small wooden bridges and a large creek toward the end.
Location_desc: Just after (going upslope) a bend after a big creek. Next to a medium-sized rock. Just before a rock  "bridge" that goes over 2 culverts.

Travel_notes: It starts out in forest, then switchbacks up into more open, meadowy habitat. Walk 363m on trail
Location_desc: The point is in the middle of some wooden steps, surrounded by Avalanche lilies. Mt. Rainier is in view (partially). Next to 50dbh mountain hemlock and 40dbh branchy pale snag.

Travel_notes: Entirely on Wonderland Trail, uphill through beautiful meadows and open Subalpine fir habitat
Location_desc: Point is before some wooden steps after small bridge crossing over creek, in open Subalpine fir, surrounded by heather, low shrub, and Avalanche Lily.

Travel_notes: Entirely on Wonderland Trail
Location_desc: Point is about 35 m after the trail to the patrol cabin. A beautiful view of Mt. Rainier.

Travel_notes: Entirely on trail- BEAUTIFUL!
Location_desc: Point is surrounded by heather, leading into Subalpine fir forest. It is just after some wooden steps.

Travel_notes: It is all on the trail through Meadow and Subalpine fir.
Location_desc: The point is at the crest of a small hill on the Wonderland Trail in a Subalpine fir forest with heather and Avalanche Lilies surrounding it. Next to two 30dbh and one 20dbh subalpine firs, two of which are semi-pistol gripped about 2m up trunk.

Travel_notes: It is entirely on the Wonderland Trail, downslope from SE07.
Location_desc: The point is on the Wonderland Trail about 10 m past a small creek and next to some large boulders on left side of trail.

Travel_notes: Downhill on Wonderland Trail. Somewhat more than 200m to account for bends in the trail. GPS coords may not be exactly on trail, trail was under quite a bit of snow in 2014.
Location_desc: Located in subalpine fir/pacific silver fir/mountain hemlock woods with some open meadows and lots of creek noise. Trail under 2 feet of snow in 2014, GPS coordinates may be slightly off-trail.

Travel_notes: Travel through some meadow, cross stream, and pass bog.
Location_desc: After crossing the kettle bog (open marshy area), there is a fallen white snag (~40dbh) on a small hill overlooking the bog - see photo. The point is at the middle of this log. Lots of heather, young subalpine firs and mountain hemlocks.

Travel_notes: Walk along meadow clearing before cutting upslope into the trees.
Location_desc: In forest at spot mostly clear of shrubs. There are only small herbaceous plants very close. There is a small drainage visible to the N and NE of point. Small rock face seen to the NW.

Travel_notes: Travel through undulating terrain in forest, minimal ground cover.
Location_desc: On slope in open understory. Upslope is a very decayed stump near Mtn. hemlock feature. Downslope to E is a very flat, almost grassy patch. There is a barkless downed tree to the S of point running upslope. Easy to cut back to trail from here.

Travel_notes: From Indian Henry's, the TO is located about 300m downhill (and across about 4 bridges) from the large, cascading creek. From the Tahoma Creek suspension bridge, the TO is uphill from the last switchback (which turns sharply left if you're climbing). Tahoma Creek Trail is probably the fastest way to access 4014, but it is unmaintained and there are some dangerous creek crossings required (especially difficult with a heavy pack) 2014: Tahoma Creek trail passable w/o any creek crossings, but check for current conditions; one area where trail ran alongside steep bank due to washouts. You can camp in the Pyramid Peak x-country zone (~30-minute hike to TO). 2021: We camped at Devil's Dream (buggy) and hiked 1.5 miles, about 40min to TO. The NW arm is not hard to follow, but may look confusing; however, there is a lot of water noise and not many birds up there.  SE arm beautiful and buggy. Tahoma Creek trail closed.
Location_desc: Point is just past a small ~1m long, single planked footbridge. Mountain hemlock and cedar saplings on SW side of trail.
Location_notes: This portion of trail was 400 m West of where the map said it should be.  We offset the TO about 400 m so that it was on the actual trail, using the intended northing.

Travel_notes: None
None
Location_desc: Point on steep hillside-slick and lush.  Mixed conifer canopy.  Mt hemlock dominates trail to SW from point, drainage to NE

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: Point is in mixed conifer forest near the drainage which flows from mirror lakes to Tahoma creek, on NE bank of creek.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: Point is located on a very steep hillside.  Stee rock-canyon walled drainage is immediately to the NE (arm of Tahoma creek from Pyramid Peak).  Mossy boulder is the point landmark feature.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: thick ixed conifer forest.  Tahoma creek arm from pyramid peak flows to east in sight of point.

Travel_notes: cross over creek
Location_desc: Point is in ferns at the foot of talus slope. Just S is a small patch of mountain hemlock with the marker. Point is directly beside mossy rock overgrown with mountain ash.

Travel_notes: Travel to point NW02 is tricky, but mostly through open terrain. The first 170m, pick your way through salmonberry, alder, and large erratic boulders. Skirt the edge of conifer forest and point is located in thick huckleberry, just inside conifer canopy.
Location_desc: Point is just inside mature hemlock wood with large trees. huckleberry understory about 2m tall. Just uphill is edge of talus slope where vegetation takes over.

Travel_notes: Travel is failry easy to NW03. open forest with a few stream crossings, then climb up to cliffband. Transect pass over cliffs, but you can skirt around at their base, in salmonberry and Devil's club, then curl around cliffs the last 40m. GPS point was 29m off - go by the features! That rock face is a good one.
Location_desc: Point is on old deadfall, 2m from unmistakable large rock face (25m tall cliff). Just SE of transect is an open canopy meadow. immediately surrounding point is hemlock saplings, salmonberry and Devil's club. Above head on cliff face is young cedar sapling and above that a larger, mature cedar overhanging cliff.

Travel_notes: Very difficult travel to NW04--tie your boots and buckle your packstraps. First 40m is steep, moist salmonberry and Devil's club thicket. pass through some mature trees with thick shrub understory, then descend to alder and salmonberry meadow. Almost impossible to pace this section. Rather, take long distance bearings and estimate between these.
Location_desc: Point is in alders, in a small berbaceous clearing where a few hidden creeks rnu together (very loud).

Travel_notes: Travel is tough through alder groves and salmonbrry thickets, travelling uphill. First 20m in first patch alders; walk through two more patches. A dry creekbed makes walking easier last 40m
Location_desc: Point is in open meadow near car-sized boulders. Distinct tree-groves nearby. 20m NW is mature conifer forest bordered by alder thicket. Undergrowth is herbaceous flowers, salmonberry and elderberry shurbs and currant.

Travel_notes: open for first 50m, then travel uphill through thick alder. At 70m or so, climb up steep rocky hill. Climb up ravine until you hit rock wall. It appears that you will cross over trail on GPS. I didn't see the trail but there was a lot of snow this year. NW06 can be seen from NW05 if you look up to where the rock cliff begins.
Location_desc: Point is against rock wall as far up the ravine as possible to travel. Point is near a fallen Doug-fir that is supported on one end by the rocky cliff

Travel_notes: Travel slightly uphill 100 m from TO.
Location_desc: Point in mixed conifer forest, dense canopy and many younger (predominantly silver fir) trees, very little undergrowth, next to a fallen log in late stages of decay.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: Point on a gradual slope next to a hemlock, dbh 50 cm, (see seen from point) in MICO with little undergrowth

Travel_notes: travel slightly uphill.
Location_desc: Point on large downed Doug-fir laying E-W in middle of devils club near small spring under an open area in the canopy.

Travel_notes: Travel across trail and Ipsut creek.
Location_desc: Point on  N side of Ipsut creek, 8 m up the bank next to a few mossy fallen trees.

Travel_notes: Travel along side slope, relatively open most of the way.
Location_desc: Point in stand of waist high young Pacific silver fir next to a dbh 70 cm silver fir in mixed conifer forest.

Travel_notes: Along side slope
Location_desc: Point on side slope in mixed conifer forest, most trees pistol gripped, next to a 100cm DBH hemlock. It is on SW edge on stand of young hemlocks, open understory.

Travel_notes: Take Wonderland Trail N from Ipsut Pass down into Ipsut Ck valley. Cross loc bridge and continue down trail 90m. TO is just beyond 90degree bend intrail. Large hemlocks uphill. NW arm is a lot of bushwhacking - grab a stick to help push the thorns away and wear protective gear. Gators wouldn't be a bad idea.
Location_desc: TO is on trail near a bend. Downhill is Ipsut Ck, riparian meadow and talus field can be seen across valley. Just uphill are a number of large hemlocks. Trail is about 60 m off, it should be 60 m further E according to GPS.  We camped cross country near TO. The NW arm is beautiful and birdy, but travel is hard thruogh difficult vegetation--lots of salmonberry and huckleberry shrub. A detour to Eunic lake and Tolmie peak is higly recommended.

Travel_notes: Travel toward Clover Lake and Upper Palisades camp from TO.  Pace 130 m past trail junction with Sunsrise Lake trail to the point.
Location_desc: Point on trail.

Travel_notes: Travel off trail at 45 degree angle, downhill along bench.
Location_desc: Point in Subalpine fir parkland on slight slope.

Travel_notes: Travel downhill along bench.
Location_desc: Point in Subalpine fir parkland on three fallen logs near rotting stump, clearing on map visible to SE.

Travel_notes: Cross a dry stream bed, follow another dry stream bed to 15 m from point, here depart the streambed for the point.
Location_desc: Point in Subalpine fir parkland with small stream 40 m to the SE next to a dead fir (see seen from point), with clearing on map visible to S and SE.

Travel_notes: Travel through Subalpine fir parkland, cross 2 streams, after crossing second stream enter closed canopy forest with no undergrowth.
Location_desc: Point on slight slope on fallen log, you can hear a stream nearby, little to no deciduous undergrowth at point.

Travel_notes: Climb over small hill, descend into and cross drainage, begin upslope toward point.
Location_desc: Point on mellow slope in Mixed conifer forest, 50 m from a dry drainage which contours along the bottom of the slope.

Travel_notes: Cut across steep slope sideslope with lots of deciduous undergrowth (Azalea), the bottom of the slope is about 44 m. below.  Near the end of the transect drop gradually into an open meadow.
Location_desc: Point 10 m. into small meadow with many old treefalls next to a few young Mtn. hemlocks.

Travel_notes: Travel 50m through open area. Then begin up side slope which levels a bit at 130m where you first hit azalea. Continue over log and past snags to point.
Location_desc: point is at 3 downed trees on slight slope. To the N, slope steepens with slight opening to horizon. To the W, is azalea patch.

Travel_notes: Continue side-slope travel on bearing. Gradual slope becomes much steeper.
Location_desc: Point on very steep slope next to several fallen trees stacked on top of each other. Azalea understory downslope. Steep upslope with very little understory.

Travel_notes: Travel 100m uptrail to point SE01. Point located just before 1/2 circle viewing area on right (north side of trail).
Location_desc: Point is on wide trail with rock edges. just uphill is spur/loop viewing trail on right (north). Rainier can be seen ahead, above the trees.

Travel_notes: Travel up trail 200m -- point is just before stone wall lookout on east side of road and parking lot. Lookout will likely be busy and distracting at sunrise.
Location_desc: Point is at the edge of parking lot where the Palisades Trail begins and goes east.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m on trail to point SE03. Take the farthest right rouute along sidewalk on N side of road and parkinglot.
Location_desc: Point is on trail, just uphill from road on ridge.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m on trail.
Location_desc: Point is on ridge with openings to the south (Cowlitz Chimneys) and north (Palisades).

Travel_notes: travel 200m on trail.
Location_desc: Point is beside small, exposed white/grey boulders to right (north) of trail--see image.

Travel_notes: Travel down trail for 200m.
Location_desc: Point is on trail just beyond many bleached snags on left (south) side of trail. Dege peak can be seen ahead along the ridge in the distance.

Travel_notes: Drop down to small gap and begin climbing ridge toward Dege peak. Cross 7 switchbacks after you start climbing.
Location_desc: Point is on trail among wooden waterbars. Moving water can be heard downhill to right. Trees mostly on the south side of ridge with expansive views to north.

Travel_notes: Continue climbing ridge 200m to point SE08.
Location_desc: point is on trai ljust before trail bends left to traverse the south aspect of Sourdough ridge. Point is on a smallish wooden waterbar. Some stunted, scraggly krummholz firs just downhill (to right).

Travel_notes: Continue climbing toward Dege Peak. Trail goes left of ridge proper to begin a climbing traverse of the south slope, parallel to road through parkland meadows.
Location_desc: Point is easily located because of small whitebark pine saplings on either side of trail. Road easily seen downhill. A little wash downhill has washed out forbs and drainage is gravelly.

Travel_notes: Travel uphill 200m. Trail gradually contours right.
Location_desc: Point is in open parkland meadow. Some gravel in trail. Phlox and lupine growing nearby.

Travel_notes: Travel gradually uphill through parkland meadows.
Location_desc: Point falls in a large meadow, mostly treeless up and downhill for 50m circle. Very conical and characteristic subalpine fir just uphill from point. Clear views of Cowlitz Chimneys and Sarvant Glacier to south. Soil rocky uphill.

Travel_notes: Travel across highpoint on ridge, past spur trail to peak. Continue beyond on the main trail, downhill to point.
Location_desc: Point is on trail with a small browngrass meadow uphill (where snow lingers) and a green meadow, full of life, downhill, just beyond a thin line of firs bordering trail. 80m beyond point, the trail bends right to aim for a gap between peaks.

Travel_notes: Travel 110 m past the far end of the viewpoint loop on the Palisades Lake trail.
Location_desc: An absolutely beautiful transect--far vistas and a sunrise, no river noise and many birds. Save this transect for a beautiful day. SE arm stays on trail and points are spaced evenly at 200m on-trail sections. Closest camping is White River walk-in (approximately 30min travel time).

Travel_notes: Travel is downhill through mature conifer forest. There is a little underbrush to contend with.
Location_desc: Point NN01 is in a small wash, moist but not soppy, with huckleberry and Devil's Club understory. Large Doug-firs around and 25m tall cedars in understory. You can hear a rushing brook approximately 30m to the east.

Travel_notes: Bearing goes west to NN02. Travel is mostly across gentle slope. Devil's club is thin and not too difficult to pass through. Point is located just before larger brook.
Location_desc: Point NN02 is 12m from perennial brook. Two large Doug-fir blowdowns cross on uphill side of point. Large trees all around--Doug-fir, W Hemlock approaching and esceeding 1.5m DBH-very nice grove.

Travel_notes: Cross large deadfall and creek and continue traversing contour. The slope progressively steepens and there is a fair bit of vegetation to 'shwhack through.
Location_desc: Point NN03 is located in wet mossy seep in a Devil's club thicket. A small drainage on south running uphill. Open canopy directly overhead.

Travel_notes: Travel to point NN04 is all uphill and steep in places.
Location_desc: Point is on relatively steep slope in the midst of recent blowdowns. To the S and E are openings in the canopy above a dry wash that runs uphill. Groundcover includes lily, vanilla-leaf and some huckleberry.

Travel_notes: Travel traverses the contour on a north bearing. Some little saplings in the way, but mostly open, mature forest.
Location_desc: Point is in a dry gully in mature forest. large hemlocks and grand (or Pacific silver) fir. Very little herbaceous groundcover immediately surrounding point.

Travel_notes: Travel on side of slight slope through fairly open old growth with occasional blowdowns (very large trees) and canopy openings. ~30m from point, devil's club makes appearance and leads you to point just past and downhill from the devil's club.
Location_desc: point is at flat spot 20m downhill from devil's club. Next to huckleberry and just before blowdown (in features seen from point)

Travel_notes: Head uphill the whole way. Steep but little understory.
Location_desc: Point located in old avalanche chute, directly under the rockface. Ground vegetation of hellebore and vanilla leaf

Travel_notes: Travel through wet area across creek and streams.  Lots of Devil's club.
Location_desc: Larger creek to the west in wet area with lots of Devil's club, alder, and snowberry. 20 m north of switchback in road.

Travel_notes: Travel steep and slippery, lots of Devil's club.
Location_desc: Point on south end of open area next to a rotting stump with a young western hemlock growing on top.  You can hear a stream to the NW.

Travel_notes: Travel uphill. When land flattens out a bit, travel through hemlock saplings. Point is just after crossing over a few logs-look for the BIG Doug-fir in description.
Location_desc: Point on slope in area clear of undergrowth.

Travel_notes: Travel along game trail first 50 m.  Slightly uphill entire way.
Location_desc: Point in young stand Pacific silver fir next to rotting log.

Travel_notes: Slightly uphill at first but then levels out, travel along contours.
Location_desc: Point in open area surrounded by many fallen logs.

Travel_notes: Travel slightly uphill, steeper near end.
Location_desc: Point on small ridge in yound stand Pacific silver fir and mountain hemlock, MORA visible through trees. One of the snags "side by side" mentioned in description has fallen.

Travel_notes: travel easy, along ridge with relatively little undergrowth
Location_desc: Point near lake George campground group site, view of lake, creek to the W.

TP is on Westside road, about 100m after large hairpin turn (switchback). You are near the point when a large Doug-fir (1.5m DBH), the first of two, is directly off north side of road. Just beyond point downhill on road a creek passes under the road. We hiked the West side road and camped at Lake George (30min hike down to TO).  SS arm parallels the trail toward camp but does not cross it, the map is a little off and it appears that you should even though you don't. NN arm fairly moderate travel and not too noisy after the first two points.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On flat bench 70 m upslope from road.  Marker on 46 cm DBH Doug-fir that is 2 m N. of 102 cm DBH Doug-fir, which is 1.5 m N. of downed 70 cm DBH Doug-fir.

Travel_notes: 30 m through open Doug-fir to steeper slope with vine maple understory.  Point is at the crest of this steeper slope.
Location_desc: 4m from crest of slope onto small ridge.  122 cm DBH Doug-fir's on ridge, smaller Doug-fir and more vine maple on approaching slope.  2 m beneath strongly curving "pistol gripped" bole of 64 cm DBH Doug-fir.

Travel_notes: Travel through Doug-fir woods with vine maple understory.  Just after small clearing begin to follow S. side of low ridge.
Location_desc: Point is exactly where fallen 66 cm DBH Doug-fir crosses decaying stump at W. edge of 50 x 30 m clearing, carpeted with salal and vanilla leaf.

Travel_notes: Follow bearing through Doug-fir woods with vine maple understory until you bisect small N/S drainage.
Location_desc: In bottom of small N/S drainage with many fallen logs and mossy boulders.  The N/S drainage joins a S.W. running drainage about 30 m to the S.

Travel_notes: Out of small drainage, 35 m to next drainage, up slope through Doug-fir with vine maple understory, cross N/S trail and another small drainage before reaching point.
Location_desc: In 40 x 30 m mossy clearing, 30 m E. from shallow drainage.  Oregon grape and salal are < 1 m high.  Point is in open Doug-fir woods with thick vine maple to W. and N.

Travel_notes: Up slope through Doug-fir with vine maple understory.  vine maple ends 50 m before W. edge of small SW drainage.  Point is on E. Slope of drainage.
Location_desc: On 1 x 2/3 m moss covered rock at E. edge of opening created by small drainage running at 206 degrees.  Thick vine maple further up drainage.  Point is 10 m short of mossy rock wall.

Travel_notes: Follow steep slope towards rocky creek drainage.  Cross creek about half way to point.  May be advisable to cross creek earlier and cut N. to avoid slippery, mossy rock faces.  Point is in open Doug-fir woods NE of creek.
Location_desc: < 1 m E of stump on 30-40 degree slope with open Doug-fir woods.  35 m W. of drainage with vine maple and exposed rock faces.

Reason_for_change: Ohanapecosh River bars off-trail point to west
Travel_notes: Walk along west shoulder of road for 100m.
Location_desc: On west shoulder of road at south edge of the next pull-off up from TO, across from a rocky outcropping. See photo to reference the rocky outcropping feature.

Travel_notes: Walk 100m northerly on west shoulder of road.
Location_desc: Point on west shoulder of road.

Travel_notes: Leave road going west, through roadside drainage, up and down rolling, fairly open woods until you reach bluff above river.
Location_desc: On a small flat area perched on steep slope leading down to bluff above river.  On the leading edge of this flat is a small-girthed but mature  Western hemlock, directly in front of (east) which is a smaller, twisted hemlock.

Reason_for_change: Ohanapecosh River bars travel to the W, NW, N
Travel_notes: Travel NE through open forest over rolling hills and depressions, across lines of mossed-over boulders.
Location_desc: On NE side of boulder ridglet, right above a marshy wash.

Travel_notes: Pick your way over fallen logs, muck your way through swampy ground until you recross the highway. 2013: Could not find any features described in nav report. Paced 200 m from NN04, but GPS had point another 50m N. Did count according to GPS and re-wrote features from point.
Location_desc: Point is just a few meters past east shoulder of road.

Travel_notes: Travel NE away from road through mixed conifer forest.
Location_desc: Point in level patch 1/4 up moss-covered hill. Road is visible to the W at ~100 meters.

Travel_notes: Travel up a brief slope then across level terrain. ~100m forest opens up w/ many snags and younger trees. Continue NE until the next hill.
Location_desc: Point is in relatively open forest w/ mossy ground. Point is at base of a E/NE slope, tucked up again a downed log that is perpendicular to slope.

Travel_notes: Travel Northeast through a mostly open understory. At approximately 80m the understory becomes more dense with a few large downed logs.
Location_desc: Point is in a mature conifer forest on a flat mossy patch surrounded by young hemlocks. The point is just Southwest of the paved road (road is not on the GPS).

Travel_notes: Camp at Ohanapecosh campground.  Drive less than 5 minutes S. on Rt. 123.  Point is at third gravel pull-off S. of campground.
Location_desc: In Road next to third gravel pull-off on W. side of road heading S. from Ohanapecosh campground.  cedar tree and boulder mentioned in marker information are at S.W. corner of pull-off, just N. of small rise.

Travel_notes: Pace 120 m on trail from TO down steps and around small bend.
Location_desc: Point on trail on a small mossy rock next to 2, dbh 30 cm, Yellow cedars, about 3 m apart, on uphill side of trail with two small snags behind and between them.

Travel_notes: Pace 230 m on trail, relatively flat and straight.
Location_desc: Point on trail next to a 1 m long flat topped boulder just N of rock slide area.

Travel_notes: Pace 230 m on trail.
Location_desc: Point on trial next to hemlock on uphill side of trail, dbh 80 cm, with gnarled roots heading toward trail and smaller hemlock, dbh 30 cm, wrapping around the side of the larger tree.

Travel_notes: Pace 230 m on trail, relatively flat and straight.
Location_desc: Point on trail next to pistol gripped cedar, dbh 40 cm, with long section of bark torn off by a bear, on downhill side of trail

Travel_notes: Pace 270 m on trail, relatively flat and straight.
Location_desc: Point on trail 30 m downtrail of trail junction sign and next to a 1/4 m tall stump and a 3 m tall , dbh 15 cm, snag, about 2 m apart on downhill side of trail.

Travel_notes: Pace 330 m on trail.  Take trail toward Eunice lake.  Pass trail junction with Ipsut pass, pass two switchbacks, and cross a rock slide area.
Location_desc: point on trail next to snag (w/branches, w/o bark) w/ crown broken and leaning against a nearby Silver fir, just past an open rock slide area under a cliff face with lost of herbacious growth.

Travel_notes: Pace 230 m on trail.  Downhill past area where you travel along the bottom of the cliff face.
Location_desc: Point on trail next to large snag flanked by 2 Pacific silver firs, dbh  20 cm.

Travel_notes: Pace 230 m on trail along relatively flat and straight section of trail.
Location_desc: Point on traill near stream from Eunice lake outlet next to 4 young Pacific silver firs.

Travel_notes: Pace 400 m on trail, up stairs, past waterfall, past 3 switchbacks.
Location_desc: Point on trail 25 m beyond 3rd switchback next to snag.

Travel_notes: Pace 400 m on trail to Eunice lake, at junction with spur trail head toward the lookout.
Location_desc: Point on trail past sign "0.9 mi to Tolmie lookout", on S side of stream where trail begins to head W along S side of Eunice lake next to large mtn hemlock and many smaller firs.

Travel_notes: Pace out 230m on trail.
Location_desc: Point most likely in open snow patch with a gorgeous view of Eunice Lake. Firs to the South are windswept and scraggly.

Travel_notes: Travel down trail 125m through one switchback and down some wooden stairs. Stop when trai flattens out and begins toparallel lakeshore.
Location_desc: Point is on trail just below a double fir and above that a wet, mossy rock.

Travel_notes: Pace 225m down trail
Location_desc: Point is along an undifferentiated section of trail. There is some exposed rock uphill. Lake 10m downhill. Look for distinctive cedar (DSC02388).

Travel_notes: Pace 200 m on trail. Stay left along lakeshore when you come to trail junction.
Location_desc: Point is 15 m past junction

Travel_notes: Pace 215 m on trail. Continue along lakeshore in mature forest until you pass out into some meadows. The wet boulder in travel features is either at 125 or 75 m (or 200?) from previous point- observer's handwriting is challenging.
Location_desc: Point is on trail just after distinctive wash/gully with a few dog-sized boulders.The lake is visible. Just downhill is a small stand of mature conifers with meadow on either side.

Travel_notes: Pace 235m on trail. There are many side trails on this section, but stay on the main drag.
Location_desc: Point is on Lakeshore trail getting close to road and campground. Lake and cliffs clearly visable. Point is downtrail 20m from a junction with spur trail leading to road.

Travel_notes: Pace 350m first down and then around perimeter of lakeshore, then up into parking lot. Bear left towards campgronud and stop on bridge over crek.
Location_desc: Point is on trail between parking lot and walk-in campground directly above outflow of Mowich Lake.

Travel_notes: Walk through camp, bearing left, to the Wonderland trail--follow to Ranger's cabin along perimeter of lakeshore. Just before the cabin, stop at SS07 after 250m from SS06.
Location_desc: Point is along raised gravel trail leading to Ranger Cabin just 10m from lakeshore. Scrubby meadow uphill. mostly open canopy.

Travel_notes: Pace 330m to SS08. Follow ranger trail to cabin and bear left on climbers trail toward knapsack pass. The first section is hardest to navigate low by the lake. if snow is present, follwo the bootpack. Climb uphill and over some switchbacks until you see the rock outcrops.
Location_desc: Point is on section of trail with many exposed roots. Rock outcrops uphill to right (S) and Mowich lake visable downhill (N). There are a couple large old decaying logs across trail here.

Travel_notes: Pace 310m to SS09. Trail is steep in sections w/ some switchbacks (addig to trail pacing length). When you get to small meadow, drop down into soggy wash and 20m up far side (see image).
Location_desc: Point is just uphill from low wash in semi-open mountain hemlock and subalpine-fir forest. Crek can be heard to right (south--approx 40m) Azalea and huckleberry shrub layer. Lily and moss groundcover.

Travel_notes: Travel is thruogh mostly open meadow with views of lake. Patches of mountain hemlock and subalpine-fir. 225m total from SS09 to SS10.
Location_desc: Point is in upland meadow between young yellow cedar saplings to either side of trail. Rock faces seen in either direction and a creek heard to the left (N).

Travel_notes: Leave Mowich walk-in camp on the Lakeshore Trail, follow around lake and just beyond lake, climb one switchback to a small gap.
Location_desc: The TO is located in a small gap/pass about 83pc. up trail from the lake. There is a small clearing on the south side of trail and a characteristic rock (see image) on north side. Camped at Mowich walk-in: 25 min. walk. This is a heavily trafficked area- you will see people (maybe even during counts)

Travel_notes: Travel is across creek then traverse down ridge into semi-open-canopy bowl. Point is on slope at the head of the bowl.
Location_desc: Point is in the head of a little bowl which has a moderately open canopy and huckleberry understory. just uphill is distinctive rock outcrop.

Travel_notes: Travel is slightly difficult due to some cliffs near transect--traverse around the base of these mossy rocks and continue through flat, open forest with dense huckleberry understory.
Location_desc: Point is on the edge of a 50m clearing, just 40m shy of the creek draining Lake James. Just downhill from point is low wash with sphagnum moss, avalanche lillies, muddy soil. Point is ni huckleberries near fuor sapling cedars.

Travel_notes: Travel is relatively easy over rolling terrain mostly huckleberry shrub. Low marshy area at 145m distinctive.
Location_desc: Point is on shoulder/ledge of a ridge 10m before significant dropoff. Open canopy forest with huckleberry shrub understory. Large cedar is very good landmark.

Travel_notes: There are two ways you can approach NW04: (1) the SE bearing to trail,  or (2) the S bearing to trail. The SE bearing is difficult--pick you way down through mossy ledges at 30m, cross a low marsh and meet rail at 120m. Continue down trial to point. Otherwise, the much easier route, travels due south around the forested pond to rail. Go left on the trail about 300m.
Location_desc: The point is 3m beyond a left-turning switchback with large hemlock in the elbow.

Travel_notes: Travel on trail for 6110m downhill past seven major switchbacks (the map is fairly accurate in this regard). After the last switchback (turns right), proceed 100m to rocky wash where NW05 is located. A left-turning switchback is just beyond point 20m.
Location_desc: Point located on trail where a shallow gully runs downhill, thus the rocky wash. Point is ni between the 7th and 8th switchback coming down from NW04.

Travel_notes: Travel down trail for 9 switchbacks. Trail meanders quite a bit from switchback 3-4 and 4-5, but only count the true hairpin turns! There are large hemlock roots growing down into the trail at switchback 5 if you lose count. You'll cross several rocky washes over trail.
Location_desc: On trail in slight bend in trail, many cut logs/fallen trees and stumps. Point is right next to water bar (as of 2018) and splintered stump. Falls can be heard nearby, rocky stream visible through few trees.

Travel_notes: Continue down trail til you reach stream. Lots of downed trees, I found it easiest to head south in stream bed for about 120m before popping up into the forest to find point. Look out for frogs!
Location_desc: In small clearing with small vaccinium and saplings in understory. Lots of downed trees in area. Rocky slope to the SW.

Travel_notes: Travel on the trail  115 m from the TO.  It is slightly uphill, there are no swithchbacks.
Location_desc: Point on trail in between two Silver fir, dbh 50 cm, about 2 m apart and directly across from eachother on each side of the trail.  The roots of the Silver fir on the N side jut into the trail forming a small step.  This same Silver fir also has three other young Silver fir clustered around it with a log jammed in betwetween them.  Many old cut logs along the trail side.

Travel_notes: travel up drainage on trail 330 m fromSE01, slighlty uphill.  There aren't any true switchbacks but the trail bends and winds.
Location_desc: Point at bend in trail (right hand bend) next to a hemlock (on the left) with gnarled roots sticking out onto the trail forming two steps and a rotting stump in late stages of decay directly across the trail form the hemlock.

Travel_notes: Travel on trail slightly uphill 340 m from SE02.  Cross a stream in an open area with lots of Devils club and Salmonberyy, cross one switchback, cross another stream, cross another switchback, recross the sencond stream at a log bridge, the trail then begins to flatten out.  Point is in the flat area.
Location_desc: Point in a flat area on trail where the trail crew has built up a gravel sidewalk with reatiining logs.  The point is at the top if the first section of this sidewalk next to a large hemlock with a 1/2 m burl on its side facing the trail.  The dead forest is visibel to the E and the rock wall to the W.

Travel_notes: Continue traveling up sidewalk  245 m from SE03, past junction for James Camp, cross 2 log trunk bridges over a stream, pass the "no camping at Lk. James" sign, and finally cross over one log bridge over a snowmelt pond.  point is on the S end of the last bridge.
Location_desc: Point on trail 10 m from the end of the third bridge on a stretch of trail with many gnarled roots in an open canopy forest next to a stream.

Travel_notes: Head up trail 380m. Cross two bridges and head up hill. Trail flattens out (kinda) after first switchback.
Location_desc: Point is located in a spot with open canopy and a cliff face to the west. Point is between several sawed logs on either side of the trail.

Travel_notes: Travel up trail 534m, going up 8 switchbacks. Continue past the ranger cabin sign.
Location_desc: Point located on flat part of trail, just past a western hemlock stump with a  jagged break. Trail ahead goes slightly downhill and then continues uphill.

Travel_notes: Travel uphill jsut past one switchback and then start going down. Pace out 410m. Point is just past where the trail is a large rock.
Location_desc: Point is between large boulder on E side of trail and feature hemlock with a mountain hemlock attached at the base.

Travel_notes: Pace on trail 275m.
Location_desc: Point next to large boulder on north side of trail. Many large hemlocks surround and downed log borders trail.

Travel_notes: Pace 580m on trail, passing 9 swithcbacks.
Location_desc: Point located next to a 120cm DBH wester red cedar (2 boles) with many roots on trail. Waterbar is a meter up trail. Photo of cedar not taken from point.

Travel_notes: Take trail NW from Lake James about .4 miles. Pass talus slope on right where trail switchbacks to the left. Continue about 120m to where trail crosses a small brook and old growth cedars grow. Difficult travel to Lake James camp if there is much snow on windy gap. Use caution and allow time or attempt in late season. 2018: Did this transect as a part of Northern Loop in July to avoid heavy snow on trails. Great move to do the loop, but bring gear to combat mosquitoes!
Location_desc: TO is on trail 5m beyond where brook crosses under trail. TO is between 2 very large yellow cedars (2+m DBH), both downslope (N) side of trail. Point is in  low spot with marshy character between two ridges. Tons of mosquitos.  We camped at Lake James, 30 minute walk to the TO.  The trail was in very poor condition, many downed logs and debris. Bring a tent. NW arm went off-trail 1st few points, but found many natural boundaries, so finished back on trail.

Travel_notes: Go left of the massive boulders at 38 m. The point is in a moss-covered boulder field just before the beginning of a dense vine maple area.
Location_desc: The point is located in a patch of large moss-covered boulders. There is a large decomposing log just south (less than 1m) of the point and a large non-moss-covered boulder just north (<1m) of the point.

Travel_notes: Travel east for 200 m along slope. Slow, because through dense vine maple and mossy rocks.
Location_desc: Point is at downslope base of rotten 3m tall snag, 30 dbh. To the west is a large blowdown of Doug-firs, river is audible.
Location_notes: This point was too close to NN01.

Travel_notes: Travel gradually upslope for 200m at east bearing. Lots of mossy boulders and downed trees as well as some vine maple.
Location_desc: Point located on slope covered in ferns and mossy boulders, immedtiately downslope from a 1 m cubed stack of three mossy boulders. Lots of rotting logs downslope, vine maple upslope. Creek audible from point.

Travel_notes: Travel east along slope for 200m, steep uphill at parts.
Location_desc: Point is just above stump on rocky mossy slope with lots of deer fern. Directly overhead is a very conspicuous mossy cedar with angular joints. WIthin arms reach to the West is another cedar with 40cm dbh.
Location_notes: This point was too close to others on the transect arm.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m along steep sideslope at east bearing; some uphill travel involved.
Location_desc: Point located between vine maple upslope and a few downed logs immediately downslope. Feature large fire snag with woodpecker holes at base and huge leaning log located close by to the east.

Travel_notes: Travel E along slope, undegrowth dense at beginning, thins out.
Location_desc: point is directly under hemlock with pronounced curve and moss at base, 20cm dbh.
Location_notes: This point was too close to NN05.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m at east bearing along steep sideslope. Some uphill travel involved. Cross avalanche chute/ravine ~15m before point.
Location_desc: On steep slope immediately below 1m wide mossy boulder and snapped off douglas fir. Ravine with running water located ~15m west, and huge overhanging mossy boulders visible upslope to the NE.
Location_notes: The rest of this arm was modified because of previous points being too close together. This newly established point falls on the same location as another point from this original arm, so the name was not changed.

Travel_notes: Traverse slope eastwards for 200m.
Location_desc: Point is directly on top of short (1m) jagged rotting cedar stump. a large patch of vanilla-leaf is 10m SE. two Doug-firs (50 and 30 dbh) are within arms reach.
Location_notes: This point was too close to NN05.

Travel_notes: Well-worn deer track upslope from NN05 travels all the way to NN06b.
Location_desc: Point is located on a well-worn deer track, steep slopes above and below. Open area with mossy boulders and vine maple ~15m upslope. Immediately below a ~30cm DBH western hemlock growing from a rotting stump.

Travel_notes: traverse slope for 200m eastwards.
Location_desc: point is on slope 1m E of 70 dbh Doug-fir. Rootball to North supports 3 hemlocks that lay N-S oriented down slope.
Location_notes: This point was retired because the rest of the arm was modified due to points being too close together. This point would have been too close to the newly established replacement points.

Travel_notes: Deer trail travels roughly east along steep slope most of the way from point NN06b, then descend to flat area west of ravine/avalanche chute. Or just follow east bearing along steep slope.
Location_desc: Point located on eastern edge of drainage/old avalanche chute. Immediately east is a doug fir laying downhill across two stumps and a small group of young western hemlocks.

Travel_notes: Follow east bearing for 200m. Easy, pleasant travel through relatively flat, open hemlock forest. Creek beds/drainages dry in 2014, may flood in the future.
Location_desc: Point located in relatively open hemlock woods - lots of downed wood and young hemlock saplings nearby. Point is immediately SSW of a ~50cm DBH hemlock with a small snag attached. 5 snags (features) may fall down in the next five years, may need to find new features at next visit.

Travel_notes: 200m due east through relatively open + flat forest
Location_desc: point is on a small tussock at base of doug-fir with a small hemlock growing out of it, and under the branches of the hemlock

Travel_notes: Walk 108m along road.
Location_desc: Point is E of stream ~30m

Travel_notes: walk 200m along road
Location_desc: point is at the far edge (east) of a pull-out.  the next pullout is roughly 95m down the road.

Travel_notes: From east end of pullout pace 200m south, starting from north side of road.  [Alternate route: walk 115m down road (east) and then pace roughly 90m at 216 degrees.] Note: travel features are for original bearing (180), not alternate route.
Location_desc: Point is just south of large 4m tall rootball with fallen moss-covered cedars pointing south.  Rootball is conspicuous, has young hemlocks growing out of top.

Travel_notes: Travel very swampy.  Go through two open stands of skunk cabbage with varying amounts of standing water.
Location_desc: Point is in area with tall alder canopy and many young short hemlock saplings.  Point is under a 15m tall alder growing from a down log. 2014 update: "snag with three part jagged top" feature appears to have changed a little since 2009 - see updated picture.

Travel_notes: Travel is not as swampy as for SS04.  There is less standing water and skunk cabbage, and more moss and ferns.  Many downed logs.
Location_desc: Point is in a mixed of Red Alder/Western Hemlock with many fallen logs.  The edge of the bank down to the river is 15m south.

Travel_notes: Travel is flat and easy, following the riverbank. Forgot to do waypoint averaging for this point, so GPS coordinates might be slightly off, but features should be easy to find.
Location_desc: Point is in mossy patch amidst red alder, Western hemlock and vine maple.

Travel_notes: Travel through WEHE/SIFI. Roundabout route favoring S reduces number of logs to be lept over.
Location_desc: Point is just after topography rises notably to the N. Point is just N of 7m sharp WEHE snag-stump. Stand in nook of blow-down root ball. Upslope from snag stump.

Travel_notes: Ascend shallow slope to road and walk to point. Point is on N side of the road near a large root ball w/ sawed off trunk (~75cm DBH).
Location_desc: Point is directly downslope from root ball with sawed off trunk mentioned in travel description.

Travel_notes:
From Tahoma Creek bridge, traveling east, the TO is circa 0.9mi.  There is a distinct turnout with a large cedar in its median, which is 0.6mi west of the TO. 20 minute drive from Cougar Rock Campground. SS arm swampy, NN steep.
 GPS coordinates for SS06 might be slightly off, but features should be easy to find. 15 minutes drive from Longmire - parked at turnaround on S side of road ~350m west of TO.
Location_desc: There is a bend in the road to the right roughly 50m of the TO.  At the bend there is a small stream crossing under the road through a culvert pipe.  11m north of the bend there is a 60DBH Western hemlock with large warty galls on the trunk for the first 15m.
Location_notes: Points NN06b, NN07b, and NN08 were renumbered to reflect the correct order in which they are to be sampled.
