There is no active NN04 (or NN04a) anymore because it fell in the same location as NN05, so there is now a gap in the numbering between points NN03a and NN05.  Also, NN06a and NN07a do not exist -- NN06b and NN07b were named as they were to avoid confusion for data collected (temporarily and mistakenly) in 2014 under NN06a and NN07a, and later reassigned after the end of the field season.

Travel_notes: Travel 200 m off-trail at 45 degrees.
Location_desc: point is in patch of oregon grape on mossy plateau in middle of a circle of 4 western hemlock and 2 Doug-fir snags

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: point is on small rise in slope, a flatter surface.  Vine maple lines the rise and are rooted just before the slope descends sharply.  The point is closest to the northernmost sturdy vine maple, (15 cm dbh) on the rise.  A closely spaced Doug-fir and Western hemlock (10 cm apart 60 cm dbh) are 1 m away.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: The point is on a mound of dirt and rock that a 25 m long dead tree has fallen on.  There are 2 dead stumps just to the E, one 15 m tall, other 3 m tall.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is located directly under a 15 cm dbh leaning 6m tall yew tree.  About 5 m away downslope there is a 36m long fallen tree lying in a north south direction.  There is also a vine maple directly above point.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is in an open mossy part of the hillside

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: point is in an open area on the side of the slope, many downed logs and snags.

Travel_notes: travel along the side of a steep hill
Location_desc: Point is looocated in a 1.5 m deep gently sloping trough running NW-SE.  Right next to a Western redcedar 35cm dbh with wide base at ground level of 60cm, rotting from the inside.

Travel_notes: 100m of flat open forest then 100m of dense, downhill forest. cross stream 1m before point
Location_desc: stream is 1m to the W. Many huge fallen trees around, and many saplings

Travel_notes: Pace downhill on the trail 100m in westerly direction.
Location_desc: Located in Hemlock Forest with little understory; some short salal & vanilla leaves present, slight opening in canopy to S.

Travel_notes: Pace 400m down trail from SW01 (As the crow flies, SW01 and SW02 are 200m apart).
Location_desc: On trail, in short straight section between road and a 90 degree bend in trail.

Travel_notes: Pace 200m down trail, cross road at 25m, take silver falls trail at 184 junction.
Location_desc: Point is on trail, river is highly audible.  Forest is similar to everywhere else on the trail so look for trail signs.

Travel_notes: Go down hill along trail, pacing 200m.  At 52m, there is a trail junction.  Go straight ahead, following sign toward campground.
Location_desc: Located on trail in hemlock/doug fir forest, river is below and is really loud.  Some vine maples hang over the trail to the north and south.

Travel_notes: Pace 200m down the trail, crossing the bridge over Laughing Water Creek at the 130m mark.
Location_desc: Located in Doug-fir/Western hemlock forest with a significant number of younger hemlocks present.  Understory is not thick but does include a few vine maples.

Travel_notes: Pace 200m on trail, traveling past a rock face adjacent to a bend in the trail and a small flow of water running across trail.
Location_desc: Located in doug fir/ hemlock forest at a bit of an opening in the canopy.  A downed log about a meter in diameter parallels trail.

Travel_notes: As you approach point, you'll pass 2 boulders on the east side of trail.  First one has vine maple growing on top.
Location_desc: Nondescript forest area near river.  Two boulders along trail, two very rotten old logs at point just on west side of trail.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: rather nondescript point surrounded by lots of snags in fairly dense forest.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is rather nondescript in the midst of hemlock/doug fir forest.  Lots of vine maple on a small ridge to the SW.  Some fallen logs parallel trail on east side.

Travel_notes: continue down trail 200m
Location_desc: Near a cascading creek crossing, very loud.  Forest is similar to rest of this transect arm so far, except canopy is a little thinner.

Travel_notes:
Pace 433 m up the trail from the Laughingwater Creek trailhead to reach TO.  Camp at Ohanapecosh campground, laughingwater trailhead is 5 minute drive, or about a 1 mile hike. ~10 min walk up trail to TO.
Some of the recorded coordinates (SW05, SW06) may be 30-40m off from actual location - pay close attention to feature descriptions.
Location_desc: TO is on top of a log in the trail (for drainage) and inside a curve in the trail.  A large fallen Douglas Fir across trail has been sawed through, 18 m to the SW

Travel_notes: NONE
Location_desc: On trail, look for gigantic cut DOFI upslope of fir feature.

Travel_notes: Walk down trail, and stop just before log bridge.  That is point 02.
Location_desc: On trail, just before bridge.  Lots of river noise.

Travel_notes: Continue over first bridge.  When you get to a 3m long log bridge with log edge on right side only, pace 150m beyond to get to point 03
Location_desc: On trail after hard left turn.  Trail turns right beyond point.  Open spot with large Doug fir visible on left (feature).

Travel_notes: Pace 200m down the trail.
Location_desc: Point just before a washed out/slidy area of trail. Look for snag ahead of you on right side of trail (feature). Small yews on either side of trail.

Travel_notes: Pace 207m on trail
Location_desc: On trail. Slope steep off to right. More open area, vine maple on W side.

Travel_notes: Pace 220 m down trail. Point is on trail after it starts to go down hill more steeply.
Location_desc: On trail.  Features obvious.  Mixed conifer forest with river noise.

Travel_notes: Walk 200m down trail.
Location_desc: Point just past giant sandy rootball on "left" side of trail. There is a big shreddy white snag just past rootball.

Travel_notes: Pace about 280 m on trail.  Look for stump on right hand side.
Location_desc: On trail under dense canopy.  Huge rotted stump on the right side of trail behind a hemlock sapling. Stump with triangular hole right next to a 2m tall barkless stump about 3m away.

Travel_notes: Walk until you can see the bridge.  Point is past this spot, straight up ahead downed log from features can be seen.
Location_desc: On trail ~30m before bridge crosses river.  Narrow section/flat and steep drop off to right.  River can be seen below. The Doug-fir snag has a top that is neatly chopped off. Hairy, taranchula-esque branch cluster covered with lichen on S side is visible from point. Tiny cut in seep 2m ahead on trail.

Travel_notes: Pace 293 m on trail.  Go over main log bridge over the falls, cross a smaller bridge (in travel features) and walk to point. 2015: this is misleading. At least 50m from 3 downstep waterlogs is the point. There are 3 root- downsteps and a large 1.5m dbh, 1m high cut stump on the right side of the trail right before the point.
Location_desc: On trail, just below a series of 3 downward "steps"  made by roots in trail.  Mixed conifer-open area forest. Point is in between a 80cm DBH cedar and 1m DBH Pacific silver fir.

Travel_notes: Pace 245m on trail, point is on trail just after trail starts to go uphill more steeply.
Location_desc: On trail before it goes over a little rise and turns to the left.  Look for mossy root ball in picture on the left side of trail and south of point. Pointed barkless snag is surrounded by <15cm dbh saplings.

Travel_notes: Pace 210m on trail, going uphill most of the way.
Location_desc: On trail in mixed conifer forest.

Travel_notes: Pace 206m along trail going uphill most of the way.
Location_desc: Open understory with mixed conifer, next to cut/decaying log chunk (see photos).

Travel_notes: NONE
Location_desc: On trail 2m beyond footbridge (1st footbridge from TO). GPS will say point is ~60m off trail but it is on the trail, follow featuers over GPS distance.

Travel_notes: 200m on trail
Location_desc: Point located at spot on trail, where water trickles down over moss covered rocks; abundant ferns on trail below.  Rocky to the west. GPS might say point is ~20m away at point, but follow features over GPS distance.

Travel_notes: Walk 200m on trail
Location_desc: Travel 16m from the end of bridge over unnamed creek.  Look for pile of cut logs on left; pt is a few meters beyond that. Follow features over GPS distance.

Travel_notes: Walk 200m on trail
Location_desc: On trail in indistinct forest.  Several large Western red cedar downslope  to east.

Travel_notes: Walk 200m on trail
Location_desc: Point located on trail just after (15m) cluster of huge Doug fir trees to west of trail (15-40m).  Look for 2 rotting snags to east and pile of logs to west of trail, and you will be at the point. Follow features over GPS distance.

Travel_notes: Walk 200m on trail.
Location_desc: Point located on trail at hollowed at log, with rotting snag behind it.  Look for 2 pillar snags east of trail 9 m before reaching point. Follow features over GPS distance.

Travel_notes: Walk 200 m on trail! :)
Location_desc: Point on trail, look for root ball/ cluster on east side of trail, and small rock wall along west side of trail 5 m beyond point. Follow features over GPS distance.

Travel_notes: Walk 200m on trail.
Location_desc: Point located on trail, indistinct forest.  Rotting snag just off trail to east.  Cluster of 5 snags is 12m beyond point on west side of trail.

Travel_notes: Walk 200m on trail ?!:)
Location_desc: Point located on trail, look for pyramid-shaped rock sticking up in trail (approx. 6 in tall)  just before a small series of root- formed steps in trail.  Root steps end at cut logs in picture.

Travel_notes: Walk 200m on trail.
Location_desc: Point on trail, indistinct location.  Look for rotting snag west of trail 12m before point.

Travel_notes: Walk 200 m on trail.  Watch for bridge over Olallie creek.
Location_desc: Along trail in indistinguishable Western hemlock mixed forest.  Cut logs to the north, small dirt covered foot bridge to the south (both along trail).  Ohanapecosh river heard to east but unable to see.

Travel_notes: Walk 200m on trail.
Location_desc: On trail next to downed tree over path. Follow features over GPS distance.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is on trail with a pond on the right, 15 meters before the wooden footbridge. It is at a large Pacific silver fir with a DBH of 40cm.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m down trail.
Location_desc: Along trail in indistinctive hemlock/Doug-fir  forest. Noticible hollowed out donut looking downed tree on west side of trail up small slope, next to a ~50dbh hemlock. On east side of trail is a large snag.

Travel_notes: Drive about 10 min from Ohanapecosh CG to Grove of the Patriarchs Trail, labeled Eastside Trail. Walk about 40 min morning speed on trail, crossing 2 major streams with bridges before TO. At trail intersection head straigh/left, do not cross suspension bridge to Grove of the Patriarchs. Look for 1 of the whopping 4 photos taken by Bob Wilkerson to find TO.
Location_desc: none

Travel_notes: First 40 m fairly flat, then it gets a lot steeper.  a lot of downed trees and debris to go over/ around
Location_desc: Point is in mature forest.  Just past a downed log perpendicular to the slope.  There is a lot of Devil's club downslope of point (and log). It is a few meters downslope of a huge (~150cm DBH) live cedar.

Travel_notes: Go up a steep slope with a lot of down trees.
Location_desc: Point is on a steep slope in open mature forest. Both directly up and downslope are several very large Doug-firs.

Travel_notes: start steep but after 40 m becomes flat terrain and open.  easy travel
Location_desc: Point is in mature open forest with a lot of downed trees. Point is at the same elevation of several massive Doug-firs W of point (including Doug-fir feature).

Travel_notes: the first 45 m are fairly open, but after that the travel gets alot slower as you enter dense sapling forest
Location_desc: Lots of western hemlock sapling, but not so thick.  you can see well around.  Lots of 2 m dbh western redcedar snags. Point is at uphill base of a 4.5m tall rotting snag. It is ~3m W of a seep filled with skunk cabbage and ferns. Root wad feature is right over it.

Reason_for_change: To avoid running into other transect
Travel_notes: Easy travel across slope initially, then a gradual uphill, leveling off as you near NW05.
Location_desc: Point is in an open area, filled mostly with beargrass and a few downed trees. It is ~12m NW of where terrain goes downhill. There is a downed tree ~2.5m to the N/NE.

Travel_notes: Very easy travel over slightly undulating terrain. Notice the seen from point root wad as you are approaching.
Location_desc: Point is ~1.5m N of a large downed tree (yes, there are a lot around, so that's not particularly helpful.). Very little understory right at point (just a little beargrass).

Travel_notes: Walk on ridge over undulating terrain. Extremely easy travel.
Location_desc: Point is right in the middle of ridge in open forest. No understory at all right at point.

Travel_notes: Easy slightly downhill. More downed trees as you approach point.
Location_desc: Near the ends of some downed trees 20m before the ridge drops harply down to the w/sw. No understory

Travel_notes: from TO, walk SW down road until you reach pulloff on the N side. pt 1 is across the road from pulloff
Location_desc: 3m south of road, in a downed Hemlock, just down small slope. Surrounded by ferns, devils club and vanilla leaf

Travel_notes: Point between 2m tall snag feature and downed tree of rootball feature
Location_desc: In Hemlock blow down area. surrounded by downed trees.  Road easily visible from point. Just uphill (~1.5m) of downed tree (of root ball).

Travel_notes: Road can be seen for much of travel. Travel through low shrubs/saplings and quite a few downed trees
Location_desc: In open, very mossy flat area. Road can be heard but not seen. Helpful to start with Doug-Fir feature and go from there.

Travel_notes: travel across mostly level terrain. Road can be seen for much of walk.
Location_desc: In small gully, 8m from bottom. Lots of downed trees and debris.

Travel_notes: In a small gully surrounded by small hemlocks and some vine maple. Travel down and up other side of gully and across level terrain, dropping down very slightly to point 5
Location_desc: In small gully surrounded by small hemlocks.  On top of a downed tree that goes across gully.

Travel_notes: Travel downhill through light shrub and a lot of downed trees.
Location_desc: Point is in a nice open area with a lot of moss. About 5m to the SE looks like a nice comfortable spot to take a nap. Very light salal right at point. Denser hemlock saplings to the S.

Travel_notes: Walk through many saplings and downed trees, crossing road at ~150m. Pretty easy travel.
Location_desc: Point is in between 2 large downed trees that are 4-5m apart where point is. There is vine maple overhead, as well as the branches of a ~45cm DBH hemlock (to the SE).

Travel_notes: Travel is pretty easy, over many downed trees and some light shrub. As you get close to point, you will notice shift into riparian habitat with lots of alders.
Location_desc: Point is ~2m SE of a small alder stand, with some Devil's club surrounding it. There are also several alders to the E of point. It looks like this area has flooded somewhat recently.

Travel_notes: Walk through small patches of devils club and small saplings until you reach the river. If the river is low can go to edge and walk to point or go through small hemlocks and alders
Location_desc: In small alder patch next to river and next to a small creek offshoot from river. Some hemlocks on N/NE edge. Across river to the edge of the tree line is about 103m.

Travel_notes: Head SW on road from Cougar Rock Campground, past Longmire. 100 M past TO there is a small gravel pullout on the right side big enough for one car.  TO is a 10 min drive from Cougar Rock CG.  NW arm was accidentally done at 320 instead of 315 degrees. Beware: HEWA/TOWA hybrids.
Location_desc: On road at a spot close enough to see the river

Travel_notes: Travel through Pacific silever fir stands, slightly downhill. Note: Bearing to point should have been 315 degrees for entire NW arm. Not sure if observer took correct bearing or 325 degrees - check map next visit.
Location_desc: Point on slight downhill slope, next to 2 down Silver fir (dbh 15 cm) on N endge of dense stand young Silver fir.

Travel_notes: Travel through yound dense stands, relativley flat, go around old pond, it is still very soggy.
Location_desc: Point next to Doug-fir root mass, 2 other fallen Doug-fir, and 2 Doug-fir, dbh 75 cm.  Point on N side of dense stand young Silver fir. 2012 updat: There are two root masses in the immediate area of point. The mass closest to pond, extending out of sapling grove is not the one next to point. Follow that downed tree (belonging to that root mass) to root mass #2, just in sapling grove. point is near that rootmass.

Travel_notes: Travel over small hills and through swampy wetlands.  Go along stream after leaving wetlands. Wetlands are easy to navigate around using downed logs.
Location_desc: Point in relatively flat area near stream, stream channel begins to cut deep in to gorgre right near point.  Mossy without many young stands. Viewed from point: two downed trees crossing over each other. Bottom one is supported on one end by the crook of two standing cedars. The top downed tree is broken at the place where they cross (see photo). 2018 - two crossed downed trees are decaying a lot and will probably not look the same when returned next.

Travel_notes: Follow stream down drainage, at bottom of valley veer away from stream and onto flat plateau.  Downhill all the way until very near the point, then slightly uphill.
Location_desc: Point in flat area, understory less dense than earlier in transect, many fallen trees, mossy floor, can still hear stream to W.

Travel_notes: travel downhill for first 100m. The land levels a little bit before declining again and then inclining. Climb hill for last ~ 40 m to point.
Location_desc: 30 m uphill from where land starts to rise- in small mossy opening.

Travel_notes: Travel uphill and then descend on a steep slope, navigating around many rocky cliffs. After passing the first set of cliffs, bear west to avoid the next few. Walk the mossy flat area until you rach a clearing on the slope covered in salal.
Location_desc: Point is located in salal patch with an open canopy. Steep slopes just below. Highway 123 can be heard below.

Reason_for_change: avoid cliffs in all other directions
Travel_notes: Point is more than 200m to ensure it is far enough away from NW05. Travel on the mossy plateau at a bearing of 180. At about 150m, you will side hill the rest of the way. Travel is easy.
Location_desc: Point located on a small knoll on the hillside, surrounded by salal and mixed conifer. Point is directly on a ~15cm dbh downed hemlock that was attached to the hemlock w/ messy branching.

Travel_notes: Travel is through moderately thick mature forest with windfall. Go up small knoll and point is just beyond the crest.
Location_desc: The point is in shrubby section of mixed conifer woods. Laughingwater Ck. can be heard clearly just downhill. Marker clearly visible from approach.

Travel_notes: Travel to point is over difficult terrain. Salal and conifer thicket understory never gets too thick, but the slope gets steep. From 90-130m you cross Laughingwater Ck. on bearing--nothing a little rock-hopping and waterproof boots can't overcome. After the creek, ascend a steep bank, crossing a few large deadfalls, which could be tricky to navigate.
Location_desc: The point is on flat ground about 30m above Laughingwater Ck. large trees nearby and fairly open canopy. Salal and huckleberry understory.

Travel_notes: Travel is mostly flat and not very difficult, though zero-ing in on the point may be tricky due to none-too-conspicuous features. look for a group of 3 large, tall hemlocks on bearing, sticking up past canopy.
Location_desc: This point may be difficult to find, as it is located in an undifferentiated, scrubby mixed conifer forest. Point is next to 3 fairly tall hemlocks, which can be seen on the approach.

Travel_notes: Travel is mostly flat and easy through open, mature forest. There is a small brook  to cross (easily hopped over), one of the nicest old-growth groves in the park to hike through, and a short uphill just prior to point.
Location_desc: The point is on a broad bench in the hillside--immediately surrounding point is flat, but steeper slope on all sides. Opening in canopy above from recent large Doug-fir blowdown (see features). Ground cover is moss, heath and OR grape. To the east, a small creek is audible.

Travel_notes: Difficult travel to point SE05. Proceed uphill from SE04 until you come to steep, mossy banked brook. I found it easy to flag my location, shoot a bearing, and walk upstream 40m to just above small waterfall, where the stream is more easily crossed. Once across and back on the bearing, continue 70m uphill through thick yew understory.
Location_desc: Point is on steep hill with sapling deadfalls. Groundcover: huckleberries, salal, OR grape, beargrass, moss, bunchberry. Just downhill is thicker understory and wide open canopy. Can hear brook approximately 35m away.

Travel_notes: Travel is easy to SE06. Climb uphill from SE 05 through undifferentiated Doug-fir and hemlock forest, with very little undergrowth. Point is only 25m beyond brook.
Location_desc: Point is on hill, just south of a feeder brook for Laughingwater Ck. (as shown on the map). 10m south of the point is a dry gully and small ridge. Very little understory except OR grape and saplings. Point is directly beside old, thoroughly decomposed pit and mound (from where a rootball pulled up soil).

Travel_notes: SE arm contains very steep slopes and creek crossings that are slippery. Recommend avoiding this transect if rain has occurred recently. 2018- camped at Ohana and hiked in. It was about a 45 minute hike.
Location_desc: TO is on trail next to pile of cut Pacific silver fir.  There is a gradual left hand bend in trail at TO. We cross-country camped very near the TO in the flats close to pond on the NW arm. The SE arm has some tough travel, but also some beautiful forest scenery--the more intrepid traveller should take this arm.

Travel_notes: Pace 110 m  on trail.
Location_desc: Point on trail on rock.

Travel_notes: Travel 210 m on trail.
Location_desc: Point on trial in small, sparse patch Subalpine fir, point is 25 m beyond the beginning of the Subalpine fir patch

Travel_notes: Travel 120m on trail until you reach the lookout.  From the backside of the lookout pace 80 m N across rock and along ridgeline.
Location_desc: Point is 80 m. N of the lookout on rocks.  It is N of a small patch Subalpine fir and an outhouse.

Travel_notes: Travel 200 m across meadow and rock.  Follow ridge.
Location_desc: Point in open meadow on the E side of a Subalpine fir stand.  This is the only large Subalpine fir stand on bearing and between NN04 and NN05 (at NN05 a more uniform forest edge begins).

Travel_notes: travel N across open meadow, dropping off the crest of the ridge and heading into Subalpine fir forest.  Point is just beyond the forest edge.
Location_desc: Point is in a stand of Subalpine fir next to two Subalpine fir in the middle of a 15 m. clearing.

Travel_notes: Hop back up on the ridge above trees and follow to high point on the end of the ridge. Point is in open meadow on east side of ridge, just before slope gets very steep.
Location_desc: Point is in open meadow on the east side of the ridge that you've been travelling on. Few trees in immediate area, but one subalpine fir stands alone right next to point.

Travel_notes: Travel is gradual descent for 100m on trail. Patchy, mat-forming krummholz on slope below trail.
Location_desc: Point is on trail beside rockwall (uphill).

Travel_notes: Travel is on trail that traverses contour below ridge. Rockwall tapers out around 90m. You are approaching point when you come to 3 very conspicuous rock outcrops--bedrock ribs--that run downhill.
Location_desc: Point is on trail where a large grey bedrock rib comes down slope (can't be seen in image). Downhill and just ahead are 3 beautiful black-rock fins rising out of hillside like teeth. point is in between dog-sized boulder and sub-alpine fir krummholz cushion (see image).

Travel_notes: Travel is uphill 200m on trail.
Location_desc: Point is in trail where some grey blocky bedrock is exposed uphill from trail (see image).

Travel_notes: Travel is 200m on trail. Continue upward traverse for 85m, where the tril curves left over the shoulder of a ridge runnning west toward subsidiary peak. Go downhill from here to point SS04.
Location_desc: Point is on trail, just below a 9m wide rock slide that appears to reach all the way to the ridge. Use features and GPS.

Travel_notes: Travel is a 200m downhill traverse toward lake.
Location_desc: Point is on trail. Just before point downhill is rocky scree. Doownhill at point is subalpine-fir krummholz patch. Use GPS--not great features.

Travel_notes: Travel is 200m downhill on trail through patchy krummholz.
Location_desc: Point is on trail where subalppine fir krummholz patches give way to open sandy meadows.

Travel_notes: Travel off-trail on SW bearing, down into gravelly, treeless basin (many AMPIs). Cross a spring and a gully and stop on the rise before 3rd gully. 225deg azimuth--line up with Steamboat Prow from SS06 and sight travel features.
Location_desc: Point is on grassy/forb-y rise between two westward-running gullies. Look for orange marker.

Travel_notes: Drop down green hillside to a dry wash which is shallow and rocky. Cross this and traverse up across large gravel bar with little vegetation and possible snow. Point is just below where azimuth crests hillside
Location_desc: Point is on what appears to be a large, broad moraine--very gravelly. Point is uphill from a perennial srping-fed brook on gravel hillside. Not much vegetation, but some conspicuous white heather uphill.

Travel_notes: Travel over rocky ground. Then becoming grassy and meadow again. Point on other side of hillside.
Location_desc: Point on hillside, very little distinguishing features. Look for closest Krummholz patches to the N and SW of point

Travel_notes: Head on azimuth towards the large boulder in front of the large patch of fir.
Location_desc: Few distinct features. Large boulder is best way to find the point. Point just before going into fir stand.

Travel_notes: Head at a N azimuth, up and over the hill. Drop down next to an obvious Kumholtz patch.
Location_desc: Point located just uphill from small drainage and just below a small Kumholtz patch.

Travel_notes: Try to survey when it is not too windy.
Location_desc: TO on a rocky, sparsly vegetated slope directly downlsope from a 10 m tall, 5 m wide patch of heather and wildflowers and S of a patch Subalpine fir just up trail. We camped at Sunrise campground. 1.75mile / 45min walk in morning.

Travel_notes: Because of trail switchback, point had to be located 561m along trail from T.O.  Best way is to start from point on trail closest to WW01, and proceed 200m on trail.
Location_desc: Point is located on trail between a large Western hemlock on uphill side and a tiny Pacific silver fir on both sides of trail.  It is just a few meters past a large fallen Doug-fir with the middle sawed out where it crossed the path.  Small creek just beyond point.

Travel_notes: Follow trail northerly for 200m.  Look for sawed-off nurse log (conspicuous feature #1).  If trail is snowed over, follow carefully, and/or instinctively.
Location_desc: Point is on trail 200m N of NN01 where a 90cm dbh nurse log is sawed off at trail edge.

Travel_notes: Proceed west up moderately steep slope, consistently uphill except at drainages and creeks.
Location_desc: Point is standing atop a small, angled boulder (0.5m at highest) with some vaccinium growing from it, on a fair slope with little undergrowth, under dense hemlock canopy.

Travel_notes: Head west over small creek where slope flattens out for about 15m.  Route is all uphill from there.
Location_desc: Located on hemlock-shaded slope w/ SE aspect.  Point is at edge of area w/ little undergrowth - hemlock saplings fill in to the north and east, and to the south there is some vine maple. Immediately next to a low spreading yew tree and a few small Pacific silver fir saplings.

Reason_for_change: To give space to western arm of transect
Travel_notes: Crest first hill and then start riding the slopeside.  Route interspersed with clifflets to climb and conifer stands to marvel at.
Location_desc: On moderate wooded slope w/ SW aspect, with partially obstructed views of Double Peak and the Cowlitz Chimneys of Mt. Rainier.  Between a small mossy boulder and a >122cm dbh Doug-fir & hemlock fused at base.

Reason_for_change: To give space to WW arm
Travel_notes: Head north past rocky outcroppings up a "two-step" hill before dropping onto a flat from which the final slope rises at 125m.  Look for where a drainage cuts into this slope and follow it up.
Location_desc: Point is in drainage crease between moderate slopes, in (presumably open - covered in snow at time of establishment) forest of lovely Abies.

Travel_notes: Continue to walk up drainage, but eventually you will go a little to the E. Also, veg in drainage will be very wet if it has rained recently.
Location_desc: Point is on top of a large boulder with cedar and fir saplings growing from it. It is the highest point within 50m.

Travel_notes: Rt. 123 to N to Owyhigh Lakes Trail, to Eastside Trail.  Camp at Deer Creek backcountry site.  Point is on Eastside Trail, 16 m S of dogleg turn. Allow plenty of time to get from TO to NN01- it is >500m away on trail. About an 18-minute walk from Owyhigh Lakes Trailhead off Hwy 123. Trailhead is about 15 minutes from Ohanapecosh Campground.
Location_desc: On Eastside Trail, 10 m E. to creek bluff, epic waterfall visible.  Mature Doug-fir/Western hemlock woods with Alaska yellow cedar and Pacific silver fir, sapling understory.

Travel_notes: Walk up trail until switchback, then walk ~100m up trail beyond that. Point is ~3m below trail- look for large western hemlock on uphill side of trail.
Location_desc: Just below trail.  Mixed age Doug-fir/Western hemlock woods with mix of saplings, pole sized trees and 80 cm Western hemlock.  Pacific silver fir, sparse vine maple and Vaccinium in understory.

Travel_notes: Travel upslope, corssing trail after 5 m.  Continue along side of slope with SE aspect, crossing tiny stream at 97 m.  Point is at the W edge of a relatively flat area with notably open understory.
Location_desc: On the W edge of an open area. There is a silver fir sapling whose branches extend to point from downhill.

Travel_notes: Travel at 270 degrees along side of slope - aspect will gradually change from S, to W, to WSW.  Drop down from steep 3 m high rock face around 90 m and enter thick brush.  Cross first channel of stream 10 m before reaching stream with boulder and point.
Location_desc: 1 m E of small creek.  2 x 2 x 3 m mossy boulder on W edge of creek.  Sparse yew brush on both sides of creek in mixed age Mixed conifer woods.  If you miss the point, run up and down the creek until you find the boulder.
Location_notes: WW03 was retired because it was too close to a point on an annual transect (4012).

Travel_notes: Follow creek up slope at 360 degrees.  Travel through mossy Western hemlock/Western redcedar woods in or along the W. side of creek bed.  Woods open up with less Western redcedar at 100m.  Continue up W. side of creek.  Bear NE for 15 m at 190 m, crossing creek bed, to correct error in route.
Location_desc: Next to > 122 cm DBH Western hemlock in pole sized Doug-fir, with yew brush 5 m N.  Bare log at base of lrage Western hemlock points down dry stream bed.  Some exposed rocks and moss in area of creek bed.

Travel_notes: Travel up slope through yew brush.  Enter small clearing with fir saplings at 60 m.  Many > 122 cm DBH Doug-fir slowly transition into 81-122 cm DBH DFWH woods with thicker understory of saplings.
Location_desc: On slope in DFWH woods with sapling understory.  Just below nurse stump - no obvious defining features.
Location_notes: This point was retired because it was too close to the other arm. A new point (WW05a) was added, going in a direction away from NN arm.

Reason_for_change: original point was 50m from a point on the other arm
Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Next to stream. Relatively open woods. Branches from a ~90cm DBH hemlock extend overhead to point.

Travel_notes: Continue NW. Follow contour/side-slope to point.
Location_desc: Next to enormous hemlock that is dead, standing, with no crown. It is in between two similarly-sized doug-firs. There is an opening in the canopy.

Travel_notes: Walk uphill through fairly open forest with some saplings and sparse shrub. Not difficult.
Location_desc: Point is on an elk trail (which obviously might not exisit next visit...). There is a small rise ~1m to the E, where a ~55cm DBH silver fir and a smaller hemlock are growing.

Travel_notes: Walk uphill through some saplings and sparse shrub- pretty easy travel. Also, there are lots of elk trails in the area.
Location_desc: Point is surrounded by a bunch of silver fir saplings. It is ~11m NE of dropoff down to creek.

Travel_notes: Go 100m NE across road, and into the woods, where shortly you will find point NE01.  Look for a deciduous thicket.
Location_desc: In 5x15m clearing in canopy, where a thick clump of slide alder has taken hold.

Travel_notes: Head NE through Mixed conifer and vaccinium, crossing several streams before the one at which point is located.
Location_desc: In Mixed conifer woodlands on gentle slope, at a small clearing in canopy, where two small streams converge.  Point is right on western edge of this drainage.

Travel_notes: Go NE 200m through Mixed conifer forest, more or less following the drainage of the small creek here.  Once you recross stream, look for a little grove of cedars.
Location_desc: On forested, moderate slope, in a tight grove of 7 Alaska yellow cedar, next to a narrow drainage.

Travel_notes: Head uphill through clumpy forest with fairly dense canopy.  As you crest first hill a slope cuts down from the right, the side of which you will ride until a broad canopy opening.
Location_desc: Point on sloped clearing loosely surrounded by Alaska yellow cedar, Pacific silver fir, and Subalpine fir, bounded by a small stream to the north.  There are several bent-over saplings in clearing.  Not much in the way of conspicuous features.

Travel_notes: Go steady NE, across a small stream and up a talus slope to a road crossing.  On the other side, carefully climb up eroded slope (skirting around to right makes it easier) and then through thick azalea and shrubs to 2nd road crossing.  Point is on other side.
Location_desc: On berm looking down on road with young Subalpine fir, Rainier behind you, and the Tattoosh range below.

Travel_notes: Continue NE into open "Sewage disposal" area, across some twisting melt creeks and up slope.
Location_desc: Point in a little grove of Subalpine fir just short of the road.  There is a view of the sewage disposal area down below to the SW and the Tattoosh Range beyond that.

Reason_for_change: To avoid trajectory towards Paradise Park transect
Travel_notes: Head N into a flat clearing and beyond into shrubby woods.  Soon you will be following the contour of the slope through woody vaccinium and mountain-ash (conspiring to make you slip).  Cross over a few seasonal drainages and through sparse forest.
Location_desc: Point on gentle slope leading down from road in dense vaccinium and mountain-ash among scattered Subalpine fir and Mtn. hemlock.  Just beyond (10m) to the north there is a seepy snowmelt stream.

Travel_notes: Cross creek (you may need to go up the creek a bit to find a safe crossing) and continue up a forested slope to point on a paved trail.
Location_desc: The point is on a paved trail surrounded by mixed fir forest and meadows. The point is 10m short of the 200m distance in order to reduce meadow impact in a high visitation area. Beautiful Spot!

Travel_notes: Travel 100m at 225 degrees from TO.
Location_desc: Point is on S edge of open, rocky path with beargrass and Vaccinium.  Three downed trees lay accross open area to NE.  Immediately upslope from the point a clump of Alaska yellow cedar hides view of the rest of the open patch.

Travel_notes: May be slightly less than 200m at 225 degrees.  Head down slope through thick Red alder for 35m.  Continue down slope through woods, reaching drainage valley at 80m.  Cross drainage and over its far lip.  Quickly head up another small rise, emerging onto the rock promentory, 10m shy of point SW02.
Location_desc: On lower terrace just past high point of open rock knob.  Rainier visible at 360 degrees.  Stunted Mixed conifer surrounds rock with beargrass, kinnickinick, moss and lichen.

Travel_notes: 12m to edge of rock face.  Climb carefully down, or skirt around, 60m sheer rock face.  Enter woods at base of rock face, reaching small 5m high rock face in woods at 28m.  Cross creek on log directly above waterfall at 20m.  Drop under log on other side of stream channel and traverse side of drainage thick with shrubs.  Exit drainage and travel 25m in woods to point.
Location_desc: Point is on downed Alaska yellow cedar among thick Western hemlock, Alaska yellow cedar and Pacific silver fir saplings in Doug-fir/Western hemlock woods.  Small (10x15m) opening to NW.  Overall, thick and non-descript woods.  Creek audible 25m NE.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m at 225 degrees.  Cross 4m wide drainage at 50m and enter small clearingwith downed logs and false azalea at 75m.  Continue 125m to point.  Look out for >122 cm Doug-fir - it stands out in the woods.
Location_desc: On gentle S facing slope among a few massive Doug-fir and midsized Pacific silver fir, Alaska yellow cedar, Western hemlock.  Point is on bare, mossy downed log next to big stump described in features.  You can't miss the big Doug-fir.  It has a pole sized Alaska yellow cedar growing up against its W side.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m at 225 degrees along side slope through Doug-fir/western hemlock woods with Pacific silver fir and Alaska yellow cedar.  Cross three brooks, described in features.  Point is at the fourth brook.
Location_desc: On N edge of small stream channel.  Stream is muddy with green shrubs and forbs above point and enters steeper N/S drainage 10m below point.

Travel_notes: Follow stream downslope 10m into drainage.  Cross drainage and continue along side slope in Doug-fir/western hemlock woods with lots of Alaska yellow cedar.  Cross another drainage at 195m.  Woods becomes thick just before this crossing and opens up after.  Slope also changes after crossing to a mellower grade.
Location_desc: 8m from end of 40m long downed Western hemlock, in Doug-fir/western hemlock woods with Pacific silver fir and Alaska yellow cedar.  Downed Western hemlock shares tip-up root mound with another smaller Western hemlock that crosses its bole near the base.  Small brook 30m ahead is audible, as well as Paradise River downslope.

Travel_notes: 190m from SW06 at 225 degrees.  Travel along S-facing slope through dim pole-sized Doug-fir/western hemlocks with lots of Alaska yellow cedars.  Cross small creek at 28m abd exit dim woods in belt of thick saplings at 120m.  Point is in open woods about 50m after saplings.
Location_desc: SW07 is on a S-facing slope in 53-81cm DBH Doug-fir/western hemlock woods, with smaller Alaska yellow cedar and Pacific silver fir mixed in.    The point is on a 1x1x1m rock that is mostly covered with soil, among Western hemlock, Alaska yellow cedar, and Pacific silver fir saplings in otherwise open woods.

Travel_notes: Head down slope and cross boggy area.
Location_desc: Point is west of bog, downslope of 2 huge snags.

Travel_notes: Drive east on the Longmire-Paradise Road.  After crossing the Nisqually River, follow L hairpin bend, then R hairpin bend.  Pulloff on wide shoulder after "Tire chains req'd on all vehicles" sign. Camped at Snow Lake backcountry site. ~20 min walk from camp to trailhead. Another 10 minutes to drive to the TO. Beautiful campsite. Kind of buggy, but probably less annoying than Cougar Rock in late July. SW arm: Lots of river noise on transect.  GPS shows aerial distance between SW02-SW03 and SW06-SW07 as less than 200m and SW04-SW05 as greater than 200m.  It may just be GPS error, but worth noting for future navigators. SW arm: Sparse birds, partly due to reduced detection areas from creek noise.  An easy transect with suprisingly varied terrain.  Rock outcrop at SW02 has a great view of the Tattoosh range.  NE arm: A fairly straightfoward transect.  The climb between 05 and 06 is a little heinous.  If putting in new poinrt, be careful of Dead Horse Creek, or skip that direction altogether - it seems treacherous if heavy with melt but still covered in snow.
Location_desc: Point is just on S side of fog line on S side of road, on a straightaway between Nisqually River and turnoff for Paradise.  There is a wide shoulder and a grassy bank leading down into Mixed conifer woods.

Travel_notes: Proceed 100m east on trail from transect origin.
Location_desc: Point on trail with mostly open view to the south.  There is abundant shrubby cedar growing on upslope edge, and scatter mixed conifer downhill.

Travel_notes: Approximately 220m on trail to east.
Location_desc: Point on trail on side of Aurora Peak's meadowed (or snowy) slopes.  There is a stand of trees below and exposed rock faces above.

Travel_notes: Approximately 265m on trail - through trail is lost in snow, so it could be more or less.  Follow trail E and then S across meadows until a tight passage between tree islands.
Location_desc: On trail where trail makes a left turn towards St. Andrew's Lake.  It is tightly bound between two Mtn. hemlock/Subalpine fir tree islands.

Travel_notes: Undetermined number of meters as trail was lost in snow at time of establishment.
Location_desc: Point on trail above St. Andrew's Lake.

Travel_notes: Undetermined number of meters down trail (snowed out at time of establishment).
Location_desc: On trail following bluff ot the west.  There is a social trail a few meters long leading to a vista spot, and point is right before where it cuts off.

Travel_notes: Proceed 230m down trail mostly following the western ridgeline, until L bend where point is.
Location_desc: Point on trail in middle of gradual bend from SW-erly to E-erly, among Subalpine fir and thick heather / vaccinium / xerophylla understory.  No conspicuous features, but you could pace back the 50m from the creek ahead on trail.

Travel_notes: 240m down trail, first following ridgeline and then bearing L to cross a tributary to St. Andrew's Creek, and traversing a meadowed slope.
Location_desc: Point on trail riding the side of alpine slope, where an arm of the rock face above reaches down to touch trail.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On trail next to some big rocks. Subalpine firs on east side of trail. Mountain hemlocks on west side of trail.

Travel_notes: Follow trail over little ridge/hump.
Location_desc: Trail was covered with snow. Flat spot on hump.

Travel_notes: Go straight down trail for about 200m.
Location_desc: Point is located where two parallel trails converge to avoid lonely little subalpine fir.

Travel_notes: Heading N on the Wonderland Trail, the TO is 50m before the point at which the woods open up into Klapatche Park.  Camping is available at K. Park backcountry camp.  If you can arrange your points to hike the section of the W.T. between Little Tahoma Ck. Tr. and South Puyallup camp, do it!  The traverse around the point of Emerald ridge is so beautiful! Beautiful area. Truly, but try to arrive once the snow is melted.
Location_desc: On S facing slope in Subalpine fir woods with many snags and gnarled trees covered in lichen.  Straight section of trail opens in Klapatche park 50m W.  Andrew ridgeline visible to E, forming W edge of drainage bowl.

Travel_notes: Trail entirely obscured by snow.  I paced 100m from TO and corrected to be on the trail via GPS.  May be close enough to the trail, or may need reestablishment.
Location_desc: On falt grading into gentle N slope of Aurora Lake basin.  Open meadow (currently snow covered) with sparse, stunted Subalpine fir.

Travel_notes: Follow trail until 200m from WW01.
Location_desc: On gentle N-facing slope of Aurora Lake basin among sparse, stunted Subalpine fir and Mtn. hemlock.

Travel_notes: Dut to curve of trail, WW03 must be located accross the lake basin in order to be 200m from WW02.
Location_desc: Point on trail on across lake from WW02. Nestled in a gap among some trees. 2019: Coordinates changed to put the point on the trail (no snow year).

Travel_notes: Trail mostly covered in snow.  Navigation will have to be based on features and GPS.  Point is just before what may be the first in a series of switchbacks after trail follows drainage out of Aurora Lake basin.  I bushwhacked down snowed over slope until I located and open section of trail, by distance in GPS shows approximately 200m.
Location_desc: Point is 8m past a sharp switchback where the trail goes from E to W. Point is just before a patch of mature trees.

Travel_notes: Almost all of Wonderland Trail is currently snow covered.  The point is on an open section of trail more than 200 aerial meters from WW04.  Next surveyor will have to rely on features and GPS to locate point.
Location_desc: On Wonderland Trail in Mixed conifer woods, in 140m gently curving stretch between two switchbacks (70m above and 65m below).  Narrow rock chute is visible 20m down trail and rocky cliffs can be seen upslope through trees.

Travel_notes: Pace 270m down trail from WW05.
Location_desc: Point on trail next to a gnarled stump found on the downslope side of the trail.

Travel_notes: Continue down a straight section of the trail crossing a small creek just before the point.
Location_desc: Point is directly next to a large flat rock in the middle of the trail. The point is located on the edge of a meadow next to a stand of young firs.

Travel_notes: Continue down the trail for approximately 250m, heading into older growth conifer forest on the ridge. The point is in the forest 10m before crossing back over the highpoint of the ridge (heading West)
Location_desc: Point is located directly next to a large decaying red log, 10m before the trail crests the ridge and goes out of sight.

Travel_notes: Use trail to get to the correct northing. Go off-trail about 40 m W to point. Point where you go off-trail is at a rocky stream bed crossing trail about 40 m from the TO.
Location_desc: Point is in small clearing amongst downed trees full of ferns. Directly to the W of the point is a long downed hemlock with a large root wad and a "window" through the roots. Point is somewhat boxed in by fallen logs.

Travel_notes: Go NW over many downed trees.
Location_desc: Point is on slope, in midst of fallen trees and small hemlock saplings, on W side of tangle of branches from downed trees. There is one particularly large Doug-fir N of point 10m behind a short snag with a hemlock growing out of it.

Travel_notes: Travel is similar from NW01 to NW02 as NW02 to NW03. Less slope. There is a small creek that you may come across. You can follow this to the NW because the point is near this stream.
Location_desc: Point is near a large grove of Western hemlock saplings, near bottom of steep slope to the S. A small creek runs just south of the point. Point is just past a log over creek.

Travel_notes: Cross small creek about halfway to point. There is a log bridge just upstream from where I crossed. Travel gets much easier nearing point.
Location_desc: Point is about 15 m N of the creek. Point it within a triangle of 3 huge Doug-firs. Point is on relatively flat area with very old, rotten logs almost buried under ground nearby.

Travel_notes: Slow travel. Walk on huge downed Doug-fir point NW04 is on until the end, then make your way over many downed trees- avoid huge boulders.
Location_desc: Point is in a mess of downed trees. It is on a huge downed Doug-fir (same fir on uphill side of cedar). There is a downed tree suspended in air (from the W) that extends almost to point. The second cedar (~1m away from cedar feature) is visible as you are approaching, but not at the point itself.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point along wide portion of trail in gentle upslope. Large, moss-covered fallen trees downhill of the trail.

Travel_notes: travel fairly steep uphill, some switchbacks.
Location_desc: Point on trail just before rocky portion of trail begins. About 20 m from the Ranger Falls entrance.

Travel_notes: Travel along steep trail with many switchbacks. Because of the numerous switchbacks, trail distance to SE04 is around 500m or so, as the crow flies, ~200m.
Location_desc: Point on trail just after a rocky switchback. Point just after the last wooden "step," on a small patch of bare trail surrounded by rocks and a few roots. Lots of hemlocks, some large Doug-firs, and a few cedars.

Travel_notes: Travel steep along trail
Location_desc: Point is on trail with a series of rocks and wooden slabs set into the uphill to act as steps and to prevent erosion. A long wooden one of these is set into trail at point. Sparse understory in forest, tons of downed trees.

Travel_notes: Be careful crossing primitive bridge- can be slippery when wet.
Location_desc: Point is along trail ~30 m past bridge. Look for features. Lots of Pacific silver firs and Doug-firs.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is about 15m past "End of maintained trail" sign at end of footpath by lake shore. Across the lake, many rock faces visible on mountains.

Travel_notes: Continue along lake trail, headed SE until it makes sense to cut up steep slope.
Location_desc: Point on slope with little understory. Mostly young Pacific silver firs. Point on stretch of slope with mossy rocks and downed trees.

Travel_notes: Continue up steep slope with many downed trees. If you hit a small stream you've gone too far. Stream is ~30m SW of point.
Location_desc: Point is on slope with 3 rotten logs .5m away to north and large mossy rocks to the south. Many baby hemlocks surround point. Very little understory.

Travel_notes: Camp at NPS housing along Carbon River Rd. (just outside of park boundary), in field if you can. 15-minute drive from there to the ranger station. From there, you can drive down gated road until the overflow parking lot (~1 mile in). From there, it's about a 2-mile walk to trailhead and about 0.9 miles more to TO. Be careful on NW arm- travel is slow and challenging, requiring balance, acrobatics, upper body strength, and an acceptance of slow speed.
Location_desc: TO along Green Lake Trail before Ranger Falls. Point along wooden slab set perpendicular to trail that acts as a footbridge and erosion control over tiny drain. Short snag on S side of trail about 4.5 m S of point. On level part of trail just before rocky portion. There is a decaying snag between Doug-fir feature and trail.

Travel_notes: Pace 120m from TO on S shoulder of Rt. 123.  Point is where Eastside Trail S side of Road.
Location_desc: Point is exactly where Eastside Trail crosses S side of Rt. 123.

Travel_notes: Pace 200m on S shoulder of Rt. 123.  Pass mile marker 16 and large S side pulloff soon after NW01.
Location_desc: On S shoulder of Rt. 123 in gradual NW bend.  Mixed conifer woods both sides of road.

Travel_notes: Pace 200m West on Rt. 123.
Location_desc: On S shoulder of Rt. 123, 18m before creek (name unknown) opposite open dirt slope.  Medium age Pacific silver fir woods on both sides of road.

Travel_notes: Leave road on 225 degree bearing.  At this point, the bearing runs you almost parallel to the road until is curves N.  Cross creek at 12m, or skirt it if it is too wide.  Climb steep W slope of creek drainage, reaching top at 93m.  Run along side slope, with road coming in and out of view, until you reach the end of the ridge at 150m.  Travel over several rolling rises until you reach point at 200m. 2013: I walked up road until as close as possible to point then cut in perpendicular to road.
Location_desc: Point is ca. 20m from opening in woods for wet creek area, among medium to very large Pacific silver fir and Mtn. hemlock.  Point is at 1.5m tall, broken off Pacific silver fir, bole on ground leads to stump described in features.  Forgot to write down bearings for features.  Next worker should collect them.

Travel_notes: 200m at 225 degrees: Cross brief, relatively open area.  Enter woods and begin uphill.  Pass distinctive 110 cm DBH Doug-fir with burls and hole at base on upslope side at 70m (see picture).  Continute along side slope, crossing E flowing creek at 97m.  Continue through woods, which open subtly 15m before point.
Location_desc: Point is in drainage that leads down from between the two major knobs of ridgeline, on N edge of 20x35m clearing in drainage.  Mossy rock wall bounds drainage on N side and Pacific silver fir woods thicken to W and E.  OPen shrub slope is over rise to S - not visible from point, but birds from habitat (Hummers) are audible.

Travel_notes: Travel 220m at 225 degrees:  Head up slope, entering Subalpine fir forest patch at 35m and exiting soon after into thick white azalea, Vaccinium and Sorbus with sparse Subalpine fir.  There are gametrails that make an easier go fo the shrub slope if you shoot an azimuth to its far edge to stay on course.  Shrub slope ends at 148m in Subalpine fir stand.  Cross well defined game trail at 166m and exit Subalpine onto open rocky slope at 177m.  Dramatically "S" surved Mtn. hemlock visible 20m S at this point.  Continue 43 m along steep rocky side slope to point.
Location_desc: On steep, open, rocky ridge with white azalea, Vaccinium and sparse Subalpine fir and Mtn. hemlock.  Just 4m shy of ridgetop woods.  Switchbacks of Rt. 410 up to Chinook Pass clearly visible to NE.  Thick, tall Subalpine fir/Mtn. hemlock stand downslope before open meadow drainage coming down from between two main knobs of ridgeline.

Travel_notes: Take a few steps up the ridge into the woods.  Head gently uphill as woods thickens.  Reach edge of woods and small lake at 78m.  Continue around lake, up small rise and into shallow drainage.  Stop 40m from steep S slope down ridge.
Location_desc: On gentle N slope of shallow drainage leaving top of ridge.  40m from beginning of steep SW slope into Boundary Ck. drainage.  In open meadow with islands of Subalpine fir, next to 5m tall Subalpine fir with crook in last 0.5m of leader (see photo).

Travel_notes: Head down a super fun (steep) slope with an awesome view!! Disregard bearing and take safest route. I stayed NW and found safe travel.
Location_desc: On a steep slope next to dirt slope with a few rocks, very open with a good view. Very birdy!

Travel_notes: Walk 100m down W shoulder of road.
Location_desc: On west shoulder of road, 100m from TO.  On opposite side, an eroded bank to the N eases to nothing where a creek goes under road among small Alaska yellow cedar.

Travel_notes: Cross road, climb eroded bank, quickly getting into shrubby Alaska yellow cedar & azalea as you ride the slope of a drainage.  Soon, however, you will come up onto a densely canopied forest of massive mixed conifers.  Route will angle into a broad drainage, where point awaits on an island of fir trees.
Location_desc: Point on tree island in middle of a broad, mellow drainage (could be dry - snowed in at time of establishment).  There are several >75cm dbh Pacific silver firs and many smaller trees beneath them, with open canopy surrounding on all sides.

Travel_notes: A straightforward tramp through classic fir forest.  There is one major creek crossing, but otherwise route is a steady uphill.
Location_desc: Point in fir/hemlock forest between melt-streams.  There is a small clearing to the west but no conspicuous features.

Travel_notes: Head uphill through fairly dense, old Mixed conifer forest.  At 100m, you will hit a rock face - skirt around it to the left, then correct your bearing up a talus slope to the road.  Once you cross, climb over a hillock of boulders and loose talus, on the other side of which is a retaining wall for the creek.
Location_desc: Point straddles a low retaining wall that guides Chinook Creek into a culvert.  It is right where this wall ends as the forest floor inclines to the east.

Travel_notes: Go 200m NE, uphill along creek before crossing it on easy stepping stones, and then up to road grade, across into Mixed conifer forest with increasingly thick vaccinium, serviceberry, and mountain-ash understory.
Location_desc: Set on the side of a vaccinium- and serviceberry-covered slope, with occasional boulders and patchy Subalpine fir that dominate immediately upslope and in the drainage below.  A tapered, silver snag leads out over the slope, and Mt. Rainier is visible through the trees.

Travel_notes: Crest the blueberry hill you're on and travel across a flat, patchy wooded area, crossing a few small melt-streams, then up steeper slope to road grade.
Location_desc: Point on rock wall bordering the southern edge of Rt. 410 around the curve.  The stone facade has crumbled away, revealing the concrete and steel core.  Chinook Crk. runs out of culvert about 20m to the SE.

Travel_notes: Cross road, Tipsoo Lake parking lot, and cross trail onto hillside above lake.  There is a small rocky outcropping about 10m upslope from point.
Location_desc: Point on side of meadowed slope above Tipsoo Lake.

Travel_notes: Gingerly tread the meadowed slope up towards the line of trees to the NE, cross a small stream and proceed under canopy for the next 105m until you emerge again, cross meadow to where trail cuts through line of trees.
Location_desc: Point is where transect bearing intersects trail that runs up out of meadow to SW btwn a line of Mtn. hemlock and Subalpine fir.  It is about 20m short of sign pointing out Naches Loop and Pacific Crest Trail, and beyond that, a footbridge over highway (and out of the park).

Travel_notes: 20 minute drive up Rt. 123 from Ohanapecosh Campground.  Park in large S side gravel pulloff just before mile marker 16 and walk back to narrow S side pulloff where TO is located. 2013: 20 minute drive from White River Campground. SS arm: A fairly direct shot from Cayuse to Chinook Pass.
Location_desc: On S shoulder of Rt. 123 at midpoint of narrow (5m wide) gravel pulloff above creek.  Medium age Mixed conifer woods on both sides of road.  Large dirt and rock slope to SE above road.

Travel_notes: Pace 100m down trail to junction.
Location_desc: Point is at intersection of Wonderland Trail with trail leading W out of park.  It is on the Wonderland Trail oppposite the S corner of the open dirt and stone triangle at the trail junction, in open ridgetop forest of mixed conifers with thick beargrass understory.

Travel_notes: Pace 423m on trail.  Make one switchback at 175m.  Follow 10m long, mossy log on downslope side of trail from 17 to 7 m before point.
Location_desc: On trail in thick woods - medium Western hemlock with thick pole-sized and sapling Pacific silver firs and Western hemlocks.  Next to 4m tall bare snag, with rutted curve at rock in trail visible ahead 17m.

Travel_notes: Pace 450m on trail.  Pass two switchback turns and then a set of two curves (almost switchbacks) that form an "S".  Pass one more switchback 85m before reaching point.
Location_desc: On trail, 5m before gentle curve from NE to E.  53-81 cm DBH Western hemlock woods with pole-sized Pacific silver fir and scattered Mtn. hemlock.  Large, leaning Western hemlock upslope on trail, small hummock formed from rotted stump downslope on edge of trail.

Travel_notes: Pace 200m down trail.  No switchbacks.  Cross mossy talus slope at 120m.  Reach edge of shrub opening 18m before point
Location_desc: On trail, 5m below 15x30 shrub clearing on downslope side of trail.  Mostly Vaccinium and some Rubus in clearing.  Mixed conifer woods with Western hemlock, Pacific silver fir and Mtn. hemlock on either side of clearing.  Slight curve in trail at point and rotten, mossy, cut log sections parallel to trail on downslope side.

Travel_notes: Pace 200m down trail.  No switchbacks!  If you come to a switchback you've gone too far.
Location_desc: 15m above switchback in 53-81cm DBH Western hemlock woods.  Rainier peak barely visible ahead through trees.

Travel_notes: Point is at 5th switchback down from NW05 - total of 450m pacing.
Location_desc: At switchback bend overlooking 50x50m vine maple clearing.

Travel_notes: Pace 700m on trail.  2nd switchback overlooks vine maple clearing further down slope.  Trail flattens and winds accross bench area for 45m after 4th and final switchback.
Location_desc: On trail in relatively flat bench area with large Western hemlock and sapling to pole-sized Pacific silver fir.  Point is 2m before the last and highest in a series of root steps on trail, next to 90cm DBH Western hemlock.

Travel_notes: Pace 400m on trail.  Follow meandering trail along flat bench area.  Trail makes 90 degree curve at 185m and begins to follow side slope again.  Two quick switchbacks are followed by straightaway to point.  Look for Western hemlock stump on downslope side.
Location_desc: On trail in open canopy Doug-fir/Western hemlock/Pacific silver fir woods.  23m up from next switchback.  Pacific silver fir and Western hemlock saplings on either side of trail.  Rainier summit visible through trees at 117 degrees.  Western hemlock stump downslope is most distinctive feature.

Travel_notes: Pace 865, down switchbacks on trail.  There is a hook curve - not a full switchback - 60m before the point.  Woods thickens and slope mellows considerably leading up to point.
Location_desc: Point is on dim, mossy section of trail with very dense Western hemlock and Pacific silver fir saplings on both sides of trail, though more open on E side.  Mossy sawed logs are piled on both sides of trail and three large Western hemlock stand on E side of trail - N-most Western hemlock is a snag.

Travel_notes: Continue down the trail along a straight section stopping just before the next switchback.
Location_desc: The point is located 20m before a switchback in a mixed conifer forest. The point is just before a >100cm dbh cedar (with a metal 'TO' tag) and a 100cm dbh hemlock on the North side of the trail.

Travel_notes: Stroll 100m easterly on trail.
Location_desc: In lush, undifferentiated beargrass heaven.

Travel_notes: Walk 200m on trail.
Location_desc: Still in beargrass heaven, right where a snag with PIWO nestholes stands a few meters downslope.

Travel_notes: Walk 200m on trail.
Location_desc: On trail on continuous slope of beargrass and vaccinium,  punctuated by firs, hemlocks, and cedars, with open views to S and SW.  There is a whitened chunk of deadwood with vaccinium and some fireweed sprouting out of it, just touching trail on L.

Travel_notes: Walk 200m southeasterly on trail, beargrass/vaccinium gradually being filled in with young forest of Pacific silver fir, Western hemlock and Alaska yellow cedar.
Location_desc: On trail, with dense young Pacific silver fir/Western hemlock below, patchy above with beargrass, azalea, vaccinium shrubs.  Just past a tiny clump of shrubby Alaska yellow cedar on left.

Travel_notes: Walk 200m on trail, through several breaks in the forest before Pacific silver fir closes in completely.
Location_desc: On trail in young Pacific silver fir forest, a few meters before four pistol-gripped firs line up on Left side of trail

Travel_notes: 200m down trail.  The young Pacific silver fir forest gives way to an older, truly mixed conifer forest with sizable noble fir well-represented.
Location_desc: On trail between where a 65cm dbh Noble fir slightly pistol-gripped, abuts trail edge, and (10m further) two 75cm dbh Pacific silver fir stand on either side of trail.

Travel_notes: Walk 225m (to compensate for bends in trail).  Stop before a lg. Pacific silver fir is sawed off where it crosses trail.
Location_desc: On trail in Mixed conifer woodlands, Alaska yellow cedar, Western hemlock, and firs dominant, point is where two 30-40cm Alaska yellow cedars stand together 1m on W side of trail, and 15m before a large Pacific silver fir is sawed off where it crosses trail (actually it blocks trail at time of establishment, but presumably it will be cut by next visit) at an acute angle.

Travel_notes: Descend into the woodlands with a 225Â° bearing, on a mostly medium slope.  There is a broad benching of slope for ~20m in the middle before it becomes steeper, heading down to the lake.
Location_desc: Point on medium slope under dense Mixed conifer canopy, on an 80cm dbh mossy downed tree trunk.  There is a small clearing to the NW mostly filled in by vaccinium and saplings.  There are numerous downed rotted trees around, and the lake is about 30m to the SW.

Travel_notes: Head west, keeping the lakeshore a distance off your left, and climbing a small dividing slope for 80m until you start to descend into creek drainage.
Location_desc: Point 09 is on a tiny island of rocks in the middle of a creek that flows out of the largest of the golden lakes.  There are, sprouting out of said rock island, devil's club and several species of Ribes and Rubus.  Fir boughs reach down from the north bank, and a 5m-wide section of bare dirt scrabbles down on the south.

Reason_for_change: Creek w/ steep dropoff running through previous bearing
Travel_notes: Cross creek. Easier to climb steep bank if you walk upstream a bit where slope is less severe. Walk back after crossing til lined up w/ SE09 and head south. Relatively flat terrain. Becomes increasingly thick w/ willows as you approach point.
Location_desc: Point next to a meter high stump. 14m from lake on slope headed towards the water.

Travel_notes: Camp at Golden Lakes Backcountry site.  Hike 50 minutes to TO.  A lovely SE transect arm on trail through open beargrass and into forest with noble fir mixed in with standard subalpine conifer types, and then down into lake basin.  NW arm is on trail down switchbacks towards Mowich R.
Location_desc: On Wonderland Trail 100m SE of junction with trail leading W out of park.  In hemlock-dominated Mixed conifer with thick beargrass understory.

Travel_notes: Travel down Stevens Canyon Rd. from Hwy 123. Pass a series of sharp curves and several wider curves until you come to a N/S straight portion. If coming from TO, walk N along Stevens Canyon Rd. for 100m.
Location_desc: Point is on W side of Stevens Canyon Rd. with rock face directly behind (to the W) and Doug-fir and W. Hemlock to the E. Point is along a straight portion of the road.

Travel_notes: Walk due N along straight portion of Stevens Canyon Rd. from NW01 until just before small waterfall and curve in the road to the E.
Location_desc: Point is on W side of Stevens Canyon Rd. just before a waterfall and stone culvert on W side of road and just before road curves to the E.

Travel_notes: Travel along road approximately 100 m from NW03 and turn off road at a slight NW bearing at culvert. Preferred route: follow N bearing from NW02 entirely.
Location_desc: Point is in relatively flat and open mossy patch just above downhill slope. Steeper slope just to E. w/huge downed Doug-fir 1m S of pt.

Reason_for_change: impassible large stream and small waterfall
Travel_notes: Can be slow travel to NW04 because of steep slope and many downed trees.
Location_desc: Point is on S side of large downed tree and limbs. On small mossy patch of slope.

Travel_notes: Head up steep slope, must cross small stream at some pt. 2016 - We crossed above waterfall, stream banks aren't as steep.
Location_desc: SW of stream on steep slope (slide area) in between large Doug-fir & large cedar in small clearing of few shrubs w/vine maple down slope.

Travel_notes: Travel up steep slope
Location_desc: Slight clearing, mossy ground w/less ground vegetation, up very steep slope, surrounded w/vine maple.

Travel_notes: From TO, go SE down a steep slope. At about 60m, the slope levels out for a stretch. Point is past an abandoned oil drum right on edge of next drop in slope.
Location_desc: Point is in between a very large fallen hemlock and two "crossing" fallen hemlocks. There are several large white snags surrounding the point, but the ones in the features are downslope from point. The point is just before another steep slope to the SE.

Travel_notes: Travel down steep slope to the SE. About halfway, there will be a steep, rocky dropoff that is passable in certain spots. You will see a large rock face to the SW about 150 m from SE01.
Location_desc: Point is right next to a rocky/boulder dropoff. In a space between the rock, a fallen log, and a large Doug-fir.

Travel_notes: About 100 m from SE02, there is a rock face directly in the path. You have to detour to one side. Can use a large diagonal fallen tree as reference point. Base of this fallen tree is about 150 m from SE02. Cros stream at 175m
Location_desc: On top of mossy hill on the SE stream bank. Very open area w/little understory. Lots of downed logs in area.
Location_notes: Is_best adjusted to 2016 field coordinates

Reason_for_change: stream bank too steep and stream uncrossable from SE03
Travel_notes: Travel across the steep slope to the SW. Travel parallel to river, through some denser vegetation (hemlocks/maple) near SE04.
Location_desc: Point is in a small creek bed uphill from the large stream. Point is in dense hemlock and vine maple. There is a large cedar snag on top of a large hump in the ground near point.

Travel_notes: Travel SW along slope. You will travel along a rock face about halfway from last point.
Location_desc: Point is on rise just after a small creek. There is a large fallen conifer directly in the path next to the point and the point itself is in front of a very large Doug-fir.

Travel_notes: Travel across slope with campground road to the E. You will cross some creeks and come to a large flat creekbed near point.
Location_desc: Point is right next to a small creek. Creek splits around a stump and joins back up directly to W of point. Surrounded by many large hemlocks. A large rocky/mossy mound is visible about 45 m to the N.

Travel_notes: Can easily drive from Ohanapecosh or even Packwood in the morning. From Stevens Canyon Entrance, drive on road south to TO. Should park at closest area to pulloff before reaching the TO. There are few to none south of the TO.
Location_desc: TO is located on the W side of the road next to a tall rock face covered in hemlocks. Directly across from the point on the E side of the road is a low rocky mound that starts just N of the point.

Travel_notes: Travel NE for 100m.
Location_desc: Point is on edge open spot. A sharp drop in elevation begins within 20m to the north. Point is on east side of Subalpine fir/yellow cedar stand.

Travel_notes: Travel along meadows, hills and small stands of Subalpine fir and Mtn. hemlocks.
Location_desc: Point is on East-facing slope overlooking large meadow downhill. Point is more open , but mossy tall Mtn. hemlocks are around. Small deertrack runs through point.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m down rest of slope, cross meadow and head into forest up a steep slope.
Location_desc: Point is a steep 40m into dense forest and inconspicuous. Many downed trees are present. When approaching from below, 2 large long mossy fallen trees are visible that are suspended 2-3m high off the ground. They lie horizontal along the slope. The lower one is a 40cm dbh Mtn. hemlock, the higher one was a 40cm dbh Silver fir.

Travel_notes: Travel up steep slope, south, for 80 m. Go along meadows and small hills for 120m.
Location_desc: Point is on meadow in drainage on edge of slope downhill to north.

Travel_notes: Travel South, into forest upslope for about 50m and onto meadow again, for 200m.
Location_desc: Point is on East-facing slope among dense tall Mtn. hemlocks. Exactly at point is a cracked Mtn. hemlock that is supported by another Mtn. hemlock that stands further upslope. The crack is at 175cm from ground, the Mtn. hemlock is 40cm dbh.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m SE across meadows.
Location_desc: Point is in inconspicuous spot on Meadow, within 50m of lake. Closest feature is a 3m wide wet area with 2 rivulets, filled with Shootingstar and a pale, protruding debarked white log.

Travel_notes: Travel SE for 200m, passing lake on right, clambering over boulderfield and into area with open spots and large Mtn. hemlocks.
Location_desc: Point is on open spot on slope, South of large lake and just east of rocky talus slope with large boulders. The east end of the lake is visible. Between talus and point is a clump of 3 80cm dbh Mtn. hemlocks. A ridgeline with more dense Mtn. hemlocks begins within 15m to the east.

Travel_notes: travel uphill through patches of dense forest and clear areas. When you reach the creek go upstream (there's a convenient game trail) until you find a safe crossing in the meadow. Once across, keep moving up
Location_desc: in a narrow strip of hemlock on the edge of a steep drop-off to the E

Travel_notes: Point is about 150m down trail.
Location_desc: Point is at a dog-leg to the left in the trail, amid many wooden staircases/waterbars. There is a view of Mother Mountain. Pt is at a curve in trail which is just past a grassy open area with cliffs above it.

Travel_notes: Go down 10 switchbacks. Point is 37m after the last switchback. A large talus slope will be on your right to the East, and you will eventually cross over to the other side of this talus slope. Point is before you round a bend and get a view of the valley floor.
Location_desc: Point is on a fairly straight section of the trail after you pass across the talus slope on the east side of the drainage. Mountain Hemlock dominates, with an occasional Pacific Silver Fir and huckleberry understory.

Travel_notes: Pace about 375m down trail. Opening at 40m and a view in the valley below. To the right at that point there is a narrow gorge with waterfalls.
Location_desc: Point is on trail amid lots of Mountain Hemlock, Pacific Silver Fir and Alaska Yellow Cedar. It is in between two waterbars. The uphill bar is 5.3m away and the downhill one is 6.2m. There seems to be some remnant of a trail going uphill parallel to the real trail, starting at the lower waterbar.

Travel_notes: Pace 330m down trail.
Location_desc: Point is along trail in a fairly nondescript location. About 130 m from Cataract Valley Campground.

Travel_notes: Go off trail at 45 degrees. Cross a stream at 100m, then climb a hill for about 75m. The point is at the top of the hill in a relatively flat area.
Location_desc: Point in a flat area at top hill. Lots of Mountain Hemlock, Alaska Yellow Cedar with fewer Pacific Silver Firs and a bunch of snags.

Travel_notes: Travel along flat ridgetop (some slight up and down), then drop down into saddle between ridge and much higher cliffs. Point is located on far side of saddle where slope heads up again.
Location_desc: In mature mixed conifer (Mountain Hemlock, Pacific Silver fir primarily) woods on mild slope w/ much steeper slope above. Open rocky/shrubby area located to the south, several large boulders in area.

Reason_for_change: Too steep, going back to original direction of travel
Travel_notes: Travel 200m North, traversing a relatively steep sideslope. Travel is fairly easy through open woods with barely any understory.
Location_desc: Point located on 20m wide forested ledge w/ steep slopes above and below. Through the trees it is possible to see the Cataract Creek Valley and the cliffs below Mother Mountain beyond the valley. Point just downslope of a 50cm DBH rotting log that crosses another next to a 60cm DBH mountain hemlock.

Travel_notes: We attempted to survey this transect the first week of July, but there was still to much snow. Large drifts and campground totally covered. July 22nd, totally melted out. 30 minute hike to TO from Cataract Valley. 2014: Campground melted out 1st week of July. NN arm relatively snow-free, NE arm quite snowy. Marmot Creek not crossable except on trail.
Location_desc: Pt is along a straight stretch of trail amid many waterbars. The creek is about 25m to the west.

Travel_notes: travel 100m through flat open meadows
Location_desc: located in open meadow, no good features to describe.  50m away from forest edge.  Hope marker is still there.

Travel_notes: enter forest at 50m, then continue, you'll be heading downhill.
Location_desc: falls inside a 2m by 2m "square" of 3 snags and one live Subalpine fir.  Several Mtn. hemlock saplings nearby.  2 of the snags have prominent black fire marks.
Location_notes: It is unclear if NW02 is in the location indicated by the map/GPS because the error was very high when established. This might need to be changed in the future if it isn't to ensure it is 200 m from NW01. Changed 2021 based on evaluating 3 coordinates for survey station.

Travel_notes: Downhill through some open areas interspersed with denser vegetation
Location_desc: located in a forest clearing with Subalpine Fir saplings.  This is a nondescript point, distinctive features lacking

Travel_notes: Start going downhill, route bottoms out at creek crossing, then heads steeply up
Location_desc: 2009: Point is on a slope in an open area with lots of beargrass surrounded by Subalpine Firs. 2014: unable to locate old feature, deactivated and set new features based on GPS coordinates. Located in clearing w/ glacier lilies and vaccinium spp. Several snags in area, forest is open and dominated by Subalpine Fir. Creek noise audible.

Travel_notes: Turn to the SW, head out of forest and into a meadow.
Location_desc: Located in an open meadow with a pond and stream draining out from pond.  Point is on flat soggy ground 10-20m from pond edge (may vary depending on yearly water levels)

Travel_notes: Cross meadow then head up a fairly steep slope.  Last 50m are flatter.
Location_desc: Located in a semi-open area, lots of larger Subalpine Firs around.

Travel_notes: Continue SW. Travel over relatively flat ground for 50m, afterwards slope is more gradual then gets very steep around 170m.
Location_desc: On slope in moderately open woods, lots of beargrass underfoot. Several downed logs in area.

Travel_notes: pass next to the marker and enter the forest patch behind it.  The point is located right when you exit the forest.
Location_desc: point is located right at the edge of forest/meadow, lots of downed logs around

Travel_notes: travel from dense forest through meadows and through next line of dense forest, point about 30m beyond the tree line/
Location_desc: point in open meadow approx 340 m from westerly tree line

Travel_notes: walk across meadow
Location_desc: point is in the meadow surrounded by patch of Subalpine fir, lots of saplings <1m @ north.  Great view of Rainier.

Travel_notes: Open Travel to forest
Location_desc: point is on edge of forest and meadow, relatively open.

Travel_notes: travel in forest right near meadow edge
Location_desc: point is in a meadow surrounded my trees, right next to the main meadow
