Travel_notes: throguh relatively open forest to open spot
Location_desc: Located in open meadow surrounded on all sides except west by trees, opening to very large meadow.  Not many features.

Travel_notes: pass a 10m thick strip of trees and travel in open meadow, point is 70m after you pass ditch.
Location_desc: point is in open meadow with a great view of Rainier.  No distinct features around.

Travel_notes: Travel through large meadow.
Location_desc: Point in the middle of large meadow, no conspicuous features, but very good gps.

Travel_notes: Continue traveling through large, open meadow.
Location_desc: Point is located in open meadow, very good GPS.

Travel_notes: travel across open meadow, through a forest strip and across a side meadow with one side open to the larger meadow
Location_desc: in a side meadow, within 15m of the far-side and back-side trees

Travel_notes:
Majestic Transect!  2009: We camped in the Grand Park cross country zone, the creek on the plateau was dry so we went toward lake eleanor to pump water in creek about 1.5 km from camp.  Bring Mosquito nets and bug spray, they are hellacious!
2014: Shortest route in (hiking) is via Lake Eleanor trail on north side of park - from Longmire, take 123 N (out of Steven's Canyon Entrance) to 410 heading towards Seattle. Take a left on FS 73 (also known as Crystal Ln or something, not super well-marked coming from the south). Follow FS 73 about ten miles past forest service gate to Eleanor Creek where the trail is visible but unmarked. Access was only available on weekends due to road work/logging; requires a NW Forest Discover Pass. Trail up to Grand Park/parking area were surprisingly popular considering how off the beaten path the trail access is located. If camping at Lake Eleanor, it's ~1 hr hike to TO and VERY buggy.
Pace 125m along trail, crossing 1 switchback.
Location_desc: Point is dense stand of Subalpine fir and Engelmann Spruce. A small gully is uphill, 7m away.

Travel_notes: pace along trail for 275m.
Location_desc: Point is on trail, in meadow, 15m beyond edge of dense stand of Subalpine Fir. Point is 3m down, past protruding root in trail.

Travel_notes: travel along trail for 275m, cross 5 switchbacks.
Location_desc: Point is on small stand of Subalpine Fir, many boulders are on trail. Point 3m beyond last switchback that climbs the slope.

Travel_notes: Travel along trail, climbing slightly, crossing meadow and reaching the "Mystic Lake" sign 60m before descending to the point.
Location_desc: Point is in 2nd switchback from top, once downhill begins. A waterbar reaches halfway over the trail. Further downhill is a large boulder located inside the next switchback

Travel_notes: Follow trail for 6 switchbacks and 575m.
Location_desc: Point is on trail at bottom of steep section with many switchbacks. Point is on a root that crosses the trail. A 5m long open sandy area borders the trail to the west.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m along trail across meadow.
Location_desc: Point is on trail on meadow, on only spot on trail where 20cm dbh Subalpine Firs are on both side of the trail.

Travel_notes: Pace ~250m down Wonderland Trail
Location_desc: Located on Wonderland Trail - to the south is a sort of alley between trees that heads back out to the open meadow through which you just traveled, to the north is an open meadow and a view of the ridge up to Moraine Park.

Travel_notes: Pace 210m down Wonderland Trail.
Location_desc: Point is on Wonderland Trail. Several young subalpine firs and mountain hemlocks to the east, thicker older growth of same species is slightly upslope to the west. Rocky cliffs of Moraine Park visible to the north and east.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: in tiny elbow on trail with a massive boulder off-trail to the NE. Walknig to the point, stop just before you're about to enter an area with trees on both sides of the trail

Travel_notes: Travel 100m at 225 degrees.
Location_desc: Down log is conspicuous.  Pt is on gently sloping hillside with many spotty sub-alpine fir.

Travel_notes: Continue at 225 degrees.  Cross a small stream.  At the stream crossing there are two branches (makes a Y). Stay to the left of the dense sub-alpine fir stand, going along the mossy streambed.  Travel up open grassy/dirt area and slightly veer back into sub-alpine firs.  Point is in a clearing with a large fallen log.  Ultimate bearing probably close to 215-220 degrees.
Location_desc: Point is in a small clearing with a large down log in the middle.  Tall stands of Englemann Spruce and Subalpine FIr to the East and West.  Many krummholtz Subalpine fir.  Great views of Rainier to the south and Old Desolate to the north.

Travel_notes: Travel due south up meadow.  Second hundred meters are steeper.  Point is at top of hill.  Stay between dense stands fo trees so that point is about 20m east of it if it were exactly at 180 degrees.
Location_desc: No conspicuous features.  Point is at top of hillside when it flattens out just as you reach the top.  Lots of Subalpine fir with some whitebark pine.  Several big clusters of white, barkless, sprawling down trees.

Travel_notes: Travel easy over sub-alpine meadow the whole way.
Location_desc: Point is in a stretch of meadow surrounded by gently flowing streams.  To the east is a dense line of conifers below Mineral Mountain.  To all other direcftions is meadow.  To the south is a large ridge of skree slope before Carbon Glacier.

Travel_notes: Continue SE for 200m.  At about 90m you encounter a very thick, very steep area of conifers.  After 140m you exit the woods and enter a strip of meadow bursting with wildflowers.  Point is on the far side of meadow near the next line of trees.
Location_desc: Point is in a narrow stretch of meadow that runs roughly NW/SE between thick stands of conifers.  It is on far (SE) side of meadow just before start of trees.  Amazing views!

Travel_notes: Travel upslope and over saddle. Go down slope into soft, silty substrate. No vegetation near point. Head waters of the W fork of the White River are very loud - will likely get visual detections only. Keep an ear out for RCKI upslope and an eye out for birds in trees downslope. NOTE: In 2020 the other side of the saddle held snow. Following wetter winters, or during slower melts, microspikes may be necessary if top layer has not begun to soften.
Location_desc: Point is out in the open on soft, silty slope. No veg within 50m. May be snow covered some years. Take extra safety precautions during high snow pack years.

Travel_notes:
Camped at Mystic Lake campground. TO is a 15 minute walk from there. Lots of mosquitoes- be prepared.
Combined w/ 4011 and 4043 into an AWESOME tour.
Location_desc: TO is on path in dense stand of Engelmann Spruce and Subalpine fir . Many roots cross path.

Travel_notes: Scramble 6 m up bare dirt slope from road.  Follow NN bearing 65 m to top of small ridge.  Go over ridge and traverse N slope of small hollow to point.
Location_desc: On SE aspect slope, 1 m below stump described in features.  Point overlooks hollow formed by S and E running ridges.  >122 cm DBH Western redcedar stands out.

Travel_notes: Follow the side of the slope through thick yew brush, crossing a drainage at 40 m.  Aspect will gradually change from SE to E.  Continute uphill, yew brush ends and bear grass / Vaccinium begins, continue to small clearing.  Pacing was a bit confusing on the way down - may need to rely of gps / features - probably closer to 220 m to point.
Location_desc: Point is on steep S facing slope of Emerald Ridge, at SW corner of 15 x 15 m clearing in little patch of Vaccinium and Pacific yew.  Clearing is mostly bear grass, Vacc. and Oregon grape.

Travel_notes: Continue up steep slope.  Enter 6 m wide, shallow, open shoot at 100 m, exit it at 135 m.  Slightly thicker, older woods at crest of slope.
Location_desc: Point is on a gentle slope about 20 m after steep S slope near crest of Emerald Ridge.  On SW corner of small (15 x 10 m) clearing, in mixed Doug-fir, Pacific silver fir, Western hemlock woods.

Travel_notes: Travel up gradual slope accross the top of Emerald Ridge.  Begin down the N slope at 100 m.
Location_desc: In small clearing in 53-81 cm DBH Mixed conifer woods with lots of Pacific silver firs.  There is > 1m of snow pack right now, so it is difficult to describe the topography, but the point seems to be on a small ridge with a clearing the E - rely on features to locate spot.

Travel_notes: Travel down slope, crossing 3-4 m wide drainage at 90 m.  The point is in the middle of the next drainage E.  As you continue down slope you will follow the W side of and eventually cross this drainage.
Location_desc: Point is on a narrow (ca. 3 m wide), mossy ridge separating two channels of a 15-20 m wide creek drainage.  Next to distinctive cat faced Western hemlock.

Travel_notes: Travel down slope, immediately crossing the E channel of the creek drainage.  Cross the next creek to the E at 75 m.  The creek at the point is 20 m to the E.  Continute down hill, coming slowly closer to the W side of the creek.  The point is 4 m W of the intersection of this third creek with the pack trail.
Location_desc: Point is on pack trail, 4 m W of small stream flowing over trail.  In mixed age Mixed conifer woods with Doug-fir, Western redcedar, Western hemlock, and Pacific silver fir.  Devils club growing in stream drainage.

Travel_notes: Travel down the hill until you reach the road, then follow the road to the point.
Location_desc: The point is located on the North side of the Westside Road just after a turn in the road. Look for the large wooden bike rack as a distinguishing feature.

Travel_notes: Head downhill through mixed forest, across one or two cross-slope benches, directly to point.
Location_desc: On moderate slope in Mixed conifer forest, where two ~85cm dbh Western redcedar and one ~45cm dbh Western hemlock are on the edge of a stand of Pacific silver fir saplings.  Nearby there is a fallen Western redcedar that intersects a larger fallen Doug-fir at a 90 degree angle.

Travel_notes: Head down medium slope to point.
Location_desc: On side of slope leading down to Fish Creek, which is audible but not visible from here.  Point is 10m upslope from where three nurse logs converge near the base of a >100cm dbh Western hemlock.

Reason_for_change: Fish Creek bars further SS'n travel
Travel_notes: Route mostly rides the contours but dips down into a few drainages.  10m before crossing a rill, notice the feeder spring to the right - bright rust-orange.  On far side of creek climb moderate slop to relatively flat forest where point is found.
Location_desc: Point is on unsloped but rolling terrain under mature forest.  Understory is vaccinium, oregon grape, and saplings.  It is between two 10-20m tall barkless snags in line with point on an e/w bearing.

Travel_notes: Head east and down the hill to a wide drainage with two creeks and massive Western redcedars.  After crossing, continue up opposite slope almost until it flattens out.
Location_desc: Near top of hill between a broad depression to the W and a creek to the E, in a Mixed conifer forest with plentiful vaccinium understory.

Travel_notes: Travel east over one small hill to reach creek, which is small but difficult to cross.  There was a lg cedar forming a slanted footbridge slightly downstream.  Head up into blowdown towards Tahoma Creek to find point.
Location_desc: Point is in a tangle of blowdown, which has created a 50m clearing opening up to Tahoma Creek to the east.

Travel_notes: Pick your way south through or over massive pile of blowdown.  You should reach the bank of the river channel (and the trail that continues the trajectory of the Westside Road where it's been washed out) where a 110cm dbh downed Doug-fir stretches out over trail.  Proceed through a smaller island of damaged forest, and out onto the gravel bar.
Location_desc: Located on the broad, rock-strewn bar of Tahoma Creek, amongst copious snags, 30m west of a stand of very young alders between here and the river.

Travel_notes: Straightforward walk on bearing through creek bed.
Continue through the rocky river wash, passing through a couple patches of dense Red Alder.
Location_desc: Point is located in a small rocky and mossy clearing surrounded by young Red Alders. The creek is about 20m East from point, out of sight, and loud.

Travel_notes: Park at closure point on Westside Road and hike up road/trail to point.  Point is at 90 degree bend beyond Tahoma Vista.  Camp backcountry in Emerald Ridge zone, or at Lake George if you're up for a long morning hike.
Location_desc: On Westside Road at 90 degree bend from S to W.  Upslope side of road is bare dirt with Red alder and Vine maple.  Downslope is thick Mixed conifer woods.

Travel_notes: Pace 100m east on trail, point located 5m beyond junction of wonderland trail split. Follow sunrise rim trail.
Location_desc: Located in a meadow interspersed with small Subalpine Fir.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On sunrise rim trail in an area slightly more dense with subalpine fir.  A gap in the trees to the SW providing great views of Emmons glacier

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: located on trail, 12m after passing wooden bridge. More super views.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Subalpine fir/ meadow habitat, al large number of snags scattered around. From point itself, a tall subalpine fir obscures view of little tahoma peak.

Travel_notes: Go 200m on trail. pass turnoff for sunrise at 155. Then pass staireway down to glacier viewpoint at 190m.
Location_desc: meadow subalpine fir area, mountain view blocked by trees

Travel_notes: follow trail towards silver forest
Location_desc: nondescript point in area of Subalpine Fir. More Subalpine fir and less meadow than previous points.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: located in meadow, much thinner tree cover than last point

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On S-facing slope. Similar habitat as previous

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: point is right next to a stand of subalpine for in an otherwise open area. Several snags to the west.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: meadow / Subalpine Firs on s-facing slope

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: more of the same habitat; several weathered fallen logs and root balls around. Point is between the two features on the trail

Travel_notes: TO located on Sunrise Rim trail, approximately a 15 minute walk from Sunrise Camp at Shadow Lake.
Location_desc: The TO is located on the wonderland trail, 95m west of trail junction.  There is a small twin-trunked Subalpine fir just off the trail on the north side.  There is a creek 10m to the west.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point on trail as it curves. To west there is a hill with dead tree on it

Travel_notes: Go 200 m on trail.
Location_desc: Mount Rainier seen from trail.  There is a Subalpine fir with bark damage and down log in front of it next to pointl

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point on the edge of a meadow, with view through trees to SE.

Travel_notes: Travel along trail approx. 200 m.
Location_desc: Point in relatively open Subalpine fir forest , no conspicuous features.

Travel_notes: Walk past lake
Location_desc: Point is 30m past the access to shadow lake.  Burrow mountain can be seen from point.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point in meadow next to Sunrise camp.  Out house, old bathroom clearly visible.

Travel_notes: Travel on Burrow trail, point is 300m after dog leg in trail
Location_desc: Point is on trail going up to Burrow mtn 30m before Emmon's Glacier Lookout.

Travel_notes: Travel up hill on trail
Location_desc: Point on steep slope in white bark pine/ Subalpine fir forest many standing and cut snags.

Travel_notes: Pace 200m up trail. Mt. Rainier becomes slightly obscured by Burroughs Mountain.
Location_desc: Point located in area of small, stunted subalpine fir, with some white bark pine and cedar.

Travel_notes: Continue along trail. Pass two sections of human-made rock walls, each 3-5m long. Trail turns right ahead. After this turn, another much longer rock wall begins. Point is just after this rock wall begins.
Location_desc: Point is on trail next to flat 1.5m wide boulder. Boulder is immediatedly adjacent to cluster of subalpine firs. Subalpine firs to observers left if sitting on boulder. Epic views of valley below.

Travel_notes: Travel 300m down trail (spaced to avoid WW arm).  Pace back was 275m - so look for boulder before 300m.
Location_desc: On trail in thick pole-sized Pacific silver fir/Western hemlock.  Small opening in canopy above boulder and water bar in trail.

Travel_notes: Pace 200m on trail.  Look for walkway over seep and marked opening in canopy.
Location_desc: At the N edge of a large opeing in the canopy, on trail next to 80cm DBH Western hemlock touching 80cm DBH sawed log.  3m S of end of log and dirt walkway over seep.  Stone bridge over small culvert for creek is 16m S on trail, around small bend.

Travel_notes: Pace 200m on trail to intersection with trail to Fryingpan Ck. trailhead.
Location_desc: Exactly at junction of Wonderland Tr. with trail from Frying Pan Ck. trailhead.

Travel_notes: pace 200m on trail.  Steep 4m high ridge along W side of trail ends 42m before point.
Location_desc: 1.5m high ridges cup the trail, giving the impression that it is sunken.  Thick Western hemlock saplings on the little ridges.  These small ridges end 5m S of the point.  Frying pan creek is 70m E and not visible.

Travel_notes: 200m pacing on trail.  Trail gently curves back and forth with slight uphill grade.
Location_desc: On trail in 53-81cm DBH Doug-fir/Western hemlock woods.  Fryingpan creek visible ca. 50m E.

Travel_notes: 195m down trail.  44m after bridge crosses creek.
Location_desc: On Wonderland Trail.  Fryingpan Ck. 50m E.  Open Doug-fir/Westen hemlock woods.  Very open on riverside with 8m high NE/SW running hill visible along river.  Clear view - no trees - 20m to 100cm Doug-fir described in features.

Travel_notes: Pace 210m on trail.
Location_desc: Just after ridge running along side of trailends.  On N edge of 15m wide, relatively open strip crossing trail, right next to small, gnarled alder.  120cm DBH Pacific silver fir is visible through clearing.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m S on trail.
Location_desc: On trail in relatively open Mixed conifer woods with >122cm DBH Doug-fir/Western hemlock and midsized Pacific silver fir and Alaska yellow cedar. 100cm DBH Western hemlock snag, broken off at 9m on E side of trail, even with single log step in trail.  Broken off top of snag has been sawed where it crosses trail.

Travel_notes: Head off trail for 200m at 270 degrees.  First 70m is dry Mixed conifer woods.  At 72m first opening with devil's club (you're in for some fun).  Larger devil's club opening at 91m with <1m wide stream at base of ridge on W edge.  Top small ridge at 150m, with stream visible to N 20m, and travel accross thick, wet devil's club clearing on 90cm DBH log.  Point is at W edge, where clearing narrows slightly.
Location_desc: In 30m wide swath of boggy creek, filled with devil's club and scattered Pacific silver fir/Alaska yellow cedar.  On bare N/S running log that spans entire boggy area.  Thick with shrubs: false azalea and vaccinium.

Travel_notes: Travel 250m at 270 degrees.  Follow boggy devil's club creek for irst 50m.  Enter mature Doug-fir/Western hemlock woods and begin to traverse side of slope at 90m.  Pass under 90cm DBH downed Western hemlock at 137m, crossing 10m wide, dry drainage at 173m.  Continue upslope to point.
Location_desc: Point is in small 1x2m depression above 28cm DBH Western hemlock on moderate slope among 81-122 cm DBH Doug-firs and Western hemlocks, with scattered Pacific silver firs.  Exposed cobble sized chunks of rock on slope.  Vine maple openings to the SE and NE.

Travel_notes: Either walk down Wonderland Trail from White River Road to 1st major bend to the right, or park on road at same bend and whack up slope to trail point. SS arm: Pacing is long between SS09 and SS10, noted on travel description.  WW arm: some hard travel up an down ridge contours and drainages made this arm pretty messy, especially coming to and going from point WW03. Camp at White River Campground.  SS arm: Stayed on Wonderland Trail for first 8 points to be sure to avoid other arm. 2013: 15 minutes from campground to first point.
Location_desc: On trail where trail bends R from a SE to a SW bearing.  There is a bare-dirt sloped bank on the inside of the curve.

Travel_notes: Ride the narrow ridge straight uphill and west from TO to find point.  Between ~30 and 60m there is an on-bearing log you can walk.
Location_desc: Point is 100m from TO, straddling the ridge that runs up from the bend in the trail, in a dense Western hemlock forest spattered with massive old Doug-firs.

Travel_notes: Go west for 200m, riding the slope, through dense, open-storied forest, pass through a few patches of Alaska yellow cedar shrub or Pacific silver fir saplings, and between massive Doug-firs.
Location_desc: Point midslope in closed Western hemlock/Pacific silver fir forest with open understory.  There is an old 40cm dbh deadfall running parallel with the slope, pinned in place by a shattered stump.

Travel_notes: Turn to the NW and start traversing the slope, which ranges from moderate to steep.
Location_desc: Point on side of steep slope in unremarkable midland Mixed conifer, right next to a 40cm dbh Pacific silver fir.  Slope here starts to curve in to stream drainage.

Travel_notes: Go 215m at 305Â° (sorry - tough traveling and bad UTM's made things messy), still traversing the slope, mostly through Western hemlock-dominated forest, dropping through two drainages, then riding a ledge until drops into a slide chute where the point lies.
Location_desc: Point located on an old talus slope covered in large part by the bark of one massive Western hemlock that apparently blew to smithereens here.  Perhaps that's its trunk lying crosswise to the S.  The canopy is open here for about 50m N/S and 20m E/W.

Travel_notes: Proceed due NW for 220 meters (the GPS thinks it's 260, but WW04 had terrible PDOP), traversing the at-times steep slope of the ridge.  After you cross the devil's club patch, watch for downed trees running downhill.
Location_desc: Point is in middle of a canopy opening caused by blowdown.  There are several lg. (81-122cm dbh) trees laid N/S down slope.

Reason_for_change: to avoid getting back on the wonderland trail
Travel_notes: Walk upslope on the diagonal (due west). Cross a couple intermittent streams. Look for the large, whitish, rock (see photo).
Location_desc: In relatively open area next to rock. Visibility at point somewhat obscured because it is in a bit of a depression. Upslope between 260 degrees and 290 degrees, there are large exposed boulders with trees growing on them (about 30 m away).

Travel_notes: Continue West traveling up and across a steep slope with a mostly open understory.
Location_desc: The point is on the crest of a small ridge on a steep slope. The forest is primarily Wetern hemlocks with some smaller Pacific silver firs. There is a thick patch of hemlock saplings just West of the point.

Travel_notes: Head uphill for 60 meters, then hit a clearing where it flattens out.  Cross the clearing.
Location_desc: Located inside a ring of subalpine fir, about 5 meters north from edge of clearing. Marker tree in tree ring.

Travel_notes: Begin by heading uphill.  After the first 80 meters, it flattens out.  Pass through meadow areas interspersed with subalpine fir.
Location_desc: In a meadowy area, 2 meters away from small creek.  Subalpine fir forest surrounds meadow and a few small groves of small tress are scattered in the meadow.

Travel_notes: Cross meadow and pass through a small grove of subalpine fir.  Then enter another meadow on the other side.
Location_desc: Located in a soggy open meadow near a creek.  Hill to the north blocks view of Mt. Rainier except for very top.  Tatoosh range visible to the south.

Travel_notes: Enter a stand of subalpine fir mixed with mountain hemlock and head uphill until you reach a semi-open area that's flatter.
Location_desc: Located next to a cluster of smaller subalpine firs in a semi open area.  Few conspicuous features.

Travel_notes: Continue going uphill, enter an open area.  You may have to cross lots of snow.
Location_desc: This point is going to look a lot different if you survey it in a not very snowy year.  This year, the open area was completely snow covered. QA note: get distance and bearing for "2 snags" feature.

Travel_notes: Continue up a gentle incline, then down through a small valley and up again.
Location_desc: Point is at the top of a small hill, with a creek flowing to the west.  Great views!  Located in open area surround by subalpine firs over 80 meters away. QA note: please add distance and bearing to "3 snags" feature next visit.

Travel_notes: Travel relatively flat over heather, lupine, grass meadow all the way to NN07
Location_desc: 1m from flat, very sparse vegetation, mostly grass dotted w/ rocks. Hill of rocks in front of you w/ some Subalpine fir and Mtn. hemlock saplings on top. Beautiful Mt. Rainier!!

Travel_notes: Start off by traveling on hilly/flat terrain for the first 100m. At ~100m, it starts to go steeply downslope.
Location_desc: Open meadow surrounded by a ring of predominantly Subalpine fir and some Mtn. hemlocks going slightly downslope. For the 2 Subalpine firs (feature), the ~15cm DBH fir is 4m tall.

Travel_notes: Traverse 97m @ 14 degrees until you hit the trail. Follow trail until ~11m from the point.
Location_desc: Beautiful view of Mt. Rainier in its splendor. In between two rock/grassbeds that used to hold water pointing down (in shape of triangle). Mtn. hemlock with scar (feature) is on the edge of a meadow in a cluster of multiple tall Mtn. hemlocks (I think-- difficult to interpret description; please update if needed).

Travel_notes: Go downhill, then cross multiple small creeks. Point is on a slight incline going up.
Location_desc: Rocks to N of point. Meadow lupine vegetation. Creek is audible 30m away. On a slight incline. There is Subalpine fir and Mountain hemlock in the distance.

Travel_notes: Travel steeply upslope. At ~170m, travel gets extremely steep. Takes a bit of time to climb; go over rocks and meadow.
Location_desc: Up near top of cliff near Mtn. hemlock to left (facing downslope) and Subalpine fir, mostly to the right. Some blueberry bushes and meadow around. Excellent view of trail (no snow) and landscape.

Travel_notes: We stayed at Cougar Rock Campground and it took 15 minutes to drive to Reflection Lake.  There is a pullout on the north side of the road by the trailhead.  Hiking time to the TO was 25 minutes.  Trailhead is just east of the smaller lake to the east of the main Reflection Lake.  TO is shortly after you take a left at the trail junction after Faraway Rock.  About 75 meters before a stream down the trail. Park at either the 2nd large (Reflection Lakes) parking lot or tiny pullout just past trailhead. For TO, the pullout is after the 2 larger parking lots where most tourists park.
Location_desc: Located on trail on edge of small meadow near a creek.  Subalpine fir dominates in the area. Marker tree is in loose clump of firs in meadow (not in larger stand of trees).

Travel_notes: Pace 210 meters on trail.
Location_desc: Point is on a bend to the left in the trail.  Just past point on the right side is a down log lying E-W.  Point is at the first left bend the trail takes after crossing the stream.  Trail mostly obscured by snow.

Travel_notes: Pace 275 meters on trail.
Location_desc: Point is on trail at a 0.5 meter tall stump on the left side of the trail.  15 meters before the point is an open meadow area.  There are some cut 3 meter long sections of log on the left side of the trail just past the point.

Travel_notes: Travel south off-trail through semi-open woods with relatively flat slope.  Then slope becomes very steep at 160 meters, and you get to a steep grassy hillside with a ground stake at the point.
Location_desc: Point is in the middle of a very open, steep meadow hillside. Next to a 15dbh and 5m long log/branch on ground. In grassy area west of low shrubbier area. Group of yellow cedars to the west/southwest. Ground stake missing.

Travel_notes: Travel down steep hillside for 30 meters.  At 50 meters, there is a thin band of trees, and then you enter a flat meadow (2010: snow-covered).  Last 100 meters are downhill through forest with Vaccinium understory.
Location_desc: Point is in forest with gaps in canopy.  Thirty meters south of point it opens up a lot more.  There are a lot of big Pacific Silver-Firs in area.  Large rotting stump by point is fairly conspicuous. South of point are bones from an old elk carcass.

Travel_notes: Travel downslope through fairly open canopy but dense brush.  Point is in the last open area before you reach a large, boggy meadow.
Location_desc: Point is in an open spot in the forest.  You can see through the treeline to the south a large meadow.  There are a bunch of 1.5 meter tall saplings in the opening.

Reason_for_change: next point would have been in a lake
Travel_notes: Pace 220 meters west.  Travel is easy through flat ground with little understory.
Location_desc: Point is 10 meters after a 2 meter wide stream.  Just down from where you cross the stream is a one meter tall waterfall over a log.  The area past the point to the west is more open.

Travel_notes: Trees, downed trees but relatively mellow flat travel. At 100m starts to open up = even easier travel.
Location_desc: In vaccinoum open area. Subalpine fir saplings dispersed in front of you. Subalpine firs surround you in a ring. Two white curved snags bent behind 2m tall feature tree, DBH <10cm.

Travel_notes: Flat vaccinium travel
Location_desc: 8m before open grass meadow. Subalpine firs all around the point like a ring around meadow. A downed 10cm DBH 4m tree kind of hovering off of ground next to you, base of fallen tree is NE of point. Vaccinium as shrub.

Travel_notes: Flat travel, low vaccinium vegetation
Location_desc: Open meadow, wet! Go too far and boots sink. Some creek waters, some trees on edge. You are near the edge of the wet meadow. There are snags & small saplings dispersed around feature Subalpine fir (in middle of meadow).

Travel_notes: Travel forested down logs (small) until 100m. Go uphill into Mixed conifer forest w/ some shrub understory.
Location_desc: Point is on uphill side of large decaying downed log (base curved where it broke off) that runs perpendicular to slope. Next to yellow cedar and western hemlock saplings. Mostly dirt/pine needle vegetation w/ some saplings and shrub.

Travel_notes: Pace 150m on trail. Point is 124m from switch back
Location_desc: Devil Dream Ck can be heard at about 50m. Cut log runs parallel to trail.

Travel_notes: First 134m is in open forest, easy walking, last 66m in a thick upslope talus meadow. Lots of roses bushes, devil club  and big boulders... enjoy! 2015: I took 1.5+ hours to find/get here. Best to focus 360 degree bearing on Iron Mountain. There are a lot of boulders in the area. Area is on the edge of an opening in the willow near marker. Large boulder 42m no longer visible. At site there are 4 boulders going down slope w/largest closest to you and smallest boulder furthest away and furthest downslope 12.2m. away. Can see 66m-100m away open forest. No real consp. features. Good views on Iron Mountain for most part. There is a 5th boulder, not in the 4 boulder rock line 15m away.
Location_desc: Point in willow bush. You can see the rock wall at 42m to West. 2015: In 5 years I don't know how helpful this will be, very shrubby and prickly = annoying and slow. Going to EE03, best to take rocky riverbed (hope it is still there!) go 6m @139 degrees. Then follow bed all the way down to logs until gone. Go about 100m. will save you immense amount of time.

Reason_for_change: rock wall at S and SE
Travel_notes: Go down the steep slope covered with willow/devil clubs. At 60m it opens up and at 120m you enter the forest.
Location_desc: Point in fairly open forest. Lots of saplings and downed trees. Can hear an unnamed creek from point. Behind the snag is a 95cm. DBH spruce and in between the shared base cedar and snag is a fallen log. To the L of the snag ~2.5m. away is a slight "pistol grip" cedar w/DBH 20cm. Shares base with larger cedar also.

Travel_notes: At 28m you pass a small creek, cross it on downed log to the N. Then go down slope.
Location_desc: Point in open forest, 20m below rock outcrop. Devil Dream Ck can be heard.

Reason_for_change: 90 degrees is creek, not crossable. 135 degrees also can add one more point feasibly
Travel_notes: Travel downslope mostly sparse vegetation. Run into clump of sapling Doug-firs around 140m or so to the point.
Location_desc: Large Doug-firs dominate. Right next to rock bed of once creek. 4.5m. away Doug-fir saplings below (SEish) Point 1m from 1m DBH Doug-fir and snag w/ bark 65cm. DBH ~50 m. tall (1.3m. away)

Travel_notes: Travel up trail to point just past the first switch back.
Location_desc: Point is on trail 5 m pass an Alaska Yellow Cedar, which is directly at the turning point of the first switch back you encounter.

Travel_notes: Travel on trail 290m from NN01
Location_desc: Point is on flat part of trail in Alaska Yellow Cedar/Mountain Hemlock forest. 1m from two yellow cedar on N side of trail (feature) and 2 mountain hemlocks sharing base on south side of trail.

Travel_notes: Travel on trail 280m from NN02
Location_desc: Point is on trail in Devil Dream CG 27m up trail from "Site 5 and 6" sign. Awkwardly close to campside #7 if it is occupied. GPS ~20m off.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point located next to small stream paralleling trail. There is a small opening/meadow on trail starting 30m up trail from point.

Travel_notes: Travel through hilly forest.
Location_desc: Point is in open forest with Alaska Yellow Cedar, silver fir, and mountain hemlock, downed logs surround the point.

Travel_notes: Travel down slope to glorious alpine meadow. Bearing led me to the other side of the stream, however I could not cross and did point 4m away on near side of stream.
Location_desc: Point is in alpine meadow next to a meandering stream (head water of Devil Dream Ck). Very flat and open... Bonus! Iron mountain  looming over meadow

Travel_notes: Easy travel, 1st through open forest, then in meadow alongside pond. First, you'll probably need to backtrack to find a way to cross the creek.
Location_desc: Point is in a clearing next to 2 white, downed logs. Pond is nearby, a few Mtn. hemlock seedlings (<2m as of 2015) are also present (along with young firs)

Travel_notes: Go up a small hill, a rock area, then up the slope of Iron Mountain. Be careful on talus slope and watch for loose rocks. Try to follow line of trees up if possible (lots of Pikas!)
Location_desc: Point is between the two sections of rocky slopes, along the line of Subalpine firs that divides them. Point is just upslope of a cluster of 6 smallish (~7-15 dbh) Subalpine firs. Lots of Pikas around, and a nice view.

Travel_notes: Travel very carefully over talus on bearing. You'll hit the end of the talus ant it becomes easier to travel on normal ground with some rocks. Head into forest through yellow cedar, then you'll hit some meadow pockets and travel becomes easier again.
Location_desc: Point in vaccinium and false azalea south of group of ~5 cedars. Next to two pale mossy snags and a 100dbh silver fir with smaller curved based silver fir next to it. Point looks over drop on hillside.

Travel_notes: Point is 30m after downslope switchback and 100m before the upslope switchback. TO is located about 5 to 10min before Devil Dream CG. The trail on the map is not representative of reality. TO is AFTER the Devil Dream Ck crossing. About 200m after the creek crossing you encounter the first safety pin switchback. TO is 30m past it.  We tried to put the TO at the exact easting and the closest northing of the original coordinate but impossible due to the imprecision of the GPS, very high PDOP. EE arm: bring gloves! 2015: Ran into a backcountry ranger. He said in the future to ask him or his supervisor for backcountry campground permits (i.e. Indian Henry Cabin, Devil's Dream, Deer Creek, etc...)
Location_desc: Point is on trail 3m after a series of 5 wood step-ups, next to 2 65-70cm dbh touching engleman spruce.

Travel_notes: 105m NE from TO.  Cross small creek 25m before point.
Location_desc: On NW side of 3m high ridge with depression at base in ca. 15x15m clearing, mature Mixed conifer woods.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m.  Through thick, big downed logs for first 80m, crossing mossy ck. bed at 100m.  Open, old Mixed conifer woods.  Stop 25m before next ck.
Location_desc: On pile of blowdown and mossy nurse logs in small depression, just before small rise.  Thick Western hemlock saplings to E.  Medium age Doug-fir/Western hemlock woods with Western redcedars. *Heads Up* The GPS puts you approximately 45m South of the actual point. The next surveyor may want to update the coordinates.

Travel_notes: Travel NE for 225m.  Cross small creek at 25m, another creek at 70m, pass a >122 cm DBH cat-faced Western redcedar at 85m, cross wide, shrubby, boggy creek at 108m, emerging from shrubs at 150m.  Cross a muddy, mossy tributary creek diagonally and continue up hill through open Doug-fir/western hemlock woods.  Cross on last small creek at 185m and stop just before next creek.
Location_desc: Point is 6m from edge of creek in Doug-fir/Western hemlock woods.  Downfall and rotting logs cover otherwise open forest floor.

Travel_notes: 230m between points.  Travel along and in creek bed fo first 75m, eventually crossing the creek just before the base of a slope.  Continue up the slope, crossing a 15m wide Vine maple chute at 130m.  Continue up hill through dim woods with many bare limbs on forest floor.
Location_desc: In dim Mixed conifer woods with very little understory vegetation and many bare branches and twigs on forest floor.  Open shrubby shoot areas visible to W and NE ca. 30m.

Travel_notes: 230m total.  Travel NE through dim woods for 30m.  Come to top of slope and descend slightly into dense, shrubby area, crossing small creek with shrub canopy at 40m.  There is an open clearing in shrubs on other side of creek.  Travel through thick Vine maple and Slide alder until 90m, when shrubby area begins to alternate with thick Pacific silver fir/Doug-fir stands with thick, dead branches to the ground.  At 166m shrubby chutes end and medium age Mixed conifer forest dominates until the point.
Location_desc: In area of downfall, with Western hemlock and Western redcedar saplings growing amoing midsized Doug-fir.  Dense woods with few distinguishing features.  Slight clearing with Vine maple 10m upslope.  More downfall downslope.

Travel_notes: Point is not quite 200m NE.  Traverse side of slope, heading gradually up hill through thick Mixed conifer woods with dense understory at times.  Round corner of ridge at 150m and decend steep slope with blowdown to creek.
Location_desc: On narrow ridge separating two creeks.  Ridge comes to point at intersection of creeks 28m below.  Pacific silver fir and Alaska yellow cedar grow on ridge, with alders, ferns and devil's club on creeks.

Travel_notes: Travel NE, crossing the creeks, then continue heading up and over through dense mysterious dark hobbit-like forest with many low branches and small downed logs.
Location_desc: Point is located near the bottom of a semi-open patch with a few vine maples surrounded by dense forest.

Travel_notes: Walk 122m on trail to reach point.
Location_desc: On stretch of ~N/S-running trail on a good moderate uphill grade.  There is a tall, narrow snag right off east side of trail with numerous PIWO nest holes.  Surrounding forest is dense young Western hemlock.  Crystal Creek audible.

Travel_notes: Walk 329m along trail.  Point is ~19m past an abrupt switchback which puts trail on a 203Â° heading.
Location_desc: On trail doglegging up through dense young hemlock and cedar.  There is a 1m high boulder on E side of trail with Western hemlock growing atop of it - roots twined down around it.

Travel_notes: Point 432m up trail, 20m past 8th switchback bend.
Location_desc: Point on a NE'erly stretch of switchback, where significant blowdown of smaller trees has occured on both sides.  To the NW is a ~65cm dbh Western hemlock with its heart rotted out and bared towards trail, but new leaders and growth above.  It stands among smaller, leaning Alaska yellow cedars and next to it is a holey, burned-black snag.

Travel_notes: Trail straightens out!  Walk 200m along trail to point.
Location_desc: On trail cut along steep slope, among dense Western hemlock forest.  There is a slight canopy opening here, a lone slide alder just upslope, and plenty of dwarf dogwood (bunchberry) along edge of trail.

Travel_notes: Walk up trail 320m.
Location_desc: Point on trail where canopy opens up on upslope (east) side of trail for 15m of sandy, eroded slope.

Travel_notes: Walk 200m up trail.  After pleasant clearing and trail split, proceed 40m further to point.
Location_desc: Point on trail in medium Western hemlock forest, with ample vacciniu, Oregon-grape, and false Azalea undergrowth.

Travel_notes: Head SE for 200m - at first staying with trail but cleaving away after about 15m.  Slope increases steadily up through truly mixed conifer woods - Doug-fir, Western hemlock, Alaska yellow cedar, at least two species of Abies.  You'll hit an old grown-over trail that you can more or less follow for the last 25m.
Location_desc: Point on grown over trail on side of moderate-steep hill, which slopes away to the SW, W, and NW.  Fairly dry, open forest w/ vanilla leaf and false solomon's seal herbaceous layer.

Travel_notes: Head straight uphill to catch the trail and follow it for approximately 300m. Pass one switchback and when the trail switches to SE again continue for 75m and then cut off the trail, traveling about 8m downslope to the point.
Location_desc: Point is on a moderate slope with little ground cover in a mixed conifer forest. The point is 8m down slope from the trail.
TO located 200m from trailhead at bend from S to NE.  Just before bend, off the right side of trail there is a canopy opening and a slope downward towards creek.  Exposed roots in trail at point.

Travel_notes: Travel downslope due East, no good features.
Location_desc: In a small clearing with Pacific Sivler Fir and Hemlocks saplings. Marker tree is not visible from approach, somewhat hidden in a clump of close growing trees. Small patches of dense vaccinium.

Travel_notes: Path has open understory, but going down slope with a slight angle.  Mostly Pacific silver fir habitat. Cross stream right before point.
Location_desc: On slope next to stream/ ravine from snow melt.  Trees have lots of moss hanging down from branches.  Point is in bear grass and conifer saplings. Near some small downed snags.

Travel_notes: Terrain is uneven. Once you reach stream you start traveling upslope until about 130m terrain flattens out.
Location_desc: Somewhat open canopy with mossy Pacific silver fir saplings, and abundant bear grass.  Can hear stream due east. On slight slope with vaccinium.

Travel_notes: Start going down slope it gets steep.  Stream crossing covered by logs.
Location_desc: Open habitat with Beargrass and other shrubs. There is a 5th Pacific silver fir in front of cluster of 4 firs, closest to point. GPS ~15m off.

Travel_notes: Habitat varies between thick understory with conifer saplings, and easy traveling with no understory shrubs.
Location_desc: Point is in open patch of beargrass and Pacific silver fir saplings. On dry seep which cuts a wide path uphill.

Travel_notes: After big rock slope is very steep, and go straight up slope (it's a short climb).  Once you reach yellow cedars the slope levels out.
Location_desc: Open habitat with yellow cedars and subalpine fir.  Point has hardly any understory.  Continuing NE, habitat gets dense after point.  Point is in small clearing.

Travel_notes: Travel dense or shrubby upslope 90m. After 90m, rolling slight uphill downhill slopes in meadow, open terrain
Location_desc: In forested area, but a meadow is visible to the E (toward 20m snag). Not much vegetation at point. Crowded space of Western redcedar and Pacific silver fir, but you can see opening clearly. Somewhat open canopy.

Travel_notes: Majority of travel is flat. Slightly downhill as you approach point.
Location_desc: Open area sandwiched between Pacific silver fir and Alaska yellow cedar. Branches of silver fir feature lean over point.

Travel_notes: We camped at Olallie CG.  TO is about 2 miles- 1.3 to Wonderland Trail junction, and 0.5 miles up Wonderland Trail.  It took about 50 min to hike to TO, sweaty uphill hike, bring an extra shirt to change into!  Very nice CG.  No good features but very good GPS.
Location_desc: At edge of a small meadow

Travel_notes: Travel off trail down slope, through subalpine fir saplings.
Location_desc: On downward slope surrounded by subalpine fir and Mountain Hemlock saplings with many snags.  Marker visible from approach.

Travel_notes: Travel along slope, no good features
Location_desc: On little slope, area covered in bear grass.

Travel_notes: Travel along slope, pace 200 m easy terrain.  Many snags, no good travel features.
Location_desc: Open patch with no ground cover, subalpine fir forest with few saplings, on slanted slope. There is a small Western hemlock to the right in front of shared base (feature), ~15cm DBH, and another small Pacific silver fir 1m away on the left, 3m high and <10cm DBH.

Travel_notes: Traverse along slope (easy terrain), then go upslope when you reach the ravine.
Location_desc: Point is on slope surrounded by Pasific silver fir saplings and bear grass.  To the SW slope is very steep. 10ft. snag now leans downhill a little and is next to another snag (45dbh)  that is barkless at the bottom but has bark from middle to top, and has large scar at the bottom. In area with downed logs, beargrass, vaccinium and silver fir saplings.

Travel_notes: Travel along slope, slope becomes hilly going up then down.
Location_desc: On slope with Subalpine fir and Doug fir saplings and bear grass.  East facing steep slope, west facing bumpy gentle slope. Right next to 2 Doug-firs, 1.5m apart. One is 95cm DBH and the other 60cm DBH. Canopy is very open, can see 70% of sky. Snag has a few short branches.

Travel_notes: Travel through saplings and low shrubs. Cross trail (GPS wrong where trail is) and back into forest. Relatively flat.
Location_desc: Relatively  flat terrian with lots of Pacific silver fir saplings and bear grass. Two Pacific silver firs to the 3 mountain hemlocks (feature) left are curled around each other, ~40cm DBH. Need to confirm that 3 mtn hemlocks feature are actually hemlocks!

Travel_notes: Easy travel, relatively flat.
Location_desc: Open canopy w/ saplings to the N. Mainly Western hemlocks and Pacific silver firs with shrub sparsely carpeting ground. Can see 70% of sky. There are 2 cedars sharing a base (DBH ~20cm) to the left of and behind the 3m tall silver fir (feature), 20m away.

Travel_notes: Travel in undulating open forest, up slope at first, then down a bit, then with last 30m steeper uphill climb.
Location_desc: Vanilla leaf understory and very little other vegetation. Western hemlock forest on a slope, 3m from 2 100cm DBH Western hemlocks to the SE and SW. Some saplings and blueberry/shrub vegetation to NE.

Travel_notes: Pace 100m along trail.
Location_desc: none

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is just past (50cm) a waterbar and directly next to a 50cm tall stump.

Travel_notes: walk down trail 100m to junction with Van Trump Park trail. Take this trail and walk about 1110m uphill. A stream is audible on the right.
Location_desc: Point is among a mixed stand of hemlock, Silver fir, Doug-fir and cedar. It is on the left bend as the trail goes uphill. There are three waterbars just ahead on trail (within 10m).

Travel_notes: Trail continues to climb uphill. Area to the right of trail becomes more steep. Silver fir become more dominant.
Location_desc: Point is on inconspicuous area on trail. There is a waterbar just before the point.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: There is a 30 cm high rotting stump just off the trail to the right of the point. two roots extend out from it across the trail directly on the point. Along the sides of the trail are beargrass and hucklberry.

Travel_notes: As trail continues to climb. More Doug-firs present.
Location_desc: Five meters from point at same bearing as stump (about 160 degrees) there are 3 large trees in a row. Two large Doug-fir (80 and 60 dbh) and one hemlock (50 dbh).

Travel_notes: Pace up trail 200m. Hike up long set of steps. Point is at second-to-last step. There is another set of steps just ahead, about 16m away.
Location_desc: Point is at second-to-last step in a long series of steps. To the right are two whitish-colored snags very close together. Up ahead, about 16m away, is another set of steps.

Travel_notes: Keep steppin' on that trail.
Location_desc: Point is just before you reach saddle-dip bordered by 2 roots in the ground.

Travel_notes:
TO is located on Wonderland Trail ~300m past junction with Rampart Ridge Trail. Trail on map doens't match up with UTMs. 
If camping at Pyramid Creek campground: Very buggy. Bring tent and head net if possible. 45 minute hike to TO.
If staying in Longmire, ~45-50 minute hike. EXTREMELY buggy transect.
Location_desc: none

Travel_notes: Travel through Pacific Silver Fir and dense shrub for 100m.
Location_desc: Point is indistinct, on edge of small patch of Hemlock without shrubs, next to 10cm dbh Pacific Silver Fir.

Travel_notes: travel west for 200m through Pacific Silver Fir/shrub mix. Occasional spots without understory are patchy and make travel easier.
Location_desc: Point is upon hillock, steep elevation change down to north. Shrubs lie southwest. Point is in stand of Douglas Fir without much understory.

Reason_for_change: avoid dropping down. Stay on ridge.
Travel_notes: travel SW for 200m
Location_desc: Point is in open stand of Western Hemlock, Douglas Fir, Western Red Cedar and Pacific Silver Fir. A Douglas Fir(25cm dbh) Pistol-grip is within arms reach.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m along slope in SW direction
Location_desc: Point is on slope, precisely 2m uphill from 70cm dbh Cedar with cut along side. Point is also between two stumps.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m at SW bearing, at first relatively open understory then increasingly dense until clearing south of point.
Location_desc: Point located on north (downhill) end of small clearing in Pacific Silver Fir woods. Point next to some very young Pacific Silver Firs and 4 large Pacific Silver Firs almost lined up east-west.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m at SW bearing along mild sideslope. First 100m, understory is relatively dense; @100m, understory opens up as you enter more mature hemlock/fir woods.
Location_desc: Point located in fir/hemlock woods with fairly open understory. Moderately steep slope heads down to the north where there is a very large rotting mossy log. Immediately 2.5m NNW of point there is a small (~15cm DBH) hemlock with deformed growth ("witch's broom") in its branches.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m along SW bearing, going slightly downhill along sideslope. Relatively open understory makes for pretty mellow travel.
Location_desc: Point located in relatively flat, open mixed conifer woods. Steeper slopes visible ~15m north and south on either side of point. Minor drainage visible ~30m to the NE.

Travel_notes: Travel through dense saplings.
Location_desc: point is on *very* old mossy stump in small clearing ringed by PASF + WEHE

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: In meadow on steep slope with rocky faces above. A few boulders strewn about in meadow. Great view with Hood and Adams at sunrise.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On relatively straight section of trail, with flat meadow clearing to the SE/E of point.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Right before footbridge across small intermittent stream.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Small stream running down center of meadow W of point. At point on trail where S travel is going up. A few small mtn. hemlocks to the E of point.

Travel_notes: To avoid being too close to points on 4014, NE05 is ~550m from NE04 as the raven flies.
Location_desc: Next to small stream in meadow. Point is in between 2 board bridge and plastic culvert placed between 2 boards.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Snag forest next to point.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On bank of stream before trail begins to turn left after crossing bridge. Rainier very visible if clear.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On small uphill section of trail before reaching one of the larger "lakes."

Travel_notes: Follow trail past 2 "lakes."
Location_desc: More densely forested area with many roots exposed on trail. On straight section after slight bend in trail

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Shrubby clearing area with pond.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Pyramid Peak is clearly visible when not cloudy. Flat and straight section of trail with sort of clear view down into glacial basin.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: At edge of flat section in large grassy basin. Two small stream channels meander across basin.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On uphill section of trail. Can see Adams through break in trees. At a section of trail with wooden steps.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: In area without many small trees immediately next to point. In years with a lot of snow, this would likely be snow-covered.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Small treeless area on inner elbow of hairpin.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On flat section of trail along floor of small valley.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Next to ??? with a meadow clearing to the right when walking down trail. (QA note- couldn't read this! Please make sense of this next visit.)

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is right before a series of small steps proceeding down trail. Subalpine meadows with clumps of firs. Can see where ridgeline continues as the trail drops below it.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: At point of hairpin switchback. Forested downslope with subalpine meadow visible on slope uphill.

Travel_notes: Camped in the Pyramid Peak x-country zone and hiked about 15 minutes to the TO.
Location_desc: Cliff face to the N, Mt. Rainier to the NE.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: Point just after the curve. Can see an opening in the forest SE of the road, opening was flooded in 2014.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: The point is right next to Shaw creek sign (west side of the bridge)

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is near outcrop rock, right next to the 1st one that has a creek running down from it. There is a patch of devil's club on the north side of the road, just NW of point.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point next to a 125cm dbh Douglas Fir, there is a gap in the forest that allows you to see it well.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Can see Shaw creek bridge from point. Forest with a lot of young Pacific Silver Fir

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: The point is located between 2 curves (~30m and ~60m) on road, just before a little creek

Travel_notes: Pass next to 5 creeks coming down slope SE of the road.The first creek is only 5m away from point 06. The point is located 15m away from the 5th creek.
Location_desc: Point is located just before a patch of shrub on SE side of road, 70m after a curve in the road

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is near 2 mile marker on the road

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is on road just before gully with creek. There is a patch of 5 alders next to point. Mostly hemlock and pacific silver fir forest with small alder and cedar.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point located in Western Hemlock forest w/ steep drop on north side of road and steep incline on south side of road. Curve visible ~135m to the west.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point on road between 2 curves (~200m apart). Western Hemlock forest with some big Douglas Firs. Lots of deadfall to north, mossy hillside to the south.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Ranger station can be see from point (340m away). There are 4 snags in open spot in forest (SE of road)

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is on W end of parking area just inside the park at White River Entrance. Big ol' doug fir is conspicuous.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point on nondescript spot on road 100m from TO, in area with a lot of downfall. There are several rotten stumps on either side of the road. Point is on the NW side.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Nondescript point on road. Point in ditch next to enbankment (NW side of road). There is a large downed tree on top of the embankment that runs parallel to the road.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point at nondescript place on road, long straight away, use GPS. Located just after culvert.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point in small opening on NW side of the road. Small scree pile present. Rock outcropping on opposite side of road.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: point on side of road, next to pond shown on map

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is on road side parking lot, a second boulder past service road (west side).

Location_desc: none

Location_desc: Point on road at beginning of a turn out.

Location_desc: Point on road, in straight way between 2 turns

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point located shortly after creek cuts close to road. There is a long line of boulders on the side of the road. The point is approximately 18m before the first boulder.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is road-side pull out just before frying pan creek bridge

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point in ditch next to road (NE side).

Travel_notes: T.O. is 300m before Shaw creek sign/bridge (if coming from White River CG). We parked the car on pullout right before bridge. TO is 160m before the pullout. We camped at White River CG, 10-15 min driving in the morning
Location_desc: None

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point in mostly Doug-fir forest ~100 from TO on trail

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point in Doug-fir forest 80m after crossing Maple creek on trail

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point in Doug-fir forest with view of talus slopes + rock face to west

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point located in Doug-fir/Western hemlock forest directly after wash on slight incline

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point in Doug-fir/Western hemlock forest with vine maple mid-story

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point in Doug-fir forest next to side arm of stream and just down trail from flat rock (8m away)

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is in river bed next to the trail, which is covered in a huge snow bank

Travel_notes: Trail mainly in river bed, then open talus/ alder
Location_desc: Point in open shruby area with talus slopes on one side and river on the other. Many red alders

Travel_notes: First 100m in open shrubby area with talus slopes.
Location_desc: Point in thick Western hemlock/Western redcedar forest with thick vine maple midstory. The rumble of sylva fall can be faintly heard.

Travel_notes: Follow trail up sustained incline into forest of mostly Doug-fir and Western red cedar. Talus slope is visible through trees on left (SW).
Location_desc: Point is in Doug-fir / Western red cedar forest with talus slope visible through trees on left (SW), just before several sawed logs on either side of trail.

Travel_notes: continue along trail; point is at the end of a large open patch you'll pass on your left. I attempted to set this point off-trail but the slope was too steep directly before would-be point.
Location_desc: on trail just before boulder on left (S) side of trail. On edge of a shrubby patch of vegetation.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: The point is near the river, which is loud, in a douglas fir forest. East of point there are 2 Western red cedar snags with burn marks on them.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is on a sandy part of trail just after it turns from going E to SE. The forest is really open here.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: The point is next to a creek at the NE end of 2nd boardwalk

Travel_notes: Go gently up. Open forest with a lot of downed trees to go over.
Location_desc: Point on a gentle NE facing slope. You can see the river. Open Douglas Fir forest with a lot of Red Alder. Lots of downed trees around. Between 2 small Western Hemlocks.

Travel_notes: Going gently up. Have to pass on top/around a lot of downfall. Open understory. The first 80m parallel an old trail.
Location_desc: Point is at the edge of outcrop (you can't see the rocks- they are under moss, under you!!!) with a really steep slope ~15m drop. There are more outcrops around.

Travel_notes: Travel on uneven ground. Lots of up and down. Understory becomes more dense after 140m. Lots of downed trees to go over.
Location_desc: Point is located in east facing slope. Douglas Fir forest with vine maple understory. Also lots of young Western Hemlocks. 2014 update: I was unable to locate the single feature from last visit, so I created new features at same GPS coordinates (or as close as I could possibly get). Point is located just west/uphill of an old elk trail.

Travel_notes: Following direct bearing will take you over a cliff at ~150m; I found an elk trail just north of bearing that followed a reasonable descent down slope.
Location_desc: Point located in clearing below tree-covered slope on relatively flat ground. Vine maple and salmonberry with some large red alders fill the clearing, and douglas firs and western hemlocks dominate the slope above.

Travel_notes: Note: NO coordinates 2020 - to find point, add appropriate numbers to you SE07 coordinates listed ON NAV REPORT - not to the coordinates reading on your GPS. Description: Cross drainage area into conifers to find elk trail leading towards point. Exit trail at150m into opening on forest floor. There is a small rise in the topography to your right as you enter the opening, keep this to your right as you traverse around it into a small drainage ditch. Walk down the ditch 20-30m then climb up onto rise in topo to your right (mentioned above).
Location_desc: Point is on small hill covered in shrubs and conifers. There is some dead stumpage right next to point, and a large mound, presumably debris from the rotting stump rising out of it, to the NNW.

Travel_notes:
The TO is about a 5 min walk from Maple Creek CG (not on the map, SE of Maple creek) (4th site by far the nicest!)
Shorter hike from Stevens Canyon (1.7 mi) versus Box Canyon parking lots (2.4 mi) but ultimately both pretty short backpacks in. If you have the time, go check out Sylvia Falls (up the Wonderland Trail to the west).
Location_desc: Point located on Wonderland trail in mainly Western Hemlock forest. Point is where steep enbankment to river starts (coming from the east)

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On trail, 100m from spur in trail. Beautiful view of St. Helens to the S. There are 2 stacked boulders blanketed by 3 different species of saplings.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On trail, located just beyond "stairs" section in trail, right before another steeper section leading to small stream.

Travel_notes: Trail on GPS is WAY off. May help to pace 200m.
Location_desc: On trail in clearing, with shrubs and a few Subalpine fir saplings. Falls are audible from below.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On trail with one switchback directly between point and the falls. Distance and bearing of funky tree/root system feature is to the stump.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is in wide open area next to river, between 2 small draining streams with rock/log artificial "irrigation" through trail.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On trail, just below rocky "stairs" section of trail. Shrubby and open.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On trail, just past a small scree slope that has much smaller rocks than previous scree slopes. 30m from entering more forested area.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On trail, just past exit of more forested area. Open and shrubby down trail from point.

Travel_notes: Travel 100m away (as crow flies) from intersection down from Van Trump Point.
Location_desc: Point is right after a 90 degree bend in trail. Near 1m long flat-topped rock. Point is farther than 100m from TO to avoid being too close to SE01.

Travel_notes: Cross log bridge at ~30m and continue on trail near river.
Location_desc: River is visible through an opening in canopy- can see mtns. poking up over far ridge (across river).

Travel_notes: Continue on trail. Pass through level meadow and continue along ridge.
Location_desc: Mt. Rainier visible at 10 degrees. Point is surrounded by lots of beargrass.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is surrounded by a small patch of meadow. Lots of beargrass. Can barely see Mt. Rainier through trees.

Travel_notes: Continue along trail and enter into fairly dense forest of Pacific silver fir and Western hemlock.
Location_desc: Trail heads steeply downhill after point. There are many silver fir saplings just off trail, and a good number of snags.

Travel_notes: Count 4 switchbacks before you walk ~50m straight on section of trail to point. Trail slopes downward at point.
Location_desc: In mature Pacific silver fir forest. Lots of debris (downed trees near point) and beargrass.

Travel_notes: Continue along trail. Canopy opens up on your left somewhat.
Location_desc: In mature Western hemlock/Pacific silver fir forest with vaccinium and beargrass.

Travel_notes: Continue along trail.
Location_desc: Point is just past opening in canopy where trail flattens out. Lots of beargrass and young mtn. hemlocks surround point. Rainier is visible through trees.

Travel_notes: Continue 200m along trail.
Location_desc: Point is in Pacific silver fir forest with many snags.

Travel_notes: Continue 200m down trail.
Location_desc: Point is in mature silver fir forest. Some debris and downed trees on both sides of the trail.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m on trail.
Location_desc: In Pacific silver fir forest. Many downed logs and debris around trail. Trail goes downhill at point.

Travel_notes: 45-minute drive from Ohanapecosh and 1-hour long hike to TO (or 45 minutes if you're booking it).
Location_desc: none

Travel_notes: Travel North down ridge, almost exactly toward lake. Bear to the W of the lake.
Location_desc: Point is on slope of ridge heading toward lake. Lake and road visible to the N. Subalpine firs on ridge to S and W.

Reason_for_change: Lake Tipsoo crossed NN bearing at 130m from NN01. Ended up going on trail
Travel_notes: Travel down ridge to curve in road by pullout. Travel on road to the NW for ~125 m from pullout.
Location_desc: Point is on NW side of road, 9.6 m away from the "Rocks" sign on the same side. Guard rail on SE side. Good view of Rainier and Naches Peak from here. Naches Loop Trailhead sign is 85 m away.

Travel_notes: Travel on road for 200m.
Location_desc: Point is on N side of road about 30 m after passing a rock face. Lots of subalpine fir along road here. About 20 m past where guard rail starts on opposite side of road. About 20 m before start of pulloff to the NW.

Travel_notes: Travel 220 m on road from previous point. Pass pullover and travel along bottom of rock face to point. Point is about 80 m from the start of the rock face.
Location_desc: Point is on the NW side of the road, next to a large rock face and guard rail on other side. Cannot see Rainier from this point.

Travel_notes: Travel on road 200 m, traveling along rock face and around curve. Travel about 110m past where guard rail ends.
Location_desc: Point is next to rock face, just before a drain in road on N side. Point is on N side of road. It is between two 35 mph speed limit signs.

Travel_notes: Travel 200 m down road, past end of rock face to where terrain opens up to N.
Location_desc: Point is on N side of road, about 34 m after rock face ends. N side of road open slope-meadow. Mt. Rainier is clearly visible. More dense subalpine fir around road. Small runoff stream with drain is about 37 m W of point.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m along road.
Location_desc: On N side of road. Upslope of point are many young cedars.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m along road.
Location_desc: Across road from point is flat plateau- relatively open with some Subalpine firs. Large boulders N and NE of point.

Travel_notes: Travel up slope on N side of road. After ~30m, you'll come to a plateau. Continue toward small lake- point is on NW side of lake among Pacific silver firs and Mtn. hemlocks.
Location_desc: Small lake S of point, drainage from lake to E. Point is in Pacific silver fir/Mtn. hemlocks.

Travel_notes: Follow game trails, crossing drainage at ~50m.
Location_desc: Point is on slope in grove of young Alaska yellow cedars. Slope to the S is open- just vaccinium, beargrass, and lupine.

Travel_notes: Clamber up the ridge from TO.
Location_desc: Point just past stands of Subalpine fir, terrain is mostly open past the point. Tipsoo Lake and small pond easily visible. Mt. Rainier visible through the trees.

Reason_for_change: impassable steep, snowy slopes to N, NE, S, and SE
Travel_notes: Travel cross-country SW from SE01. SE02 is more like 170-175 m from SE01.
Location_desc: Point near base of steep slope to the NE. Fairly open and snowy with scattered stands of Subalpine fir and Mtn. hemlock. Mt. Rainier imposing to the W.

Travel_notes: Pace 220m cross-country from SE02 at a SW bearing. You should be able to stay in the "gullies" the whole way if it's snowy.
Location_desc: Point by "gully" just before dropoff. Mt. Rainier prominent to the W. Mixed conifer, Subalpine fir, and Mtn. hemlock stands surrounding the point. "Valley" below is mostly open.

Reason_for_change: steep, snowy, slippery, impassible slope (without ice axe)
Travel_notes: Travel x-country W from SE03. Undulating terrain.
Location_desc: Point at edge of open area near beginning of slope. Road with rock outcroppings on both sides visible to the N. Mt. Rainier is no longer visible.

Travel_notes: Cross open, treeless expanse and enter grove of Subalpine firs.
Location_desc: Point is in grove of Subalpine firs.

Travel_notes: About a 5-10-minute hike to TO from pulloff in front of Tipsoo Lake (not the picnic area and restrooms parking lot). 25-minute drive from Ohanapecosh.
Location_desc: TO is in between patches of subalpine fir. Just N of TO, you can still see the lake. At TO, you can see the road.
Location_notes: The TO had to be moved due to proximity to the park boundary. At its intended location, at least one arm would not have been able to avoid crossing over the boundary. It was moved to a location that was far enough from the boundary to allow a sufficient number of points on each arm within the park.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point on road north of trail leading to Patrol Cabin, and just north of trail leading to Dennan Fall (north side of River)

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point on road in Doug-fir and hemlock forest.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is on curvy section of road, just up from road gap in small wall.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is in Doug-fir forest on road.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point on Road in Doug-fir forest, nondescript. 2014 update: Unable to locate "small triangular / pointed boulder on side of road."

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is located on straight-away of road near large grove of vine maple (on top of embankment).

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is on straight-away of road, in Fir/Doug-fir//hemlock forest

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point on curve in road across from large nearly treeless embankment on E side of road. No real distinguishable features present. 2014 update: Unable to locate "boulder on edge of embankment leading downhill (west) 1mx5m."

Travel_notes: Pace 200 m up road. There is a rock outcropping on the right and a fairly open view on the left.
Location_desc: Point located on road, on straightaway between two curves, just past a black cottonwood (?) with 20 dbh. View is hindered by patch of fir.

Travel_notes: Lots of big down trees to go over/under. Be careful.
Location_desc: open Western Hemlock forest. The road can be seen between the trees. Lots of downed trees.

Travel_notes: Travel in thick young Western Hemlock understory.
Location_desc: lots of bare snags around. On a mossy downed log just uphill of an imaginary straight line between two ~1m DBH Douglas firs.

Travel_notes: Really thick young Western Hemlock (2m) understory. Hard to navigate through. 2014 - unable to locate features, used GPS coordinates to get as close as possible.
Location_desc: Point is in Western Hemlock/Douglas Fir forest. A lot of snags and downed trees. On a slope w/ creek audible to the north.

Travel_notes: Understory opens up! Lots of snags and logs to cross.
Location_desc: Point is in open Western Hemlock/Douglas Fir forest. Lots of <1m Western Hemlock. Lots of downed trees surrounding the point. Point is located next to small, twisted rotting stump. Vaccinium dominates understory.

Travel_notes: Fairly open and flat travel.
Location_desc: Point on top of downed log in open, Doug-fir/hemlock forest. Silver fir and vaccinium understory. Many snags and downed trees in area.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m @ 135 degrees through open hemlock woods. Travel is mostly uphill, some level. First 20-30m through dense saplings and over downed logs.
Location_desc: Point located on a mild slope in open hemlock woods. Young silver fir and vaccinium make up understory; some downed trees though not as much as at previous points. Next to mound that used to be old rotting stump.

Travel_notes: Travel mostly flat through huckleberry understory. ~50m from point trees get smaller and canpoy gets denser.
Location_desc: Point in small opening next to >1m DBH sharp snag ~10-12m tall. Had snow in 2020. Point directly between sharp snag and smaller 3m snag stump (~75cm DBH).

Travel_notes: There is no good cross country camp around there (not that we could find). Try to arrange camping at the Ranger Station if possible. 2014: Stayed at St. Andrew's Patrol Cabin. Accessed via Westside Road - we rode bikes, making it a fairly quick and easy (despite lots of uphill pedaling) day of travel.
Location_desc: TO located next to pullout just down road from St-Andrew Creek Bridge.

Travel_notes: Travel up trail to N/NW for about 120 m. Travel up steep slope, then trail levels out before point.
Location_desc: Point is on flat section of trail, near a large pile of downed logs. Lots of broken-off trees and woody debris in area.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is on slope, almost at top of a ridge. Top is visible from point. There is a downed log just next to point and marked tree. Lots of small jagged stumps on top of ridge and several large hemlocks to the W.

Travel_notes: Travel 200 m W to point. Travel along side of ridge for ~50 m, then drop down along contour into flat area.
Location_desc: Point is on flatter ground next to steep ridge, river valley below to NW. Point is in area with a lot of stumps and fallen logs. It is right next to an old rotten log and stump. Feature silver fir is in group of lots of silver firs around point.

Travel_notes: Travel 200 m across flat ground. Drop down a slight slope toward river, but point is before steep dropoff down to Lee Creek.
Location_desc: Point is in flat area, just before steep dropoff to Lee Creek. Some of river is visible from point, but not all of it. Stump is pretty distinctive, one side is way longer than the other and it is right next to point.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On slope with no understory, lots of woody debris on ground. On ridgeline with small depressions on either side. A couple of large Doug-firs (80cm DBH) visible from point, behind cedar feature.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: 3 snags in triangle formation. The nearest one is the feature with shelf fungus. Lots of hemlock saplings immediately upslope. Many other downed logs in area, all older. On a slope.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On slope with many small cedar saplings in immediate area. Two downed logs, crossed right next to point.

Travel_notes: It is easiest to travel along the trail for 100 m until the correct northing and then exit the trail to the west, going 20 m downslope.
Location_desc: Point is in open Western hemlock forest with nonexistent understory except for a few saplings and lots of downed logs. Large rock 3 m uphill from point. Point in very small depression.

Travel_notes: Easiest travel may be to return to trail and head S for 200 m until the correct Northing, then head west down slope for ~40 m.
Location_desc: Point in open Western hemlock forest with lots of downed trees. Point at large mossy rock about 40 m downslope from trail.

Travel_notes: Return to trail from SS02 and travel uphill along trail until you reach correct coordinates.
Location_desc: Point is along uphill portion of trail in mixed Western hemlock/yellow cedar forest. Spray Creek can be heard to the S.

Travel_notes: Travel 250 m down trail from SS03 through mixed hemlock/cedar forest, passing Eagle Cliffs viewpoint spur trail at 65m.
Location_desc: Cedar/hemlock forest with steep slopes on both sides of trail. Thin understory of vaccinium N of point.

Travel_notes: Pace 250 m down trail. Undulating and winding travel.
Location_desc: Steep slopes on both sides of trail. Downslope has lots of hemlock saplings. Upslope is more open with large, mossy rock face protruding at about 50m. Spray Falls is fairly loud.

Travel_notes: Travel 250 m on trail, winding and easy. Make sure to stay toward Spray Park.
Location_desc: Fairly steep slopes on both sides of trail. Creek close and visible. Mostly Pacific silver fir forest with a few western hemlocks and cedars, too.

Travel_notes: Travel 475 m up trail. Travel is steep and rocky and there are lots of switchbacks.
Location_desc: Point in mostly Pacific silver fir forest with tons of small snags around. Open forest and steep. Scattered groundcover of beargrass. Lots of lichen hanging from trees.

Travel_notes: Travel 450m up trail, encountering one major switchback. Point is ~240m as the crow flies from SS07.
Location_desc: Point is in fairly dense mixed conifer forest with open understory. Mostly snow-covered in 2011. At point in trail with small drainage on upslope side, many rocks visible out of mud on upslope side as well.

Travel_notes: Travel through Subalpine fir habitat, snow-covered in 2011. Travel about 300m.
Location_desc: Snow-covered in 2011. On ridge at edge of mixed conifer forest looking down on Grant Creek below. Hessong Rock is to the NW. Great view.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is in area with meadow on one side and forested on the other. Meadow is draining significant water all across it. Can still see Hessong Rock. Small steps at area where point is located.

Travel_notes: 25-minute hike from Mowich Lake Camp. Campground is about a 2.5-hour drive from Longmire.
