Location_desc: In Western hemlock forest, fairly mature with lots of saplings. At a large cedar with roots sprawling across trail.

Travel_notes: Take the trail until ~30m away - then cut off to point.
Location_desc: Point is in a douglas fir/western hemlock forest on west side of dry river channel. Thick huckleberry surrounds point, however at point, there is very limited understory.

Travel_notes: Flat travel through vaccinium.
Location_desc: Point is in relatively open forest with some blow downed trees. Point is on 45cm dbh downed western hemlock running perpendicular to bearing (part of the "T" feature).

Travel_notes: Travel through relatively open forest with many blow downs
Location_desc: Point is in an impressive doug fir/western hemlock forest. Directly at point is a 1.5m splintered stump.

Travel_notes: Travel throught open forest with many downed logs to flat, sandy river channel. Point is 5m before open river channel.
Location_desc: Point is in a flat, rocky defunct river channel rise with a sandy tree covered channel to the east. There is a small stand of cedars ~7m to the W.

Travel_notes: Travel through forest, then rocky, open river channel.
Location_desc: Point is in river channel about 15m from flowing river (this may change!). A large burnt parch of forest is seen to the south. On the edge of some alder. To the W (across river) are a bunch of tall Red alders.

Travel_notes: Walk away from river at 90 degree bearing. Right before point, you climb up a short steep slope. Once at the top, point is ~6m from there.
Location_desc: Point is on a downed tree with a large branch coming off of it (where point is). It is ~6m SE from the edge of a steep slope down (toward river). Lots of silver fir saplings.

Travel_notes: Walk on level terrain through forest-- many downed trees, but travel isn't bad. Cross unmaintained trail at ~150m.
Location_desc: Point is in a mossy spot with some vaccinium, but less than in surrounding areas. There is a moss-covered boulder ~2.5m E of point. Look for the leaning hemlock- it's distinctive.

Travel_notes: Walk through similar terrain until you reach a small creek at ~80m. Cross this, then climb up short, steep bank. Gradual slope over many downed trees to point.
Location_desc: Point is in a mossy area with less understory than much of the surrounding area. There is a downed tree suspended in air ~6 ft. up, ~1.5m W of point. There are several large downed trees within 5m upslope of point.

Travel_notes: Travel on trail until near perpendicular to point (about 70 degrees bearing). Travel off trail over some downed logs to point,
Location_desc: Point is surrounded by downed logs almost like a fence. Red Stone Peak can be seen from point. In little dip in the ground with small rocks. Next to 1.5m x 1.5m flat boulder.  A downed cedar is running perpendicular to the dip area and is broken in 3 places.

Travel_notes: Travel through a lot of down fall. Last 43m in the rocky river bed.
Location_desc: Point on rocky river bed, 17m from the east bank. There is a little creek flowing in this part of the river. The main river is flowing on the other side of tree strip to W (82m).

Travel_notes: After entering the forest follow (go around) the edge of the collapse for 22m. After this it's easy walking in the forest.
Location_desc: Point is in open forest with a lot of large douglas firs and downed logs, not much understory. Just next to a 150cm dbh douglas fir and in between 2 pacific silver firs (5 and 15cm dbh). GPS ~25-30m off. (Need to check bearing on "very pale barkless snag" feature, bearing is either 332 or 352 but handwriting was hard to read)

Reason_for_change: rock wall at 150m to SE and E
Travel_notes: Go up across/up slope with a lot of downed trees.
Location_desc: Point on NW facing slope surrounded by downed fall

Travel_notes: Steep, with many logs and sometimes dense understory; still, not unmanageable.
Location_desc: Point is on moss-covered ground in Western hemlock forest. Feature #1 is mostly barkless and has fallen downslope. A 70cm DBH Doug-fir with small Pacific silver fir rooted at the base is ~5m upslope (see photo).

Travel_notes: Not as steep as from SS04 to SS05.
Location_desc: Point is at a triple Western hemlock with one main trunk (DBH ~80cm) and 2 smaller trunks. One of the smaller trunks is a snag ~12m tall. A tall tree (DBH ~30cm) has fallen between them. Many Western hemlock and Pacific silver fir saplings. A large moss-covered log is ~3m away.

Travel_notes: Fairly dense with some large logs.
Location_desc: Point is adjacent to 4 fallen trees, one of which (a cedar) has many branches. There is a clearing at about 155 degrees, 15m away with many fir seedlings.

Travel_notes: About a 9-mile hike from Sunrise. We combined this with 4083 and 4011 to do the full Northern Loop Trail, which was a great 4-day hike! It is a long day going from 4068 to Mystic Lake, though; you might want to take 5 days. TO is before the west fork trail (about 400m). We camped in the west fork x-country zone. Okay camping along the now unmaintained west fork trail. Looked like there might be good camping near NN04 too. Do not approach from yellowstone cliff early in the season or in high snow years. Be aware that GPS may have low accuracy (up to 20m off). SS arm after SS03 is fairly steep with occasional dense understory.
Location_desc: TO is in a forested flood plain of the west fork river. Douglas fir and Western hemlock dominate (with some very large trees around!). TO is on the trail ~17m after a "dip" in the trail (if coming from Sunrise) where a dry river chanel passes through 2 large douglas-firs straddle the trail by river channel.

Travel_notes: 135m on trail from TO
Location_desc: Point is on a sloped part of trail in relatively open Western Hemlock forest. Many cut logs around and some broken snags.

Travel_notes: 212m on trail from NE01
Location_desc: Point is on trail 12m before a switch back(feature) in open western hemlock forest, Pistol grip snag at switchback

Travel_notes: 225m on trail from NE02
Location_desc: none

Travel_notes: 298m on trail from NE03
Location_desc: Point is on bend in trail at a nice view point looking into Kautz ck. There is a large flat rock at foot of point.

Travel_notes: 200m on trail from NE04
Location_desc: Point is on sloped and rocky part of the trail in Western Hemlock forest, right after passing vine maple bush(feature) . Steep slope to W. There are quite a few twin/shared base western hemlocks, feature one in area across from vine maple with other small hemlocks

Travel_notes: 225m on tail from NE05
Location_desc: Point is on trail in open Western Hemlock forest with bear grass ground cover

Travel_notes: Point is about 210m on trail from NE06
Location_desc: Point is on flat portion of trail in Western Hemlock forest, relatively indistinctive. Turn in trail 30m away

Travel_notes: Point is about 313m on trail from NE07
Location_desc: Point is in Western Hemlock forest in a small opening. Point is just before a bend in the trail.

Travel_notes: Travel ~202 meters down trail
Location_desc: Water bar and cut is ahead on trail next to bright silver Pacific silver fir (DBH ~30cm). Entwined Pacific silver firs are on left side of the trail as you go down. The point is on trail 10m past a large stump on the left side.

Travel_notes: Continue on trail 193 meters
Location_desc: Between perpendicular log 0.5m off trail and stump 1m off trail. The 60cm DBH Doug-fir and 40cm DBH Western hemlock almost share a base and lean away from each other. They are on the right side of the trail before the point.

Travel_notes: Clear understory at first, then it gets more dense as you head downslope. Easy travel
Location_desc: Point is at a 1m tall 80cm DBH stump with a couple Western hemlock saplings growing from it. Just E of a small clearing. Clearing has a rootwad rounded like an ant mount with large (~60cm DBH) downed tree with massive tangle of branches. The pistol-gripped Pacific silver fir is also in the clearing. There is also a Western redcedar 5m away with a 10cm DBH.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is at a ~1m tall stump (~70cm DBH). There are a few small roots or dead vines growing on it. Pleasant woodland. A cedar (~70cm DBH) is 2m away (one of only 2 seen in vicinity).

Travel_notes: Walk in open forest with lots of downed logs.
Location_desc: Point is in Western Hemlock/ Doug fir forest. Lots of the trees around have markers on them.

Travel_notes: Walk 200m in open forest with lots of downed logs,easy travel
Location_desc: Point in open Western Hemlock/Douglas fir forest, with a lot of downed trees/snags/root balls.

Travel_notes: First 80m fairly flat. Then go down a rock outcrop (go around by south side). Travel goes down after the outcrop.
Location_desc: Point on south facing slope with a lots of downed trees and snags next to a 75cm rotting stump. Large fallen S-shaped hemlock near point. Ground covered in lichen and saplings

Travel_notes: Go gently up the whole time.
Location_desc: Point is in open forest on a small south facing slope, lots of downed trees and snags around. Mossy area, beargrass. Lots of salal especially to the N/E. Western hemlock snags with bark are abundant. Somewhat open canopy at the point; you can see the sky well with only 40% canopy cover from trees. Adjacent hemlock/cedar feature is towards the hemlock

Travel_notes: Travel in open forest with a lots of downed trees.
Location_desc: Point in Western Hemlock/Douglas fir forest on the SE edge of opening in canopy. Lots of downed trees around. In an opening with moss, bear grass and salal. About 60-70% of sky visible. Many small snags and stumps of 20cm dbh, 1-10m tall.

Travel_notes: At 100m intense downhill. Downed tres, no groundcover and Western hemlock forest. First 100 easy travel with beargrass/moss and Western hemlocks

Reason_for_change: In danger of running into potential added points of 4025 if we cont. 270 degrees.
Travel_notes: Travel down side of slope with lots of downed trees. Patches of beargrass and moss 80-130m from SW06.
Location_desc: Western hemlock forest with some smaller dbh cedars. Many barkless and barked snags. No undergrowth, just downed trees.

Travel_notes: Side slope walking slow with lots of downed trees. No undergrowth or groundcover. Tall 60-80cm dbh predominantly Western hemlock forest. Cross small mossy stream approx 40-45m before reaching point
Location_desc: Western hemlock forest. Point right next to a creek (if you cross the creek to the other side, you are past the point). Small hemlock saplings and sword fern follow edges of creek. Quite a few snags, especially at E and N of point; densest hemlock sapling patch to N of point.

Travel_notes: Take the trail of the Shadows and then the Rampart Trail. TO is just before the 6th switchback (about 22m before) and 19m after the trickle of water. We camped at Cougar Rock, which takes about 10 minutes to get to from Longmire. From the Longmire Complex, it takes about 30 minutes to get to TO. NE01 and NE03 are located about 125 m apart due to intense switchbacks and lack of GPS reception (thick fog). The trail on the map is not representative of reality.
Location_desc: Point is on turning section of trail in open forest (Western Hemlock). Large flat area to S with many downed trees. Both features are on trail on right side.

Travel_notes: Head uphill to point 01, marker visible from approach.
Location_desc: Open forest with many small Pacific Silver firs. One large hemlock near point and a few downed logs too. (Next visit: check if hemlocks sharing base feature are snags or not)

Travel_notes: Continue east until you hit the trail. Continue 8 m upslope. GPS thinks point is 25-30m downhill, go up to trail near stream and use features to find point from there.
Location_desc: Upslope of trail, easily visible from point. Next to broken fallen logs. Streambed visible as well.

Travel_notes: Travel uphill for a short ways, then head downhill and across slope, crossing the trail and heading back into the forest. Three downed logs obvious. Point is 21m past.
Location_desc: On close side of large downed log with left end sticking up in the air. Point is 5m from the end of it, next to log. 2015: The 1m downed log pointing up is still there but the end has rotted off. Now only 3m away from end

Travel_notes: Travel slightly downhill to point 04. Easy walking, look for obvious features.
Location_desc: In open forest right by small hemlock saplings. Mostly barkless snag also right next to point. No groundcover at point but vine maple patch visible. Next to 70cm DBH hemlock. Silver fir feature is slightly hidden from point, better view of it from stump feature near point.

Travel_notes: Travel across slope, mostly downhill. Walk through large wet area and find stream at far end.
Location_desc: Open Pacific Silver fir forest. Just past wet area with ground cover. By a barkless downed log no moss (so far) ~60cm DBH.

Travel_notes: Travel across slope, down slightly and back up to point near river. Look for obvious snag close to point. Go past the cluster of stumps, fallen down tree, hemlock saplings. The location is like the picture where the ground is open with saplings. The GPS told me a location that was too dense, too many snags, and fallen trees.
Location_desc: On bank, 10m away from dropoff down to Laughingwater Creek. In open Pacific Silver fir forest. Very open. Smaller Pacific silver fir all around.

Travel_notes: Cross over creek, then climb pretty steep but short slope on other side of creek.
Location_desc: Very small creek right next to point. Two curved hemlocks near point and a small stump. Distance and bearing for cluster of 5 snags feature is to the shortest and thickest snag.

Travel_notes: Walk along trail and cross three major streams. Continue uphill to point where trail makes a huge obvious turn to the left. Point is in the middle of the bend. Trail on map is about 200m north of where it actually is, according to the GPS. We camped on the northwest side of the lake, about 1 mile in from Laughingwater Creek trailhead (cross-country zone permit required). From our site it took 1 hour to hike to TO, but from trailhead would be about 1.5 hours.
Location_desc: TO is on trail just as it bends to the left.
Location_notes: Trail is off on the map, so the TO needed to be offset about 240 m for it to be on-trail.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: Point located on slight southwest slope. Creek runs through plot to the south/southeast. Forest Western hemlock-dominated, with Doug fir, Pacific Silver fir, Western Red cedar across log. Point located at broken Pacific Silver fir in photo.

Travel_notes: Pass through many Pacific Fir saplings. Path crosses a few wet patches with lots of skunk cabbage. Then cross log over marsh or go around.
Location_desc: Flat area surrounded by vanilla leaf with Pacific Silver fir and Western Red cedar saplings. Can hear creek to the southwest about 50m (not visible). Point near 3 HUGE silver fir boardering marsh.

Travel_notes: Transect parallels trail for 50m (to north of trail) after it crosses trail.
Location_desc: Point located just past (7m) large fallen snag. Many large Doug firs present. Understory Vaccinium sp. after mossy ground cover.

Travel_notes: Path crosses over many large downed trees.
Location_desc: Next to a dip in slope with rotting snags and vine maple.

Travel_notes: Gentle sideslope over lots of downed trees.
Location_desc: On slope surrounded by Doug fir snags, DBH>122cm, vine maple.

Travel_notes: Cross small creek with vinemaple boarder.
Location_desc: On slanted slope, vine maple 20m upslope with young conifer saplings.

Travel_notes: Walk on slanted slope, relatively easy path, ending on game trail. 2015 note: game trail is no longer obvious.
Location_desc: On slanted slope, on wildlife trail next to 2 Doug firs DBH 40cm and 60cm.

Travel_notes: Travel is sideslope with little understory.
Location_desc: The point is in a clearing of vanilla-leaf, at the base of a lone, 2m tall vine maple that spreads downslope (see photo). There are no other vine maples downslope within ~30m, but there are many upslope. The Western red cedar doesn't initially stand out, but will hopefully be useful since there are only 2 or 3 red cears in the vicinity.

Travel_notes: Travel uphill into krummholz forest. Trees are patchy and the going is tough.
Location_desc: Point is un very undifferentiated patchy subalpine fir. Some deadwood and large down snags nearby. A cliff is present 20m to east.

Travel_notes: Travel up and through patchy krummholz forest. When you come to dropoff at 70m, spot your destination (flat gravel/heather area) directly beside brook. Then, follow the tops of large grey boulders to your left until you reach a more gradual talus slope down--watch your step!
Location_desc: Point is on flat opening where the outlet brook from Frozen Lake drains. Amazing view from Rainier clear to Eastern mountains. Some blocky grey bedrock with white veins exposed at site. Also heather and gravel. Brook is 5m to the north. Trail seen across talus slope to north.

Travel_notes: Travel features unimportant here, because you don't want to walk a straight line to pt NE03 (unless you like thick krummholz and rock climbing). Rather, follow the creekbed down to where it cuts through a 20m tall rockband, cross creek/snowfield and traverse hillside going east under rocky cliffs. Point is just before small brook.
Location_desc: Point is on hillside downhill from impassive, grey blocky rockband. A small brook runs downhill 10m from point. Frozen Lake brook is 40m to west. Immediately surrounding point is heather and yellow cedar saplings.

Travel_notes: Travel downhill mostly through open meadow. last 70m you paralle creek downhill.
Location_desc: Point is uphill on north bank of the brook that drains Frozen lake. Distinctive whitebark pines nearby.

Travel_notes: Travel downhill, cross brook, go up to road and cross it. Continue out into open meadow. You will come to the brook again, cross it, and pass through a narrow subalpine-fir stand. The point is just on the far side of trees.
Location_desc: Point is in beautiful little meadow with lazy S-curving brook flowing through. Views of mountain to west. Point is in opening between clumps of subapline-fir. Creek is NW 20m--can hear it flowing.

Travel_notes: Travel across the meadow bottom to creek. Hop across creek and climb steep, short bank and pass thruogh narrow band of subalpine fir. Wlk downhill through final meadow with snags and beautiful views of the mountain--from Summerland to Little Tahoma to the peak.
Location_desc: Point is in small forest opening near some evidence of recent fire. Larger openings present SE and NW. Grass and forb groundcover. The Wonderland Trail is beyond trees approx 70m to SE.

Travel_notes: Cross trail at 60m and continue downhill through patches of Subalpine fir and Whitebark pine
Location_desc: Subalpine fir and WBPI hillside meadow (undifferentiated)

Travel_notes: Head SW through the subalpine fir forest with meadow understory. Point just 40 meters after crossing the creekbed.
Location_desc: Point in center of subalpine firs, 1m North of the dead one. Meadow understory and fir overstory. A more open meadow directly uphill.

Travel_notes: Head SW through meadow/subalpine fir and then climb hill up to the Wonderland trail. Point on top of hill just across the trail.
Location_desc: Point located on top of small hill, just past a small subalpine blowdown. Open canopy, with many subalpine firs and snags surrounding.

Travel_notes: Head SW over the Wonderland trail and into the thicker subalpine fir. You'll hit a wall of trees with a downed tree behind it. The point is just on the other side.
Location_desc: Point located next to downed log, about center of the tree with a small meadow to the North and SW.

Travel_notes: Pace 110 m on trial up rocky (and potentially snow covered) ridge.
Location_desc: Point is on a rocky ridge (prensently snow covered) next to a small stream.

Travel_notes: Pace 260 m on trail.  Take trail to Burroughs mountain at the trail junction.  Point is 50 m beyond the trail junction.
Location_desc: Point is on trail near 4-way junction.

Travel_notes: Pace 250 m on trail.
Location_desc: Poin on trail next to two large, flat rocks laid across the trail to form a step.  Surrounding area is meadow, begins to get steep and rocky further upslope.

Travel_notes: Pace 250 m on trail.
Location_desc: Point is on trail with a rock wall on the uphill side (rock wall poorly built and beginning to fall apart).

Travel_notes: Pace 250 m on trail.
Location_desc: Point is on trail along a section with a built rock wall on the uphill side.  the top of the ridge is 20m up on the SE side.

Travel_notes: pace 230 m on trail.  Finish traverse along sideslope and come out onto plateau.
Location_desc: Point is on trail next to a large rock on the right hand side of the trail.  To the east is flat meadow, to the west is a steep rocky slope.

Travel_notes: Travel 200 m SE across rock/sand/meadow over a slight crest in the plateau.
Location_desc: Point in flat, sandy wash.  Surrounding area is rocky, no meadow within 50 m.

Travel_notes: 200 m SW, cross the trail twice.  Point is just beyond the second crossing.
Location_desc: Point is in meadow next to a rock, 1 m across, and a small Subalpine fir.  Sparse patches Subalpine fir and White bark pine in area.

Travel_notes: Travel about 200m downtrail. Point is shortly after a large patch of subalpine fir and right next to a large white-bark pine growing out over the rock wall (see photo)
Location_desc: Point is on trail and right next to a large white-bark pine growing out over the rock wall (see photo)

Travel_notes: Travel about 200m down trail
Location_desc: Point is on trail, upslope from a large-ish white bark pine (see features)

Travel_notes: Travel on trail about 200m. Point is near some stone steps before reaching a sign on trail.
Location_desc: Point on trail near stone steps. Roof of Sunrise lodge/visitor center visible in distance.

Travel_notes: Travel about 200m downtrail. Heading down, you'll enter slightly more forested/vegetated area.
Location_desc: Point is on trail in an area with more trees and more birds! Look for large pine that is growing at a dramatic angle over the trail (see photo). Point is 3m past this.

Travel_notes: Last transect done in MORA in 2018-no snow on NE arm.
Location_desc: TO is on trail near a boulder / Subalpine-fir and spruce and whitebark pine krummholz clump. Camped at Sunrise walk in site/Shadow lake, 30 min away from TO. The bushwhack on NE arm is tricky--thick krummholz, rock scrambling and some snow (tread carefully on early morning snow--it can be very slick). It's best to navigate with landscape features here (ie forest edges, brooks and cliff ledges) then using GPS rather than trying to pace straight lines.

Travel_notes: Travel 100 meters at 315 degrees.  Bearing stays close to trail for much of travel until you ascend a slippery, moss-covered rocky seepage for the last ~30 meters.
Location_desc: Point is in an open spot in the canopy, but a dense understory of cedar and silver-fir saplings, and dense low shrubs (vaccinium), specifically shrubby on the way to the point.  There is a downed 20 DBH cedar one meter past point. Cedar feature stands out right away, south of point.

Travel_notes: Travel north.  Cross two streams then head upslope for the rest of travel.  There is a dense patch of silver-fir saplings 30 meters after you cross the streams.
Location_desc: Point is right on the edge of a large, open wet meadow area. Directly in front (to the north) of you is a 70cm DBH barkless snag.  The snag is the last tall standing tree for 40 meters. There is a large boulder directly "in front of" snag (between snag and point). There is a stream to the west. There is a silver fir whose branches extend onto point (from meadow side). Top has been damaged and branches are all growing from that point.

Travel_notes: Point may be a little east of a true north bearing.  GPS has bad reception.  Walk through the open, meadow area hugging the right edge.  Then head back into forest and travel upslope for 20 meters, then traverse rest of way to point, which is close to road.  Stay east of creek.
Location_desc: The point is at a 50 DBH snag with some bark missing.  To the east, there is a depression with a seep flowing through it, and then just after that is the road.  To the west is a small ravine with a creek flowing through it.

Travel_notes: Cross road and then travel upslope to point.  Most of travel obscured by snow (2010).
Location_desc: Point is just below the highway at the beginning of a small drainage.  Towards road is a boulder field.  There is a small stream starting just below point.  There are lots of large boulders at point.

Travel_notes: Climb upslope into forest.  There is a break in the forest at ~100 meters and you cross an open, probably snow-covered area.  Then climb upslope a ways to the point.
Location_desc: Point is in a forested area with very open understory and numerous large mountain hemlock and silver-fir nearby. 100 DBH snag feature is next to large 80 DBH stump that is rotting.

Travel_notes: Travel through forest for beginning of travel, then break out into open meadow area.  Cross a small stream, then walk back into a forested section.  Emerge from that, cross another stream, and then point is on the edge of the foest with view of a large boulder field to the NW.
Location_desc: Point is in an open area on the edge of the forest.  The highway is visible to the NW, above a large boulder pile area.  Seen just above the road is a section of cliff.  The understory is very open with snow patches and indian hellebore growing where the snow has melted.  Many large boulders around point. Point is on a large (kitchen table-sized) flat boulder.

Travel_notes: Walk uphill ~45m, at which point you'll cross a maintained trail (is this the Eastside Trail that is mapped totally wrong??), you'll cross it again immediately and realize that it goes in the same general direction you're going. Follow it until you reach boulder field area, then climb uphill to point.
Location_desc: Point is on the edge of dense slide alder and a boulder field on the other side. It is on a large rock, the most downhill of rocks before reaching more slide alder to the SW (downhill). There is a tall(ish) yellow cedar sapling <1m S of point. It is ~5m SE of two rocks with white spots (very fawn-like pattern/coloration).

Travel_notes: Walk up above slide alder and creepily walk below road. There is a pullout that you'll want to get to. From pullout, there is a faint elk/deer trail (or human?), right near "Rocks" sign. Take this so you can get off road and out of sight ASAP. Mellow travel uphill to next segment of road from there.
Location_desc: Awkwardly close to the road (~7m), but thankfully wedged in with the subalpine and silver fir saplings, so you're not visible from the road. Point is on the cut end of a downed tree (~20cm DBH). There is a line of 3 similarly-sized Mtn. hemlock saplings ~2m SW of point. If the area still has some snowpack you might be more visible from the road, but still kind of able to hide behind saplings.

Travel_notes: Pace 100 meters south on trail from TO.  Trail bends 90 degrees left 5 meters before point.
Location_desc: On trail in mountain hemlock/pacific silver-fir forest.  Small gaps in canopy to NW and SE. Point between yellow cedar and mountain hemlock features.

Travel_notes: Follow trail. It is necessary to walk 240 meters in order to be 200 meters from previous point due to bends in trail.
Location_desc: On trail in mountain hemlock/pacific silver-fir forest near small creek.  Several very large mountain hemlocks nearby, and clumps of small silver-fir.  Clearing to SE.

Travel_notes: Walk ~189m down trail.
Location_desc: Point is ~7m after bridge crossing.. On trail next to mountain hemlock feature and near a small stream.

Travel_notes: Pace ~400m down trail. Note: Points are ~375m apart.
Location_desc: On trail in mature forest with sparse understory.  Steep uphill slope to west, gentle downhill slope to east.

Travel_notes: 200 meters on trail, heading downhill.
Location_desc: Pacific silver fir forest, some understory but not dense.  Creek to the east, uphill slope west. It is ~3.5m down trail from where two ~80cm DBH silver firs are directly across trail from each other.

Travel_notes: Travel down steep hill on trail.
Location_desc: Located in a small gap in canopy where trail levels off after a steep downhill.  Lots of devil's club on either side.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Located along trail in a stand of vine maples.  Steep slopes on both sides. Decaying stump on W side of trail is very large and obvious. There is another splintered snag ~1m to the S.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Slope on either side of trail.  Forest is western hemlock, pacific silver-fir, and doug-fir.  Few distinguishing features.

Travel_notes: Travel down trail. After 3rd switchback, pace ~180m to point.
Location_desc: On trail in open forest, next to silver fir saplings and 70cm DBH silver fir. GPS is ~20m off.

Travel_notes: Continue on trail, gently downhill.
Location_desc: Along trail in mature coniferous forest: pacific silver-fir, western hemlock, and doug-fir.  Lush vanilla-leaf ground layer with a few small devil's club.

Travel_notes: Walk down gradual slope to creek, cross it (in low water year can rock hop, in high water year there are lots of log crossings - one good group of 3 logs in a row found in 2021), then climb up steeply (but briefly). After this steep climb, slope levels off and it's very easy walking to point.
Location_desc: There is a slight depression ~1m S/SW of point. It is at the transition (if going SE) between bare open ground and more groundcover/saplings.

Travel_notes: Walk uphill gradually to SS11. You can follow elk trails for part of it. Easy walking.
Location_desc: Point is ~4m N/NE of a much greener, herbaceous area (probably a seep running through there). There are several giant Doug-firs to the W of point, more or less in a line (though spaced ~50m apart from the most downhill to the most uphill of firs). Right at point are mainly silver fir saplings and a few 10-25cm DBH silver firs.

Travel_notes: Driving time 25 minutes from White River Campground.  A ten minute hike to the TO.  Park at the first big pullout on the west side of the road coming south from Cayuse Pass.  Trail isn't obvious, it's about 50 meters south of large pullout, by a stream.  TO is shortly after the trail crosses a stream. Note: TO is on Eastside Trail, not to be confused with the many social trails that leave right from the huge pullout, which seem to just lead to various dump sites for diapers and beer cans. NW arm crosses the highway several times due to the unfortunate placement of switchbacks on the road-- be careful; cars fly here.
From TO, return to the close trail junction and turn right. From the junction, pace 140 m to SE01.
Location_desc: Point is just past pile of large mossy rocks on the right side of trail. Steep slope with thick Red alder on left. Point just before you exit the Red alder stand.

Travel_notes: Pace 210 m up trail. You will pass through a small open area containing Devil's Club and Red Alder just before the point.
Location_desc: Point just past Red Alder/Devil's Club clearing w/close patch of conifers. Fairly steep slopes on both sides. Point set by the last of a series of steps on trail.

Travel_notes: Travel uphill along trail until about 40 m past the 3rd (and last) switchback.
Location_desc: Point along trail with steep slopes on both sides. Point at small clearing to the N. Mt. Rainier highly visible from here.

Travel_notes: Travel approx. 300 m down trail from SE03. Winding for the first ~200m, the last 100m fairly straight.
Location_desc: Point is in Mountain hemlock forest with a few scattered trees of other species, fairly flat. Lots of pale lichen growing from the trees.

Reason_for_change: went off-trail. Steep, snowy slope to SE
Travel_notes: Pace 200 m E from SE04. Easy travel through open forest.
Location_desc: Point off trail (but quite close to trail) in fairly mature Mountain hemlock forest. Lots of lichen hanging off the trees. Point on SE slope, becoming visibly steeper to the S. Pinnacle Peak visible through the trees to the S/SE. Several large fallen logs downslope from point.

Travel_notes: Return to trail and walk paralleling road (cross bridge) and cut off trail when it makes sense. Only ~20m off trail.
Location_desc: Point just south, downslope of Wonderland Trail in grove of young Pacific silver firs w/larger Alaska yellow cedars around it. Stream further to south.

Travel_notes: Return to trail and follow east until GPS says to cut off trail towards river. Cross small wet gully 5 m SE of trail and continue ~30m into forest. Start off trail 50m before Wonderland crosses road.
Location_desc: Point is ~15m north of river in grove of ~20cm dbh Pacific silver firs.

Travel_notes: Return to trail and head east until trail hits road. Follow road past "Reflection Lakes" sign and eventually cut back to Wonderland Trail on end of lake.
Location_desc: Point on Wonderland Trail between road and Reflection Lake.

Travel_notes: Cut back to raod and follow east until GPS says to cut up slope on south side of road. Travel ~40m from road. A good place to cut up is where brick wall on north side of road turns to brick and wood fence. Water drainage on south side of road.
Location_desc: Point is in fairly open clearing. Mtn. hemlock, Pacific silver fir, Subalpine fir, and some cedars surround point.

Travel_notes: Pace 150 m down trail toward Longmire, compensating for closeness to other arm.
Location_desc: Point is just after a set of log "stairs" down trail, just before a culvert with a bridge set into trail over it. Lots of downed trees, stumps, and woody debris to either side of trail.

Travel_notes: Travel 200 m down trail to SW. Cross five bridges over small streams, including one after SW01.
Location_desc: Point is just after a large section of roots in the trail coming from a very large Doug-fir. Right before wood bridge crossing stream. Lots of redcedars around.

Travel_notes: Travel 200 m down trail to the SW. Travel downhill with lots of roots in trail. Cross three small creeks and parallel a culvert for 50 m.
Location_desc: Point is on flat section of trail. Lots of stumps on sides of trail here and very large hemlock growing on trail. Bank on E side of trail cut deep along point.

Travel_notes: Pace 200 m down trail to SW. Pass 3 old stream crossing bridges. Point is just after last bridge (~15 m). Parallel an old fallen tree with large rootwad next to trail until point about 45m.
Location_desc: Point is at end of log paralleling trail on the S side. Trail wide here with lots of large hemlocks around.

Travel_notes: Pace 200 m down trail to SW.
Location_desc: Point is just before a series of long stairs on trail leading down to river. Trail has a lot of exposed roots in this area.

Travel_notes: Pace 240 m down trail to SW. Travel down long log stairs for first ~50m. Continue down trail until you reach Paradise River Bridge.
Location_desc: Point is just before (E side) bridge crossing Paradise River. It is between the "arms" of the rocks and log that border trail just before the bridge. Point is directly across from last rock on S side of trail.

Travel_notes: Pace down trail 140 m until just after you cross the third bridge. Go off-trail up slope, then down toward drainage, about 80m.
Location_desc: Point ison E slope of drainage. Mostly Western hemlock and Pacific silver fir with little understory.

Travel_notes: Head up hill towards Steven's Canyon Rd. Travel upslope across dry gully next to pt SW07.
Location_desc: Point is on slight slope, very little understory, predominantly Pacific silver fir. Large decomposing stump next to point.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: Small outcrop of Alaska yellow cedars to the SW, many slender snags at 45 degrees or less to ground. Can hear road and see cars (barely) driving by.

Travel_notes: About a 40-minute drive to Narada Falls pulloff from Ohanapecosh. If camping, Paradise River Camp is 0.7 miles from fork in trail below falls, or 0.7 miles from TO. 5-10 minute walk to TO from pulloff. Cougar Rocks CG is a 20 min drive.
Location_desc: Point on Wonderland Trail shortly after turning off of Narada Falls Trail. Point on trail, 14 m before (distance to base) before 2 large, side-by-side rocks (largest has ~5m diameter and looks like a seat) beside small rock and western hemlock (on right).

Travel_notes: Pace 110 m along trail from TO.
Location_desc: Both sides of trail from point covered in thick salal and vaccinium with lots of Doug-fir and Western hemlock saplings and fallen logs.

Travel_notes: Pace 235 m down trail. Mostly gradual uphill travel.
Location_desc: Dense young forest on right side of trail. Slightly older, more open forest on left side, with lots of mossy rotting logs.

Travel_notes: Pace 265 m along trail. Travel winding and slightly uphill.
Location_desc: Point in young, very dense forest of mostly western hemlock. Understory nonexistent, lots of downed mossy logs. Point 1 m past waterbar beside rotten log that parallels the trail.

Travel_notes: Pace 220 m along trail, all uphill.
Location_desc: Point is in relatively mature Doug-fir/Western hemlock forest along a straighter, wider, more open stretch of trail with several water bars. Steep slopes on both sides of trail. Loud creek noise.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On trail in area with quite a few slide alders right next to trail. In open area with mostly young trees; canopy does not cover trail.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Open section of canopy immediately above point. On straight section of trail with mostly young trees making up forest.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On trail in area surrounded by lots of Vaccinium, relatively open canopy. There are a number of roots exposed on trail, with a decomposing log almost completely moss-covered right next to point.

Travel_notes: Easiest to follow trail, then cut into point.
Location_desc: In stand with many younger trees (5cm-15cm DBH). Point has very decomposed stumps right next to it (one larger and one smaller stump).

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: At edge of forested and shrubby areas. Lots of downed logs- most seem pretty old and are very moss-covered.

Travel_notes: Travel through dense shrubs. Emerge from shrubs to small clearing.
Location_desc: In small open area without shrubs. Almost no understory. Features form a triangle.

Travel_notes: Pace from TO about 130 m. Travel slightly downhill.
Location_desc: There are three large old snags that form a ring around the point. One very large one is directly across from point. There is a small "alcove" next to the trail at the point that protrudes onto downhill slope. Point is just after a log support on trail.

Travel_notes: Pace 200 m down trail to SE. Travel is mostly downhill. You will come to a large opening in canopy where you can see down toward river at point.
Location_desc: Point is at a large opening in the canopy where you can see the Puyallup River Valley. Lots of salal and vine maple surrounding point. Point is right before a large white hemlock snag, where the trail goes straight and flat.

Travel_notes: Travel 200 m SE on trail to point. Travel slightly downhill and across some clearings.
Location_desc: Point is just after flatter section of trail. There is a lot of woody debris just downhill of point and along trail just ahead of the point. Root wad can be seen in clearing downslope from point. Point is near a lot of Devil's club, ferns, and blueberry.

Travel_notes: Pace 200 m down trail to SE. Cross a small creek after about 50 m. At about 160 m, you will see a huge white snag with some huge Doug-firs around it and a large downed log across from it.
Location_desc: Poine is on a straightaway section with a lot of Oregon grape surrounding it. Large Doug-firs and western hemlock saplings surround it and there is a "ridge" on side of trail next to a tree where point is located.

Travel_notes: Pace 200 m down trail to SE. Trail gets more gravely nearing point.
Location_desc: Point is next to a large pile of downed logs and rootwads. There is a rock face upslope with boulders in front. Point is in open area of canopy with lots of ferns and vine maple on both sides of trail.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: About 5m before edge of rocky slide area that has a lot of vine maple, both up and downslope.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On relatively flat section of trail, right before a bend.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: At point on trail 2m from end of mossy log that parallels the trail. Immediately downslope ~55m away is a barkless snag.

Travel_notes: Cross stream at ~170m.
Location_desc: Substantial cliff face densely covered with moss and a few small herbaceous plants on upslope side of trail. Puyallup River visible through the trees from point.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: At point on trail where it begins to descend more sharply to the Slip 'n Slide rock.

Travel_notes: ~50m from last toilet is point.
Location_desc: Surrounded by lots of small hemlock and Doug-fir saplings.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: In open area with many large trees within a 20m radius. Waterfall with lots of ladyfern on upslope side. You could probably see Rainier on a clear day up valley.

Travel_notes: Camp at North Puyallup Camp, about a 25-30 minute walk to TO in the morning. Lots of overgrown shrub on trail.
Location_desc: Several small vine maples near point. Steep slopes on both sides of trail; lots of ferns and vaccinium.

Travel_notes: Pace down trail to E about 115m, until just before the next switchback, not including one next to TO. You will see a bunch of mushroomy logs and boulder in trail before switchback at TO. There is a large log pile on trail between EE01 and TO.
Location_desc: Point is just before first switchback in trail (besides one next to TO). Point is just next to a mossy boulder on the trail, just past some large logs with mushrooms growing on them. There is a large log paralleling trail to the S (upslope). There are two large (1.5m DBH) Doug-firs straight off the end of the switchback.

Travel_notes: Travel 795 m down trail (switchbacks). Traverse 6 switchbacks total. Trail goes straight after the last one.
Location_desc: Point is on straight section of trail, with small "hills" in trail around point. Point is perpendicular to end of a large fallen log with a jagged end upslope. Several large stumps around, but weird one is unique and next to jagged log.

Travel_notes: Travel 200 m down trail. Fairly straight, undulating, easy walk.
Location_desc: Point is in clearing in trees just past a large rootwad on downslope side of trail. Large hemlock is right next to point; its roots form a wall on the side of trail.

Travel_notes: Travel 580 m down trail toward river. Last half is in river floodplain and flat.
Location_desc: Point is in flat floodplain with a lot of downed trees around. Point is next to a large fallen alder log and surrounded by small conifers. Lots of undergrowth. Root wad is right next to trail and about 7 feet tall.

Travel_notes: Cross 2 sets of bridges from floodplain to river. Cross first bridge across actual river. Pace 200 m from EE04.
Location_desc: Point is in river bed of S Mowich River, just after first bridge across actual river. Far peaks upstream are visible on a clear day.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point located on trail where river has cut away most of bank right up to the trail.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is on trail in area with dense understory. There are lots of hemlock and Doug-fir saplings and many cut logs next to trail S of point. Located in a straight section between two bends. Cannot see farther than 7.4m N or 15m S down trail.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Very close to where trail opens up to Mowich River. There are many Doug-fir saplings and huckleberry bushes.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Right at point next to trail, there are many downed trees that have been cut. It is right where flat section of trail begins to climb and switchback up to Mowich Lake. Very open canopy. Cluster of larger hemlocks and Doug-firs (85+cm DBH).

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Very mossy on both sides of trails with pretty open canopy. Upslope from boulder feature is rootwad. Many saplings make up the understory.

Travel_notes: Travel 110 m up trail from TO. Point just past second bend in trail.
Location_desc: Point is just after the trail bends sharply to left. Small patch of open forest with no understory on right. Old sawed log beside trail on left. 15 m past point is a small clearing with lots of ferns, vanilla leaf, and Devil's club.

Travel_notes: Pace 210 m from SS01 along trail. Travel mostly level or gradually uphill.
Location_desc: Point 1 m past huge root wad that sticks out into the trail. Steep slopes on both sides of trail. Note: GPS reading may be way off.

Travel_notes: Pace 350m uphill on trail. Point is just after 4th switchback.
Location_desc: Note: GPS coordinates may be way off. Point is 1 m past 4th switchback. Median of switchback covered with vanilla leaf and Devil's club. Steep slopes on both sides of trail.

Travel_notes: Travel approximately 700 m (yes, 700 m) up trail through 4 switchbacks. Switchbacks make travel much longer than it should be. Steep slopes on both sides of trail.
Location_desc: Point on a straighter portion of the trail where young hemlock saplings are not so thick. 22 m past the point is a not so sharp hairpin curve in the trail. Distinctive features hard to find.

Travel_notes: Travel up trail 275 m. Gradual uphill, slightly winding travel through an understory of hemlock saplings and vaccinium.
Location_desc: Point is 5 m past the only switchback. Vaccinium understory on both sides of trail.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: In slightly more open area with many low Pacific silver fir saplings. There are about 3 snags in sapling clearing.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On trail surrounded by many silver fir and hemlock saplings and huckleberry bushes. Barkless log across trail about 3m away, which will likely be gone by next visit, but look for remains. The smaller of the 2 purplish trees (in features) has a pulley device on downslope side of it (distance/bearing to larger one).

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Area has many small Pacific silver firs (10-15cm DBH).

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: There is another smaller version of the silver fir feature immediately to the left of snag feature. Located at slight bend in trail with dense silver fir sapling grove upslope. Little understory with lots of woody debris on ground.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Pacific silver fir forest with little understory. Some open spots with shrubs growing. Many decaying stumps and logs in immediate area. Distance and bearing of stump feature is to the one at the base of the mtn. hemlock.

Travel_notes: TO is a 35-minute walk from South Mowich River Camp. Make sure to check with rangers about S Mowich Bridge condition before hiking to this transect- it gets washed out often.
Location_desc: TO just past switchback between a large western hemlock and western redcedar (marker tree), both of which are within the median of the switchback. Note: coordinates of pre-loaded trail on GPS are 50-100m off. GPS reception also very poor, thus I established the TO as close as I thought I could.

Travel_notes: Walk down trail ~110m.
Location_desc: Point is on trail near some running water. It is about 8m up trail from a water bar. Mtn. ash is directly upslope of trail from point.

Travel_notes: Walk generally uphill, but terrain is undulating. Cross a small creek at ~145m.
Location_desc: Very little understory at point, but a lot of downed trees. There is an intersection of multiple downed trees ~1m S of point. Boulder field very visible through trees, ~40m SE of point.

Travel_notes: Walk gradually uphill for the 1st ~100m, crossing a small meadow. At ~100m, slope will get exponentially steeper with the last ~20m being a bit dicey with steep rock. Be careful.
Location_desc: In some steep rocks. Be careful around here- it can be a bit sketchy. Just uphill of an Engelmann spruce sapling that is growing among rocks. There is a lot of common juniper growing just upslope of point.

Travel_notes: Walk up steeply (be careful)- going a bit SE might be better. It will level off soon, then you'll cross a small creek at ~75m. Easy walking from there.
Location_desc: Point is in an open area with some subalpine firs and mtn. hemlocks, standing in a game/mountain goat trail. Just to the N/NE, it gets a little more dense with trees (but only very briefly). It is ~20m N of a small stream/drainage. Features are hard here!

Travel_notes: Easy walking up through meadow and sparse subalpine fir. Stay to the left of the small stream/drainage.
Location_desc: Point is on the edge of a more wooded (subalpine fir) area. It is about 5m upslope of flat valley bottom. Heather, vaccinium, and beargrass right at point with a few subalpine fir saplings downslope.

Travel_notes: Walk up little valley, staying below the trees, even if you're off-bearing a bit. That will get you there.
Location_desc: Point is on lower edge of a more wooded zone (mainly subalpine firs), on the edge of a wet meadow. It is ~11m upslope from the valley bottom.

Travel_notes: Easiest way is to drop down below trees and walk up valley to point. Very easy walking.
Location_desc: There are a bunch of subalpine fir saplings right at point. Downslope of point, it is all heather (no more firs).

Travel_notes: Look at small rock outcrop with subalpine firs at 225 degree bearing. Walk there (upslope)- that is where point is.
Location_desc: Point is on a small outcrop, where there are a bunch of subalpine firs (and some young mtn. hemlocks). You can just barely see the top of Rainier from point. It is where slope levels off briefly.

Travel_notes: Walk upslope, steeply at times. There is a small knob (that you can see from NN08)- head for that. You can use mountain goat trails for much of it.
Location_desc: Beautiful point, with a great view of Rainier. In a boulder field ~20m below the ridge. Upslope of point (~10m), there are fewer boulders and more vegetation- a lot of heather.

Travel_notes: Travel along trail 277m.
Location_desc: Point is just after a clearing and before a boulder on the right side of the trail. Talus slope is visible to left through the trees.

Travel_notes: Travel along trail 220m.
Location_desc: Point is between two water bars.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: Point is ~4m before a large root crosses the trail and is alongside a line of Mtn. hemlocks 8m off-trail to the left. After 3 wooden steps.

Travel_notes: Travel ~217m on trail.
Location_desc: Creek (or dry creekbed) is less than 1m from trail. Point is before a water cut with stones and gravel (crossing trail).

Travel_notes: Travel along trail 221m.
Location_desc: Point is just before some wooden steps and just after a slight hill.

Reason_for_change: Could go off-trail without getting trapped
Travel_notes: Travel across meadow to forest edge.
Location_desc: Point is on forest edge amongst Subalpine fir saplings. Note that curved Subalpine fir photo was taken a few meters from the point.

Travel_notes: Head along bearing and continue upslope a short distance.
Location_desc: Point is on a slope, ~5m from a small bubbling stream in a meadow/clearing, surrounded by Mtn. hemlock and Subalpine fir saplings. The large meadow is visible down and to the right.

Travel_notes: Cross small stream and continue on bearing until reaching an open area with a game path heading uphill. Follow the path until hitting a large creekbed and continue up along creekbed.
Location_desc: Point is in creekbed next to a car-sized boulder. The cliff begins ~15m to the W. Note that large boulder photo was taken from below the point itself.

Travel_notes: Travel is easiest along stream in the open area between cliff and forest. Follow stream about 180m to where it curves into forest and continues upslope about 20m to get to a gap in the Subalpine fir (you can see another meadow on the other side).
Location_desc: Point is in a gap in the line of Subalpine firs, separating the two open areas. The creek is audible. A large waterfall is visible (through the trees) across Carbon Glacier at about 254 degrees.

Travel_notes: Stay in E meadow on your way to point
Location_desc: In lupine meadow near line of subalpine fir (~20m away). Excellent view of Rainier!

Travel_notes: It took us about 50 minutes from Mystic Camp to TO.  If Mystic is not available there is good camping in Lower Carbon (Curtis Ridge) x-country zone. Head off ridge right before dropping into Mustic (after big climb). There is an obvious social trail that takes you to good spots. We hiked the whole Northern Loop Trail, combined with 4068 and 4011 (can also add 4004). Great trip. SS arm is along trail for the first 5 points, then heads up to Moraine Park for the last 4. Fairly easy travel in open areas. Watch for Mountain goats! Also, note that SS01 is 200m from TO (rather than 100m). There is water by SS08!
Location_desc: Note: no tag. TO is on trail as trail parallels creekbed, 2.5m before a water bar. Mountain ash on upslope, shading point.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On trail with surrounding forest of Western hemlock and Pacific silver fir, with little herbaceous and shrubby understory.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On trail next to Josephine Creek. There is a large partially barkless snag 2m from point. About 5m from the side of foot bridge.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: In mostly hemlock forest with a couple of Doug-firs mixed in. Ground is very mossy with little understory. On gentle slope.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On longer slope than previous point. Lots of mature hemlocks with silver fir saplings.

Travel_notes: Moderate stream drainage with steep banks ~80m from point.
Location_desc: Mostly Western hemlock forest, with a few Doug-firs mixed in. There are quite a few (5+) sizable cedar saplings in immediate area as well. Point is next to a 3.5m tall snag.

Travel_notes: Moderate blowdown area.
Location_desc: Immediate area surrounded by 5cm DBH Pacific silver fir saplings and a large decomposing log 0.5m from point on downslope side. Moderate slope with many saplings make up understory.

Travel_notes: Intermittent stream about 170m from point. Drainage gets quite steep to West. Going upstream to find good crossing might be a better option.
Location_desc: On relatively steep slope with large amount of debris to South (downed trees and branches). Surrounded by many Pacific silver fir saplings.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On slope with little herbaceous understory and lots of woody debris. The immediate area has 2 downed Pacific silver firs right next to it in an X position (see photo of point).

Travel_notes: Slope gets significantly steeper between SE01 and SE02.
Location_desc: In forested area with almost no understory. Many small DBH  (10-20cm) trees with some larger mixed in. Lots of woody debris on ground. Long log (60m) upslope, at base of hemlock feature.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Area closely surrounded by saplings and has 2 decaying logs right next to it.

Travel_notes: none (QA note: I'm not sure how this ended up being on trail-- update travel description next visit)
Location_desc: Trail is less used, narrower with more herbacious plants creeping onto it. Quite a few downed trees around and on trail. One long log, 40+m above trail.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Much more open area with a few saplings and not many shrubs in immediate area. There are two decomposing stumps next to point on trail.

Travel_notes: Follow the trail.
Location_desc: Area has lots of decomposing woody debris. At least 4 stumps/snags, and many downed logs.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: There are 4 cut chunks of log right next to point, ~30m to edge of clearing in trees.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: In area where forest is more open, with many small saplings. More obvious open area to the S of point.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Larger trees, mostly hemlocks. Shrub is mostly false laurel (QA note- no such thing-- false azalea maybe?).

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Down trail from stream by 20m. Small open patch at about 20 degrees immediately off-trail. Mossy with low huckleberry bushes.

Travel_notes: ~1 hour, 15 minute hike without packs from FS Huckleberry Creek Trailhead. Large blowdown about 45 minutes in slows travel. Trail relatively maintained except for downed logs. 3.5 mile hike from the Mt. Baker Snoqualmie FS Entrance. Sunrise entrance could be very snowy until toward the end of season. We x-country camped ~2.5 miles down trail before significant patch of blowdown (in 2016).
Location_desc: Located on trail in hemlock-dominated forest. Lots of understory with huckleberry and Devil's club. Large downed Doug-fir, which probably won't be there next time, but it's at 4m, 30 degrees.

Travel_notes: Walk southwest on gravel road across Highway 20 from turn-off to NC 213 Road to first powerline tower. Point is 10m due west from west corner of tower.  Point is ~20m NW of gravel road.
Location_desc: Point is located in powerline corridor near first tower on the gravel powerline access road. Area is open and mostly thimbleberry and some maple. To the west of point there is a somewhat deep, dry stream channel. Point is about 20 m NW of gravel road.

Travel_notes: Go back to gravel road. Pace ~215m up road and cut in NW ~13m to point.
Location_desc: Point is ~20m SE of powerlines and ~13m NW of gravel road. Salad groundcover. There is a cluster of vine maple ~4.5m to the N/NE whose branches extend to between point and feature birch.

Reason_for_change: To allow for off-road transect bearings
Travel_notes: Pace 230 m along gravel road until you reach a T (at ~180m). From the T, take a left and walk up that road ~50m. At ~230m, there is a large rotting cedar stump on the west bank of the road with a multi-branched big leaf maple above it. From there, pace 70 m due west (upslope) to point.
Location_desc: Point is on moderate slope. Right at point is mostly Oregon Grape groundcover with a few of every possible tree species: Doug-fir, hemlock, cedar, alder, maple, and birch. There is more moss on ground immediately to the N than right at point.

Travel_notes: Travel up steep slope following a NW bearing, travel becomes less steep about 80 meters before next point.
Location_desc: Point approximately midway up a south facing slope, right under the branches of a ~30cm DBH cedar (on downhill side). Forest dominated by hemlock, Doug fir, and cedar with salal and Oregon grape understory/ground cover.

Travel_notes: Travel over relatively open ground cover in maple and cedar forest (occasional large Doug firs present) reaching a more level area by NN05. Look for feature Doug-firs as you get close - they are fairly obvious.
Location_desc: Point is near the top of a southeasterly facing slope. Slope flattens out within 5m below and above point. Under small cedar between two >100dbh doug firs.

Travel_notes: Travel is pretty mellow the whole way. It is a gradual uphill walk, getting increasingly more open as you near point. The last ~50m are in very open forest.
Location_desc: Point is ~10m W of where slope becomes steeper. Groundcover at point is primarily Oregon Grape. There are several large Doug-firs within 10m N of point.

Travel_notes: Pace along either of two side roads, there is an easterly and southerly road, to best GPS point then pace into the woods to locate point. Pace about 60m SE of gravel road paralleling Hwy 20. Dark forest through moderate shrub.
Location_desc: Point located in deciduous dominated riparian forest consisting of red alder and big leaf maple. Understory of sword fern and salmonberry. Nettle along both roadsides! Beware, it is evil.

Travel_notes: Travel 200 meters following a southwest bearing (225 degrees) through deciduous riparian forest. There is a somewhat deep ditch within the first 100 meters.
Location_desc: Point located in riparian forest at top of steep bank to the Skagit River. Forest is mostly composed of red alder with salmonberry, bracken fern and sword fern understory.

Travel_notes: Travel west following a WW bearing. At about 40 meters you reach a clearing with a dirt road and dirt mound on the road. Continue up a small embankment heading towards Highway 20.
Location_desc: Point is located in an alder forest approximately 35m from Highway 20 on the East side of the road. The understory consists of vine maple with abundant salmonberry and false-lily-of-the-valley  in the surrounding area. The buttressed stump (feature) has vine maple growing from it, a snag that has fallen onto it, and a ~30cm DBH alder leaning over it. There is a ~90cm DBH Doug-fir to the N/NE of each of the stumps. There is a cluster of alders partially obscuring stumps from point. In 5 years, they may not even be at all visible from point.

Travel_notes: Cut out to Highway 20 and pace 200m west then cut back into forest on northside of the road when you reach the yellow 45mph warning sign to find the point.
Location_desc: Point is located in a mixed deciduous strip of forest bordering Hwy 20. The road is visible through the trees from the point. There is a ~90cm DBH cottonwood blocking the yellow road sign from being visible from point.

Travel_notes: Best way is probably to drop back down to Hwy 20 and walk W until it looks mellow to get up to gravel road that borders powerlines to the N. Wide open - GPS should work. Walk the gravel road until you are near point. Point is about 5m S of gravel road.
Location_desc: Point is under powerlines ~5m S of the gravel road that runs along the north edge of the powerline corridor. Wide open. Be careful about counting the same birds at SE07 - sound carries very far here.

Travel_notes: Walk WSW along gravel road under powerlines to old gravel quarry. There is a small offshoot that heads toward the quarry. Then bushwack down to bottom where offshoot ends (pretty much immediately now). It is overgrown now. Point is at the bottom of quarry.
Location_desc: Point is 15m from the east wall of quarry in an open spot, surrounded by newly regenerating alder and cottonwood. There are several small lodgepole pines around point. It will probably be much more grown up next visit. Update! Great satellite reception.

Travel_notes: Best way is to walk back up to gravel road and walk W on it until almost at end. GPS coverage should be good here - when you're about at correct easting, go due S, crossing Hwy 20 ~60m N of point.
Location_desc: Point is ~60m S of Hwy 20. It is in a pretty open, small mossy spot, surrounded by mostly salal. Powerlines are visible (through trees) from point. There are a bunch of moss-covered rocks immediately to the W.

Travel_notes: Allow about 20-25 minutes of driving from Diablo.
Location_desc: Drove to transect from Diablo, parking area is just after Ross Lake NRA/North Cascades National Park Complex entrance sign. Turn left onto NP 213 road (brown sign) and park behind gate. TO is on the road between parking NP 213 road turnoff and Park Complex Entrance sign.

Travel_notes: Paced 120 m on trail to make up for bends in trail.
Location_desc: Point is in subalpine parkland amidst Pacific silver firs.

Travel_notes: Paced 280 m between points on trail to achieve 200 m distance in northing.
Location_desc: Point is just S of camp, on trail next to a small stream.

Travel_notes: The trail bends a lot, but there are only two real switchbacks between NN02 and NN03. I paced about 510 m on trail between points.
Location_desc: Point is in meadow in subalpine parkland. Running from trail directly upslope of point, there seems to be a "rabbit" trail.

Travel_notes: There are no switchbacks between NN03 and NN04, so pacing on trail is just 240 m.
Location_desc: Point is at the foot of a talus slope about 20 m across at its widest. Otherwise, this is an area of trees (Mountain hemlock and Pacific silver fir) rather than meadow. There are two large Mountain hemlocks (40cm dbh), one on either side of trail, 1 m W of point.

Travel_notes: Paced about 300 m between points; there is only one switchback in trail between NN04 and NN05.
Location_desc: Point is on top of a sort of small ridge in the trail where it goes over a rocky outcropping. There is a larger rocky face visible to the NE, about 50 m away. Featured mountain hemlock just right of rocky trail in the picture.

Travel_notes: Paced about 360 m on trail in between points (I may have lost count though); there are two switchbacks between NN05 and NN06.
Location_desc: "3 40-cm trunks feature" continues: three 40-cm fir trunks on downslope edge of trail; the trunk closest to the trail is a decaying snag about 1.5 m high, and roots come out onto trail (shown from other side in picture).  Point is on a steep slope in subalpine parkland, about 3m downtrail from the three featured trunks, next to a small downslope tree.

Travel_notes: Threre are no switchbacks between NN06 and NN07, so pacing on trail is just over 200 m.
Location_desc: Point is in subalpine parkland that is mostly meadow. There are two 50cm dbh fir trunks, one on either side of the trail, 1 m W of pt. NN07. The trunk on downslope side is a snag, the other is living.

Travel_notes: Paced about 620 m on trail between points; there were about 8 switchbacks between NN07 and NN08.
Location_desc: Point is on top of Sourdough Ridge. I had to pace the last 20 m or so on snow, so I'm not sure if it's exactly on trail, but it should be pretty close, and GPS reception is good. The habitat near the point is half snow and half alpine heather with small mountain hemlock.

Reason_for_change: left trail and went the only possible direction without hitting steep terrain or being closer than 200m to NN08
Travel_notes: Travel along ridge at a 90 degree bearing. As one nears the final hill to the lookout, one will drop a bit off the N side of the ridge to reach the point.
Location_desc: Point is in open area, just a bit north of the top of the ridge, probably in meadow (all snow in 2012 when established).

Travel_notes: Travel at 90 degrees from NN09 through open terrain. Alternatively, might be easiest to jump on the ridge and take the trail down until the GPS reads close, before leaving ridge, then curve down to the edge of the small basin where the point is located.
Location_desc: Point is at eastern edge of a small basin under Sourdough Ridge. All snow in 2012.

Travel_notes: Travel downslope 100 m from TO.
Location_desc: Point on SE slope of Sourdough Mtn. overlooking Diablo Lake and Thunder Arm. A creek is audible from point. Surrounding forest is mixed conifer.

Travel_notes: Travel downslope 200 m to next point. There is a small, dried stump (that has been cut by trail crew) on trail about 40 m down. You will cross 2 streams flowing over the trail, the first one at 125 m is the larger of the 2.
Location_desc: Point located on trail on steep SE facing slope of mountain. Forest is dominated by Pacific silver fir. Creek upslope is audible from point. Point is next to moss-covered limestone rock about 1 m high and large ~80cm DBH Pacific silver fir.

Travel_notes: Travel downslope along trail on SE ridge of Sourdough Mtn. At ~150 m, you will pass by a rocky outcrop to the right (W of trail).
Location_desc: Mixed coniferous forest on SE facing slope of Sourdough. Diablo Lake, Hwy 20, and opposite ridgeline all visible from this point. Point directly on a higher bit of trail due to a tree stump growing on it.

Travel_notes: Travel downslope on trail along ridge crossing a steep, dry, rocky creek bed at about 40 m.
Location_desc: Mixed conifer forest on gentle east-facing slope.

Travel_notes: Travel down trail about 250 m through Doug-fir forest which turns into a Doug-fir/Pacific silver fir forest with scattered boulders.
Location_desc: Point on nearly level part of trail when first leaving a mixed coniferous forest and entering a small open area. Canopy is thicker to the N and E with Pacific silver fir and hemlock. The area to the W is open with Doug-fir.

Travel_notes: Travel down trail about 250 m (longer to account for trail switchbacks/meandering). Pass Ross Lake NRA boundary post (to the left) at 190 m.
Location_desc: Point overlooking SW side of mountain in Doug-fir forest. Trees upslope (Lodgepole pines) to the NW look wind-battered/dead. Last point Diablo Lake can be seen below through the trees before reentering the forest.

Travel_notes: Travel down trail through somewhat open Doug-fir forest with scattered boulders. Cross over a small downed log at 8 m, then a larger barkless downed log at 10 m. Pass by a Doug-fir without bark from base to 3 m high (growing on SW side of trail). The trail switchbacks several times and 3 times in the last 100 m (about every 30 m).
Location_desc: Point on trail on S slope of mountain in Doug-fir forest.

Travel_notes: Travel down trail about 230 m to next point. The trail switchbacks several times at about 60 m, 90 m, and 150 m. There is a large downed tree bridging the trail at 193 m or so.
Location_desc: Point located on trail of SW-facing slope in a fairly open Doug-fir forest, just above a small opening downslope of trail and just before the two featured closely growing doug-firs. Slope is fairly steep and the lower part of the trail can be seen from point.

Travel_notes: Travel down trail crossing a downed log at about 15 m (which crosses the switchback) and again at 22 m. Trail continues to meander downslope.
Location_desc: Point located on trail near a small dry creek bed in a Doug-fir forest. The dry creek bed is filled with vine maple below the trail.

Travel_notes: Travel downslope (slightly further than 200 m). Cross a large downed log at about 75 m. The trail switchbacks at about 115 m and a creek is audible near this point in the trail. Continue down trail another 100 m or so until you reach the transition to Lodgepole pine forest.
Location_desc: Point on trail on SW-facing slope near transition between Lodgepole pine forest (with lots of downed logs and snags) to the S/SE and a mixed conifer forest. Point located directly between featured stump and rock.

Travel_notes: Definitely bring ice axe and crampons and know how to use them if it's a high snow year.
Location_desc: Point on trail approx. 400 m down trail from Sourdough Creek Campground. Upslope from point, the canopy is open and there is a large willow component. Sourdough Creek is also audible from point. Hike up Sourdough Mtn. very steep. Took about 2-3 hours with full packs. All points on trail due to steep terrain; therefore, only TO was marked with a tag.

Travel_notes: From TO, travel downslope following a NE bearing. You will reach the bottom/fairly level area a little over halfway. Continuing on you will cross a small creek at about 85-90m. Point is on other side of creek as is Cottonwood tree with aluminum tag. Although visible from across the creek, the tag may be hard to see due to its color match the tree trunk and low light levels in the forest.
Location_desc: Point is located in Western redcedar dominated forest near a small stream. General area is wetter than surrounding forest with Devil's club and a diverse herbaceous layer. There are numerous downed trees as well. Point is about 0.5 m S/SE of a ~80cm DBH cedar. It is about 5 m NE of end of large pile of downed trees.

Travel_notes: Travel across lots of downed logs following a NE bearing. Thee forest becomes drier at about 50 m and then begins to travel up for the rest of the way. NE02 is located near the top of a small knoll.
Location_desc: Point located near the top of a small knoll. Forest canopy is fairly open and most trees are smaller/younger; mostly Doug-fir. It is more open right at point- immediately downslope (~5m), it is less open.

Travel_notes: Travel NE to top of small knoll NE02 was on, continue downhill for a bit and then uphill again at a little less than halfway to next point. Forest in fairly uniform Doug-fir/Western hemlock with lots of smaller (<23 cm dbh) downed wood.
Location_desc: Point located in Doug-fir/Western hemlock forest. The ground is moss-covered with lots of smaller downed conifers.

Travel_notes: Travel NE down gengly sloping hill. Forest is mixed conifer with lots of smaller (<23 cm dbh) downed conifer logs. Forest floor is moss-covered with Oregon grape and other low growing herbs. There are no obviously conspicuous travel features to point.
Location_desc: Point is located on small slope of the SW shore of Hozomeen Lake. Forest canopy mostly Doug-fir with a mixed conifer understory. There are lots of small (<23 cm dbh) downed conifers. Ground cover Oregon grape and moss. Lake is slightly visible through trees. Not a lot of obviously conspicuous features at this point.

Travel_notes: Travel E down slight slope toward lake. Following an E bearing, you will travel along down toward lake reaching what appears to be a manmade or animal trail that follows inside of lakshore (this is about 150 m). The slope becomes markedly steep for the next 50 m or so to point NE05.
Location_desc: Point located on southern slope of Hozomeen Lake. Slope is moderately steep with lots of downed logs. Mixed conifer forest with largest species being Doug-fir. Lakeshore/lake visible downslope from point.

Travel_notes: Travel across slope following an easterly bearing. First 50 m or so is somewhat steep and lots of downed trees make it slightly more difficult. After 50 m or so, slope is gentler and forest becomes more enclosed and moss-covered.
Location_desc: Point located in W. hemlock forest on small slope on southest slope of lake. Small Western redcedars comprise understory and there are lots of downed trees. Ground covered by moss and Oregon grape.

Travel_notes: Walk upslope for 200 meters. After ~40m, the forest gets more open with occasional sections of denser forest. Point itself is in open forest.
Location_desc: Point is on moderately steep slope in fairly open forest. Right at point, there isn't much understory, but the branches of a vine maple extend overhead at point (from upslope). There are several large Doug-firs within 15m N of point. Feature Doug-firs are just below a decaying log. The one that is slightly downhill is a bit smaller (~90cm DBH) and closer to point. The more uphill Doug-fir leans downhill.

Travel_notes: Pace 100 m down trail.
Location_desc: Point is on a serpentine 40 m stretch of trail, ground is flat on both sides.

Travel_notes: Easiest way is to pace 200 m down trail to the "short cut stump" feature, then go off trail to point for remaining ~70m.
Location_desc: Dense forest.

Travel_notes: Travel fairly direct and easy, more Doug-fir as you get closer to SE03.
Location_desc: Point is on moderate slope in Douglas-fir dominated forest, though a lot of Western hemlock and Western redcedar are present also. Open understory of Oregon grape, numerous small mossy boulders.

Travel_notes: Travel across slope until about halfway, bearing leads onto flatter area; small boulders are less common when you leave the slope. No distinctive travel features, but the understory is open (mostly Oregon grape) and travel is fairly easy.
Location_desc: Point is in relatively flat area at the foot of a general slope to the SW. Numerous small Pacific yew trees are immediately near the point. Sparse Devil's club visible in a couple locations.

Travel_notes: After about 55 m, bearing leads up slope and away from flatter area where there was occasional Devil's club and Pacific yew. Travel isn't bad. No other distinctive features.
Location_desc: Point is in Douglas-fir forest with open understory of mostly Oregon grape. Running water is audible to the NE.

Travel_notes: Travel is more upslope than other points so far, but still fairly easy.
Location_desc: Next to 47 cm dbh western red cedar, surrounded by w. hemlock, doug-fir, vine maple.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On moderate slope. Small Spring can be heard 15 m away, it is only above ground for about 10 meters.

Travel_notes: Moderate slope becomes steep about halfway there. Open understory.
Location_desc: On steep slope about 30 m E/SE of stream.

Travel_notes: Survey this transect with the Desolation one (1019)-they are ~18 miles apart. Check with Resources, Maintenance, and Rangers about getting a boat ride up lake.
Location_desc: Point is in open Douglas-fir forest with open understory. Oregon Grape on both sides of the trail. We were able to catch a boat ride up Ross Lake and then hiked in to Hozomeen Lake Campground (~2.5 hrs, which includes the boat ride up lake). (Excellent!) The transect origin was about a15-min. hike from campground. (about 10 from campground to trail and another 5 min. up trail (SE). I give this transect 5 stars (on a scale of 1-5, 5 being super sweet).

Travel_notes: Travel down trail from TO 200m until you reach easting.
Location_desc: Point is located on trail in an area with several newly fallen/cut firs (about 4-5 tree stumps). The canopy is fairly open with about 10 Doug-fir snags on north side of trail. 3 large stumps on immediate north side of trail. Company Creek slightly audible but not entirely visible.

Travel_notes: Travel down trail (toward trailhead/downslope) until the Easting and then travel upslope/North about 30-35 m.
Location_desc: Point located on slope on north side of trail. The slope has sparse trees, mostly Doug-firs. An exposed rocky ridge is visible to the NE. There are also several downed trees on the slope. Point located next to a downed Ponderosa pine.

Travel_notes: Travel downslope following an EE bearing. About halfway downslope to next point, there are several large exposed boulders on the slope.
Location_desc: Point located on slope in Doug-fir forest with lots of downed wood. Exposed rock slope lies to the NW ~40 m away. Point is 10 m south of point halfway between two large Doug-fir snags.

Travel_notes: Travel downslope following an EE bearing. There are lots of downed trees. You should pass an extremely large downed Doug-fir (~1.1 m dbh) at about 100m. There are several smaller downed firs that fell with it and they lie E (downslope). To the immediate N of these fallen trees is a small grove of younger Doug-firs.
Location_desc: Point located on slope of Doug-fir forest with open understory and lots of smaller downed fir trees. Point is located next to a Doug-fir stump ~22cm dbh with about 1/3 of trunk still standing and no branches.

Travel_notes: Travel downslope following an E bearing. You will encounter a large section of large downed Doug-firs. At ~135 m, there are several exposed boulders on the slope. It is easier to travel under them rather than over.
Location_desc: Point located on fairly open slope in a Doug-fir forest. Exposed rock faces are scattered throughout, mostly visible upslope and to the N. Many small Doug-fir saplings near point.

Travel_notes: Travel downslope following an E bearing. At ~55m, you will pass below a moss-covered boulder. There seems to be an old trail bed or animal trail here. You will cross the trail three times: at 94, 144, and 180m. You may choose to follow trail to the Easting and then pace 10 m S.
