Travel_notes: Heading W from Diablo, pass mile marker 114 on route to TO (about 0.6 miles past 114). Pullout is between TO and WW01. It is about a 20-minute drive from Diablo.  Be careful on WW arm - many points are on Hwy 20; stay off the actual road! Cars! Probably better to do this transect (WW arm in particular) on a weekday due to tourist traffic. There is an S curve road sign right down from the marker tree
Walk on road from 1017 origin coordinates, generally south about 100m.
Location_desc: Point is on east shoulder of road, about 13 m before the beginning of the guardrail.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: Point is on road overlooking Skagit River. It is ~39m after you pass the beginning of the second guardrail. Large exposed rock facing road 15 m from point

Travel_notes: walk generally south on road from point WW02
Location_desc: Point falls on shoulder of road along cement barrier on E side of Hwy 20 (left if coming from WW02).

Travel_notes: I ran this transect through the forest. However, it would be possible to walk along the dirt 2-track road from point 3 to the jct. where it splits.
Location_desc: Point falls at junction of dirt 2-track road, on West or uphill side of road

Travel_notes: From WW04, take road that goes to the left. When road starts to veer to the right at ~65m, go off-trail at ~160 degrees until you reach cleared area with power lines.
Location_desc: Point falls on edge of swath cleared for power lines. It is ~20m NW of powerlines. Power tower is just barely visible from the point to the E/NE. An old 2-track grown over with grass runs between point and power lines.

Travel_notes: a slog through mossy vine maple, ferns and salmonberry. Yet, travel not too slow.
Location_desc: point falls 7 m from small creek. Lots of cottonwood, maple, and alder. Creek is loud.

Travel_notes: more slogging, still not too slow - only 100m b/t points by mistake
Location_desc: Point falls in deciduous-conifer mis under moderately open canopy. Understory is salmonberry and fern
Location_notes: Location retired.  Points locations WW07 located too close to 06 in 2005.  2006 field observer placed WW07 a the proper distance from 06 and thus WW07 retired.

Travel_notes: from pt 5 went directly East to hwy 20 and walked along road.
Location_desc: Point is on NW of highway 20 surrounded by Bigleaf maple forest

Travel_notes: yet another slog through mossy vine maple, ferns and salmonberry. Added 2012: Cross road and head into woods. Route is flat with moderate shrub and fairly dense fern at times. Pretty mellow. You will parallel hwy for most of it.
Location_desc: Point falls amid deep lady and sword ferns and mossy logs vine maple and other. The canopy is fairly closed. Cars on the road are visible and audible. Added 2012: Point is right on the line between Bigleaf maple and Red Alder forests. It is in a pretty open spot in otherwise fairly thick understory surrounding point. Look for the feature - it is very distinctive and obvious. Note from 2012: Marked as a first visit, but already another WW08 in the system.Changed bearing to match that of this year (180 instead of the previous 160).
Location_notes: Location retired due to incongruity caused by miss-pacing between WW06 and WW07 during the 2005 field season.  See notes for WW07.

Travel_notes: Cross road and head into woods. Route is flat with moderate shrub and fairly dense fern at times. Pretty mellow. You will parallel Hwy 20 for most of it.
Location_desc: Point is right on the line between Bigleaf maple and Red alder forests. It is in a pretty open spot in otherwise fairly thick understory surrounding point. Look for the feature- it is very distinctive and obvious.

Travel_notes: Walk west through forest to Highway 20. Cross highway and climb slope 40 - 45 m to point.
Location_desc: It is ~5 m to the northeast of where it drops into moderately steep slope of drainage. On a relatively level spot on top of 2 downed birches..

Travel_notes: About 90m from TO.
Location_desc: Point location indistinct, forest Pacific Silver/West. Hemlock. Point is almost directly in line with (on trail) "twisted yellow sign..." feature.

Travel_notes: NW02 is about 225m from NW01
Location_desc: Point indistinct.  Located in Pacific Silver forest w/ western Helock commonly associated. It is on a brief downhill section of the trail before leveling off.

Travel_notes: Travel through forest on trail, nothing distinct to mention.
Location_desc: Point located on trail in forested area with shrubby understory.  Look for large amounts of downed trees (Pacific Silver and West Hemlock) that are on both sides of the trail.

Travel_notes: look for tangle of downed trees @ 25 m, then a small dry indistinct streambed--pt 4 is 105 m beyond the streambed.
Location_desc: Point is in a small dry streambed with another streambed 8 meters beyond.  Rocks scattered around near trail.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: Point located in forest, 10 m beyond point is a small creek in a ditch 3 m wide.  20 m to the SW is a large stand of dead trees.

Travel_notes: Travel through forest, when at the far end of a rocky area about 30 m wide (looks like a recent rock slide or flood) cross over stream and travel another 100 m.
Location_desc: Point located in Pac silver fir forest West. Hemlock associated.  Few distinct features present, lots of downed trees.  Lok for root ball described above.

Travel_notes: Travel down trail and enter avalanche chute at 175 meters.  Point 07 is 25 meters past forest edge.
Location_desc: Point located in avalanche chute approx 25 m from SE forest edge.  Clear view of mountains and waterfall seen across canyon.  Look for pile of bowling ball-sized boulders on the left (SW) side of trail with a slight break in shrub/vegetation.

Travel_notes: travel approx 115 m beyond edge of where avalanche chute transitions back into forest.
Location_desc: Look for the downed snag on the ground and broken directly over a rock on the So. Side of the trail.  Forest Pac silver fir w/ associated west. Hemlock.

Travel_notes: Pace 200 m along trail that goes up and down and through a couple of open areas.
Location_desc: Under Pacific silver fir canopy. It is ~15m after the start of a very slight downhill (after a brief uphill).

Travel_notes: Travel slightly more than 200 m along trail passing a bunch of cut logs- biggest described in travel features
Location_desc: Mixed coniferous point with some vine maple. Feature hemlock is right up next to trail on "left" side. About 6m after passing log cut at edge of trail (both sides of trail).

Travel_notes: Walk on trail through forest until you reach a slightly more open section with deciduous trees.
Location_desc: In open forest, in a small strip (running perpendicular to trail) of vine maple and alder.  Look for small, obvious boulder (described in features) on right hand side of trail. Note: it is not at the large, tall boulder on the left side of trail, ~20m before point.

Travel_notes: Continue down trail until you emerge from the forest into a large clearing.  Point is found in clearing.
Location_desc: Toward the northwest side of a clearing full of vine maple and willows.  Walk just past young Pacific silver fir on left.  In patch of thimbleberry.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point is on trail under moderately closed mixed conifer canopy. Understory consists of vine maple, devil's club, rubus sp. And thimbleberry.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point is under moderately closed canopy (mixed conifer). Understory is 1 m tall, comprised of devil's club, vaccinium, fern, rubus sp., and seedling conifers. Triangular boulder is closest of several large boulders to the trail.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point is on trail 1 m before creek, next to small mossy boulder, on edge between shrub habitat and mixed conifer.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point is on trail under moderately dense mixed conifer canopy. Understory, especially along trail, is thick with vaccinium along with thimbleberry and vine maple. Upslope the understory is more open, w/ mossy hummocks. Point is next to 2 m dbh Doug-fir on right side of trail.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point is on trail under moderate density mixed conifer canopy. Understory is relatively open in this particular spot but within 5 to 15 m is densely populated with vine maple, vaccinium, and other shrubs. Next to larger, mossy boulder.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: Point is on trail under mixed conifer canopy of moderate density. Understory is composed of abundant vine maple, devil's club, rubus sp. And ferns.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point is on trail under mixed conifer, largely pacific silver fir, canopy. Understory is mostly open but littered with down logs.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point is on trail under open mixed conifer canopy. Understory consists of vaccinium shrubs and a few seedling conifers.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: Point is about 8 m down trail from significant creek crossing. Snow fringed cliff face on distant mountain.  This point is approx. 2.5 m down trail from main channel of creek. Creek also runs onto the trail at this point but very shallow/able to stand on small rocks without freezing your toes during point count. Open shrub habitat.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is on a straightened and raised section of trail, 10 m down trail from a broken-off cedar snag with spectacular flowing roots encasing a white boulder on the upslope edge of trail.

Travel_notes: Continue down trail, pacing out 200 m
Location_desc: Point is at the down-trail end of a section of straightened and raised trail

Travel_notes: There are now three small bridges between SE11 and SE12.
Location_desc: Point on trail surrounded by mixed conifers and saplings. About 2 m beyond (SE of) 40 cm dbh Pacific silver fir, just along right (SW) side of trail.

Travel_notes: Travel on trail for 200 m.
Location_desc: Point at broad curve in trail with protruding vine maple on left side and less on right. Cliffs of mountain across Big Beaver Creek barely visible.

Travel_notes: One wet stream crossing on NW arm (creek flows down trail). Several extremely wet meadows toward end of NW arm. From Luna Camp, TO is a 20-minute walk northwest. Campground falls between points SE07 and SE08. Definitely wear sandals- multiple creek crossings on both arms. Point SE09 and travel between SE 07-08 are very wet. Bring sandals and towel or waterproof footwear and gaiters to keep feet warm/dry
Location_desc: Point is on trail just past several 70cm DBH fallen mossy logs, cut in middle for trail passage.  Marker easily visible from southern approach, on left side of trail.

Travel_notes: Pace ~125m from TO to NN01, through camp and up main trail.
Location_desc: Point is on trail in open Subalpine Fir woodland, amid Mountain Ash, Willow and Vaccinium. There is a cluster of subalpine firs on E side of trail (very close) right at point. It is more open immediately S of cluster.

Travel_notes: Pace ~410m over 5 switchbacks to NN02. Walk ~20-25m past 5th switchback to point.
Location_desc: point located on trail, 25 m uphill from 5th switchback. Open subalpine fir habitat and meadow. Jack mtn. clearly seen in the distance, no name drainage as well. Steep switchbacks - gps signal very strong.

Travel_notes: Pace ~550m on trail traversing 10 switchbacks.
Location_desc: point is on trail, on a straightaway. Ridge appears to drop off downslope. Ridge here is open subalpine fir woodland with a meadowlike appearance - lots of wildflowers and grasses, few shrubs. There is a downed tree parallel to trail about 1.5m upslope of point.

Travel_notes: Pace ~260m along trail, trail follows ridge and then dips to NN04.
Location_desc: point located on trail along ridge leading up to desolation peak and is surrounded by mountain hemlocks and subalpine firs. From NN04 to 05, trail dips down then goes back up to NN05. Strong GPS signal. 2012: Not sure if I'm exactly on trail (because of snow), so bearing of new features may need to be updated.

Travel_notes: Pace ~255m up trail to point.
Location_desc: point is on level section of trail along ridge. To the east, the ridge drops off dramatically; to the west it is more gradual. The Desolation Repeater is visible from here. Note: There is an even smaller boulder in between the 2 feature boulders.

Travel_notes: Pace ~210m up trail - if you walk another ~10m, you will be able to see lookout.
Location_desc: Point located on trail about 60 m before Desolation Peak lookout tower. Vast views to south, east, west. All  in Cascade Range clearly visible.

Travel_notes: Walk up to lookout, then go beyond it while veering to the left (NW/W). Go down moderately steep slope until about 30m before it drops off steeply.
Location_desc: Point is on a small rock outcrop just below a ~35cm DBH Subalpine fir (farther south of 2 similar-sized firs, ~6m apart). Good view of Jackass, but not Hozomeen right from point.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Ross Lake seen downslope. Lots of saplings and downed wood.

Travel_notes: easiest route is to go E to ridge, then S. SS02 is more than 300m from SS01.
Location_desc: point is on rock outcrop before steep drop-off on west slope of ridge. It is in open subalpine fir woodland / subalpine shrub habitat.

Travel_notes: Follow ridge about 200m to SS03.
Location_desc: point located on ridge, slope and aspect fall away in 3 directions but generally to the south. Few distinct features close by, forest is open subalpine fir, shrubs abundant. Jack Mountain's highest point is at 163 degrees

Travel_notes: Recommend going more to the E to avoid steepest part of the gully.
Location_desc: Small clearing with huckleberry and mountain ash next to line of Pacific silver firs and subalpine firs. Clearing may actually be caused by snow covering and bending a bunch of saplings.There are a few Mountain hemlocks ~3m to the SE.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: Rocky clearing with down bleached logs. There is a line of boulders about 4-5m to the S.

Travel_notes: Head downhill and SE into denser subalpine fir. Flat for first 70m, then downhill. Gets colder and more closed-canopy.
Location_desc: Near the bottom of a little gully. Subalpine fir of all ages.

Travel_notes: Head south. At ~20m, head over hill. Terrain gently rolls until ~70m and then goes downhill (not steep). Moderate to dense subalpine fir the whole way.
Location_desc: Point is in a little clearing in subalpine fir. Ground seems level at this point. Point is on the W side of 2 ~10cm DBH Subalpine firs growing around each other.

Travel_notes: traverse small hill and then continue on moderate downhill through Subalpine and huckleberry forest. Opens up after 120m
Location_desc: on small rock in clearing of open subalpine fir forest. Lots of grasses and bare ground. Ross lake is just out of view (you're able to see it as you approach point)

Travel_notes: To start off, follow open meadow/Subalpine fir to west instead of following direct bearing through dense Subalpine fir. After this, work your way downslope following openings in forest.
Location_desc: Point on NW side of meadow that both features are in. Point is right next to a willow bush in a line of young SUBF that blocks mext meadow to NW.

Travel_notes: Try to contact a ranger to see if a boat ride up lake is possible. Otherwise, it's a great hike up the East Bank trail, but an extra 4-day trip in July can be tough to squeeze in. Unless you know for certain that there is going to be snow there, bring your own water. TO is at second campground site if approaching from main trail (there is no #2 marker). Be careful with salty items! Salt-deprived wildlife is around.
Location_desc: From junction of main Desolation Pk. Trail and Desolation Pk. Campsite trail, go toward campsites, look for campsite markers on the South side of the trail, the second one passed is th Transect origination point.   Bring your own water to Campground if there is no snow.
Location_notes: The TO was originally near the end of the trail and the transect dead-ended at NN02 because it was too steep to safely go off-trail, particularly with snow. The TO was offset down the trail about 800 m to allow there to be 6 points on the arm that goes to the end of the trail (and Desolation Peak).

Travel_notes: Walk 100m at 90 degrees from T.O.
Location_desc: Point is 25m from clearing with four buildings in it, under dense mixed conifer-deciduous canopy. It is ~6-7m W of a >120cm dbh Grand Fir (see features) and Doug-fir.

Travel_notes: Go NW out driveway to road, then walk N on road, keeping yurts on right. Take a right onto drive closest to brown house with green roof. When driveway turns toward garage, keep going straight on overgrown track through grassy area for ~80m until it veers toward woods. Pace ~110m on track through woods (along river). Then veer ~20m W off track from there.
Location_desc: Point is at the edge of water bog, under 40cm DBH big-leaf maple.  Aforementioned sign is on red alder. Rootball of fallen cedar is ~4m tall.  Set of rusty red pipes within 1m NW of point.

Reason_for_change: avoid creeks, rivers, and other unnavigable water
Travel_notes: Go back out to dirt track you took to get to EE02. From there, keep walking until you reach Maintenance/recycling facilities. EE03 is 300m from EE02
Location_desc: Point is ~4m W of corner of pale yellowish, tan aluminum-sided maintenance building. Pt is between that building and pink cinder-block building.

Reason_for_change: maintain distance from other arm of transect
Travel_notes: Point is at SE corner of driveway closest to Harlequin Camp (on opposite side of driveway from telephone pole). Walk on road out to main road. Take a left (away from bridge) and walk until you reach the first house on right side of road.
Location_desc: Point is at SE corner of driveway closest to Harlequin Camp (on opposite side of driveway from telephone pole).

Travel_notes: cross 2-3 flowing channels (depending on where the water is shallowest) 50 - 30 m before point EE05. I took my boots and socks off - deepest water was knee-depth
Location_desc: point is on a point of land between a creek and the stehekin river. Unfortunately the creek does not appear on the map. Point is about 45 m up the south side of the peninsula.
Location_notes: These points (EE05-EE07) haven't been visited since 2005 because the river has a new channel and now requires a deep crossing to access these points.

Reason_for_change: Company Creek in spring flood and inaccessible
Travel_notes: Swampy with several pools to circumvent. Best to go to the SW corner of Harlequin Bridge, and, starting from the rectangular warning sign with diagonal black and yellow stripes, pace 30 m along the road in its southwesterly direction. From there, turn right and pace 11 m perpendicular to the road.
Location_desc: Point is in the upper floodplain of the Stehekin River. Open understory with several large (>2 m dbh) cedars nearby. There are two side-by-side cedars ~10m to the NE/E.

Travel_notes: * at this point it looks like transect is going to cross creek but it doesn't!
Location_desc: point is on undulating ground under mixed conifer -deciduous canopy. The creek to the southwest is audible
Location_notes: These points (EE05-EE07) haven't been visited since 2005 because the river has a new channel and now requires a deep crossing to access these points.

Reason_for_change: Stehekin River, moved point to road across the river
Travel_notes: Cross Harlequin Bridge, pace 200m (northwest) along road from one lane bridge sign on the north bank of the Stehekin River.
Location_desc: Point on road parallel to Stehekin River (Stehekin River Road) on north bank of river between river and talus slope which leads up to a cliff face. River is entirely audible from point, also slightly visibile through the thick roadside vegetation.

Travel_notes: there is a gully before the one the point is in which could easily be confused from the description
Location_desc: point is in gully / former streambed / depression winding through forest, between stehekin river and creek, though neither are audible nor visible
Location_notes: These points (EE05-EE07) haven't been visited since 2005 because the river has a new channel and now requires a deep crossing to access these points.

Travel_notes: Pace 200 m along left side of Stehekin River Rd. from EE07a.
Location_desc: Point on left side of road in a small pullout, 14m beyond a Doug-fir snag. River visible.

Travel_notes: Pace 200m along road in NW direction.
Location_desc: Point is on SW side of road on small shoulder, directly next to large boulder.  River is audible and visible.

Travel_notes: Pace just over 200m up the road. The features are all on the river side of the road (except for Ponderosa), so just watch for them.
Location_desc: Point is on edge of road. There is a stump of a tree that has been cut ~4.5m up the road (NW) from point.

Travel_notes: the best way is probably to go up rainbow loop trail (just past ee09). After the 3rd switchback walk ~50m, then walk up ~60m upslope from there
Location_desc: point is under/within some Bigleaf Maple saplings. There's a ~85cm dbh doug fir directly downslope of point (~5.5m). There's a large downed tree below fir. It's on some debris-covered large rocks. Terrain dips down on both sides from point.

Travel_notes: An easy, fairly developed EE arm. Camp at Harlequin Camp, but check the flood status first. It was ominously creeping into our camp in the late afternoons/evenings. It is a ~7min walk from Harlequin Camp. It is the second left turn after passing the yurts if coming from Harlequin. Try to survey this transect when it isn't windy - it can really affect bird activity, especially on EE arm. It can be windy in this area.
Location_desc: Point located on road to burn pile, South of the NOCA NP maintenance facility.  Origin located 20 -25 m before woodpile road splits into two distinct roads to make a small circle around the burn pile.
Location_notes: Road on which TO was supposed to be located does not exist, so TO was offset as close as possible to the intended location, but on an existing road.

Travel_notes: Walk NW to road that leads to air strip. Take left and walk to air strip. See features for exact location.
Location_desc: Point located 12 m SE of air strip signs on the NE edge of air strip.  Dirt two track road running along NE side of airstrip is 2 m from point.  Best way to find the point is to locate signs on the road and pace 12 m SE down road from point.

Travel_notes: cross landing strip following a west bearing, head into forest.  Proceed about 30 m beyond a line of tall doug-fir trees to an open area with a noticeable line of big-leaf maple trees. Walk 240m at a bearing of 268.
Location_desc: Point is located in a clearing of small Doug-firs with Bigleaf Maples.  The point is right next to an old eggplant shaped Douglas-fir stump with a 131 cm DBH.  Small dogwood due west of the stump (1 meter).

Travel_notes: Head West, pass the quarry outhouse on the North side and the quarry itself on the South side.  Proceed uphill and down into swale behind quarry.
Location_desc: point located in swale behind quarry.  The back side of the quarry slope can be seen 25 m from point.  Forest recently burned.  Topography slopes steeply upwards toward the South.  The point is right next to a burnt, downed log in the middle of a gully between the quarry and a steeply rising slope.

Travel_notes: No distinct features between points. WW04 actually 220 m from WW03.
Location_desc: Point located in open Doug-fir forest, recently burned.  Abrupt change in slope 28 m away @ 240 degrees, rocky steep slope changes form less-sloped grass, covered ground.  The point is located in an open Doug- Fir/Ponderosa Pine forest, 2 meters away from a 35 cm DBH Douglas-fir.

Travel_notes: Look for dirt two-track, vegetation remains similar.
Location_desc: Open Doug-fir forest, recently burned. Near transition of where terrain starts to go down more steeply.

Travel_notes: None. WW06 is actually 275 m from WW05.
Location_desc: The point is located in a rocky outcrop, clearing open ~20m on all sides.  White flowering low shrub (snowbrush) present all around the clearing.  This point is 275 meters from WW05.

Travel_notes: Travel downslope, when veg changes from open forest to shrub point is approx 60 m further. WW07 actually 240 m from WW06.
Location_desc: Point located in dry forest/open shrub habitat 18 m SW of Company Creek road.  Bridge over Company Creek is 50 m down road (North) from transect intersection w/ road.  Open view of Stehekin Valley.

Travel_notes: Cross gravel road, go through dry forest/shrub veg and across a 10 m wide rock lined ditch--past the ditch vegetation begins to change into deciduous dominated vegetation.  Drop down slpe into dense riparian veg, small creek just ahead.
Location_desc: The point is located just after a braided stream section (or in the stream, based the on water level that year). Point is next to a ~150-200 DBH cedar and a 150 DBH cottonwood ~5m apart. Surrounded by vine maple to the N&W.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: Down trail from point there are a bunch of cut off log segments on both sides of trail. It is right next to a mountain ash (on uphill side) that looms over trail/point.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: Point located ~5m past bottom of trail section lined on both sides by logs supporting trail bed for approx 15 m.  Down trail 13 m look for barkless snag on the south side of the trail.

Travel_notes: travel down trail, small creek crosses trail @ 25 m.  NN03 only about 135 m from NN02.
Location_desc: The point is located at the top of the section of trail supported by logs on both sides, right before stepping on said part of trail with logs.

Travel_notes: Follow trail downhill, be wary of switchbacks--GPS signal OK. After a broad switchback, pace about 35 m to next switchback and NE04.
Location_desc: At apex of switchback curve approx 65 m before creek # 1 described on NE05 point sampling form.

Travel_notes: Pass 3 creeks on the way to NN05, the first 2 at apex of switchback curves.  Pacing is difficult due to long switchbacks.  NN05 located 25 m beyond creek.
Location_desc: Dense forest along trail, chilliwack river heard below. Point next to featured 75cm dbh 5m high snag with straddle base. On S side of trail are 2 pistol-gripped hemlocks.

Travel_notes: Travel down switchbacks and pass over 2 creeks, once over the second creek (Hells gorge Creek) pace 30 m around the corner until creek just out of sight.
Location_desc: Point located on trail 30 m beyond creek coming out of Hells Gorge, between featured snag and cut log.

Travel_notes: Follow trail.
Location_desc: Look for small stream crossing over trail at a bend in the trail 5 m before point. Point right next to featured logs stuck between trees.

Travel_notes: Follow trail, look for log bridge crossing over small stream 45 m before point. Point next to large 100 cm dbh Mountain hemlock.
Location_desc: Point located on trail

Travel_notes: Pace 200 m along trail, terrain steep on either side.
Location_desc: Bleached snag approximately 30 m tall on S side of trail around 17 m before point. Some exposed views of rock face and mountain across river.

Travel_notes: Pace 200 m along trail, more exposed views to the S.
Location_desc: Point is located between two large (~100-120dbh) trees (hemlock and fir), both on the S side of trail. Point right after a dug out trail water drainage.

Travel_notes: Travel down trail approximately 200 m, crossing over raised portion of trail over small creek channel at about 70 m.
Location_desc: Point located on bend in trail (sloping down in a northeasterly direction). Forest is mixed conifer with hemlock, Doug-fir, and cedar.

Travel_notes: Travel along trail downslope. Adjust pacing for switchbacks and elevation loss. A small rocky stream crosses the trail at 66 m.
Location_desc: In mixed conifer forest with moss-covered ground and moss-covered downed logs scattered throughout. Point on trail next to featured 2 small moss covered boulders.

Travel_notes: Travel at NE bearing through vaccinium and lots of downed trees and branches- moderate travel until reach ridge/streambank of Copper Creek.
Location_desc: Point located on ridge before slope drops to Copper Creek. Featured large rootwad just downslope and featured bleached snag just upslope. Ground cover is mostly vaccinium.

Travel_notes: 10min hike from Boundary Camp to TO. There is an Admin site at Boundary Camp that you can camp at if the other camp is full/snowy. If needed, ask WIC for permission and directions. Hike from Hannegan Peak is about an hour with full packs. Much easier to camp at Boundary Camp, but Hannegan is beautiful!
Location_desc: After passing featured rotting, bleached snag, look for the cluster of 3 Pacific Silver firs just downslope from the trail (2016 note: one of the trees is now a 3m tall snag); the largest is the marker tree. Pacific Silver-fir forest with large, mature trees. Camped at Boundary Camp (~5 miles from trailhead, 2 hr. hike or so). Origin is located about 600 m down Chilliwack River Trail from Campsite.

Travel_notes: point located on trail 100 m upslope from origination point.
Location_desc: Relatively open forest with vaccinium and silver fir saplings on both sides of trail right at point.

Travel_notes: Small creek closest to point 2 is 55 m before the point - direct  pacing around a switchback convex curve. 2019-GPS off 30m from features- rely on features to verify correct location.
Location_desc: Trail is relatively flat and straight at and before point for 20 - 25 m. 30 m beyond point trail drops and turns north to a switchback beyond. The feature silver firs are across the trail from each other, right where trail bends to the N.

Travel_notes: travel upslope and most of the way through the meadow. Stop about 30 m before trail junction.
Location_desc: point is located in open meadow about 30 m down Chilliwack Valley Trail from Copper Ridge Trail Junction. Boundary Camp is clearly visible to the southwest.  Right next to a large (but low) flat rock on S side of trail.

Travel_notes: From trail junction, walk 600 m on Copper Ridge Trail or until easting corresponds with GPS coordinates.
Location_desc: Point is on trail under open Mountain hemlock canopy. Understory is vaccinium and Pacific Silver fir seedlings. There are many rounds of trees that have been cut on the S side oof trail about 5 m down trail from point. Point directly at base of rotting cut log.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point is on trail under open  Mtn. hemlock / Pacific silver fir canopy. Understory is vaccinium and Pacific silver fir seedlings. Slope is steep

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point is on trail under moderate-density Mountain Hemlock / Pacific Silver Fir forest. Understory is vaccinium, Pacific silver fir seedlings and some herbs

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point is on trail under open Pacific Silver Fir / Mountain Hemlock forest canopy . Understory is vaccinium and Pacific silver fir saplings.

Travel_notes: Eight switchbacks between points. WW08 is about 105m past the 8th switchback.
Location_desc: point is under open mountain hemlock / pacific silver fir forest canopy, on trail. Understory is vaccinium shrub and pacific silver fir saplings. Slope is moderate. At point in trail where many exposed roots are on and beside trail. There are a few young yellow cedars downslope (and slightly to the E) of trail right at point.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point is on trail on moderately steep slope with excellent view of peaks! Also, on edge between mountain hemlock and meadow habitats. Look for mountain goat on cliffs above!

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point is on trail on steep hillside, on open section of slope - peaks are visible across the valley. It is about 12 m before crossing drainage and about 3 m after it becomes more open on S side of trail (much fewer mtn. hemlocks).

Travel_notes: Walk up trail about 200 m, crossing 2 drainages along the way. Point is ~40m past second drainage.
Location_desc: Mostly vaccinium on N side of trail, vaccinium and saplings on S side. On a relatively flat section of trail.

Travel_notes: Head up trail towards ridgeline. stop before before trail gets to the rocky drainage
Location_desc: point located about 4m past where the trail bends north towards the rocky outcrop and drainage. Many mountain hemlock saplings just upslope and downslope of trail

Travel_notes: Continue up Pierce Mt. Trail until you reach Lodgepole Pine that has broken halfway up and fallen across trail creating right angle shape overhead. At this point head due N (360 degrees) for 25m to point.
Location_desc: No distinctive features present.  Point located on the NW edge of a dense patch of Lodgepole pines, all small growing (<10 cm dbh).  Just NW is more open Doug-fir forest with fern and blueberry understory. Just beyond that, 30 m away is edge of another lodgepole sapling thicket. Trail is just barely visible from point.

Travel_notes: travel very steep, use caution.  Travel downslope through thick saplings on a NW bearing, continue travelling as far as possible up rocky cliff until travel is stopped by cliff.
Location_desc: Point located at the base of steep rock face, very distinctive--moss-covered and impassible in most places. There is a side-by-side Doug-fir and Western hemlock on rock wall.  Doug-fir is ~85cm DBH, about 2.5x larger than hemlock. A steeply cut, narrow ravine occurs just in front of the rock wall when approaching from pt 01.

Travel_notes: When leaving NW02, skirt rock wall to the S. Look for moss-covered rock slab 130m beyond NW02. Traverse around the downhill edge of this cliffband and follow the 270 degree bearing across steep slope from there.
Location_desc: Point is on steep hill in Western redcedar/Doug-fir forest with little understory. Many large boulders protruding out of ground on hillside. One such boulder just uphill from point (see image).

Travel_notes: Travel directly up very steep slope for 200 m.  The first 100 m is up steep slope, but little vegetation or downed timber makes the going easy. Once the slope mellows out, you cross through a few flat mossy openings.
Location_desc: Location indistinct overall. Doug-fir forest, abundant moss on ground.   Point is on slight hill in open, mature Doug-fir forest. Ground cover is blueberry, Oregon grape, and moss. The lake can be seen to NE. There is a large boulder to the SE of point that is very obvious as you approach (see feature).

Travel_notes: Travel gradually upslope over varied terrain for 110 m, after passing over indistinct rock ridgeline, travel will be flat or slightly down hill to point. Point is actually 150 meters from NW04.
Location_desc: location indistinct.  Varied topography.  Forest dominated by doug-firs with western hemlock associated.  Point is on broad mossy shelf of ridgeline. Just uphill is steep slope (45+ degrees). The point is directly next to a washing machine-sized boulder (see image).

Travel_notes: Travel across sloped terrain traversing for the most part until 150-160 m when a marked slope change will coincide with a large, moss-covered rock structure. Point is actually 245 meters from NW05
Location_desc: Point located in an open Doug-fir forest with minimal understory.  18 m down slope topography flattens, this is where the pond occurs.  Beware - there is a larger pool about 50m to the W. There are several large boulders just upslope of point (to the W of twin cedars). Varied topography, few distinctive features.

Travel_notes: travel at a bearing of 270 downslope over mossy logs and rocks. Keep skunk cabbage on left, then descend towards creek. Creek will be just out of view when you reach point
Location_desc: Point on relatively flat ground 5m from obvious pulled up root mass, Mixed conifer forest surrounds, creek can be heard but not quite seen.

Travel_notes: Travel down to stream, cross easily across rocks and travel up moderate slope to the peak of small "mountain."
Location_desc: Point at the peak of large hill (small mountain), in small mossy clearing of primarily Doug-fir forest. Point is 2m from Double trunk Doug-fir snag roughly 20m tall.

Travel_notes: Descend off hilltop down moderate slope that gets steeper after 50m. After getting steeper the terrain flattens out before reaching a cliff. Skirt left around steep part of cliff and wrap back around to point above
Location_desc: point is in DOFI and WEHE forest wtih little to no understory. There is a ~50 cm DBH snag held up by leaning on another tree 2m from point to NE that I did not include as a feature because it might fall soon

Travel_notes: walk then climb carefully down moss-covered outcrops. Point is 25 m below the last of these.
Location_desc: point is on slope of small, unstable rocks covered with moss, under a cascara and vine maple subcanopy. Doug fir prevails above

Travel_notes: travel eases up once you cross the trail. After crossing trails, transect drops into small gully. After this, it climbs up "hummock of rock." Point is on the SE side of this.
Location_desc: point falls just past a mossy hummock of rock (there are two) on a gently sloping "bench". Forest is composed of short, scrawny doug firs with lots of moss and lichen hanging from their branches.

Travel_notes: descend shoulder of small "bench" where SE02 is located. Continue down steep slope. Note that the distance between SE02 and SE03 is only ~160m.
Location_desc: point is on steep slope just above border where alders begin to infiltrate the subcanopy of the doug fir forest.

Travel_notes: traverse steep slope
Location_desc: point falls under mature doug fir canopy. Understory is open but littered with downed logs and debris. Slope is moderate.

Travel_notes: Easy walking, either a gentle sideslope or basically flat the whole way.
Location_desc: point is on moderately steep slope under mature doug fir canopy. Understory is open but littered with down logs and debris. Herb layer consists primarily of moss and oregon grape.

Travel_notes: Easy walking for first ~80m, then it gets progressively steeper and denser. The last ~70m are steep, but free of dense understory.
Location_desc: point on steep terrain sloping down toward Ross Lake. Cougar Island seen from point. About 8 m to the S are 2 Doug-firs side-by-side, both with curve in lower part of trunk.

Travel_notes: transect goes up steep slope which becomes more gradual at 60 m or so rom previous point. Transect runs on or next to trail from about 60 m to the point. Once you skirt large boulders (stay downhil), you can cut up to trail.
Location_desc: Point is downhill from trail under forest of short, skinny conifers, many snags and all dangling moss and lichen from branches. Understory is open, no shrubs taller than 0.5 m. Some moss-covered rock directly upslope from point and trail.

Travel_notes: Relatively easy over thin downed logs/snags. Forest young and over mossy rocks.
Location_desc: Just below trail (about 15 m) on slope with downed trees and lots of mossy covered boulders and rocks. Red alder, predominately

Travel_notes: Cut up to trail, pace ~170 m before heading W for remaining 20-30 m.
Location_desc: Located on dry, open hillside with dying lodgepole pines. Lots of downed wood to scramble over. It is ~4m above the edge of a mossy ledge.

Travel_notes: Easy trail travel, then steep final 30 m.
Location_desc: Point is on a soft, mossy ledge where it starts to flatten out. Note: photo of doug fir sapling amongst pines was not taken from point (taken closer).

Travel_notes: The TO is about a one-hour walk from Green Point Campground (with full packs). To reach TO, walk up the main trail until you reach the junction with Pierce Mountain Trail.  Head up the Pierce Mountain Trail for approximately 5-10 minutes.  The TO is located in the middle of a 10m section of trail running NE/SW with a dog leg on both ends.  The SE arm is very mellow. The transect is very buggy (but Green Point is not!)- a headnet would definitely come in handy. One possible option is to camp at Cougar Island and paddle to closest shore-- a convenient trail (not on maps) is located on the mainland directly W of campsite, which climbs hill to junction of Sourdough Trail and the Big Beaver Trail. Paddle plus hike= 30 minutes. This works better if you aren't combining this transect with others in the Big Beaver area. Watch out for yellowjackets!
Location_desc: Origination point located on the trail as close as possible to the intended location.  Trail off 30 m to the North according to the GPS unit.  When at intended Easting on the trail, look for a linear section in the trail approx. 5 m in length running NW/SE. The origin point is midway through the 5 m long linear section.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point is on side of road under open conifer canopy. Creek flows by at ~40 m

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point is on roadside under mixed conifer/deciduous canopy. Creek is at 18 m from point, and loud

Travel_notes: travel up road from NN02.
Location_desc: Point located on road.  Large cedar tree up road from point, almost growing in road.  East of the road there is a shrub dominated area with exposed rock cliffs above it.  West of the road red alder trunks can be seen with occasional cedars, a shrub understory, and the river.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point is on edge of road under open mixed conifer/deciduous canopy. Bank falls steeply to creek 8 m away

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point is on side of road under mixed conifer and deciduous canopy. Creek is 25-30 m away and loud.  grove of alders to the left of the road.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: Point is on side of road amid primarily conifers. Bank falls steeply to cobbled former creekbed. Slope is measured on road. Dense stand of Hemlock to right of road.  Creek 10m to left of road.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point is on road next to huge s-turn in creek, which is about 2 m from the edge of the road. Shrub habitat is adjacent at 10 m.

Travel_notes: Pass bathroom and parking lot on the right.
Location_desc: point is on road under moderately open conifer / deciduous mix. Open shrub habitat is adjacent at 10m.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point is on road in middle of pullout under moderately open conifer/deciduous mix. Shrub habitat at 20 m provides interesting diversity of bird spp. Creek is relatively quieter.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point is on road a short distance from creek, which is relatively quieter. Stands of tall (1 m) cow parsnip line the road.

Travel_notes: Continue up road 200 m
Location_desc: Point is between two 6-m long sections of the referenced fallen tree snag, one section on each side of road

Travel_notes: Point is on bridge.  Travel 200m on road.
Location_desc: none

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: point is 20m past turnout on S side of road. Creek is very loud.

Travel_notes: Travel 100 m down road from origination point.
Location_desc: Located on road.  Cascade River heard and seen to NW.  Mile-marker 19 best distinguishing feature, located 29 m NNE of point on E side of road, but hard to see in ferns.

Travel_notes: Travel down road from SS01.
Location_desc: Indistinct road side point.  Shoulder falls off approx 7 m on west side of road.  No distance for new hemlock feature though, so please update this next visit.

Travel_notes: Travel down road from SS02.
Location_desc: Look for two cedar trees described above almost directly across road from each other.

Travel_notes: Travel down road from SS03.
Location_desc: Indistinct roadside point.  Most distinguishing feature are two Cedar trees.  The first is 21.5 m beyong SS04--it is forked near the top and vegetated on its uppermost branches.  The second isnow a flat, broken stump, ~20m past the first (still standing) cedar.  Both trees are in the picture and are on the west side of the road.

Travel_notes: travel down road from SS04.
Location_desc: Linear dirt pullout on North side of road 10 m before point. 2019: GPS seems off- difficult to find exact point based on features. I took coordinates from the NE side of the pullout and updated features.

Travel_notes: Travel down road from SS05.
Location_desc: Indistinct roadside point.  Look for red Alder dominated forest and two very large cedar trees 20 m up road on No. side of road towards SS05.

Travel_notes: Travel down road from SS06.
Location_desc: Indistinct roadside point located in conifer and decidious forest. Point is 46m after several human-cut trees with 2-meter long chunks on side of road.

Travel_notes: Travel on road from SS07. Right before reaching point, will pass the bare-topped Doug-fir in picture.
Location_desc: Roadside point.  NOCA Cascade River entrance sign 44 m towards the SW on the north side of the road, sign has small pullout in front of it.  View of exposed rock cliff seen on No. side of Cascade river.

Travel_notes: First 160 m of travel is gradual uphill through dense understory and lots of down trees. Then, travel uphill approx. 40 meters to point. 2018 update: to avoid 100m of Devils Club head back toward SS07 ~20m and enter forest where Devils club clears.
Location_desc: Point on relatively steep slope located between two snags only 3 meters apart, seen on right side of picture of marker tree. Area with many fallen trees. Large Doug-firs and Western redcedars dominate. Relatively open canopy directly above.

Travel_notes: Lots of creek noise. GPS wasn't reading too close to points; careful to rely on features. NN arm stays close to Cascade river and tributaries the whole way, very loud at all points. SS arm easy until SS09, which is off-trail. GPS signal was weak and features from nav report were hard to pinpoint. 1 hour 10 min drive from Diablo if you don't camp at Mineral Creek.
Location_desc: 63 meters up the road from mile-marker 19 in middle of small hill that crests by a stream coming down (nice pullout on hillcrest).  We camped at the free campsite directly across road from Mineral Park -- East Campground (a NF fee cpgd). 10min drive to TO.

Travel_notes: Sea of dense shrubs.  Better to take the trail up to PCT, then head east at the junction.  Pace 160 meters from junction, then pace off-trail approx. 20 meters in SW direction to first point.
Location_desc: right at transition between shrubfield and forest.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: Point is on NE side of 20-m wide homogenous bracken fern patch.  There is a fallen log at the edge of the fern patch, directly next to the point.

Travel_notes: Moderately easy travel through light shrub until the last ~25 m, where it gets much more dense. On uphill end of shrubby area. GPS might point you a little farther downslope.
Location_desc: Point is at NW corner of a small shrubfield, mostly serviceberry and cherry, in a very small grassy area within the shrubby area  (that is all surrounded by douglas-fir.) There is a ~60cm DBH Doug-fir whose branches extend downhill to point. On uphill end of shrubby area. GPS might point you a little farther downslope.

Travel_notes: Horribly dense shrubs--extremely difficult.  I recommend bushwacking to the trail from point 03; when trail crosses talus slope, leave trail and walk down talus slope approx 60 m.
Location_desc: Point is on the narrow talus chute; amid a sea of very dense shrubs. It is on a section of the talus slope where the talus extends farther to the E, and there is some shrub between point and the main talus chute. Some branches of bitter cherry extend E to point.

Travel_notes: head up talus slope approx 100 m, then up through shrubs for approx 100 m.
Location_desc: Pt. is a little shy of 200 m from previous point; but position on top of large, rock outcropping gives a great panorama over area. It is about 2 m N of the edge where vegetation ends, where rock outcrop starts to drop off.

Travel_notes: Bushwack to closest part of stream, then walk N along creek for 200 m; point is just up out of creek on W bank.
Location_desc: Point is about 5 m W of the creek, on the edge of dense shrub. VERY loud.

Travel_notes: Travel upstream for approx. 60 meters. Keep heading North and go up gradual hill past prominent rock outcrop. Continue for 75 meters through shrubs up relatively steep slope. There are several large snags with branches ~15m upslope from point.
Location_desc: Point is on E side of stream approximately 30 meters away. On steep slope in fairly dense shrub next to pistol-gripped Doug-fir (25 cm dbh). This tree stands alone within a 15 m radius. There are severl large snags with branches about 15m upslope from point. Beautiful vista from point. Bridge Creek visible in distance. Very loud point!

Travel_notes: Travel is through open but steep Doug-fir forest until the last 50m where it becomes more brushy.
Location_desc: Point is in a small open rocky section on top of a small rock spine with brush below and thicker Doug-fir forest upslope.

Travel_notes: You can follow az225 straight through the shrubs (it isn't that terrible) or head west on the trail and cut south once you're closer.
Location_desc: Dense shrubsceanothus/maple.  Some small firs in plot. On edge of willow thicket.  On slope facing South Fork camp.

Travel_notes: Travel is through dense willow/ceanothus shrub habitat--slow going. Or save some time by climbing back to the trail and hiking W until you hit a (mostly) dry creek bed. Follow that downhill to the point
Location_desc: Relatively open, N-S running line of cottonwood 15 m W of Pt.  Twin doug-firs (12 m apart) located 25 m E of Pt.  Veg is mixed shrub hab.

Travel_notes: Revised in 2006: When travelling to SW03, I suggest hiking up dry creekbed 15 m W of point SW02 to PCT and then hike to exact easting on trail. Then proceed up approximately 15 m N to point SW03. 2013: I strongly support 2006 revision to travel.
Location_desc: Spot is on a cluster of rocks 25 m from trail.

Travel_notes: Travel through dense willow/ceanothus
Location_desc: point located in fairly dense willow/ceanothus/shrubs.  Point is just NW of two large Doug-firs.  Northernmost Doug-fir is 13 m at 320 degrees.

Travel_notes: dense brush most of way until under forest canopy, then start to climb outcrops (easier travel)
Location_desc: Point is just downslope of dead tree feature in the center of a shrubby chute.

Travel_notes: Travel is up a very steep slope.  Recommend traveling up rocky drainage until reaching intended northing (there are two small Douglas-firs growing out of the same stump on W. side of drainage).  From here, traverse W. following old game trail to point.
Location_desc: Point located on relatively open ground, littered with rocks on steep slope. Good views of peaks to the south on a clear day.

Travel_notes: Travel is steep, perhaps a bit sketchy at points. You pass through a shrubby drainage after 140m or so. Don't rush up, make sure to have ample time to get to point.
Location_desc: point is on large rock precipice just before vertical wall. To the E the rock is a steep downhill slab to a drainage. West is clumps of oceanspray. The precipice/ridge runs N-S 8m before turning into a cliff. A breathtaking view

Travel_notes: An unpleasant (shrubby) transect when wet, but very birdy! It is probably a good idea to wait until first week in July (but no later) to survey this transect - creek noise will be a lot quieter then. There was a newly installed bear box at South Fork- check to confirm this before going out. Creek noise is an issue with this transect- try to survey this at times when it isn't or hasn't super recently been hot and/or raining a lot. You can monitor the CFS of the Stehekin River on the USGS river gage site.
Location_desc: Stayed at South Fork Campground (about 2-3 hour hike in from Rainy Pass Trailhead or about 3 hours from Bridge Creek Camp). TO on trail to campground (~5 min. hike to TO). All open shrub here. Just down trail from where shrub gets much taller on S side.

Travel_notes: For easiest travel, hike to junction of Little Beaver Trail. Turn left and pace 20 meters. You will see a 60 dbh Doug-fir 2 meters off trail on the N side. The point is just behind that tree.
Location_desc: Point is 4 meters from Little Beaver Trail (on N side). Large 100 cm dbh Western redcedar NW of point.

Travel_notes: Travel up gradual slope to NW02. Many large Douglas Firs and Red Cedars. Lots of down trees.
Location_desc: Point on gradual slope surrounded by sapling conifers. You may be able to see cedar over rock feature better as you're approaching, than from point itself. It is ~7m SE of barkless, decayed snag, but beware- there are several others to the E/SE.

Travel_notes: Travel up slope. After approx. 140 meters, slope increases
Location_desc: Point on very steep slope above many downed trees. Point is on the NE of a large boulder (~4m tall from downslope) with Douglas maple growing from it. There are several large (>60cm DBH) downed trees lying E/SE to W/NW, starting ~6m s of point.

Reason_for_change: Much too steep to remain on bearing.
Travel_notes: Travel is difficult with the many down trees and steep slope. At 60 meters, enter small but dense section of vine maple. Then, continue through Douglas-fir forest.
Location_desc: Point is on a small ridge on a steep slope in area with several sapling cedars. Douglas-fir still dominates. There are a few small boulders right around point.

Travel_notes: Navigate across steep slope through mostly open Douglas-fir forest. You will notice large rock slab. Point is 20 meters SE of that.
Location_desc: Point located on boulder 20 meters to south of very large, smooth rock slab. Large, bus-sized boulder to ~5m West of point. Good view of mountains. Peaks to SW are glaciated. About 2m NE of start of thick vine maple.

Travel_notes: Travel difficult through vine maple then slide alder, but view makes it worth it. Once entered into Doug-fir stand, slope gets steeper. Many boulders to go over and around.
Location_desc: Point 10 m South of large boulder, approx. 4m tall and 7 m wide. Steep N-S slope. Scattered vine maple, but relatively open understory. To SE are two mid-size boulders. It is at the base (uphill side) of a ~60cm DBH Doug-fir. There is another boulder (larger) ~30m to the NE. Lots of other boulders around, too. Look at photo.

Travel_notes: cross bridge over Little Beaver.
Location_desc: Point directly next to log (truck-sized boulder) on S side of trail. 10 m E of 3 other large boulders (even larger than the one next to point) on both sides of trail.

Travel_notes: Cross open boulder field, re-enter closed canopy forest. Point in forest.
Location_desc: Point next to large (3 m) boulder on N side of trail on rocky section of trail.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point in open boulder field, forest edge seen 100 m to the W. Point is 10 m W of truck-sized boulder with small western redcedar growing on top.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point in between the cut ends of a Doug-fir recently cleared from trail and 3 m W of a large Western hemlock (dbh 90 cm) on downhill side of trail.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point 3 m E of dry streambed.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is 3 m E of cut ends of fallen tree on either side of trail. Small stream heard to N.

Travel_notes: At Stillwell Campground sign post, continue 20 m on trail toward the camp. Do not take trail toward Beaver Pass.
Location_desc: Point next to 1 m dbh Western hemlock on N side of trail, 3 m beyond dry streambed and 20 m past sign for Stillwell Campground.

Travel_notes: Travel easy, flat terrain, little understory.
Location_desc: Dense Doug-fir and Western hemlock canopy cover, lady fern predominant understory. Slight slope to the N.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point next to >1 m dbh Westerh hemlock (largest in area) on W end of 15 m patch Devil's Club. Dry streambed seen to W on bearing.

Travel_notes: Mosquitoes- be prepared.
Location_desc: Point is 5 m from N end of bridge over Little Beaver directly next to a cut stump on one side and cut end of Doug-fir log on other side of trail. 20 minute hike from Stillwell Camp.
Location_notes: Trail was off on map, so TO was offset in order for it to be located on-trail.

Travel_notes: Travel 150 m on trail from TO.
Location_desc: Point on trail in dense mixed conifer forest. Small stream heard to S.

Travel_notes: Pace 250 m on trail.
Location_desc: Point is 4 m beyond a bend in trail to the E, directly next to a 3 m tall stump on the S side of the trail.

Travel_notes: Pace 230 m on trail. Pass the Pasaytan Wilderness sign at 100 m.
Location_desc: Point is in relatively open area along trail directly atop a rock that acts as a step.

Travel_notes: Travel 290 m on trail.
Location_desc: Point is 5 m down trail from a dogleg across a small dry drainage and at the centerpoint of 2 mossy cut logs running parallel to the trail.

Travel_notes: Pace 230 m on trail.
Location_desc: Vine maple along each side of trail. Point is 4 m up trail from the cut end of a log running SW-NE along the trail.

Travel_notes: Travel slightly down hill. First 150 m, more open Western hemlock/Doug-fir forest (dbh 23-53 cm), last 50 m very dense Western hemlock/Doug-fir forest (dbh <23 cm)
Location_desc: Point in dense, young Western hemlock and Doug-fir forest atop an old mossy rotting log.

Travel_notes: travel through dense mixed conifer forest at bearing 270
Location_desc: Point is located in dense conifer forest alongside a large, reddish, fire-scarred doug-fir.

Travel_notes: First ~100m is dense Doug-fir/Western hemlock forest. Then, as you start to climb there's lots of blow down and going over and under small lodgepoles. Forest remains relatively young.
Location_desc: Point is in a young open doug-fir forest with tons of blowdown. Point is in a more level area ~20m after steep climb. There is a rotten downed snag directly at point. There are two 7-m tall snags-the one due south is the feature.

Travel_notes: Pace 120 meters on trail from TO to NN01
Location_desc: Point on curvy but relatively straight section of trail heading NE-SW. It is about 7 m past downed tree cut at trail's edge.

Travel_notes: Pace 310 meters on trail to NN02
Location_desc: Point in mix of cedar and Doug-fir with a mess of downed trees around area. Look for feature Doug-fir on "right" (North) side of trail. It is very obvious.

Travel_notes: Pace 400 meters on trail to NN03. It is about 160m (pacing anyway) from the 4th switchback.
Location_desc: Point on trail, ~1m down trail from water bar. 2 roots, 1 meter apart ahead on trail. Look for burnt snag, 10 meters off East side of trail. I forgot to get the distance to the hemlock but it is within 5m of point. Please add this next visit.

Travel_notes: Travel over many down trees. Terrain relatively flat.
Location_desc: Many downed trees and cedar saplings near point. There are also a lot of young Doug-firs; feature Doug-fir is notably larger. Ross Lake seen through trees.

Travel_notes: Travel is relatively flat, but filled with many down trees. Young Doug-fir most of the way.
Location_desc: Point is on edge of small rock face (uphill of), on NE side. Lots of birches downhill from rock face. Right below some oceanspray. There is a cluster of Douglas maple uphill from point (about 7m) whose branches extend almost to point.

Travel_notes: Start out travelling through brushy understory. At 115 meters enter open vista with beautiful view. At 150 meters, habitat resembles first 100 meters of travel.
Location_desc: Point is in a small birch stand with a few Doug-firs and other conifers mixed in. It is under some vine maple branches (from downslope). Look for two of the largest Doug-firs (~70cm DBH) to the SW, about 4m apart- there isn't much in between them (except Oregon Grape).

Travel_notes: Make your way through some vine maple (not too much) and then through a litter of down trees. Ground covered by down trees all the way to NN07.
Location_desc: Point in relatively open area with several snags and fallen trees. Downward slope begins toward stream bed 15 m beyond point. Less understory right at point, but surrounded by downed trees.

Travel_notes: Travel down slope of stream bed and then start an uphill traverse of a relatively steep slope to NN08.
Location_desc: Point is on a steep slope ~2m E of a cluster of Douglas maples (there is another cluster about 5 m to the NE). Downslope of point is mossy with less understory than surrounding area.

Travel_notes: First ~100m of travel along fairly steep slope with moderate brush and moss-covered boulders. Continue across moss and grass-covered sheer boulder face. Descend back into more forested area at ~175m. Continue through trees to NN09.
Location_desc: NN09 is 1m upslope of intertwined clump of 5-10cm dbh vine maples, right next to ~20cm dbh dead cedar. Lots of small downed limbs and logs in area, mostly Doug firs. Lots on vine maple on mossy slope to N/NE.

Travel_notes: TO is about a 30-minute uphill hike from Devil's Junction Camp (which is about 12.5 miles up East Bank Trail). Devil's Creek Camp is a little closer, but it's not as nice (not on the water)- only one site at Devil's Junction; make sure you specify when getting a permit. You will have to pace more than 200m between on-trail points because of curves and switchbacks.
Location_desc: Point at center of 30 m straight section of trail that runs N-S. Small stream heard to W. Mt. Prophet visible through trees.

Travel_notes: Travel slightly uphill through moderately dense understory.
Location_desc: Point next to downed log running SW-NE with many branches (Pacific silver fir)

Travel_notes: Travel downhill. At 50 m hit stream, transect follows this stream for next 50 m.
Location_desc: Point is about 15 m off trail- barely visible through understory- in dense patch of vine maple.

Travel_notes: Travel through dense understory. Cross trail twice and climb out of closed canopy forest to open shrubland at EE03.
Location_desc: Point in dense understory with open canopy, McGregor visible to E, Stehekin River heard to W, next to 2 downed logs lying E-W.

Travel_notes: Dense understory. Drop off ridge and cross small valley and dry stream bed, slightly uphill rest of the way but with less understory near point.
Location_desc: Point on rock pile next to Doug-fir rootmass on vegetation edge where understory becomes present and dense (compared to 20 m leading up to point) and a second downed Doug-fir with many branches running E-W.

Travel_notes: Travel upslope, dense understory for first 50 m. At 130 m, cross trail and continue upslope.
Location_desc: Point on fallen log between two groups of Doug-fir (dbh 35 cm) on flat terrain with open understory. Large rocky outcrops to the NE.

Travel_notes: Travel back to trail from EE05, take trail all the way until crossing trail 5 m from EE06 before stream crossing. Travel easy, little understory.
Location_desc: Point is 2 m off trail directly beside a 100 cm dbh Doug-fir just before stream crossing.

Travel_notes: Continue down trail to next stream crossing.
Location_desc: Point is 15m before stream crossing, and 5 meters off trail to the west, next to a 75cm dbh doug fir snag with a very curved trunk.

Travel_notes: Pace 250m down trail. Hike over boulder and into shrub just before little trail and sign for coon lake.
Location_desc: in a slight depression filled with shrub.

Travel_notes: We camped at Tumwater, about a 20-25 minute walk to TO (Dolly Varden flooded and is now closed). We walked up the road then took the old wagon trail (about 7 minutes) to the TO. Some points on EE arm cross trails, though they are not seen at the same location on map- follow nav. report. A 26 minute drive from Harlequin camp to trailhead.
Location_desc: Point is about 2 m after bend in trail to the North after small straight stretch due East

Travel_notes: Travel 100 m through relatively flat, relatively dense Mixed Conifer forest, crossing small creek just over halfway. Near creek more deciduous vegetation appears.
Location_desc: Point below overhanging Bigleaf maple. Large variety of vegetation present. Creek visible to both NE and S, 20-30 m away. Point on small hill above stream bed, not quite at the top.

Travel_notes: Travel through undulating terrain and down steep slope of stream/stream bed. Other than that slope, travel is relatively easy.
Location_desc: Point in open, grassy area near stream. Several snags surround the area10 m NW of point, slope drops rapidly. Shart peaks seen in distance to S/SW.

Travel_notes: Travel is up and down. FIrst, descend to cross creek, then travel uphill going over or around large boulders.
Location_desc: Point located on round, large boulder on edge, next to steep dropoff 5 meters to West of point. Relatively open, but surrounded by a denser stand. Large boulders all around. Glaciated peak visible to south.

Travel_notes: I strongly advise you to travel around the steep dropoff immediately beyond point. Beyond that travel begins uphill then ends going downhill. Travel is relatively easy after first 10 meters.
Location_desc: Pile of fallen trees 15 meters to North and point is 50 meters west of several boulder faces. Terrain begins sharp slope 30 meters beyond point toward river. River can be seen through the trees.

Travel_notes: Travel is relatively flat for first 100 meters or so. Then climb the slope to the top where it will then continue to be generally flat.
Location_desc: Point on terrain sloping down to the west. Distinct mound 20 meters to west. Canopy relatively open. There is a large downed tree running NE-SW about 25 m to the N/NE.

Travel_notes: Easy walking, through open forest, then an open grassy area. Go back into open forest before point.
Location_desc: Point on westward downhill slope. Directly below is more open Doug-fir stand that thickens to N and E. Snowy, rounded peaks with point in center visible to W-SW. There is a cluster of a variety of shrubs (including willow, predominantly) ~12 m downslope of point (and slightly to the N).

Travel_notes: Travel through open Doug-fir forest for 130 m, then down steep slope of stream gully and cross creek at 150 m. You then climb up and ultimately traverse through Doug-fir stand with denser understory for 50 m to WW07.
Location_desc: Point directly underneath overhanging Douglas maple with a variety of small shrubs/plants. Branches of Douglas maple extend beyond point on both sides of it. Point approx. 50 m beyond creek. Terrain gradually sloping West.

Travel_notes: After crossing trail, walk through light to moderate shrub until you reach boulder field at ~150m. Look for one of the tallest boulders on the NW side. Point is just beyond that.
Location_desc: Point is in burn, surrounded by some giant boulders. Point is on a bit of a ledge, compared to above and below point. Right on the line between non-vegetated (SE) and vegetated (NW)- mostly fireweed and ferns. It is almost directly downslope of the only live Bigleaf maple at base of cliffs. I forgot to add this as a feature; I just noticed it as I was walking away.

Travel_notes: Pace 210 m on trail to Devore Creek Bridge and 200 m after that to NN01, totalling 410 m.
Location_desc: Point on trail at junction of Devore Creek Trail with Stehekin River Trail. Point is at the sign that reads "Stehekin River Trail" at the top.

Travel_notes: Travel slightly downhill on old flood plain. Crosses several old stream beds.
Location_desc: Flood plain area with stream roaring 35 m away. Groundcover predominantly bigleaf maple. Telephone pole to SW.

Reason_for_change: flooding and steep slopes forced on-trail points
Travel_notes: Return to NN01 then pace 230 m on trail in NW direction (toward Stehekin Rd.)
Location_desc: Point on flat terrain but hilly to South and SE and a fairly steep rock slope to the W. Doug fir dominates with some bigleaf maple throughout. Many downed trees on ground near point and on hills to SE. It is right next to a large (~85cm DBH) Doug-fir on NE side of trail.

Travel_notes: Pace 210 m on trail to NN04.
Location_desc: Point in generally flat area on trail with lots of shrubby deciduous trees. Sharp slope to SW of point. Trees mostly Doug-fir with Bigleaf maple interspersed, mostly to the W. Exposed cliff face NW from point.

Travel_notes: Pace 210 m on trail to NN05. Look for Doug-fir feature; it is across the trail from two small Bigleaf maples.
Location_desc: Point on trail in generally flat area next to small pile of boulders. Lots of young growth of mixed deciduous trees. Large cliff face seen to the SW.

Travel_notes: Pace 240 m on trail from NN05 to NN06.
Location_desc: Point in flood plain filled with deciduous trees of varying size. Point is about 15 m after small downhill slope of trail. River branch flows parallel to this part of trail 10 m away. On opposite side is steep slope.

Travel_notes: Travel begins in dense, wet sapling forest. This continues for about 110 m and then you must travel perpendicular to talus slope for about 90 m. Point is about 10 m beyond talus.
Location_desc: Point on steep slope with cliff face 4 m away, running NW-SE. Just beyond boulder/talus slope about 10 m to closest point. Several Big leaf maples surround talus and point with few Doug-firs.

Travel_notes: Walk up steep slope, initially through shrub and talus, then just shrub. Final ~70m are more open and grassy with less shrub. Pretty slow travel.
Location_desc: Point is on a steep slope in open forest. It is ~12m E of where forest/shrub gets more dense. There are two downed trees above point that intersect almost exactly straight uphill from point (~10m). Both have rootwads on the downslope side. There is a broken Doug-fir snag ~3m tall where the downed trees intersect.

Travel_notes: We didn't walk the most direct way, but generally head downslope through moderate shrub. Point is ~275m from NN08 to make sure it's 200m from NN07.
Location_desc: Point is on a downed tree, just upslope of a ~40cm DBH live Doug-fir. It is on the W edge of area with more live trees- a bunch of dead trees to the W/NW.

Travel_notes: Walk down to trail from NN09, then walk down trail ~105m.
Location_desc: Point is ~5m past the Bigleaf maple on N side of trail, the branches of which extend over point. It is ~5m before (SE of) the closest of downed trees at trail's edge.

Travel_notes: Travel 100 m along rocky, undulating terrain with several downed trees.
Location_desc: SS01 is located on undulating, rocky terrain with several downed trees around. Point next to old stream bed and beside 2 very large Doug-fir trees- closer one is broken off 30 m up. Can see telephone wires to the E. Devore Creek heard from point.

Travel_notes: 200 m through open Doug-fir forest. Terrain relatively flat. Many trees are at least partially burnt.
Location_desc: Point at fairly level ground next to a gully/dump 10 m away. A pipe runs E-W 17 m from point. Surrounded by burnt or partially burnt Doug-fir trees. Lake can be seen through trees in S-SE direction.

Travel_notes: Go 140 m through open Doug-fir habitat with evidence of low burn. Then, then young deciduous mix habitat. Cross small seasonal stream near SS03.
Location_desc: Point in middle of sapling dogwoods on generally flat spot about 50 m from much steeper terrain. Small stream north of point, 4 m away at closest point. Doug-fir dominates beyond small stand of dogwoods and maples.

Travel_notes: Travel 220 m to SS04. Travel begins through young growth habitat then enter open Doug-fir forest after 50 m. At approx. 195 m, enter a deciduous mix habitat and follow to lake shore.
Location_desc: Point on rocky lake shore 2 m from lake and 5 m from ledge marking previous level of lake when dammed to high water.

Travel_notes: May have to climb over logs on lake beach. then, trek through the campsite to SS05.
Location_desc: Point on relatively flat, undulating terrain in Weaver Point Campground. Many buildings seen from point in all directions. River delta/lake to the E. Waterfront house to the SE. At a table and fire ring.

Travel_notes: Travel on relatively flat terrain through Weaver Point Campground.
Location_desc: Point on relatively flat, undulating terrain near delta of Stehekin River (at nearest point 30 m NE). Just outside campground area. Next to point to the W is a small rise in the terrain with a Doug-fir and Big leaf maple at the top. Seen from point is campground and house on waterfront to S-SE.

Travel_notes: Pace about 210 m NW on trail from Stehekin River Trail sign above campground. Weaver Point campground is about 3 miles from Harlequin Camp. TO is less than 5 minutes from Weaver Point.
Location_desc: TO is at bend in trail of about 90 degrees to parallel Devore Creek. Just beyond point, trail descends into old stream gully. Devore Creek seen from point in W-NW direction. Power lines overhead in SE to NW direction.

Travel_notes: Travel 100 m across dry riverbed.  Red Alder vegetation begins at 90 m.
Location_desc: Point in dry riverbed among many Red alders with two very young Doug-firs on either side of point.  Point directly atop a pile of rocks and old river debris.

Travel_notes: Travel 70 m across a dry stream bed until you cross a small, seasonal stream.  10 m. beyond stream begin a mellow uphill climb through a small valley up to the point.
Location_desc: Point in a young Doug-fir forest, salal thick in understory.  Point is next to a small rocky ridge (microfeature) with many downed logs laying across it.  Point in between two of these logs which lay across the ridge in the SW-NE direction.

Travel_notes: Cross trail at 100m and proceed up steep, mossy, rocky slope.  Point is 40 m beyond crest of steep slope.
Location_desc: Point in open canopy, mossy area.  Point on slight slope, 10 m from edge of steep slope to the S.  Diablo lake visible through the trees to the SE.

Travel_notes: Travel up and down over moderate terrain.  Cliff, easy to get around, and trail crossing in last 50 m.
Location_desc: Point on edge of 10 m, steep rock face covered in moss, 30 m past where transect crosses trail (though trail at point of crossing cannot be seen, it can be seen to the W-NW).

Travel_notes: Travel easy across moderate terrain, last 50 m traverse mild slope.
Location_desc: Point is 10 m beyond beginning edge of plateau next to fallen Lodgepole pine (lying NE-SW) and mossy rock at midway point down Lodgepole (good sittin') and near a pile of cut and stacked Lodgepole.

Travel_notes: Travel 40 m. across plateau, the rest of the transect is up and down across gentle hills.
Location_desc: Point is SE of a small, dense stand Doug-fir and one larger Doug-fir, dbh ~50 cm.

Travel_notes: Travel first 40 m uphill over small rise, for remainder of transect traverse mellow sideslope.
Location_desc: Point is on gradual slope, downhill to the E, mossy with salal underfoot in open Lodgepole pine and Doug-fir forest.  Highway can be heard through trees to E ( and seen but with bins and difficult to find).  Point on downhill end of fallen Lodgepole pointing due E.

Travel_notes: Go uphill/traverse slope, then drop back down steeply into gully. Then climb up about 40-50m to point.
Location_desc: Close to the top of hill, located where slope begins to level off. Point is in between ledge and downed logs that run NE/SW. Point lies along transition zone between Doug-fir and Lodgepole pine forests.

Travel_notes: Travel over rocks first 60 meters, then meander over and under down trees for last 40 meters. Small seasonal stream or branch of colonial creek must be crossed. Point is just beyond stream but before main branch of colonial creek.
Location_desc: Point between seasonal stream and colonial creek in log jam. Seasonal stream only 1 m from point at closest spot. Colonial creek 10 m to S of point.

Travel_notes: Due to the stream I could not cross stream on bearing, but instead crossed with the several downed logs and continued on bearing.  Terrain is relatively flat.
Location_desc: Point is on side of steep NE-facing slope near top of hill. Road is ~50m away, despite GPS putting it on the road. Next to a debarked 4 m tall snag.

Reason_for_change: Cliffed out, falling 50 m to stream
Travel_notes: Travel was through undulating terrain, but easily traversed. Vegetation mostly Doug-fir.
Location_desc: Point on terrain sloping to the north with gully to West. Several large, fire-scarred doug firs in area.

Travel_notes: Travel through conifer forest over boulders on a small, but significant slope. At 160 meters, enter mossed-over talus with sparse vegetation throughout that area.
Location_desc: Point on the far end of a mossed-over talus slope. Lake and road can both be seen from point (to the N-NE, respectively). Large cliff to East.

Reason_for_change: cliffs sforced me to head down slope
Travel_notes: Slope to SS05 is very steep. Beyond the slope, the terrain is more level as you near Hwy 20 and the campground
Location_desc: Point in flat spot 50 m beyond where slope levels out. Dirt road about 20 m N of point. Mixed conifers in area.

Travel_notes: Pace 200 meters through relatively dense understory and slash of mixed conifer stand. Steep slope before and after road, but relatively flat beyond that.
Location_desc: Point on relatively flat terrain surrounded by Western redcedar and Pacific silver fir. Behind brown park building (to the N). Road is to south of point, but not seen.

Travel_notes: Point is 200m SE of SW06. To avoid a creek crossing, walk the road into Colonial Crk Campground (on the SE side of SR 20). Then, at "speed limit 10 mph" sign, head 211 degrees for 120m. At 70 m there are three 100+ cm dbh doug-firs in a row. It's about 20 m between the 1st and 3rd. Continue past 3rd doug-fir in same direction for 30 m to point.
Location_desc: Point is on a mossy knoll next to a W Red Cedar (approx. 50 cm dbh) that is missinhg a 6" wide strip of bark from the base up as high as you can see.

Travel_notes: Park at Colonial Cr (on NW side) and take the Thunder Knob trail.  Cross two log bridges and from end of second bridge pace 70 m on trail to TO.  Drive from Diablo 10 min.
Location_desc: TO in dry riverbed 12 m from forest edge. There are several small alders on both sides of trail right at TO. It is just before a dogleg where trail turns to head directly upriver.

Travel_notes: Pass 2 switchbacks from TO. From 2nd switchback, pace 85 m to point.
Location_desc: Point next to young subalpine fir (uphill) with younger and smaller Pacific silver fir wrapping around it and toward the trail. 3 downed trees lay perpendicular to trail 10 m beyond point.

Travel_notes: From NW01, pass one switchback. From switchback, pace 255 m on trail. Small rock on downhill side of trail encroaches onto trail ~2m past point.
Location_desc: Point in open shrubby area with lots of W. Mtn. ash and Falsebox. Bend in Bridge Creek (long section with many rapids) seen down valley. Small rock on downhill side of trail encroaches onto trail about 2m past point.

Travel_notes: Travel to switchback, point is here.
Location_desc: Point at switchback on edge between Subalpine fir forest and open shrub area with small stream.

Travel_notes: Pace 260 m from NW03 to switchback.
Location_desc: Point at switchback next to large Doug-fir (dbh 80 cm), pistol-gripped and makes a nice bench. It is about 2m past switchback (if continuing straight, rather than switching back on trail).

Travel_notes: From NW04, pass 2 switchbacks. Point is 140 m beyond second switchback.
Location_desc: Point is on trail in open area between patches of Subalpine fir. Downed tree on uphill side perpendicular to trail 3 m beyond point.
