Travel_notes: From NW05, pass 5 switchbacks. Point is 110 m from last switchback.
Location_desc: Point is in open meadow. It is ~3m past small cluster of Subalpine Fir (on uphill side of trail). The father W (left) of 2 snags in features is somewhat obscured by subalpine fir.

Travel_notes: From NW06, pass 3 switchbacks, one dogleg, and one more switchback. From final switchback, NW07 is at next switchback on trail.
Location_desc: Point at switchback on edge of closed canopy Mountain hemlock forest.

Travel_notes: From NW07, pass 2 switchbacks. Point is ~175 m beyond 2nd switchback
Location_desc: Point on trail next to 1-m boulder, Subalpine fir upslope and boulders below. 30 m beyond point, trail crosses open (rock and tree free) meadow. Bridge Creek Valley visible to E. Glacier Peak visible to S and Cascade Pass area peaks visible to SW.

Travel_notes: Pace ~220 m up trail thrugh mostly open meadow. No switchbacks.
Location_desc: Point is on trail, ~1.5 downslope of a young whiteback pine. It is ~3m past end of mtn. hemlock/subalpine fir stand on downhill side of trail. Bridge Creek and trail (and bridge!) visible from point. Mostly Mtn. ash downslope of point. A large boulder/rock face immediately upslope of trail/point.

Travel_notes: Pace 100 meters on trail to SE01
Location_desc: Point on N-S stretch of trail. Point just beside cut tree on W side of trail. Large Doug-fir on E side of trail with funky fork from base.

Travel_notes: Travel 230 meters on trail. No switchbacks. Look for three-tree cluster on right side of trail, described below.
Location_desc: Point on NE-SW stretch of trail, next to cluster of 3 Douglas FIrst, all with curve at base.

Travel_notes: Total of 600 meters between SE02 and SE03. Once you reach the third switchback, pace 30 meters to point.
Location_desc: Point 30 meters beyond switchback. Just after 75 cm dbh Doug-fir beside trail. Outcrops and boulders cover W/SW region. Peaks visible to S and SW.

Travel_notes: Pace 250 meters to SE04. No switchbacks.
Location_desc: Point is next to trickling stream that flows over trail 2 meters behind point and 10 meters beyond point. Good view of mountains with snow chute down middle. Very brushy area with thick understory and many deciduous trees.

Travel_notes: 5 switchbacks en route to SE05. Point is 35 meters beyond 5th switchback. 650 meters total between points.
Location_desc: Many snags around, and several fallen trees surrounding area. To N/NE is an area containing at least 10 snags.

Travel_notes: One switchback, many turns/curves in trail. Approximately 460 meters between points. 360 meters beyond switchback. Last 100 meters includes numerous curves, bends, and turns in trail.
Location_desc: Beautiful, open view of peaks to SW. Several down trees on E side of trail. Multiple snags around.

Travel_notes: 4 switchbacks en route to SE07. Point lies 75 meters beyond 4th switchback. Approx. 525 meters total between points.
Location_desc: Point on relatively level section of trail. Highly deciduous understory and subcanopy. Look for large pistol butt Doug-fir feature.

Travel_notes: Travel on trail 250 meters to SE08. 30 meters beyond "lookout" over Bridge Creek.
Location_desc: Point on trail 30 meters beyond "lookout" over Bridge Creek. Minimal understory. Dropoff 30 meters to E of point. Cliff face visible in distance to NE.

Travel_notes: Travel approx. 280 meters to end of trail/junction with road.
Location_desc: Point 5 meters beyond Goode Lookout Trailhead, on edge of road.

Travel_notes: Travel left on the road, or toward the campground, for 310 meters. Or, simply go 15 meters beyond PCT trail junction.
Location_desc: Point approx. 15 meters beyond junctino of PCT/Bridge Creek Trail

Travel_notes: Travel over a few boulders in first 75 meters, then traverse through dense understory to point. Tree is south of 90 degree beaing, in open vine maple patch.
Location_desc: Point amidst dense understory of vine maple. Seven meters before stream and just beyond fallen log approx. 40 cm dbh.

Travel_notes: Travel to TO took approx. 1 hour and 5 minutes from camp. Very steep. Camp at Bridge Creek. Trail not well maintained (brushy), which can slow travel down to TO. Approx. 4000' elevation difference between end of SE and end of NW arm.
Location_desc: Point at switchback, after approx. 330 meters of trail in mostly Northerly direction. Peaks visible in both E/SE and NW directions.TO is at switchback immediately following SE01 (Monitor GPS/nav. report as you're getting close.)

Travel_notes: Mellow walk from TO. At ~75m, you will enter burn.
Location_desc: Point is on a large downed tree (barkless), the same log that leads to the stump feature (feature removed). About 4.5m N of where another downed tree intersects log that point is on. In a high severity burn.

Travel_notes: Very mellow walk from NN01 through burn. GPS is very good here.
Location_desc: Point is ~2.5 from gully (on the S side of it). These is a 2.5m tall stump about 3m to the SW. This will probably look different next visit (much more grown up).

Travel_notes: Walk down steep slope through burn for most of the way. Exit the burn around 140-150m.
Location_desc: Point is at the base (uphill side) of a ~100cm DBH Engelmann Spruce. It is immediately downslope of a boulder (~1m across). About 7.5m W of where it starts to get more shrubby.

Travel_notes: Walk downslope until you reach creek. Cross and walk through shrub/herbaceous vegetation to trail. Point is ~16m past trail.
Location_desc: Point is in the middle of shrubs and small subalpine fir. It is immediately S of several (at least 3) Subalpine Firs that are leaning dramatically toward creek. It is ~16m E of Trail. Photo of subalpine fir taken from ~2m downhill of point (better view of it).

Travel_notes: Walk through shrub/Subalpine Fir saplings most of the way, crossing small gully at ~75m
Location_desc: Point is about half way between 2 rocks (feature is upslope one to the SE, larger). Just upslope of a large patch of White Rhododendron. In a relatively open area surrounded by mostly Subalpine Firs.

Travel_notes: Walk through subalpine fir forest until you reach meadow. Walk through entire meadow. At ~175m, you will reach small subalpine fir stands. Go through that; point is just on other side of it.
Location_desc: Point is on S edge of small stand of subalpine firs, amidst herbacesus vegetation and loose rock/soil, ~10m before entering another slightly larger stand of Subalpine firs. About 1m to the W/NW is a large (but low) flat boulder up against shrub & subalpine fir.

Travel_notes: Walk through the meadow for ~10m, then through moderately dense subalpine fir, then through another meadow. At ~170m, you will climb small, steep, slope to ridge about 30m to point (denser subalpine fir/ whitebark pine saplings here).
Location_desc: Point is a small herbaceous/shrubby ridge. It is ~30m N of small creek. Lots of small whitebark pines and subalpine firs on ridge. Point itself is in a fairly bare area, right at the base (downhill) of a subalpine fir sapling.

Travel_notes: Travel over gully and stream and enter meadow. Cross meadow and enter smallish subalpine fir forest. Forest matures further on.
Location_desc: Point is on a moderate slope directly downslope of a dense patch of subalpine fir. West is a swath of low shrubs running N-S about 10-14m wide.

Travel_notes: Easy travel to point through open terrain
Location_desc: Point is located at W end of a ditch directly next to base of a fallen larch. 2019: took new coordinates and features, point difficult to find. Next to base/roots of ~85cm dbh fallen larch lying east to west- point is at east end of log. A small ditch lies to the west of the point. Creek noise can be heard.

Travel_notes: Travel through open forest and boulder field up a moderate slope to point.
Location_desc: Point is located on boulder field near base of steep, flat cliff face with curved 45cm dbh larch growing at base of rock wall, upslope of point. In open subalpine fir & larch forest and heather in abundance.

Travel_notes: Head E along cliff face and across top of talus field. At end of talus slope, traverse through open forest at a bearing of 170 for ~50m, then upslope to point.
Location_desc: Point is located on open slope beside a young whitebark pine and 60m below ridgeline. 2019: point hard to find- updated features.

Travel_notes: Traverse moderate slope through open larch forest to point.
Location_desc: Point is located in open larch forest at top of talus field

Travel_notes: Traverse steep slope through open larch forest
Location_desc: Point is located on small, flat area above base of a pistol-gripped whitebark pine and below a large larch snag.

Travel_notes: Travel upslope then across talus slope and through open larch forest
Location_desc: Point is located on W edge of talus slope 6m above edge of larch forest

Reason_for_change: Steep talus slope, difficult to traverse
Travel_notes: Travel east from SS06 across talus, through another larch forest, across more talus, and then cut downslope to point.
Location_desc: Point is on open, flat rocky area ~8m from sheer rock cliff edge that drops sharply, on eastern edge of larch forest.
Location_notes: Point was retired because it fell outside of the NPS boundary.

Travel_notes: About a 20-25 minute hike from Reynolds Camp, which is 3.5 miles from Juanita Lake, which is about 10 miles up War Creek Trail (from Twisp). NN arms goes through burn for part of it. It will likely look very different in 5 years and will probably be much more difficult to travel through. Update as needed. If it's a snowy year, ice axe needed/crampons recommended for travel between points SS02-SS06.
Location_desc: Point ~15m  W of small stream crossing trail. Larch with blaze on front (as trail marker) stands alone on S side of trail with a lot of bare ground surrounding it.

Travel_notes: walk up road 100m
Location_desc: point is in road beneath rock face.  The snag/stump only has bark on its W side.  To its S is a similarly pale stump with more bark.

Travel_notes: pace 200m on road and trail, point is located 75m beyond the trailhead at roads end.
Location_desc: point is located on trail directly next to large moss covered boulder that protrude onto trail.  Closest one is 1.5m wide.

Travel_notes: pace 230m on trail (legibility issues- could be less than 230 m- verify this next visit)
Location_desc: point on trail lots of red alders on west side, bigleaf maple to east.

Travel_notes: pace 200m along trail
Location_desc: on trail, large Red Alder to E, smaller Red Alder to W.  Best found by large rectangular boulder to west, 4 by 2 meters, 50 cm high and moss covered.

Travel_notes: pace 200m on trail
Location_desc: On trail, between two 40cm dbh Lodgepole Pines, debarked at base that stand 1m downslope off trail.

Travel_notes: pace 200m on trail
Location_desc: point is on trail in patch of goatsbeard.

Travel_notes: pace 200m along trail
Location_desc: point on trail, tall 30cm dbh Alaska yellow cedar to NE, 2 20m tall snags to its right, lots of young red alders to west.

Travel_notes: pace 200m along trail
Location_desc: point on trail, look for fir to NW.

Travel_notes: pace 200m on trail, cross runoff
Location_desc: point is on trail, 1 meter downslope of 6sm Western Red Cedar that stands alone in patch of thimbleberry and goatsbeard.  Prominent cluster of 7 Red Alders (to 40 cm dbh) to west.

Travel_notes: pace 200m down trail.
Location_desc: point is on trail, large boulder on both sides of trail.

Reason_for_change: bend in trail, off trail inaccessible
Travel_notes: Pace ~410m around bend in train and over Thorton creek, continue beyond where the creek run off flows down trail.
Location_desc: Point is located under conifer deciduous mixed forest canopy 10m from where small creek crosses trail.

Travel_notes: Nondescript point, just pace 100 m SW from TO.
Location_desc: Point nondescript, located along road with mixed conifer forest on both sides. Look for the largest alder within 50m on S side of road. Boulders on S side, right in front of alder.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point located on road on edge of an opening in forest cnopy, many young trees ahead to the SW. On NW side of road (right at point) is a steep rock outcrop

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Forest is mostly coniferous but with a few alders, including a large one SE of road at the point. Point is about 20m past (SW of) end of rock outcrop. There is a reflector at NW side of road right at point.

Travel_notes: go down the road 200 m, stop just before you get to a pullout at a curve in the road. you can see "rock in pullout" feature from SW03, walk until you reach that pullout
Location_desc: Located in a more open area with younger trees near a pullout in the road.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point located on road with lots of alders in the area and some conifers with lots of lichen on them, upslope from road. It is ~20m past (SW of) end of mossy rock face on NW side of road.

Travel_notes: continue along road, it begins to go downhill more steeply.
Location_desc: located along road near a creek crossing (sky creek, accoring to the map)  Also near a small waterfall which is very loud.  There is a parking area to the southeast which appears to have recently been used for camping.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: not much distinctive about this point, its about 35 m from where alder stand ends, forest is coniferous with more canopy cover than previous points.  Lots of vine maple on road edges. There is a patch of ferns on SE side of road directly lined up with point.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Indistinct point, located in between two stands of alders.  A fairly large rocky outcropping begins 1-2 m NE of point. Point is at a small pullout on the road, right under 2 young bigleaf maples.

Travel_notes: travel along road going downhill go through a fairly extensive alder patch.
Location_desc: Indistinct point located in mixed conifers with alders nearby. There is a steep rock face on W side of road right at poin. It is just past a wide spot in the road.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is located on a pile of rocks several meters from the edge of a road at a switchback.

Travel_notes: There is some old road bed (totally overgrown now) that you can start walking on to avoid steep drop right away. Gradually make your way down when it seems less steep and walk the rest of the way more or less on bearing through light to moderate shrubby understory.
Location_desc: Point is essentially right where you break out into less shrubby understory and more open forest with larger trees. Salal + huckleberry shrub layer at point, but even that ends ~4m S of point. There is a small downed tree lying E-W that point is on. There are many young cedars immediately (within 10m) to the N.

Travel_notes: Just walk down slope (going down small gully initially probably easiest) through open Doug-Fir forest. Pretty easy going.
Location_desc: In relatively open Doug-Fir forest ~7m SE of a line of large boulders. It is in salal, which ends as dominant ground cover ~6m to the NW. Very open right at point.

Travel_notes: Travel up Thornton creek RD almost all the way to the top, TO is about 300 m from the end of the road at the trailhead.  Travel time from Marblemount is about 40 minutes, 15 to the Thornton Lakes turnoff, and 25 to the end of the road.  Road is slow and rough, allow plenty of time. There is a pullout right near the TO, but it is also very fast to walk from trailhead down road.
Location_desc: TO is located in road 6m from a large bare rock face with a few shrubs growing out of it.  A dense patch of vine maple is to the south. There are a bunch of mossy boulders on S side of road at point. Vine maple is also on the N side of road right at point.

Travel_notes: Travel through vine maple and Devil's club for first 20 m. It opens up for the rest of the way.
Location_desc: Point on gently sloping terrain. Vaccinium and young Western hemlock understory.

Travel_notes: Cross dry stream beds at 45, 60, and 90 m, walk by large boulder at 190 m.
Location_desc: Point in small gully next to a small (1 m) mossy rock and fallen log lying across gully (1 m above ground at point).

Travel_notes: Travel across relatively flat and open terrain.
Location_desc: Point NW of large Western hemlock (dbh 80 cm) 16m N of trail. Peaks and vegetation surrounding ponds seen to S.

Travel_notes: Travel slightly upslope across uneven terrain.
Location_desc: Point in dense stand young Western hemlock atop mossy rock (1 m). Point is ~5m upslope from small open area (free from understory).

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point on moderate slope in young Doug-fir and W. hemlock forest, 1 m downhill from washing machine-sized boulder and on the other side large Doug-fir (dbh 70 cm). Ponds visible to S. Stream heard to E.

Travel_notes: Traverse moderate sideslope.
Location_desc: Point on slight slope in Doug-fir and W. hemlock forest. Lots of downed tress immediately upslope and the the E of point. Bare ground (not mossy) right at point. Mtns. visible to S through trees.

Travel_notes: A downslope traverse of a moderate slope through occasional downed trees, but otherwise pretty mellow.
Location_desc: Point is right on edge of where it becomes less mossy if continuing W (more duff, less vegetation). It goes uphill slightly ~5m to the W. It is under the branches of a ~10 cm DBH hemlock (S of Hemlock).

Travel_notes: Continue traversing the slope across mellow terrain, paralleling the trail, stopping at the small ridge before the creek.
Location_desc: The point is located on a flat spot between a dry ditch 10m to the East and the loud creek 10m to the West. The point is within a few small Vine Maples with two 100cm Doug-firs overhead.

Travel_notes: Travel 200 meters on trail to SS01
Location_desc: Point on trail between 2 massive cedars, at top of small bend in trail. Dense understory on both sides of trail.

Travel_notes: Start out through dense cover of Devil's Club and other shrubby plants. After 50 meters or so it lessens but is still present up to SS02. Many large trees. Relatively flat terrain.
Location_desc: Point in middle of a circle of fallen trees. Directly between 3 small hemlocks and a small batch of Devil's Club. Large cedars and first surround area. Ground flat. Many sapling hemlocks.

Travel_notes: Travel slightly uphill through Doug-fir forest with open understory
Location_desc: Point on undulating terrain with many fallen trees and snags. Generally indistinct.

Travel_notes: Travel over many fallen trees. Terrain is mostly flat. Open understory.
Location_desc: Point in a mossy Douglas Fir stand with not much understory. Several down trees. Generally indistinct.

Travel_notes: Travel through relatively open forest. Easy travel. Many down trees.
Location_desc: Point 50 meters before stream, but it is not visible. In front of large fallen tree on top of boulder. 3 very large boulders >10 meters wide are in immediate area. Mix of conifers and deciduous overstory.

Travel_notes: Steam is rocky enough to pass rather easily. Thick vine maple as you near SS06.
Location_desc: Point in slight break from vine maple onslaught, though point location is underneath dense cluster of vine maple hanging over rocky ground. Open sky 30 meters East of point.

Travel_notes: Make your way through small but very dense section of vine maple, then enter a more open stand of mixed conifers. Many down trees to climb over.
Location_desc: Point on small, mossy section of small rocks. Several down trees around immediate area. Terrain sloping down to the south. Relatively open stop in contrast to surrounding area.

Travel_notes: From 39 mile CG, head E, cross 39 mile Creek and another creek about 1/2 way to TO. Final creek shown on map next to TO is dry.  It is about an 11-mile hike from Ross Dam Trailhead. Mosquitoes! Bring a headnet, if you're into that. About 15 minutes from 39-mile Camp
Location_desc: Point in between 2 old growth western redcedars (dbh>100 cm) on either side of the trail. Western redcedars on S side of trail has western hemlock with many sapsucker holes (50 cm) growing next to it. Just after 2 dips from old stream beds.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: willow lake is 20m away

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: to the right of trail the ground slopes down and willow lake is fairly close.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: many downed trees E of trail.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: point in an inconspicuous stand of red cedar and doug fir

Travel_notes: Point is located directly on top of fallen and decaying trunk of "70cm dbh snag" feature. Wood and bark debris all around
Location_desc: Point located directly on top of fallen and decaying trunk of "70cm DBH snag" feature. Wood and bark debris all around.

Travel_notes: travel is shrubby for first 60m then understory thins out, many large Doug-firs and Western redcedars
Location_desc: point is in a stand with numerous large Doug-firs and Western redcedars and lots of small Western hemlocks; stream can be heard.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: point is at a bend in the trail slightly after trail starts going downhill, there is a moderate amount of noise from the creek nearby

Travel_notes: GPS needed to find point. Start down trail to mossy gully then sharply up steep. Travel not too difficult aside from steep slope.
Location_desc: point is closely surrounded by mixed conifer forest, fallen logs throughout. Slope is quite steep

Travel_notes: Closest place to camp is Willow Lake CG.  It only has one site. TO is about 500m E of Willow Lake Camp, but Hozomeen Lake is amazing! It takes about 50-55 minutes to get to TO from there. Combine this transect with 1019 (Desolation) if possible. Try to get a boat ride at least one way up or down lake (contact Hozomeen rangers). We camped middle night at Lightning Creek (much nicer than Deer Lick).
Location_desc: picture contains both features.  Four meters west of the point there is a rotting 2m tall stump which is not visible directly from point.

Travel_notes: travel W on trail 100m from TO
Location_desc: point is on trail under Doug fir with conspicuous bend in branches 6m high, a small 1 by .5 by .5 m boulder lies 2m west N of trail. There is a downed tree lying parallel to trail on N side right at point and vine maple towering over trail within 2 m of point (W? check this).

Travel_notes: travel 200m on trail
Location_desc: point on trail 8 m W of short bend where it starts to go downhill if traveling W. There are many cut logs on S side of trail at point. The 2 Doug-firs feature are right next to some vine maple.

Travel_notes: Travel trail for 200 m.
Location_desc: on trail, 28m past (W of) Willow Lake CG sign. Vine maple towers overhead from S side of trail right at point.

Travel_notes: Travel 200 m along trail
Location_desc: Point is on slope in trail among stand of vine maple. There are 3 hemlock saplings on S edge of trail. There is a ~30cm DBH Doug-fir about 1m up trail (W), on S side.

Travel_notes: Travel 200 m along trail.
Location_desc: On trail next to stand of mature Doug-fir forest. On N side of trail, there is a Doug-fir, cedar, and snag lined up next to each other. Doug-fir is almost directly lined up with point.

Travel_notes: Travel 200 m along trail.
Location_desc: on trail by felled logs, shorter ones are east, larger ones west. Cedar branches extend to trail on N side, hemlock on S side of trail.

Travel_notes: Travel along trail for 200 m.
Location_desc: Point is next to three equidistant Doug-firs and is above a small slope on its E side.  Doug-firs are S of trail. Point is 1m N/NE from the closest one to the trail. Branches from a small hemlock on S side of trail extend over point. There are a bunch of white pine saplings on N side of trail (within 5m).

Travel_notes: Travel 200 m along trail.
Location_desc: Point is on trail, directly under a 20m Western hemlock snag, 50cm dbh. There are a bunch of cut logs on S side of trail (E of point).

Travel_notes: travel uphill at bearing of 353 through dense shrubs, downfall and vine maple.
Location_desc: point located directly at edge of vine maple a beginning of moss covered open area with mature doug firs that are covered by lots of moss.  A large boulder offers a seat, A long thin log without many branches lies fallen downhill within reach.

Travel_notes: Walk upslope initially. It levels off about halfway to WW10 (slightly less). Then make your way over downed trees on a very mellow slope for the remainder.
Location_desc: Point is on a slope with a North/Northwesterly aspect. It is at the base (downhill side) of a ~70cm DBH hemlock. There are a bunch of white pine saplings about 5m to the NE/E. There are several leaning snags downslope, but it looks like they won't be standing in 5 years.

Travel_notes: Travel SE along road 100m to junction with Rainbow Loop Trail.
Location_desc: Point is in road at the junction with the Rainbow Loop Trail.

Travel_notes: Go up Rainbow Loop Trail to the third switchback. Pace 175m from the third switchback. Pass a large wash at 130 m. Point is in a smaller wash.
Location_desc: Point is along Rainbow Loop Trail where small wash crosses trail. This is the second wash after the third switchback. Point is in closed canopy Doug-fir/maple forest.

Travel_notes: Hike trail past 5th switchback after point SE02, to the middle of small talus field.
Location_desc: Point is along trail in a mostly talus field and is surrounded by tall Doug-firs.

Travel_notes: Go 200m uptrail. No need to worry about switchback, trail flattens out.
Location_desc: Point is in stand of fairly large Doug-firs. A few small maples to the South.

Travel_notes: Continue along Rainbow Loop Trail for 200 m.
Location_desc: Point is on trail in a Doug-fir forest. Portion hillside immediately upslope has little ground vegetation. Large patch of thimbleberries in gully to SE.

Travel_notes: Continue 200m along trail.
Location_desc: Point is on edge of an open area at a gully and a Doug-fir forest. There is a small stand of small maples right off the downhill side of the trail and the hillside upslope is covered in lupines.

Travel_notes: continue 200 m along trail.
Location_desc: Point is in a Doug-fir forest with numerous small trees and a few larger ones. Very little understory and lots of woody debris on hillside to East.

Travel_notes: continue 200m along trail.
Location_desc: Point is located in Doug-fir forest with numerous dogwoods in understory layer.

Travel_notes: Continue 200m along set. Trail heads uphill, but no switchbacks to worry about.
Location_desc: Point is in a Doug-fir forest with no understory and minimal ground cover. Surrounded by a number of large boulders.

Travel_notes: Travel up trail for 200m, uphill. You will reach some switchback not shown on map. The point is at the thrid switchback, 100m beyond second switchback.
Location_desc: Point is at switchback in trail. A smaller side trail branches off ahead, while the main trail goes around a switchback. There is a 60cm dbh Doug-fir at the split.

Travel_notes: Follow trail past three switchbacks into Doug-fir and Ponderosa stand with little understory.
Location_desc: Point on slow bend in trail; small clearing and downed pile visible to NE.

Travel_notes: Trail ascends gradually then beings to descend into burn area.
Location_desc: In small opening just before dense ponderosa and douglas-fir grove showing signs of burn.

Travel_notes: Travel on trail through burn. Point is at beginning of transition to meadow.
Location_desc: Meadow in front of burnt Mixed conifer forest. Grass and wildflowers. Trail is wet at point.

Travel_notes: Camped at Harlequin Camp, a 15 minute walk to TO from there. FOR SE ARM!: GPS and map show point SE02 downslope and offtrail (which it is not). Follow nav. report closely regarding counting switchbacks - GPS coordinates are ~130m off from features.
Location_desc: point is in road, 100m upriver from junction with rainbow loop trail. walk upriver along the road about 1km from Harlequin Bridge.

Travel_notes: Walk 100m on road from TO.
Location_desc: Point is on left (S) side of road. There is a pullout ~5m up road on right (opposite) side of road.

Travel_notes: Walk 200 m along road.
Location_desc: Swampy on left (S) side of road (below road) with some Bigleaf maple saplings right at point (below). Mostly vine maple and dogwood on right (N) side of road.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m along road
Location_desc: none

Travel_notes: Travel 200m along road.
Location_desc: In open area with little canopy cover.

Travel_notes: travel along road for 200m
Location_desc: Point is ~10m down road (toward TO) from where river is starting to erode road.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m along road. House will be obvious on your left.
Location_desc: Point is roughly 60m past house

Travel_notes: Travel along road for 200m. No distinct features.
Location_desc: There are some Bigleaf maple saplings on edge of right (NE) side of road at point and within ~5m up road from point.

Travel_notes: Groundcover vegetation tapers off in last 50m. Travel upslope at 360 degrees for 200m.
Location_desc: Homogenous stand of Doug-fir with an open understory. No very conspicuous features seen from point besides marker.

Travel_notes: Cross small ditch at 20m. Point located in an open area of many dead trees with downed logs.
Location_desc: A lot of snags visible from point (10-15). Many of these are 40-70cm dbh and 5-15m tall. Point is alongside a downed log about 40m long, covered with 2-3cm round fungi. Many trees dead.

Travel_notes: Last 100m contain many large boulders. Travel over many downed trees in first 60m. Understory is more open after dry streambed at 60m.
Location_desc: Point is in area with lots of exposed rock face. Two houses are visible toward the road. About 10-15m SE of where it starts to drop down into small gully.

Travel_notes: Through Doug-fir forest. Travel easy, down into gully, up onto small ridge with no understory, down other side through maples into open understory again.
Location_desc: In Doug-fir forest with isolated boulders and very little understory vegetation. Small maples can be seen to north and south. Can see rocky slope and cliff to northeast.

Travel_notes: Travel through open forest with little understory vegetation.
Location_desc: Point at northern edge of series of small gullies in Doug-fir forest with some alders. Rock next to point (<1 m away, about 1 m long).

Travel_notes: Two switchbacks (I think- somewhat snow-covered right now) between TO and EE01. Walk until you are ~26m from Silesia sign.
Location_desc: Point is about 18 m before reaching switchback right before Silesia Camp Trail junction.

Travel_notes: pace ~255m to point.
Location_desc: point is 25m before reaching the spur trail that goes down to Egg Lake. Egg Lake is visible from point.

Travel_notes: pace ~250 to point.
Location_desc: Point is ~8m after trail rounds small bend. Look for boulder feature- very distinctive. Heather & loose rock on W side of trail (downslope), heather and eventually vaccinium & mtn. hemlock upslope (~7m).

Travel_notes: pace 4 switchbaclks, then pace~160m from 4th to EE04.
Location_desc: point is ~8m past where the trail reaches top of very small hill (then continues to go back downhill). Distance to mtn. hemlock feature seems too close, but that is what the Rangefinder tells me.

Travel_notes: pace ~245m from EE04
Location_desc: Point is in all open heather, ~65m before cluster of small mtn. hemlocks right at edge of N side of trail. It is right after trail starts to level out.

Travel_notes: pace ~210m up trail from EE05
Location_desc: Point is just downslope of a cluster of AK Yellow Cedars. Difficult to find features here. Point is just where trail starts to bend slightly to the S. There are a few larger rocks on trail right at point (still small, though).

Travel_notes: pace ~250m up trail from EE06
Location_desc: Point is in between patches of mtn. ash on S side of trail and immediately downslope of a small patch on N side of trail. Otherwise, heather and vaccinium on both sides of trail. About 3m up trail from point, it gets a bit more herbaceous.

Travel_notes: pace ~220m up trail from EE07.
Location_desc: Point is in open heather (on N side) and mtn. hemlocks (on S side). It is about 1-2 m past the last of the trees/saplings on N side of trail.

Travel_notes: All open. You can see the 2 large mtn. hemlocks (feature) for more than half of the 200m. Point is ~25m after trail makes an almost 90 degree turn.
Location_desc: Point is located right where you start seeing more trees near trail, just before a small hill on the trail.

Travel_notes: Walk past 8 distinct switchbacks. Point is ~15m past 8th one.
Location_desc: Point is on a steep section of trail running SE-NW. There are some yellow cedar saplings upslope of trail, ~2m down trail from point. Mtn. ash on S side of trail right at point (~4m off trail). Point on wooden step in trail. Sweeping view of Mt. Shuksan, Mt. Baker, and entire ridge.

Travel_notes: You will pass a bunch of switchbacks (lost track because a Prairie falcon flew over!) then it will straighten out for the remainder. When you are ~45m from EE11, you will pass a huge boulder on "right" side of trail. Point is ~45m from end of boulder.
Location_desc: Point is in open heather. Beyond the white snag feature is a huge boulder (in photo) -all are in line with Mineral Mtn.

Travel_notes: Trail is relatively straight for most of it. There are 2 sets of back-to-back switchbacks. Point is ~12m past of the 2nd switchback of the 2nd set.
Location_desc: Point is where there is a slight break in the trees on downhill side of trail. It is ~2m after slight bend in trail (but there are many of these, so that might not be all that helpful).

Travel_notes: Steep section of trail- travel up several short switchbacks until you reach the base of the short rocky slope on the eastern edge of the lookout building- lookout visible from point.
Location_desc: Point is located on small  rock outcrop at the bottom of the short slope on the east side of the lookout building.  Point is right next to a wooken plank step on the trail.

Travel_notes: Continue on trail past lookout, over ridgetop, and start to descend on trail on north side of ridge. Point is near boulder pile on relatively straight part of trail, ~15m before trail starts to steeply descend.
Location_desc: Point is on trail directly next to a flat boulder on the "right" side of the trail. Large boulder pile 8m to the "left" of the trail at point. Trail can be seen winding down the ridge to the north.

Travel_notes: TO is less than 5 minutes from Silesia Camp. However, we were asked not to camp there becasue it was a Friday night and fills up, so we stayed at Admin. site at lookout. It took 50-55 minutes to get to TO from there. This would not be optimal in a snowy year because the snow that we did encounter was very icy. Try to avoid doing this on a weekend if it's a low snow year, but I recognize sometimes that's impossible (tell that to WIC!). A beautiful transect with spectacular views throughout.
Location_desc: Point located in open area covered in heather (or snow, depending on the year) beside several Mountain Hemlock saplings

Travel_notes: Easy travel downhill 100m from TO.
Location_desc: Point located on exposed boulders on trail.

Travel_notes: Easy travel downhill to point
Location_desc: Point is located 22m above first switchback where wooden support crosses trail with a small white boulder on each side.

Travel_notes: Travel downhill through four switchbacks and then slight uphill for ~40m to point
Location_desc: Point located immediately past 15m section of young trees on either side of trail

Travel_notes: Easy travel on-trail uphill to point.
Location_desc: Point located in open heather covered area beside a small white boulder on N edge of trail w/ view of Pickett range to SE and 14m from forest edge to the E

Travel_notes: Travel uphill, then across flatter section of trail and uphill through three switchbacks to point.
Location_desc: Point located in open area of small ridge just above large exposed boulder
Location_notes: K. Beirne changed northing from 5419652 to 5416952 after C. Ray noticed the locaiton was incorrect on 7/12/2017.

Travel_notes: Easy on-trail travel downhill and through two switchbacks to point.
Location_desc: Point on-trail overlooking valley floor and Copper mountain to N at small boulder and wood support across trail

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point located on-trail below a pistol-gripped fir sapling

Travel_notes: Easy on-trail travel
Location_desc: Point is on-trail beneath two overlapping pistol-gripped mountain hemlocks alongside exposed rock chute

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Hidden Hand creek can be heard from the point. Steep slope on both sides with vine maple under story. Both sapling features are currently less than 5' tall. There is a small root wad and 2 cut logs on non-creek side of trail.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Doug-fir forest with thick understory of vine maple. Vine maple extends over trail at point. There are several cut logs about 2 m up trail from point.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Nondescript point in Doug-fir forest. There is a bunch of vine maple on east side of trail right next to point, and a bunch of small cut logs on west side.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Doug-fir forest with almost no understory or mid-story. Can see the talus slope from point. It is 3 m past small root wad of downed tree running down the side of trail (going SW).

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is at northern end of talus slope @ 80m (bearing 248)

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is in Doug-fir forest with open understory vine maple as understory. Look for large boulder on right (E) side of trail.

Travel_notes: First 110m in open forest with big Doug-fir and hemlock.  After 100m it starts going up. Point is where it starts to level off.
Location_desc: Point in open forest with many saplings around (more than NW of point, which is more open).

Travel_notes: Travel across down slope facing 338.  Some flatter areas .
Location_desc: The Point is on a down facing slope ( 338 degrees) in second gully.  Doug-fir forest with many downed trees (30dbh). It is right at a downed tree lying upslope-downslope.

Travel_notes: A mellow walk, mostly a traverse going slightly downslope through open forest the whole way.
Location_desc: In open forest. Transitions into a mossier groundcover about 4 m west of point (versus bare ground right at point and to the east).

Travel_notes: Walk about 100 m through dark, flat forest, until reach an unmapped cliff. You can go upslope (or downslope? I didn't check down) to where it is less steep. Climb to the top and correct yourself about 45 m to the north, then walk 40 m to the west. Beautiful!
Location_desc: Best point of the day, by far! Surrounded by a bunch of old, white, small downed trees. Ross Lake visible through trees. There are a lot of lodgepole pines near point. There is a line of young lodgepoles (10+) ~ 8 m to the E/SE. Point is 10 m SE of where it starts to drop steeply beyond boulder feature. You will be tempted to stay here for hours, but it will eventually be time to return to the dark, silent forest.

Travel_notes: We camped at hidden hand campground, just over 3 miles from East Bank Trailhead. TO is 20-25min from Hidden Hand CG. No bear box at Hidden Hand Camp.
Location_desc: TO is exactly where trail turns NW next to 75 cm DBH Doug-fir.

Travel_notes: Go W from TO down slope to gully. Point is directly at base of slope to gully. If you reach creek, you have gone too far.
Location_desc: Point is in a gully with Doug-fir Forest and open under story.  Hidden hand creek is about 15m west of point.

Travel_notes: Travel through extremely thick vine maple uderstory with many downed trees.
Location_desc: Point in Doug-fir forest with light vine maple mid-story and Oregon Grape understory. There are several large Doug-firs downslope of point. Lots of paper birch from point and upslope.

Travel_notes: Slight down hill grade, forest thick for first 55m, then thinning out.
Location_desc: Point on slope with Doug-fir forest. Open under story. Look for rock outcrop starting ~10m W of point.

Travel_notes: Mostly down hill with some rock obstacles
Location_desc: Point in open area at the edge of a rock out-crop over looking Ross Lake.

Travel_notes: Travael mostly down hill changing between 2 levels of flat ground
Location_desc: Point in relatively open Doug-fir forest. Downed trees criss-cross point. Rock out cropping to north

Travel_notes: Easy travel through open Doug-fir forest toward Ross lake. Transitions to thicker forest, then re-opens to exposed clearing on cliff head.
Location_desc: Point lies along northern edge of clearing, about 20 m back from cliff edge with lots of Doug-firs nearby.

Travel_notes: Traverse down steep, loose rocky slope into conifer-deciduous woods.
Location_desc: On moderate slope under Doug-fir forest with some birch and vine maple. Point is 1 m from 70cm DBH Doug-fir. About 35 m upslope from lake, ~10m W of edge of boulder field.

Travel_notes: Traverse northwest uphill through Doug-fir woods and beyond clearing. Travel manageable, but lots of small logs.
Location_desc: Point on slight slope underneath a stand of Doug-firs that borders a clearing. Lots of barkless fallen snags in the area.

Travel_notes: Pace 115 meters to SE01
Location_desc: Point 1 m before boulder pile. 3 sapling hemlocks next to trail mark point. Heather abundant. McGregor Mtn. visible to E/SE.

Travel_notes: Pace 350 meters to SE02
Location_desc: Point 5 m beyond small waterfall that flows over trail and continues down gully into valley. Large boulder on N side of trail marks point.

Travel_notes: Pace 350 meters to next point. Beyond ~ 90 meters, talus takes over area.
Location_desc: Point on trail amidst heavy talus slope.

Travel_notes: Pace 250 meters over rocky trail. Next point is approx. 20 meters from where shrubs become more abundant.
Location_desc: Point is 20 meters beyond where shrubs take over talus slope. 3 waterfalls visible on opposite mountain.

Travel_notes: Pace 225 meters on trail to SE05
Location_desc: Very shrubby on either side of trail with interspersed Mtn. hemlock saplings. Open view of waterfall cascading down cliff on opposite mountain.

Travel_notes: Pace 225 meters on trail to next point.
Location_desc: Point directly underneath a small, pistol-gripped Mountain Hemlock amidst a shrubby bank over trail. Mountain to S and SE very visible with glacier between.

Travel_notes: Pace 220 meters on trail to next point
Location_desc: Point 3 meters beyond 75 cm dbh and 100 cm dbh mountain hemlocks on either side of trail. Here you can see the mountains on the back side for the first time. Trail bends from relatively southward direction to an easterly direction.

Travel_notes: Pace 275 meters on trail to next point. Emerge around other side of mountain (much warmer side, too).
Location_desc: Point on trail amidst large Mtn. hemlock. Rock outcrops to south and southwest. River visible way down valley, through trees.

Travel_notes: Pace 200 meters on trail to SE09
Location_desc: Point on trail. On SW side is variety of shrubs, including alder and small cedars, and both hemlock and deciduous saplings. Twin waterfall visible on opposite mountain to NE, wide view of valley below.

Travel_notes: Pace 200 meters on trail to SE10. No switchbacks.
Location_desc: Point 25 meters before trail begins to switch back down valley. McGregor Mtn. visible through vally, in distance.

Travel_notes: Hike through 9 switchbacks. From the 9th, pace 50 meters to SE11.
Location_desc: Point on trail below overhanging saplings McGregor Mtn. prominent to east. Clump of mountain hemlock and Alaska yellow cedar just downslope to south, with alder directly downslope of point.

Travel_notes: Hike from TH at Johannesburg to TO ~1 hr, 15 min. From Pelton Basin (camp), about 20 minutes to TO.
Location_desc: TO at switchback on trail about 70 m downhill from Sahale Arm Trail junction heading toward Pelton Basin. 3 m tall snag (80 cm dbh) and remains of fallen log at point.

Travel_notes: Pace 30 m on trail W of Cascade Pass.
Location_desc: Point 30 m past Cascade Pass and 3 m past end of rock path leading to pass.

Travel_notes: Pace 240 m on trail.
Location_desc: Point in boulder field 50 m NW beyond the edge of the boulder field.

Travel_notes: Pace 210 m on trail.
Location_desc: Point on edge of meadow/boulder field 8 m SE of dense shrub patch with small young clumps of Mountain hemlock.

Travel_notes: Pace 235 m on trail.
Location_desc: Point is 60 m S of forest edge with open meadow to the E and small patches of Mtn. hemlock to the W. 3-m boulder above trail at point.

Travel_notes: Pace 235 m on trail.
Location_desc: Point next to small boulder field on W side of trail. Parking lot seen below. Metal culvert/pipe on trail 3 m S of point.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point on 2m x 2m rock on trail, 4 m from small stream running down rock face to the N.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point 15 m from switchback visible down trail.

Travel_notes: From WW07, pass 8 switchbacks, from 8th switchback, pace 100 m to point.
Location_desc: Point next to 3 m boulder on downhill side of trail. Avalanche chute seen 40 m N.

Travel_notes: Pass 10 switchbacks on trail. Point is at the 11th switchback.
Location_desc: none

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: In a small opening about 23m from next switchback. Downslope of a clump of Devil's Club and a cut log.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: In youngish stand of Pacific silver fir 27m before next switchback. Point is just after passing shrubby open section of trail.

Travel_notes: From TO, walk past 2 switchbacks. NN01 is ~50m past 2nd switchback.
Location_desc: Point is ~20m past slight bend in trail with small drainage/slight trickle of water. Right at point, there are a bunch of small rocks on W side of trail. The cut stump/tree feature is obvious and right next to point.

Travel_notes: Pace 240 meters to NN02
Location_desc: Point 1 meter before two ~50cm DBH subalpine firs just off W side of trail

Travel_notes: Pace 225 meters to NN03
Location_desc: Point on 20 meter straight stretch of trail heading N-S. Stream 20 m to SE with waterfall pouring into it. Right next to a ~35cm DBH subalpine fir on the E side of trail.

Travel_notes: Pace 210 meters along trail to NN04
Location_desc: Point in very shrubby area, dense on both sides of trail

Travel_notes: Pace 220 m on trail to get to NN05
Location_desc: Point on uphill part of trail. Talus slope visible through trees to N/NW. Large solitary root across trail about 3m up trail from point. Point is right next to round rock on W side of trail.

Travel_notes: Pace 225 meters to NN06
Location_desc: Point immediately before small stream crossing trail, 10 meters beyond where talus goes directly onto trail. Cliff views are extraordinary from here.

Travel_notes: Pace 220 meters on trail to NN07
Location_desc: Creek 25 m SE of point. Relatively indistinct spot.

Travel_notes: Pace 250 meters on trail to NN08
Location_desc: Cliff faces visible from point to the NW through shrub and subalpine fir. It is 4.3m beyond bottom of 2 wooden steps.

Travel_notes: Pace approx. 260 meters to NN09
Location_desc: Point near end of large fallen tree that parallels tree (30 m long and 50 cm dbh). It is 9m before an obvious, large bridge.

Travel_notes: Pace 300 meters on trail from NN09 to NN10
Location_desc: Point at 90 degree turn in trail toward NW. Trail continues in this direction for 8 m then turns again to the West
Location_notes: Trail has been re-routed, so it is now on a trail that trail crew is trying to close off. Also, keeping it would make it more difficult to reach the final 3 points of the NN arm.

Travel_notes: From NN09, you will pass 5 switchbacks. Point is ~6m before reaching the 6th.
Location_desc: Point is ~6m before reaching 6th switch back after NN09. Rocks on both side of trail at switchback.

Travel_notes: Travel through 9 switchbacks. From the ninth, pace 50 meters to NN12.
Location_desc: Point 10 meters before trail switchback. Rocky with less vegetation (than surrounding area) above trail at point.

Travel_notes: Travel through nine switchbacks. From the ninth, pace 115 m to NN13.
Location_desc: Point 5 m before ~50% grade rock face, which extends about 50 meters to top. Many spruce trees around. Trail ahead curvy for 25 meters until out of view.

Travel_notes: Pace 60 m beyond VW bug-sized boulder on downhill side of trail.
Location_desc: Point on trail next to small (1/3 m) mossy rock in downhill side of trail and 30 cm dbh Lodgepole pine snag (with woodpecker holes), 20 m tall, on uphill side of trail. Point is 5 m beyond a 90 degree bend in trail. About 3m above several cut logs on downhill side of trail.

Travel_notes: Pace 220 m on trail.
Location_desc: Point on trail in gradual downhill stretch at the bottom of which the trail turns from SW to S.

Travel_notes: From Bowan CG sign, pace 50 m on trail.
Location_desc: 15 m beyond point is dry stream bed. There are cut logs on both sides of trail right at point.

Travel_notes: 15 m from SS03, cross a dry stream bed. After crossing 2nd stream bed, pace 105 m on trail to SS04.
Location_desc: Point on trail in mixed Lodgepole, Engelmann spruce, and Subalpine fir forest. Next to 2 small rocks on uphill side of trail and cut end of fallen Lodgepole pine running perpendicular to trail and about 1 m above ground.

Travel_notes: Pace 210 m on trail.
Location_desc: Point in open Lodgepole pine forest with vaccinium understory. it is 15m before trail makes a slight bend.

Travel_notes: Travel gradual and upslope through open Lodgepole pine forest, paralleling (between 50 and 70 m away) distinctively different forest type with many young firs seen to N.
Location_desc: Point in between 2 (1/2 m) boulders, ~15m after slope begins to get very steep.

Travel_notes: First 50 m is easy, then enter dense shrubs- travel very slow- emerge from shrubs into open forest near point.
Location_desc: Point is 15 m beyond edge of shrubs. Stream heard to NW. About 3m downslope of downed tree running perpendicular to slope.

Travel_notes: Traverse mellow side slope. Last 40 m slightly downhill.
Location_desc: Point in open Lodgepole pine forest with grass and vaccinium understory, 20 m beyond small patch of slide alder on transect. GPS was a bit off here. If this seems to be the case next visit, do is_best for coordinates collected, assuming there is a low error.

Travel_notes: Travel 5-10 min. up the trail From Bowen CG. TO is about 50 m beyond VW bug-sized boulder on downhill side of trail. It's possible to combine this transect w/ 1016 & 1032 or with 1024 and maybe 1031. It makes for a nice thru-hike or loop hike.
Location_desc: TO located  ~20m past where canopy opens and shrubland across Rainbow Creek comes into full view and 15 m below a small cliff band. TO directly atop a 1/2 m across rock protruding from downhill side of trail. GPS might be a little off.

Travel_notes: lots of cut down trees.
Location_desc: Open forest with a lot of snags.  Hand cut log around the point.

Travel_notes: Due to switchbacks, travel 250m on the trail.
Location_desc: Cut down trees next to the point.  Open forest with lots of big Western redcedars, Western hemlocks, Doug-firs.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: none

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Open forest with a lot of Pacific silver firs <23bdh.  lots of snags.

Travel_notes: Lots of switch backs on trail.  Need to pace 350m on trail.
Location_desc: Open Western hemlock forest with lots of snags.

Travel_notes: Due to switchbacks, you need to pace 250m on trail to be 200m away from previous point.  The distance for travel features are paced on the trail.
Location_desc: Creek about 5m away.  Open froest with a lot of snags.  Salal understory. Many tall conifers with branches only at top.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Open Western redcedar forest.  4m away from creek.

Travel_notes: Follow the creek for the first 60m, can be crossed anytime, the path is not clear.  At 125m, the forest opens with salal understory and Western hemlock become dominant species.
Location_desc: really open Western hemlock forest with salal understory.  Hear the creek.

Reason_for_change: to go off-trail and away from creek
Travel_notes: the slope becomes very steep but understory is open and travel is not particularly treacherous
Location_desc: peaceful spot directly next to a small quiet stream. In conifer forest in flat shalf between slopes. Some vine maple and ferns

Reason_for_change: did not want to hit hwy 20
Travel_notes: traverse a steep slope the entire way
Location_desc: open conifer forest w/ salal understory. View of mountains, highway noise

Travel_notes: Hike is about an hour uphill from trailhead.  The UTM's provided for the T.O. didn't seem to be on the trail, so we established it the closest we could.  The trail on the map didn't seem to match up exactly with where it really was.
Location_desc: TO is located in the cut sections of the 1.8m wide Doug-fir 15m before dog leg where the trail starts going up.

Travel_notes: Travel 100m west from TO.
Location_desc: The point is in a stand of mixed conifers.  THere are Doug-firs, Western redcedars, Western hemlocks, and Pacific silver firs.  The two trees used as features are very large and conspicuous.

Travel_notes: Walk 200m at 270 degrees.
Location_desc: Point is in an area with many short Pacific silver fir saplings.  There is a distant ridgeline visible through an opening to the north.

Travel_notes: Travel west for 200m.  Many small saplings between open areas with large trees.
Location_desc: Point is in a mossy area with the following in a 1m radius: a moss-covered boulder, a 20m tall snag, and a 5m tall 70cm DBH stump.

Travel_notes: Travel downslope at 360 degrees for 200m.
Location_desc: Point is in a stand of mostly Western hemlocks with many snags.

Travel_notes: Travel downslope at 270 degrees for 200m.  Point is just beyond the bottom of the hill in a wet, relatively flat, floodplain area.
Location_desc: Point is in a riparian floodplain near Pyramid Creek.  It is located at the transitional edge between large Western Hemlock/Western Red Cedar and lots of shrubs.  Snow-covered ridgeline is visible to the SW.

Travel_notes: Travel north 200m.  FIrst 30m very dense and shrubby.  Then things open up after that.  You won't ever actually cross Pyramid Creek, although you walk close to it for the last 100m.
Location_desc: Point is close to Pyramid Creek on the east bank.  It is in a stand of western hemlocks with an understorey of lady fern, vine maple, devil's club, salmonberry, and huckleberry.  The point is directly next to a 1m tall rootball.  Two trees that have fallen over the creek with large rootballs are conspicuous.

Travel_notes: overall bearing is 270, but crossing creeking will take you off course. There are lots of downed trees and rocks in stream so get creative or get wet. Recommend heading downstream of ww06, cross stream then angle back upslope to avoid shrubby creek bank
Location_desc: point is on moderately mossy slope with lots of young doug fir and western hemlock and downed saplings in close proximity. Point is b/w 3 large doug firs, two of which are described features.

Travel_notes: Traverse diagonally across slope, and then straight up slope. Travel is slow- be patient with yourself.
Location_desc: Point located just upslope of 2 PASF that have bases less than a meter apart. Large boulder directly upslope.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is in forested section of trail 15m past bend in the trail after the TO.

Travel_notes: Point is 236m on trail from NE01.
Location_desc: Point is on open part of trail with almost no canopy above.

Travel_notes: Point is 212m on trail from NE02.
Location_desc: Point is on trail in douglas fir forest, just before a dip in the trail.

Travel_notes: Point is 265m on trail from NE03.
Location_desc: Point is on trail with open view to valley to the south. Trail begins to go uphill in about 9m, at the broken douglas fir snag.

Travel_notes: Walk 218m on trail from NE04.
Location_desc: Point is on level part of trail between a small opening in the veg (uphill side) and a small vine maple. Lightning Creek visible to south.

Travel_notes: Leave trail on a N bearing, climb steep hill before reaching more level area.
Location_desc: Point is in open douglas fir forest next to a large rock (the only large rock in the area).

Travel_notes: Travel is through mostly open douglas fir forest. Last 60m becoming thick with hemlock and cedar saplings.
Location_desc: Point is in young undescriptive western hemlock, western red cedar forest with mostly closed canopy. Many downed trees and limbs on ground.

Travel_notes: Pace 100m on the trail.
Location_desc: none

Travel_notes: Walk 230 m on the trail. Point is 12m after the trickle of water (trail goes a little up and then down, so trickle can not be seen from point)
Location_desc: Point is in mixed forest.

Travel_notes: Walk 216m on the trail. Point is 18m after the trickle of water.
Location_desc: Point in Douglas Fir forest 6m before trail turns SW. Right next to 2 Doug Firs <1m apart on W side of trail.

Travel_notes: Walk 230m on trail. Last 100m along rock outcrop.
Location_desc: Can hear the river clearly from point. Exposed small rock next to point. See photo.

Travel_notes: Walk 205m on the trail
Location_desc: There is a good amount of paper birch surrounding the point. Otherwise nondistinct location.

Travel_notes: Walk 290m on the trail. After 50m you will pass a 1m dbh douglas fir and reach an opening that gives you a 180-degree view.
Location_desc: Point is next to a massive 2x1.5 m root ball. The douglas fir forest is fairly open, can see the mountain through the tree.

Travel_notes: Walk 230m on trail.
Location_desc: Point next to 8m rock outcrop with 70cm douglas fir in front of it.

Travel_notes: Walk 230m on trail. Point is 30m after second rock outcrop you will pass.
Location_desc: Point is in douglas fir forest with a lot of vine maple. Pistol butt Doug Fir feature dist/bearing to closer tree.

Travel_notes: Travel 237m on trail.
Location_desc: Point is in open part of an old slide with 2 large rock faces and a Big Leaf Maple upslope. Stellar view.

Travel_notes: Pace 267m on trail.
Location_desc: Point is in fairly open canopy sandwiched between the gnarliest Doug Fir with burly rock covering roots, dbh=120cm, on the trail and a bunch of Douglas Maple saplings.

Travel_notes: TO is about halfway between Lightning Creek CG (1hour) and Deerlick CG (50min). Killer switchbacks from Lightning Creek CG! We arranged a boat ride to Lightning Creek.
Location_desc: Point is on trail in a mix deciduous/conifer forest on steep sloping hill side. Point is under an arching paper birch and 7m before a bend in the trail (goes NE).

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: point is on old road just as it bends north and zig zags across rocks.  can see talus slope South.

Travel_notes: walk on trail 210m out of forest and into open shrub
Location_desc: point is in a meadow where vine maple dominates.  rock face can be seen north and south of point. Surrounded by shrubs, thimbleberry, and douglas maple. A few taller willows and bigleaf maples are around. The feature fir is the only conifer for 100m

Travel_notes: walk 215m on trail
Location_desc: point is between two 120cm dbh doug-firs on the trail

Travel_notes: first 100m  in thick douglas maple, then becoming fairly steep
Location_desc: Point is in open spot of the lichen covered doug fir forest just south of douglas fir stump (with bark all over it, not a broken tree, about 2m high).  Can see the surrounding mountain and rock face with waterfall.

Travel_notes: Frist half not to bad to keep a bearing, tall douglas fir in line with it.  Second half much harder, going up against vine and douglas maple.
Location_desc: point lost in a sea of vine and douglas maple with tall douglas firs to the west and pacific silver firs to the east. Point is surrounded by young 5m tall willow trees as well. Bearing is to nearest conifer

Travel_notes: a sisyphian effort of swimming, falling and surfing through Douglas and vine maple (along with many other shrubs). Good luck!
Location_desc: Point surrounded by dense snowbush, douglas maple, and vine maple just over head height. A few young big leaf maples stick out above the shrub to the west (~8m away). A line of conifers (Pacific silver firs?) 50m North

Reason_for_change: Dense vine maple made travel to a 7th point along original bearing too time consuming for survey time window.
Location_desc: Point is in Big Leaf Maple clearing surrounded by shrub with DOFIs to the SW.

Travel_notes: travel is up slope through douglas fir forest, to edge of large vine and Douglas maple forest/ avalanche chute.
Location_desc: Point is in nondescript edge habitat. Douglas-fir forest to the East and vine maple to the West. Marker is very obvious as you approach.

Travel_notes: It's faster to go back to trail after NN01, and head W (on trail), then N (uphill) into shrub. It opens up as you get closer to NN02.
Location_desc: Point is in forested area with relatively open understory.  About 50 m west of avalanche chute.

Reason_for_change: bearing led to middle of river. the trail was the only choice
Travel_notes: Travel through douglas fir forest, then thick vine maple chute at 270 degrees, until trail is reached about 110m, walk west on trail 90m to point.
Location_desc: Point is on gravelly section of trail surrounded by thick willows and vine maple in yet another avalanche chute.  VERY BIRDY!! There is a grassy patch on trail, ~6m W of point.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: point is on trail about 20 m before it turns into forest away from river.  large snow field can be seen to the north.

Travel_notes: Walk to as close as you can get (on trail) to point, then veer off S/SW to point, ~75m.
Location_desc: Point is located in dense vine/Douglas maple, ~75m from trail. There are 3 Cottonwoods in a line generally SE of point (point is 11m to middle of 3 Cottonwoods).

Travel_notes: Probably best (though not that much faster) to go back out to trail, then walk ~200m up trail to near point. Go ~20m S of trail to point, through dense shrub.
Location_desc: Point is in dense shrub, mostly vine maple right at point. It is ~5 or 6m SE of a sprawling cluster of yews.

Travel_notes: Best way to go is to go back up to trail and walk ~200m until approximate easting is reached. Then walk ~50m N off-trail through dense shrub to point.
Location_desc: In dense shrub, mostly vine maple and ? (see photo) right at point. Point is on a medium-sized rock. Look for feature Doug-fir- it is very obvious and a good landmark. Sorry for the lack of features- can't really see anything from here.

Travel_notes: It is about a 20-min hike from Cottonwood Camp. We combined with a few other early season stehekin transects and then hiked out over Cascade Pass to Cascade River Rd. for an awesome thru-hike. If you can make it happen, do it! It was great, but apparently in normal snow years, the crossing at Doubtful Creek can be treacherous in early season. Very shrubby transect. You can use trail for much of NN arm, which makes travel much more tolerable.
Location_desc: point is on road/trail in what looks like an overgrown pullout across from a most scenic waterfall.  trail is flat, bending slightly to the west

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is between droopy Doug Firs downslope and large boulder upslope.

Travel_notes: walk 200m on trail
Location_desc: Point on trail as it's bending to cross the unnamed creek. Can see Boulder ck down slope.  Big out crop upslope

Travel_notes: Pace 275m on the trail
Location_desc: Point in open Ponderosa pine/ douglas fir forest. Lots of burned trees Point is on W edge of 10m wide landslide.

Travel_notes: walk 200m on the trail
Location_desc: Point is on really steep part of the trail. You can see Boulder ck down slope and the other side of river (which is really steep up slope and cover with downed trees). Upslope is a large rock outcrop.

Travel_notes: Walk 215m on the trail
Location_desc: Point is in burned section of the forest, next to a 1m dbh ponderosa pine (first 2m have burn marks). The side facing boulder ck is really open. Open view of mountain surrounding the point

Travel_notes: walk 200m on trail
Location_desc: Point is on upslope trail, just before a turn. When you look upslope you can see rock outcrop

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is at sharp bend in trail which looks like a drainage (dry in 2015) surrounded by few burnt Doug Firs.

Travel_notes: travel up steep slope along dry drainage from NE07. Boulder field on W side of drainage makes travel somewhat easier.
Location_desc: Point is where terain levels out a bit more on a ridge with the drainage ~30m W. To the South there is a small cliff (easiest to approach from W). Poin is located on top of a medium sized-boulder in small patch of rocks with Doug Firs around.

Travel_notes: Camped at Hooter, 45 min walk to TO. Hooter has room for 1 tent and has water very close by (~50m downtrail).
Location_desc: TO is in an area with lots of ferns, fireweed, and thimblrberry as well as some Big Leaf Maple. Either side of the trail is steep with many Doug Fir snags. E of the TO is shrubbier with more deciduous trees and farther W of the TO is drier and rockier.

Travel_notes: Walk 105m on the trail
Location_desc: Point is just beyond a turn/precipitous on trail. Open, rocky area in small dry stream, eroded area

Travel_notes: Walk 260m on trail from WW01
Location_desc: Point is in open shruby part of trail, 16m before small rocky up hill part of trail

Travel_notes: Walk 265m, on trail, from WW02
Location_desc: Point is 10m before a stream, in thick shruby vegetation.

Travel_notes: Point is 253m on trail from WW03
Location_desc: Point is on slightly down hill part of trail in a brushy area dominated by snow brush. Lots of snag around

Travel_notes: Travel up steep slope though thick snowbrush to gully (80m). Then proceed through very thick snowbrush but more level area to the point.
Location_desc: Point is in open Ponderosa pine forest with thick snowbrush understory. Point is located between 3 larges broken Ponderosa snag (2-3m tall) in a clump of snowbrush.

Travel_notes: Contour the hillside. After you crest the 1st hill you'll drop into a lush drainage (watch for ripe thimbleberries!). Then continue West through fairly open hillside, sometimes steep with loose dirt.
Location_desc: Point is between a large Ponderosa dbh 90cm and Dough Fir dbh 75cm growing 4m apart. To the West 25m is a dry drainage.

Travel_notes: It is better to follow the hill's contour than a direct bearing. After ~110m you'll drop into a steep drainage. Best to follow drainage down a ways then cut across steep hill for the last 50m or so.
Location_desc: Point is on curvy Doug Fir beside a large jutting rock face 10m tall. Surrounded by mostly scree. The drainage is 15m to the E and below the hill drops steepy down to the trail.

Travel_notes: Head up steep slope.
Location_desc: Open Hemlock/Doug fir forest.  On steep slope. Vine maple and saplings downslope.

Travel_notes: Head up and across steep slope - slow travel. Travel north until you reach large boulders scattered around.  Point is 2m past the first boulder.
Location_desc: Sitting on the edge of a boulder that has a drop off to the south.

Travel_notes: Travel down and across slope - keep downslope of the rocky outcrop - until you reach a large boulder field.  Point is in the middle of it in the rocks.
Location_desc: In the middle of the boulder field. Look and listen for pika!

Travel_notes: Travel on side slope over large downed trees. Cross 3 gullies, and just past the third is point 04.
Location_desc: On slope leading down to gully that you cross on way to point.  Open forest.  Big mossy patch near point.  Closest to largest Doug fir around (see features).

Travel_notes: Continue NE along slope, through a few patches of dense Yew until you reach a small flowing stream (good spot to cross stream slightly off bearing).  Point is 28m beyond.
Location_desc: In open cedar forest on top of large downed cedar (see nearest feature).  Stream can still be seen - loud. Little to no understory. 2021-My gps is 35m off, use travel/loc des. to confirm location.

Travel_notes: Go down then up a steep drainage directly after NW05. After that it's mostly traversing the slope. There are intermittent streams and wet spots hidden beneath mossy patch so watch out. Vine maple starts right before point.
Location_desc: Point is on edge of very! steep! drainage running down to stream. There is a downed Pac Silver fir running parallel to the stream at the point (dbh =50cm)

Travel_notes: Travel down slope 100m to point.
Location_desc: Point is in Western hemlock forest just past a series of fallen logs.  Area is relatively flat.

Travel_notes: Travel downhill and across small creek, then up and over hill to hillside facing creek.
Location_desc: Point just above flat river area on a steep slope.  One large Doug firs at point.  Panther Creek is visible to SE through vegetation. Large mossy rock at point, about size of a backpacking pack.

Travel_notes: Travel along steep gully above creek, cross creek and go up over ridge to hillside above dry gully. Point is near the top of that ridge.
Location_desc: Point is on steep south facing slope of a gully without a creek.  A large blowdown is at point, many branches are all around.

Travel_notes: Travel is through relatively flat Western hemlock forest.
Location_desc: Point is in flat area on top of a large rock outcrop.

Travel_notes: Travel is through western hemlock forest up steep slope.
Location_desc: Point is on slope next to downed Western hemlock and a long linear outcrop parallel to bearing to the SE.

Travel_notes: Travel through mostly open forest upslope, parallel to rocky outcrop on your left.
Location_desc: Point on flat slope in between large hemlock and large 1m tall stump feature (note - 1m tall stump feature looks 1m from the point, but from the other side it is 3m tall because it goes down a small ledge). Point aslo near ~200cm DBH twin hemlocks sharing a base. Rocky slope is ~45m SE. Some small Doug-fir saplings around.

Travel_notes: Camp at 4th of July CG.  30min walk to TO.
Location_desc: Point is in Western hemlock forest with Grand fir and Douglas Fir throughout.  Point is on trail on relatively flat section just before down hill section.

Reason_for_change: too steep, point located on trail
Travel_notes: Continue on trail toward North Fork Campsite
Location_desc: Pace 100 meters on trail.  Bridge not in view.  River and view of valley from narrow point on trail.

Travel_notes: Continue pacing on trail approximately 200 meters in direction of North Fork Campsite
Location_desc: On trail in rocky area with full view of bridge and creek. Approximately 1 minute walk from campsite.

Reason_for_change: Too steep to go off trail
Travel_notes: Pace 520 meters up trail and switchbacks to reach point.
Location_desc: Point located on trail after last switchback.  Ground covered in dense, low shrubs.  River is not visible, but may be heard.  On a clear day, the opposite side of valley and many snowy peaks are visible.

Reason_for_change: Landscape now suitable for off-trail points
Travel_notes: Travel between points easy, over gentle slope and low shrubs.
Location_desc: The point is located on a gentle slope, approximately 4 meters SE of dropoff into Douglas-fir forest.  Many burned trees, largely indistinct.  Large path of ceonothus NE of point.  Peak visible at 280 degrees on a clear day.  Ground shrubby with many downed trees.

Travel_notes: Travel down into small, shrubby valley staying close to edge of slope, then traverse slope and begin to climb to point.
Location_desc: Point located on medium slope in Douglas-fir forest.  Dense 1 ft shrubs all around.  Many small to medium boulders on the ground.. A vine maple is located due north with adjacent rocky outcropping 50 meters on opposite slope.

Travel_notes: Travel upslope through low groundcover, pass large boulder area to the east and continue up.
Location_desc: Point located in dense, low shrubs, surrounded by small-medium Douglas-firs.  The ground is relatively flat.  The point is actually located exactly on a downed Douglas-fir log.  Many mosquitos, bring a headnet.

Travel_notes: Travel upslope with low ground cover.  Terrain levels out after 100 meters and ground cover breaks and becomes almost nonexistent.
Location_desc: Point is located in clearing of Douglas-fir with some small shrubby understory.  Also, in middle of new larger, taller 1 meter high woody shrub with white flowers.  Small rocks strewn about ground.  Many mosquitoes.

Travel_notes: Travel upslope until a tall shrub patch (you can skirt around this by hanging to the east) and continue up as slope increases towards open area with exposed bedrock and sweet views.
Location_desc: Point is located on a rather steep slope of grasses, wildflowers and low shrubs.  Douglas-firs abundant.  On a clear day, views of adjacent valley and peaks is lovely.  Again, many mosquitoes.  Small boulders scattered downslope of point.  Large shrub 2 meters upslope of point.

Travel_notes: Moderately steep upslope travel.
Location_desc: Point is adjacent to a patch of tall shrubs (hazelnut?) and about 20m beyond the rocky clearing.

Travel_notes: Travel through dense riparian shrub.  Once the slope becomes steep, continue for 40 meters to first point.
Location_desc: Point located on steep, shrubby slope clearing.  To the west lies a line of 8 snags.

Travel_notes: Travel 150 meters up steep slope; ground becomes more level as you continue South.  The last 20 meters are through dense shrub.
Location_desc: Point located in a clearing with dense shrubs and vine maple encompassed by snags and dying hemlocks.

Travel_notes: It's a leg burner.  Travel is mostly easy, upslope and strewn with shrub and downed wood.  There are no prominent travel features.
Location_desc: The point is located at the root of a downed, old, burned, Douglas-fir on the edge of a vine maple cluster with a clearing to the west.  Snags are located everywhere.

Travel_notes: Even more of a burn. Steep climb but travel is easy.
Location_desc: Point is located in a small clearing with a small stream drainage 25 meters west.  Great view!

Travel_notes: Travel is steep and most difficult.  When rock outcrop is reached, travel up shrub areas. Stay off of the moss covered rock.
Location_desc: Beautiful view.  Shrub and downed wood everywhere on steep slope.

Travel_notes: Travel eases after initial ascent from moss-covered slabs. Top out at a slabby clearing. Promptly penetrate the thin band of alder and maple, then traverse right (south) staying above the boundary of forest and shrubs. Some game trails help as you near the point.
Location_desc: Stand directly between two comparatively large douglas firs. There is a western white pine (seemingly the only one around) 1m away at a 9 degree bearing.

Travel_notes: Camp at North Fork Camp (~5 minute walk to TO).  First 3 NE points are located on trail in direction of camp and up switchbacks.  NE bearing starts after NE03.  Really mellow off-trail travel and last point ends with a sweet view of the valley.  To access TO-Leave North Fork campground and turn right to cross the bridge. Continue up the trail.  40 meters prior to TO, trail curves to the left and flattens out.
Location_desc: 5 minute walk from camp.  At bend in trail with open flat area to the NW

Travel_notes: Pace along trail for 100m.
Location_desc: Point in Larch/Engelmann Spruce forest, 100m from TO on trail.

Travel_notes: on trail 200 m.
Location_desc: Point is on trail next to marshy area with pond.

Travel_notes: Travel northeast through marshy meadow, navigate around marshiest spots.
Location_desc: Point is on open meadow, nearly flat. Some avalanche debris to west.

Travel_notes: Travel through semi-dense forest to opening with large boulders
Location_desc: Point in clearing with some large boulders present.

Travel_notes: Travel across slope, mostly in meadow.
Location_desc: Point on slope with view of High Camp meadow.

Travel_notes: Travel across slope through alternating forest and meadow... Great Views!
Location_desc: Point is on rock outcrop in sloped meadow. Very nice view of McAllister. Point is immediately past Engelmann Spruce forest.

Travel_notes: Traverse NE up steep slope through meadow and scattered Subalpine Fir stands.
Location_desc: Point located on steep slope in indistinct spot in meadow, 210m NE of a stand of subalpine firs. South Pass Trail is visible through gap in Subalpine Firs (beyond log feature).

Travel_notes: Traverse up slope past stand of Subalpine Firs, beyond meadow with larches and whitebark pines and rock and then through more consistent Subalpine Fir forest.
Location_desc: Point is in clearing just as slope face begins to curve north. Many larches present, and belly between two peaks visible to the east.

Travel_notes: adjust azimuth and head south, downslope to aviod the park boundary
Location_desc: point located on steep slope overlooking the valley. Mosty rocky meadow and scattered SUBF around.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point on a steep slope. Lots of loose rock south of it. Open. About 10m upslope of where line of firs and larches end.

Travel_notes: Travel across the talus when rock out crop is reached go around (below), then when cluster of Subalpine fir is reach go around (above)
Location_desc: Point on steep out crop rock. Pound can be seen down slope, next to trail

Travel_notes: walked on the edge of rock/soil for 1st 30m
Location_desc: Point located about 15m in talus loose boulder, clear view of around there is false hellabore SE to SW of point. Steep out crop NW of point

Travel_notes: First 85m you are walking on rock. Once you reack Subalpine fir the ground is a mixed between soil/flower and rock
Location_desc: The point is at the edge of the talus, next to a 3m tall larch and down tree. Really open

Travel_notes: Go across talus for 100m. Afte you reach outcrop rock (easier to go around, between outcrop and larch)
Location_desc: Point in open avalanche chute meadow, really rocky, SE-E of a cluster of Subalpine Fir. You have a view of Rainbow creek valley.

Travel_notes: Traverse west along talus/heather slope until coming up onto small peak. Then continue onto the backside and stop along the treeline on the west edge
Location_desc: point along the small treeline on the west edge of the small peak. Fewer to trees to the immediate east of point. Do not descend down west slope very steep and large cliffs

Travel_notes: travel down along mellow ridgeline then descend steeper rocky slope to cliff edge. lots of SOGR flushed along ridge so get ready to be startled
Location_desc: point on flat spot near cliff edge. There are still a row of trees and shrubs so its not dangerous. Point next to large whitebark snag feature

Travel_notes: from NW07 travel back up steeper rocky slope you came down to get to point. Then wrap around cliff section of ridge to get to lower ridgeline. Do not follow bearing from start
Location_desc: point on S/SW side of clump of MOHE that partially blocks bleached log. point in open mixed conifer forest
