Travel_notes: About 500m from the High Camp Post sign. Point is located 10min away from high camp in a beautiful Alpine meadow. Mosquitoes can be hellacious! We hiked in from bridge creek
Location_desc: Point on flat spot in trail in Larch, Engelmann Spruce, Subalpine Fir forest.

Travel_notes: you travel 425m on the trail, 6 swithcbacks, you will end up 100m from TO as crow flies.
Location_desc: point on down slope past turn in trail. It is ~ 15m before reaching creek/switchback (if walking up trail).

Travel_notes: walk 320 m along trail.
Location_desc: point is in Mountain Hemlock forest with outcropping of rock on N and steep slope S, a creek can be heard from point. The twin hemlock and fir features are both curved, especially the mtn hemlock.

Travel_notes: need to go 450 m on trail to get far enough away from SW03
Location_desc: Point right at the junction between Thornton Lake trail and Trapper Peak trail, which is not shown on the map.

Travel_notes: take Trapper Peak trail, heading North
Location_desc: point is on the edge of Mtn. hemlock forest and meadow.  Outcropping of rock wall seen NE at 45m. There are many small Alaska yellow cedars on NW side of trail right at point. There are many on SE side, just down trail from point (within 3m)

Travel_notes: need to pace 300m on trail to be 200m from NW04, very steep trail climbing next to outcrop.
Location_desc: point is on crest with Mountain Hemlock around.  Lakes cannot be seen from point. It is ~10-15m before (down trail) a slight bend in the trail. Not sure if I'm exactly on trail right now because of snow - distances and bearings might be slightly off.

Travel_notes: follow the main path on the crest go west around the outcrop toward the lake.  Walk on flat, go down and up, walk on that for 50m, then go down and up when you see 3 lakes again, it's 5m from point
Location_desc: facing Thornton lakes, they can all be seen, don't see Newhalem anymore.

Travel_notes: Continue walking up trail to Trappers for a little over 200m. Point is on a brief flat section of trail after (and before) climbing uphill.
Location_desc: Point is on flat section of trail, ~6m after it levels off. Mostly heather on W side of trail, various low shrub on E. About 6m past (up trail) from several Mtn. hemlocks on both sides of trail.

Travel_notes: Continue trail up to Trappers Peak and follow a less obvious boot trail from the peak down, a little more to the W. Aim for rock outcrop with squarish top. If it is snowy this visit, you might not want to do this point. There is a slightly exposed section (very short) ~50m in, so be careful. If not comfortable or if snowy, turn around.
Location_desc: Point is on a boot trail beyond (NWish) Trappers Peak. It is ~2m S of the start of a rock outcrop. In between point and rock outcrop are several small Alaska yellow cedars. It is on a flat part of the boot trail.

Travel_notes: point is 198m on trail from TO, many switchbacks.
Location_desc: point is mostly in Mtn. hemlock forest on the edge of a meadowy stream.

Travel_notes: point is 310 m down trail, this point may be a little short, sraight-distance-wise, forgot to use GPS.
Location_desc: point directly on switchback in trail, there is a very curvy hemlock 1m away

Travel_notes: point is 408m on trail due to curves and switchbacks
Location_desc: point located directly on turn in switchback, there is a large rock wall 20m to the west.

Travel_notes: point is 218m on trail
Location_desc: point in Western Hemlock/Alaska Yellow Cedar forest next to small stream. Massive fallen logs have created trail revision at point, broken log bridge can be seen

Travel_notes: travel 370m on steeply switchbacked trail to a relatively level spot
Location_desc: point on flat part of trail near small stream, a large rotten log parallels trail.

Travel_notes: walk 200m down trail
Location_desc: Point is up against huge hemlock trunk that has fallen across trail. A stump and a rock flank the respective sides of the trail directly at point as well. There is a small trickle of a creek with thick red alder riparian immediately down trail

Travel_notes: Travel down trail.
Location_desc: Point is on trail between two hemlocks with roots entering trail on both sides. Rock 2m ahead marks the start of a short but steep grade change on trail.

Travel_notes: Travel through many switchbacks and steepish trail
Location_desc: Point on flat section of trail just before slight increase in grade with thick roots from Hemlock buried in trail.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point on slight downhill just before quick and steep zig-zag downhill. There is a .5m tall crumbly stump directly adjacent to the "right" (South) side of trail right at point

Travel_notes: Travel along trail- you will soon come to the flat old part of trail. Follow this to point.
Location_desc: Point on trail below small cliff uphill. It is just past where a lot of gravel and small rocks create a small slide from cliff to trail. Point is at gradual bend in trail.

Travel_notes: Quick and easy travel along trail.
Location_desc: Point on straight section of trail with a small cliff bordering N side of it.

Travel_notes: About 350m along the trail from park boundary.  The NW arm follows the trail until the jct with Thornton LK/ Trapper peak trial, then it follows the trapper peak trail, which is not on the map.  The trail may be dificult to follow if snow levels are high, use extreme caution especially on trail past the rock outcropping, recommended for both members of party to go and check it out on trappers peak:  Breathtaking view also!  Capmed at thornton laked CG about a 1hr walk from TO in the morning, the climb to get out may be difficult to manage at 4am! 2014: A difficult transect (logistically) if snowy. Trail down to Thornton Lake from ridge/junction tends to melt out later than rest of trail/transect itself. TO is ~4 miles from trailhead. A long walk in the AM as a day trip, but otherwise, it would be better to wait for most of snow to melt to get down to lake. There are no other places to camp.
Location_desc: Point is right at the turn on the second switchback, there is a really steep slope NE and a cliff SW.

Travel_notes: travel 210m along trail to reach point
Location_desc: Point is on trail directly at first junction of trail and social trail to a washing-machine sized boulder that leads 15m up to view of hozomeen mt.  Directly above point is a 3m tall rock face.

Travel_notes: pace 250m on trail
Location_desc: point is on trail on section where many roots cross path.  pond visible to east.

Travel_notes: travel NE for 200m along meadows, ponds and mountain hemlock.  Keep both ponds on your right.  If you reach a pond around 200m, travel N along its drainage to point.  Point is in drainage.
Location_desc: point is in small drainage that runs N-S, a meadow is to the south.  Tall Mtn. hemlocks are N, W, and E.

Travel_notes: travel upslope for 200m through Mtn. hemlock, cedar, shrubs and rocky open spots
Location_desc: point is on rocky outcrop just after more densely forested area.  2 snags (3m tall, 10 dbh) are within reach.  End of upward slope is within 20m

Travel_notes: travel over rocky rise, drop down into dense forest and shrubs.  Probably easier to go along the open area until you reach the correct Northing, and then drop down slope.
Location_desc: point is in dense Mtn. hemlock forest, understory is choked with cedar and dense shrubs.  Point is inconspicuous but at base of rotten, pale fallen log.

Travel_notes: Travel NE for 200m out of forest and onto boulders and open area.  Climb up rock face to emerge onto plateau, then travel gets easier, gradual downward slope begins
Location_desc: point is located 5m NE of small cluster of Mtn. hemlock on rocky outcrop.  A refrigerator-sized boulder lies 4m to the north.

Travel_notes: Travel NE along ridgeline.
Location_desc: Point on rock ledge/small saddle below highest point which is a large rock outcropping

Travel_notes: pace for 190m uphill on trail
Location_desc: point amid Mountain hemlock and Subalpine fir. There is a small seep of water 10m further down trail

Travel_notes: pace about 340 m on trail
Location_desc: none

Travel_notes: pace 240m on trail
Location_desc: point just before base of large rocky area with the lookout tower at the top.  View of Jack Mt. just behind you

Travel_notes: travel 255m along trail, you start to climb up large rocky mound.
Location_desc: none

Travel_notes: travel on trail 240m
Location_desc: Inconspicuous point, great views of Hozomeen, Ross lake including Ruby arm, Jack Mt, Crater Mt, Ruby Mt, etc.  There is a rock cairn just ahead on the trail

Travel_notes: travel 200m at 180 degrees
Location_desc: There is a small stream 6m before point.  Point located in inconspicuous patch of ehather, stream just before can be seen traveling down hillside for several hundred meters.

Travel_notes: walk upslope 200m, follow large swath of rock jutting out of hillside.  Point is just before you drop into a shallow depression filled with snow
Location_desc: on the edge of a rocky area overlooking small gully with a pool of standing water amid snow clumps

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On rock outcrop overlooking steep drop through subalpine fir to Diablo Lake. In heather.

Travel_notes: Travel through vegetation, then emerge and follow ridgeline up to point. Note that bearing to point is 350 degrees.
Location_desc: In open area about 10m from trail, in snow/rock/heather. On top of the world!

Travel_notes: Descend from ridge, crossing rock/heather/snow.
Location_desc: On boulder overlooking Big Beaver and Ross Lake. Heather and snow around point.

Travel_notes: TO is approx. 365m east of junction for the spur trail leading to Pierce Mt. Campground.  Amazing views.  Very Buggy. About a 10-minute hike from Pierce Mountain Camp. TO is about 9 miles up Pierce Mountain Trail from Ross Dam Trailhead (much less steep and less snowy than Sourdough Trail).
Location_desc: Located between 2 stands of tree, one on each side of trail.  There is a distincive rock face 20m from point across a small gully

Travel_notes: Pace 100 m east down trail from TO. Point is just past the last campsite in Cosho camp.
Location_desc: On trail among Devil's club and other ground cover.

Travel_notes: Travel easily through forest or walk down trail until proper easting is achieved, and then walk 20 m north.
Location_desc: On a very long mossy downed log, surrounded by large Western hemlock and smaller Pacific silver fir. Ferns, saplings, and other assorted groundcover.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: few distinct features. located in dense Western hemlock/Pacific silver fir forest.

Travel_notes: Travel through forest over many downed logs
Location_desc: Point surrounded by young hemlocks on a mound of earth.

Travel_notes: Travel through steeper forest
Location_desc: Point is just west of an opening with talus and a braided stream. Groundcover includes ferns and some Devil's club.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On a small protruding rock at base of a rotting stump.

Travel_notes: Final 75m very difficult travel. There is a seasonal/dry drainage about 25 meters from point. Use to travel further upslope if you find that eases travel.
Location_desc: Point located in somewhat clear spot amongst the messy, shrubby abyss. Gorgeous views of entire valley.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: none

Travel_notes: Travel through open forest or walk 20m down to trail and follow until you reach braided river section.
Location_desc: Located in middle of washed out, dry river braid.

Travel_notes: Travel up rising slope under Western hemlock canopy until you reach thick vine maple area. Continue 10 m into vine maple.
Location_desc: Point located 10 m into vine maple city. Part of a broken off conifer trunk lies on top of maple just N of point. 2 cottonwoods growing NE of Point. A taller douglas maple emerges from shrubmania just NW of point.

Travel_notes: Travel through really thick vine maple. Slow going. Cross three rocky stream beds at ~100m.
Location_desc: point located in dense vine maple but with clearing to the south looking down to Fisher Creek. A few boulders stand up right at point.

Travel_notes: Travel through very thick unyielding vine maple until reaching Doug-fir/Western hemlock forest. Point is 10 m into forest.
Location_desc: In Doug-fir/Western hemlock forest on steep slope with little ground cover.

Travel_notes: Camped at Cosho Camp. TO located right before first established campground.
Location_desc: Located just before the first established campsite at cosho camp. Trail must have been moved across the river (original coordinates 100m south of new TO). Camped at Cosho, 17 second walk to TO in the morning.

Travel_notes: Follow the trail for 5m before entering the forest.
Location_desc: Point is in small clearing with moderate understory

Travel_notes: Traverse upslope through thick shrub for 30m, then it opens into dense forest until you reach meadow. Travel to edge far edge of dry gully
Location_desc: Point is on immediate NW bank of dry gully, ~10m from Forest/Meadow edge

Travel_notes: open for most of the way.  some down trees.
Location_desc: In a meadow with Subalpine Fir. Lots of down wood around. No distinct features.

Travel_notes: Travel in meadow and forest with dense understory and fallen log.
Location_desc: The point is as you reach a west-facing slope.  Have a view of rainbow ridge towards the west.

Travel_notes: Travel starts off through dense Subalpine fir, then opens up into more open, talus rocky slopes. At about 165m, you come will to dense section of slide alder. It might be easier to go up and then back down? I followed azimuth and it was slow going.
Location_desc: Point in open meadow on NE side of slide alder patch. The meadow turns into a rocky slope about 36m upslope. Some SUBF in meadow.

Travel_notes: Looking from NE05, you can see a section of the slide alder patch ahead that is very narrow. Go through it there- there is an animal trail. After this, follow bearing to point.
Location_desc: Point at NE edge of slide alder patch in the meadow. there are sections of forest to SE and NW. There is a dying whitebark pine just upslope from point (2nd feature).

Travel_notes: Travel goes through patches of Subalpine fir and meadow, some parts faster than others. When you come to a patch of slide alder, go below it to get around it.
Location_desc: Point on SE edge of line of conifers and brush. There is a small meadow to SE before another patch of conifers.

Travel_notes: Point may be at a little less than 100m from TO.
Location_desc: Point in dense forest near edge of vibrant meadow.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point in clearing with many blowdowns and man-cut logs.

Travel_notes: Point 212m down trail.
Location_desc: Point on trail on edge of small opening. There is some mountain ash on both sides of trail right at point.

Travel_notes: Point 240m down trail.
Location_desc: Point in between two large Doug-firs on either side of trail.  Trail is relatively flat.

Travel_notes: Point is 285m on trail.
Location_desc: Point on downhill portion of trail in Subalpine Fir/ Engelmann Spruce forest.

Travel_notes: Point is 252m on trail.
Location_desc: Point on downhill portion of trail in Subalpine fir forest. There is a drain dug ~1m up trail from point.

Travel_notes: Point is 260m down trail.
Location_desc: Point on level part of trail in Engelmann Spruce/Subalpine fir Fir forest. It is next to a long downed trail paralleling S side of trail for ~15m.

Travel_notes: Continue down trail a bit over 200m. No switchbacks.
Location_desc: Point is in some shrub. There is a large willow just downslope of trail at point and willow/Douglas maple upslope. There is also a lot of huckleberry immediately upslope. Ferns down the trail a few meters. Several snags are downslope of trail from point.

Travel_notes: Walk ~175m past second switchback down trail. (Forgot to get distance for switchbacks in my heat-induced delirium- please do this next visit).
Location_desc: Point is downslope of a triangle of 3 similar-sized Doug-firs. Ceanothus upslope (as well as downslope) of trail right at point. Very open (and HOT) here. Shrubby.

Travel_notes: Travel over 200m on trail, past two switchbacks. Ran into trail crew and lost track of pacing. Get distance next time.
Location_desc: Point is located just down trail of a willow shrub on the south side and several boulders on the north. Mainly open canopy with a ~40cm DBH DOFI downslope of trail.

Travel_notes: Travel ~280m down trail passing two switchbacks.
Location_desc: Point located directly under branches of two DOFI upslope. The creek is pretty noisy from here.

Travel_notes: Point about a 10-minute walk from hiker Rainbow Meadow campground. It is a ~55-minute hike from Rainbow Lake, which is a nice alternative if it is hot. Beautiful. 9.8 miles up from Stehekin Rd.
Location_desc: Point is on trail, next to about 7 man-cut logs on south side of trail.  It is on the edge of a clearing with many snags surrounded by a mostly Pacific Silver Fir forest.

Travel_notes: Pace 175 m from TO
Location_desc: Located on trail in dense shrubby vegetation. Medium sized boulder with smaller rocks around is right at point.

Travel_notes: Pace 215 m up trail from NE01
Location_desc: Located at end of broken wooden walkway. Tapto creek can be heard to E.

Travel_notes: pace 325 m from NE02
Location_desc: Trail levels out briefly right at point. There is a small rock face on uphill side of trail. There is a large (~75cm DBH) silver fir on N side of trail ~2m down trail from point.

Travel_notes: Travel 220 m from NE03 due to debris from avalanche
Location_desc: located on trail at beginning of small footbridge (near the end of avalanche debris) large talus slope seen to SE.

Travel_notes: Head N from NE04, cross over remnants of old trail and continue to small clearing (not to be confused with larger, wetter clearing to the N).
Location_desc: located in small clearing surrounded by clumps of mtn. Hemlock and Pacific silver fir saplings.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is ~15m E of a loud creek, lots of rocks around. Talus slope seen to N and many down logs. Bad GPS coverage here.

Travel_notes: Travel upslope (N) to point across talus field and up over small river
Location_desc: Located in area with lots of silver fir and hemlock saplings, on moderately steep slope. Gully to the west and river can be heard just over bank of the gully.

Travel_notes: Walk upslope through occasional moderately dense shrub. It gets to be more open forest toward the end.
Location_desc: Point is in open forest with very little understory. There is more shrub ~9m to the N (mainly false azalea). It is ~1m to the W of a curved ~75cm DBH mtn. hemlock and ~5m downhill of a downed tree lying W-E.

Travel_notes:
Traveling E on trail, switchback to the left, stop when you are halfway between the switchback you just walked up and the one you see ahead bending up and right. Camped at Graybeal Camp (~2 km from TO). Hike to TO took about an hour in morning due to some sketchy river crossings and overgrown trail. Trail out to Graybeal very overgrown, lots of avalanche debris. If time allows, the next point on the west arm 
(WW12) should be off-trail. Took us about 45 minutes to get to the TO at a brisk pace, in 2016. You can also camp at Whatcom Camp (near pass), which would probably take less time (downhill), especially if you're combining this with Big Beaver transects. It could be snowy though.
Location_desc: Point is located on flat trail between two switchbacks. 2016 update" the silver fir just north of the marker tree is now a 3m tall snag.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is just past a level spot where trail is lined with rocks. At edge of narrow vine maple clearing.

Travel_notes: Cross stream in clearing ~ 15 m before point.
Location_desc: In opening with assorted groundcover, 15m past stream and ~19 m before entering cedars.

Travel_notes: Continue downtrail.
Location_desc: In opening ~45 m before a rocky stream. many young cedar trees in area. Some Alaska Yellow Cedars droop over the trail from upslope.

Travel_notes: Travel across two streams, entering forest after about 100 m. Beware sketchy snowbridges that may or may not exist during subsequent surveys.
Location_desc: On trail in dense vine maple. Next to square-cut rock on left (downhill) side of trail. Views of cool mountains, waterfalls, etc.

Travel_notes: Travel downtrail. Past boulders on both sides of trail near the point.
Location_desc: Point is on trail 7 m before a rock bridge over a small stream in dense Western hemlock/Pacific silver fir forest.

Travel_notes: Travel downtrail, switchbacking several times.
Location_desc: ~15 m before edge of wooded area. Pacific silver fir/Western hemlock forest with very little groundcover.

Travel_notes: Travel about 310m downtrail.
Location_desc: Point is on a cafeteria-tray-sized rock in the trail. Brush Creek is visible not far below. About 4m before a big 1m DBH cut log on both sides of the trail.

Travel_notes: Travel about 240m down trail.
Location_desc: Just past a shrub clearing, on edge of a forest. Brush Creek is audible, but not really visible.

Travel_notes: Travel about 200m down trail.
Location_desc: In 2016, point is on a thick log crossing the trail- may have been removed by next visit (3m away). There is a large boulder adjacent to the trail (upslope), next to the snag feature.

Travel_notes: Travel about 200m down trail.
Location_desc: Point is on trail in shrub: vine maple, slide alder, etc. It is about 26m from where the trail left the forest. Brush creek is quieter here.

Travel_notes: Pass Graybeal Camp.
Location_desc: Point is just past Graybeal, next to a huge doug-fir.

Travel_notes: Trail follows the river.
Location_desc: There is a 4m high rock wall reaching the trail.  The point is on the NW end of it right where it starts.  The river is 4m away.  You can see the road guard from point.

Travel_notes: The trail was under water at 100 m.
Location_desc: There is a river, raging from snow melt, 4m to one side, and a steep slope with 7m boulders creating a wall. A lot of vine maple and cedar around the point.

Reason_for_change: EE transect ran into park boundary
Travel_notes: Start off-trail travel through two "smal cliff" features in EE02. Travel rocky and steep in beginning, but not dangerous. Try to stay on left side of small cliffs as you walk uphill. At 120m, slope mellows a little.
Location_desc: Point 2.5m from ~80cm DBH DOFI (largest in area). Point is in open understory DOFI forest with thicker vine maple to west and an open talus slope NE.

Travel_notes: The transect is located along Ruby Creek. Takes about 20 min to walk to TO.Be careful, there are ticks around! 2014: moved TO so WW01 through WW07 and EE01 and EE02 are all one arm. Points are extremely noisy-- could not hear any birds on WW01, WW03, EE01, EE02; identification impossible on WW05 and WW04 for some birds. Prepare for frustration!! Transect was modified because it ran into park boundary last visit. Note that one person does points WW07 and all points E (including EE arm), the other person does WW08-WW14. Off-trail points on WW arm are shrubby and steep at times. Slow travel. Most of trail points are very close to Ruby Creek and impossibly loud.
Location_desc: TO is on trail bordered on both sides by young Doug-firs. The river is to one side, and land slopes steeply up on the other.

Travel_notes: The trail goes down and then up.  Point is half of the way up.
Location_desc: The point is in the slope as its going up.  28 m from top and 25 m from bottom.  The river is 13m away 11m down.  There is a steep slope on other side.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: The river is 25m down, there is a steep slope on the other side, Doug-fir are dominant.  You can see the road and cliff and waterfall on the other side of river.

Travel_notes: The slope goes down, the point is right at the bottom of it.
Location_desc: The point is right at the bottom of the slope at the same level as the river, 2m away.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: on a flat part of the trail, River is 10m away.  Steep slope starts at 18m away, at 32 deg. bearing.

Travel_notes: Trail goes up, then down again.
Location_desc: Flat spot near river (same level). steep slope at 38 deg.

Travel_notes: At fork with bridge over Ross River, take a right (East Bank Trail.)
Location_desc: Point located on steep slope, Doug-fir/Western hemlock forest.  A creek up trail is visible.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point in clearing with ferns growing on north side of trail, river not visible.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Clearing in forest, surrounded by vine maple and Doug-fir. There are 2 ~10-15cm DBH Doug-firs right near cut end of cut log feature. Vine maple isn't as dense downslope of point as it is in surrounding areas.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is located in thick patch of sapling vine maple and big leaf maples.

Travel_notes: Walk uphill through mostly sparse to dense shrub. You will cross a gully at ~60-80m (depending on where you cross it) and reach a flat area that is randomly flagged (old trail?) at ~120m. The remainder is a steep climb through moderate shrub to point.
Location_desc: Point is ~11m SW (downslope) of large cliff, on steep slope. There are a bunch of rocks (under moss) at and surrounding point. It is ~4m downslope (NW/W) of a large boulder up against the rocky cliff.

Travel_notes: To get around cliff, walk NW and then correct yourself when you get to flat terrain. Enjoy this because at ~75m, you start climbing through shrub for much of the rest of the transect.
Location_desc: Point is at edge of where it becomes more forested (with shrub), rather than just shrub. There are a bunch of white downed trees within 5m NE of point.

Travel_notes: There is no good way to go. Pick your way through the dense shrub, crossing a small creek at~ 160-170m (depending on where you cross it) - may the force be with you.
Location_desc: In dense vine maple (and other shrub), traveling overhead, so finding/locating features is/will be difficult. The Doug-fir feature (along with another ~3m W of it) are 2 of the only large Doug-firs visible from point. Look for those.

Travel_notes: Walk up steep slope through varying levels of dense shrub. Look for boulders/rock face. Point is just below that.
Location_desc: Point is at the base of a bunch of steep boulders/rock face. It is ~0.5m down from rock. Branches from a dying lodgepole pine extend over point from boulders above. Extensive shrub below.

Travel_notes: The best way to go is walk W (immediately) to get around large rock face. Shortly after, wou will hit a small, pretty open ridge, which you can walk up until you're about 25m SE of point. Go down to point from there.
Location_desc: Point is on mossy slope, surrounded by a lot of shrub. The worst of it is just upslope and to the W of point, though. The Doug-fir that the boulder feature is below is within 2m downslope of 2 other similar-sized Doug-firs. It is ~25m NW of a small ridge (that you might have walked up to get here). Douglas Maple and vine maple extend almost over point from upslope.

Travel_notes: Head due east from point to point 01. Trail can be seen from point. Downhill the whole way.
Location_desc: In the midst of lots of heather, on a slope facing down the valley toward Stehekin. Rocky outcrops in all directions. Stream (barely running in 2010) visible down slope and trail about 27m away. Just above a spot where it drops down sharply to where stream is running.

Travel_notes: Walk off trail down hill and then along the flat until you reach point 02. When approaching, you will see a line of tall mt. hemlock and grand firs running north and south. Point is near the southernmost of these trees.
Location_desc: Point is on a south-facing slope, on the south side of a group of small mountain hemlocks and cedars, and on the southern end of a line of trees mentioned above. Good mountain views. Looking down the hill, mostly open with tiny clump of hemlocks in the middle of the clearing.

Travel_notes: Walk down hill to Doubtful Creek. Best place to cross is exactly where you hit creek. Continue through bushy areas until you see stump/snag in photo. Point 03 is to the right of this stump on an open granite patch, on the south side.
Location_desc: On the southern edge of open granite slab. Look for stump to navigate, not seen from point but the top of it is.

Travel_notes: Travel uphill, pass rocky outcrop and enter dense mountain hemlock. Continue through this until you reach point 04, traveling uphill more steeply toward the end.
Location_desc: On a steep hillside in blueberry and heather surrounded by mountain hemlocks. Good mountain views. Look for small stream with scattered rocks. Uphill view from point is a grassy streambed and more granite boulders.

Travel_notes: Easiest to follow the steep streambed of EE04 N uphill (dry in 2015) until the forest/shrub clears after 70m. Then turn E/NE to get back to original bearing over tallus and meadow.
Location_desc: Point is on rock outcrop surrounded mostly by blueberry. Probably the most scenic pt I have established (views of Pelton Basin and all surrounding ranges and Doubtful Lake). 20m is a small cliff and to the NE is a small stream running down a rockface.

Travel_notes: Choose your route carefully... it is a bit of a scramble. Once you are over the first rockwall, it is tallus and stream meadow to the point.
Location_desc: Point rivals EE05 for most scenic. Similar view, but slightly higher. On moderately steep rocky meadow 9m E of a stream and ~18m before another steep sections of rocks to the N.

Travel_notes: Fun transect! Stayed at Sahale Glacier. Takes 1.5 hours to hike to TO. Steep trail up to camp but well worth it to stay there instead of Pelton Basin. Didn't have time to establish fifth point but could maybe continue NE or E - may be too steep! Be prepared for stream crossing on EE arm. Lots of good high elevation and meadow birds on WW arm. To find TO: hike down trail toward Doubtful Lake. Go through one patch of mountain hemlock, continue through open area, and hit second patch of mountain hemlock. TO is at a switchback where the trail heads straight down toward the lake.
Location_desc: On trail with shrubby mountain hemlocks on the left and clumps of hemlock on the right. Short switchbacks on trail just below point.

Travel_notes: Head up trail. When trail makes a long switchback going west, point 01 is close. Stop before you reach some mountain hemlock. Up ahead on trail look for trees in photo.
Location_desc: On trail, good view of lake. Open at point but trees ahead and down below on either side of trail.

Travel_notes: Walk up to intersection and head up trail toward Sahale Glacier. Stop when you get to the first clump of mountain hemlocks on the right.
Location_desc: On trail.

Travel_notes: Walk along trail, down then up some rock steps. Continue past hemlocks to your right and left. Point 03 is in open section of trail 6m past a shrubby hemlock 1m tall on the right side of the trail.
Location_desc: On trail with view of rock steps in the distance.

Travel_notes: Head up trail, passing a viewpoint for the lake on the right and crossing a meadow. Head up trail and stop at the base of the next series of rock steps.
Location_desc: On the bottom (and biggest) step of a series of rock steps going up. Pinkish granite step 80 x 50cm and very flat.

Travel_notes: Head up rock steps, and up trail as it winds back and forth. Head up a set of evenly spaced rock steps and pass a large boulder on your left. Head up two switchbacks and stop just as the trail turns right again.
Location_desc: On trail 2m after it turns to the right. Below two large boulders in trail.

Travel_notes: Walk uphill up trail, when it levels out, continue past the boulders and stop just past the 3rd of 3 rock slats in trail.
Location_desc: On trail in open flat spot. Trail ahead curves around to the left, around a biggish hill.

Travel_notes: Head up trail and look for obvious rock pile, right next to trail and with one long skinny rock sticking straight up.
Location_desc: On trail in meadow. Very birdy. Lots of lupine and rolling grassy hills.

Travel_notes: Walk uphill. Point is in a rocky section of trail past a dirt section. Flat spot with low grassy patch to the west.
Location_desc: Look for boulder (featured) behind you and on the right (east) side of trail. In open heather field with many apparent boulders.

Travel_notes: Head up trail as it gets steeper and switchbacks. Point 09 is past a slight leftward bend in trail.
Location_desc: On trail, rocky outcropping and heather surrounding point. Look behind you for boulder outcrop that you pass at 170m to find point.

Travel_notes: Transition from meadow to tallus/scree after 60m trail turns muddy form water/snowmelt running down.
Location_desc: Point is on trail surrounded by scree slopes. The slab feature looks like a solid ridge of rocks sticking above the scree. Water can be hear running W of point.

Travel_notes: Up a steep slope, travel is easy through grassy open areas.
Location_desc: Point is located in a grassy and open area with a large fallen Pacific Silver Fir.

Travel_notes: Travel continues up slope and is grassy with downed wood.
Location_desc: Point is surrounded by downed logs and low shrubs.  It is on the north side of a large downed Douglas-fir log. Great view.

Travel_notes: Travel north, contouring along the steep slope with low shrubs and downed wood. Very steep.
Location_desc: Point is under a mid-large Western white pine (~30cm DBH), one of only a few in the vicinity.

Travel_notes: After rock outcrop with beautiful view is down slope into thick thimbleberry and downed wood.
Location_desc: Open area covered in thimbleberry and some Devil's Club.

Travel_notes: Travel continues downslope through riparian vegetation.
Location_desc: Point is amongst large Engelmann's spruces and low vegetation

Travel_notes: After 50 meters fo following a northerly bearing, drop down to trail.  Follow trail until a clearing and two large Firs on west side of trail.  Go east upslope 40 meters to the point.
Location_desc: Next to a downed Pacific silver fir.

Travel_notes: Go back to trail.  Pace 200 meters northbound on trail.  Once you see a large boulder on the east side, continue for 30 paces and head off trail 30 m E to point.
Location_desc: Point is located on the edge of a clearing with many snags and low shrub layer.

Travel_notes: Go back to the trail and continue northbound.  Point is located 220 meters north of point NN07.  An area with flowing water is reached and the trail disappears.  On the north side where the trail is reached, go 20 meters E to the point.
Location_desc: Fast moving water and downed logs everywhere.  Point is on two downed logs creating an 'X'.

Travel_notes: From T.O. travel steeply downhill at 180 degree bearing, crossing many downed logs and low dense shrubs.  River audible from point.
Location_desc: The point is located on a moderate slope toward the river.  Many ~30 DBH Douglas-fir trees are immediately downslope.  Understory is composed of a dense carpet of Vaccinium and False Solomon's Seal.  Downed wood visible all around, especially to the SE of the point.

Travel_notes: Travel SE toward SS02 over downed logs, relatively flat and easy terrain to navigate.  If you reach the stock trail, you have gone too far.
Location_desc: The point is located on flat terrain, due west of a large pile of downed Pacific Silver Fir and in a large patch of low, dense, woody shrubs. River is very audible from the point.  It is surrounded by many live and dead Pacific Silver Firs of ~25 DBH.

Travel_notes: It's easiest to walk downslope to McAlester Trail, then jump off it near SS03.
Location_desc: Point is located on flat terrain, with many low lying lilies and yellow violets on ground and many small Pacific Silver Fir saplings.  Point is surrounded by many ~35-50 DBH Pacific Silver Firs. River is very audible.

Travel_notes: Walk back to trail, then continue up it until you can jump off for SS04.
Location_desc: Point located on downed, highly decayed log.  Due N/NW there is open, standing, boggy water with many bracken, thimbleberry and lilies growing in and around.  Many downed logs lay due N/NW and the river is clearly audible.  Point surrounded by ~25 DBH Pacific Silver Fir.

Travel_notes: Travel steeply uphill over fallen logs and dense shrub at 45 degree bearing to avoid the river.  Vegetation dominantly Pacific Silver Fir and scattered Douglas-firs of a large size.
Location_desc: Point is located on a steep slope next to a large, mostly barkless, fallen Pacific Silver Fir.  SE of the point is a dense Red Alder and Vaccinium shrub field.  NE and downslope of the point are many flowering Mountain Ash shrubs and downed wood.  On a clear day, the rock face of a mountain is visible at 180 degrees.

Travel_notes: Travel upslope and over logs to the trail.
Location_desc: Point is on trail in forest, just past a barkless log upslope, with a shrubby patch up the trail.

Travel_notes: Travel on trail just past avalanche chute with shrubs.
Location_desc: Point is atop a downed 80cm DBH Pacific silver fir, ~10m off-trail.

Travel_notes: 219m at 90 degrees. Walk on trail for ~200m, then head upslope 25m into the slide alder (it's not too bad).
Location_desc: Point is at a mossy microwave-sized boulder with a smaller rock just upslope of it. Sorry- no features- slide alder obscures everything. Use GPS to get as close as you can.

Travel_notes: We camped at Fireweed Camp. It is a 15 minute (1km) walk to the T.O. in the morning, up Twisp Pass Trail. The NN arm travels upslope for two points and then steeply down before running into the trail on the east side of Bridge Creek.  Points NN06-08 can be accessed by taking the trail to intended northing and then traveling a short distance off of the trail.  NN08 is in a large wetland area where the trail disappears.  I was unable to cross the creek on the SS arm, so the direction was changed to NE. NN arm is very steep at points- use caution and good footwear.
Location_desc: Point is located just past cut logs on south side of trail.  Boulders and Vine Maples to the north.

Travel_notes: Travel is on trail.
Location_desc: Point is on trail surrounded by fallen logs.

Travel_notes: Travel is on trail
Location_desc: Point on incline on trail beside a ~1m boulder.

Travel_notes: Travel is on trail.
Location_desc: Point is on trail in dense forest on slight incline. Trail bends out of sight to the N 8.6m from point.

Travel_notes: Travel is on trail.
Location_desc: Point is on trail.

Travel_notes: none
Travel is on trail.
Location_desc: Point is on trail on an incline w/ rocks lining the trail and large boulders upslope.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is on trail in a ~50m flat section before an incline with an abundance of fallen trees up and down slope of point.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is on trail on flatter section between inclines.

Travel_notes: Travel is on trail. forest opens up to a talus slope 55m before point.
Location_desc: Point is on trail above talus slope.

Travel_notes: Continue N on trail until terrian becomes less steep/rocky on E side. Cut E/NE into forest with many downed trees and head upslope at ~70 degrees.
Location_desc: Point is located just after a rise in a mossy, open hemlock forest. Pretty.

Travel_notes: About a 35-40 minute walk up Thunder Creek Trail from Junction Camp. Junction is about 10 miles up the trail from Colonial Creek Trailhead. Horrible mosquitoes- a headnet is highly recommended. GPS seems to be a bit unreliable in this area, so don't rely too heavily on it.
Location_desc: Point is about 35m before trail makes a sharp turn toward river. About 35-40 minutes from Junction Camp.

Travel_notes: Walk downslope 100m through dark, but relatively open forest.
Location_desc: Located on slope 100m W from TO.

Travel_notes: Walk downhill until slope levels off, then walk the rest of the way through thicker vegetation and Devil's Club (and over downed trees).
Location_desc: Point is in the middle of dense Devil's Club, surrounded by some large cedars. It is less than 1m S/SW of a ~65cm DBH hemlock snag.

Travel_notes: Walk through thick Devil's Club for most of the way. There are some breaks, but it is pretty shrubby for most of it. Walk until you reach gravel bar. Fun times.
Location_desc: On edge of gravel bar, but it is being encroached on by saplings/shrub.

Travel_notes: Just parallel the creek in the least shrubby, most optimal route possible. Maybe there will be more of a gravel bar next visit. Point is about 20m SE of creek.
Location_desc: Point is about 20 m SE of creek on a downed tree lying NE-SW. Log is surrounded by Devil's club (and other downed trees). Hemlock branches extend over point from a tree to the W/SW.

Travel_notes: Walk through moderate shrub for most of the way. It lessens at ~170m (just past final Devil's Club).
Location_desc: Point has a mossy understory with huckleberry bushes. There are several large downed trees stacked together, forming a triangle just to the E of point.

Travel_notes: Walk about 125m through pretty mellow forest. Then go over several small streams and many downed trees all of the rest of the way to point.
Location_desc: Hemlock and silver fir branches extend over point (at eye level). On higher ground above (SW of) dried-up channel.

Travel_notes: Travel across small streams and tons of downed trees for ~125m. Then it opens up into easier-to-travel-through forest for the remainder.
Location_desc: Point is located next to a large Doug-fir (~120cm DBH) with a mossy understory. The creek is audible from point.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: point is just before larg moss/lichen covered slab on W side of trail. Immeadiately east is a group of 8+ subalpine firs w/ 2 mountain hemlocks sticking up slightly high above them

Travel_notes: pace 215m on trail
Location_desc: point is 13m before waterfall and stream crossing, surrounded by vaccinium, mountain hemlock saplings and heather

Travel_notes: climb up stream offtrail and stick to the right (N) side of the waterfall. There is a way-trail that shoots off through some yellow cedar saplings. After passing through those you'll go through a meadow into a boulderfield. Boulder hop to the highest point and scramble up a heather chute until you plateau
Location_desc: Point is in a small level area w/ large rock outcrops uphill and a boulderfield to the S and E. Heather is surrounding point along with scattered mountain hemlocks

Travel_notes: If dry, follow a N bearing across steep heather and mountain hemlock saplings. You'll countour the hillside and then go down into Granite Basin. If snowy, it may be better to backtrack down the boulderfields and follow them to the NE to get into the basin.
Location_desc: Point is at the NE tip of a large slab where it is closest to the S edge of a small alpine lake. Boulders strewn around heather and braided streams coming from the N and NW. Superb high country

Travel_notes: Skirt the N edge of the small lake and head up through open meadow. Try to use rocks to avoid crushing sensitive plants
Location_desc: point located 35m uphill from pond bed (dry in 2015). Surrounded by small boulders, heathe and tiny vaccinium

Travel_notes: Travel up and over a small hill. After 70m you enter a flat meadow and then onto a large boulder field
Location_desc: Point is about halfway up a large boulderfield on a 3m tall boulder. A larger bould just W of the point has a smiley face made up of two off-colored patches of granite/lichen and a crack (see photo). This would be a great spot for hide and seek.

Travel_notes: continue along the boulderfield and after ~120m travel becomes steep heather and vaccinium. Use rocks for solid hand/foot holds
Location_desc: point is on small fouton sized rock with a 1m tall subalpine fir sapline growing next to it. Immeadiately NE is a 15m tall overhanging cliff and to the N (where the hill meets the cliff) is a slot cave big enough to stand in.

Travel_notes: scurry and scramble across talus, scree and boulders. I find it helmps my footwork to think like a pika.
Location_desc: point is at the base of some epic cliffs nearing the upper rim of granite basin. Surrounded by scree, boulder and some Ptarmigan's foot. It's on a 2x1x1m tapered rectangular boulder with the skinniest end pointing E

Travel_notes: Walk about 110m down trail from TO, until you're about 8m from creek (before crossing it).
Location_desc: Point is about 8m N of where small creek crosses trail. Heather on W side of trail. Heather, blueberry, and mtn. hemlock saplings on E side. There are several slightly taller mtn. hemlocks on E side of trail, about 0.5m N of point. There are several large boulders on W side of trail, ~1.5m up from point (N of).

Travel_notes: Pass 2 (not-so-extreme) switchbacks on trail. Travel generally uphill. Look for giant rabbit boulder on E side of trail.
Location_desc: There is some mtn. ash on W side of trail amid heather and vaccinium. There are a lot of roots on trail immediately (within 2m) S of point. Point is in between 2 small rocks (which are ~7m apart) that are on trail. Lots of subalpine fir saplings.

Travel_notes: Walk up to trail junction (with Copper Lake), take left toward Lookout. Walk past 5 switchbacks. Point is about 30m past 5th switchback.
Location_desc: Point is about 6m down trail (toward lake) from a switchback. There are very few saplings immediately surrounding point. Heather on downslope side, heather and rock upslope. It is exactly at uphill end of where trail is supported by rocks (flat rock feature marks end of this).

Travel_notes: Walk past 17 switchbacks (though the last one isn't really a sharp switchback; more just a bend in trail). Point is about 35-40m past the 17th.
Location_desc: Point is where trail starts to straighten out a bit (after all of the switchbacks). There is a rock serving as a water bar about 1m down trail from point. It is about 15m before (down trail of) cresting a ridge and ~10m down trail from several small mtn. hemlocks on SW side of trail.

Travel_notes: Walk up trail. There are many bends in trail, but SS05 is at the third distinct switchback that you pass/reach.
Location_desc: Right at a switchback with heather, cedar, mtn. ash, mtn. hemlock, and vaccinium at outside corner. There are rock "steps" up trail from point.

Travel_notes: Walk past 3 switchbacks until trail straightens out and you can see the lookout. Point is in this straightaway section.
Location_desc: Point is ~20m before (SW of) reaching the end of the line of trees on the NW side of trail. The lookout is visible. Heather dominates. There are fewer boulders downslope of trail right at point than to the SW.

Travel_notes: Walk up trail a little way, until it gets more gradual off-trail (to the NW)- also, you won't be stomping through as much heather this way-- mostly talus-- route is all open, primarily through a boulder field.
Location_desc: Point is in a boulder field, which is a little hard to describe. There is a lot of green vegetation immediately to the NE of point. There is a steeper "pile" of boulders ~10m to the S of point.

Travel_notes: Walk across boulder field. Slightly steep at times. GPS should work great.
Location_desc: In a boulder field, on a larger slab of rock. Slope rises abruptly to the W/SW of point.

Travel_notes: Walk across boulder field for 200m. Steep at times.
Location_desc: In a slightly more vegetated spot, where there is actually a potential for birds! In a small gully-like topographic feature.

Travel_notes: Walk across boulder field for 200m, crossing a steep drainage along the way. All open.
Location_desc: In boulder field with very little vegetation. More veg to the E and downslope. There is a mound ~20m to the NW, where rock feature is (basically the high point of the mound).

Travel_notes: 35-minute hike from Copper Lookout to TO w/ no snow. 8-min. hike to TO from Copper Lake. It is much easier to camp at Copper Lake, but you might be asked to camp at the lookout. Established in 2015 with no snow anywhere on trail (and relatively none off-trail as well). Whoever does the NN arm should be comfortable with travelling over large boulderfields and steep scree at times. Boulder fields on SS arm as well. Both arms are beautiful!
Location_desc: If coming from Copper Lake, point is right where there starts to be rock lining the W side of trail. Above that, heather. Alaska yellow cedars on E side of trail. It is about 9.5m past (N of) a large dog head-shaped boulder on W side of trail (moss-covered).

Travel_notes: Point is 115m from TO. Walk down to switchback, then go off-trail from there. Travel until you reach the edge of talus slope. Marker should be visible from route.
Location_desc: Point located at the edge of talus slope. Next to stunted conifer.

Travel_notes: First 80m go down talus slope, the rest is easy walking. Avoid talus by going slightly to "right" (south).
Location_desc: Point is in small south facing slope above boggy area with small stream flowing in the middle of it.

Travel_notes: Walk across meadow, point is 35m after you reach small outcrop
Location_desc: Point has good view of summit around. Can see lake Juanita + trail to go to hiker camp site. About 10m upslope of 2 small larches growing close together, on edge of small dropoff.

Travel_notes: First 78m go down steep slope. After, it's "rolly" travel toward lake Juanita
Location_desc: Point is next rock outcrop by the junction to tail for hiker camp and trail to horse camps (+ going down to Stehekin) and creek.

Travel_notes: Leave Ne04 using 135 degree bearing, walk around Juanita Lake and head towards Admin campsite.
Location_desc: Point is directly uphill from Admin campsite, on a rock outcropping with 1 foot wide dark intrussion.

Travel_notes: Walk downhill, past admin site, cross a small stream (dry in 2015), and head uphill again.
Location_desc: On rocks, ~18m S of point, slope steepens, trees thin, and view opens considerably to South.

Travel_notes: Continue at 135 degree bearing. Traverse on gradually steeper slopes through Englemann Spruce and Subalpine Fir to prominent outcropping.
Location_desc: On steep rock outcrop, with commanding views to South, Lake Chelan (west shore) just barely visible.

Travel_notes: Probably best to walk off-trail directly from NE07, avoiding the rock outcrop just to the SE by going above it (maybe?). I tried to use the trail to avoid the outcrop, but it was kind of a pain and likely took longer.
Location_desc: Point is ~1m NW of a ~25cm DBH Subalpine fir. About 10m to the NE are a bunch of boulders stacked on each other.

Travel_notes: Travel down trail 190m to point.
Location_desc: Point is on trail just in a larch forest grove, scree slope visible 8m away up trail. Large rock outcrop starts directly uphill.

Travel_notes: Downtrail from SE01 by ~250 m where trail rounds shoulder of slope, coming out of a larch forest into a small meadow; rock outcropping upslope.
Location_desc: Point is in open area surrounded by larch forest. It overlooks Juanita lake and basin.

Travel_notes: Walk on trail pass trail junction take purple pass trail.
Location_desc: Point is in open area on steep hill side. The forest is patchy (whitebark pine and subalpine fir). Point is near the edge of thick upslope forest along trail (5m).

Travel_notes: Descend down steep slope into nearly flat bottomed basin.
Location_desc: Point is in the bottom of basin in between 2 clumps of thick subalpine fir forest. False hellebore surrounds the point, but is thickest to the east.

Travel_notes: Walk through meadow 90m, then open subalpine fir forest. A slighty steeper grade down hill starts at 170m.
Location_desc: Point is in open area surrounded by subalpine fir forest and sporadic whitebark pine. Point is situated at east end of large vaccinium sp. patch. Saplings abundant.

Reason_for_change: avoid getting too close to NE arm of transect.
Travel_notes: Change bearing to SE and head down gentle slope through mostly open forest.
Location_desc: In a somewhat open area with numerous Subalpine Fir saplings surrounding point. Scattered stones and bare ground 3m away to E. Area surrounded by fir, WB Pine and spruce.

Travel_notes: Continue down gentle slope through open forest on bearing. Point is near a cluster of snags with two fallen logs nearby.
Location_desc: Point is between 2 small snags, a third more branchy snag is 3m away to S. 2 fallen logs to the W. Photo is of point (red pack and pole) between 2 snags (from E).
Point is in small clearing surrounded by young firs, WB pines. Several sapling snags around point

Travel_notes: From Juanita CG take the trail that goes down to Stehekin (Purple pass trail, not marked). Pass by horse tie-ups. Take Boulder Butte Trail when you reach it. TO is 50m after the first switchback (after the boulder field). Camped at Lake Juanita CG, TO is about 20 min. walk from there.
Location_desc: Lots of larch and really rocky ground. Juanita lake can be seen from TO.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is in a gully with many fallen logs.  The only gully from TO.

Travel_notes: Really steep!  Leave the gully a little before reaching root ball. GPS is not helpful when finding this point.
Location_desc: Point located by one of many dog leg-like Western redcedar.  Lots of >25 Western hemlocks. Look for bent cedars to find this point.

Travel_notes: Steep slope- be careful on the way down. Flat between 90 and 100 m. A lot of downed trees.
Location_desc: Point located on steep slope in Doug-fir forest, open. You can hear the Stetattle. Can see both pictures through the tree between 2 snags on right and left.

Travel_notes: After 100m you cross a downed log with no bark on it.  The slope flattens for 20m and then starts  to go up again. Steep slope- be careful on the way down. Easier to follow ridgeline, then drop down when near point.
Location_desc: Open Doug-fir forest.  Point is on slope facing SE. You can hear Bucket Creek, but cannot see it (about 30-40 m away).

Travel_notes: Travel is up and across steep slope. Many fallen trees, stretches of loose debris.
Location_desc: In middle of clearing with many parallel logs. Lots of pine saplings. Clear view of mountains to SW through only a few trees and snags.

Travel_notes: Travel is difficult and requires scrambling up very steep slopes with some trees and shrubs and a lot of loose material. Following the ridge is easier than cutting across slopes.
Location_desc: In open Doug-fir forest with view of tree-covered ridge to east. Very steep slope that ends in cliff to creek. Point is just upslope of tall Doug-fir between a 4-m snag (8-cm DBH) and fallen log.

Travel_notes: Have to travel across steep slope, takes a little time.
Location_desc: Very noisy from bucket creek. point is right next to (1m from each) a VW bug sized boulder that is covered in moss and a 1m high stump split down the middle.

Travel_notes: Hike takes about 45 minutes from Stetattle Trailhead in Diablo. Cross bucket creek which was the 4th running stream we encountered and the largest (the map only shows 1 running creek before bucket)  The TO is 95m before the next unnamed running creek.  Some may want to bring sandals, a few crossings can be tough. 2014: several stream crossings where sandals are advisable. A bit difficult to get to points WW06 and WW07 due to blowdown. Use caution. Hiking in requires attention (otherwise might lose trail in dark).
Location_desc: TO in western hemlock forest near unnamed stream.  There are many streams not on the map, use GPS to get in close.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point immediately after river crossing on trail.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point on trail, in small clearing. Mostly Western hemlock forest

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On trail, relatively open surrounded by dense forest.  Point in grove of very large Cedars.  Point just after where trail turns and heads up hill.

Travel_notes: Easy to get confused because there are several large Western redcedars in area. Pacing helps.
Location_desc: Point in dense forest with shrubby understory.

Travel_notes: Trail becomes overgrown, take care to try an stay on it.  Go north around blowdown, trail is on slope.
Location_desc: On trail, no very conspicuous features.  Point located in small patch of young silver firs.  Some large cedars are present, shrubby area of trail.

Travel_notes: Point is 107m on trail from where trail begins to ascend after creek crossing. Travel is difficult after heading upslope. Detouring downed trees by going above trail and circling around is recommended.
Location_desc: Point on over-grown trail in Hemlock/Western redcedar forest.  Large patches of snow visible on opposite side of Stetattle creek though trees.

Travel_notes: Travel is difficult and requires navigating through a mess of fallen trees. Easier to go up and around, rather than straight through.
Location_desc: In small clearing with large amount of blowdown. Shrubby understory, surrounded by somewhat open Western hemlock/Doug-fir forest.

Travel_notes: Travel carefully. Go north of the vine maples to find a thinner way through.
Location_desc: point on other side of dry creekbed in an area full of vine maples.

Travel_notes: Head NW and you will run into the flagged trail again. Point will be on the trail.
Location_desc: Point located on flagged trail right before the hemlocks that are on either side of the trail.

Travel_notes: Travel through mostly open forest and enter dense vine maple. Continue to point 01.
Location_desc: Thick vine maple understory, and mix of douglas fir and western red cedar.

Travel_notes: Travel through dense vine maple entire time, and slope gets steep.
Location_desc: In exremely dense vine maple and Bigleaf maple saplings. Sky is not visible. Difficult to find features. In a slight dip in the terrain.

Travel_notes: Travel up slope and through extremely dense vine maple.  Opens up a little nearer point 3.  When you see a rocky slope ahead, you are close to the point.
Location_desc: Clear view of opposite side of valley.  Steep cliffy descent to river.  Relatively open with a few big (50 cm dbh) douglas firs.
Location_notes: NN03 was retired because it was surrounded by cliffs and therefore trapped surveyor from continuing in any direction from there.

Travel_notes: Walk through extremely dense vine maple most of the way. Acrobatics (and patience) required. Just before point, it opens up a bit and you'll see some cliffy rock outcrops. Stay below those and be happy that you're out of the shrub for a minute.
Location_desc: Point is just below (and slightly to W) a large rock outcrop. At uphill side of a ~100cm DBH Doug-fir. There are lots of yews surrounding point.

Travel_notes: After initial openness (free from dense shrub), go back into it for most of the remaining distance to NN04.
Location_desc: Point is in moderate vine maple and other shrub on some mossy rocks, much more open than previously. There are a bunch of rocks on all sides of point, but the rock that the point is on seems to be slightly taller than the surrounding ones. It is in the middle (and slightly uphill) of 2 similarly-sized Doug-firs (~90cm DBH).

Travel_notes: After the first ~30m of moderate vine maple and other shrub, your life is going to get much easier for the remainder of the transect. Open forest with very light understory until NN05.
Location_desc: Point is ~10m W of a small, dry, bouldery streambed. There are a lot of boulders around, so feature isn't a particularly good one, but see photo. Pretty open understory right at point.

Travel_notes: Walk initially through relatively open forest, then go through thick vine maple again for ~50m. The remainder is on-and-off shrubbiness, but not very dense.
Location_desc: Point is on top of a mossy boulder just upslope of cedar feature. It is ~2m W of a hollowed-out downed tree. Open forest.

Travel_notes: Walk down slope, which turns to a steeper slope down to the river.
Location_desc: Flat area with large western red cedars with dbh greater than 120cm , right before river. Point is just East of large (dbh=170cm) Red Cedar, boulder feature is hidden behind cedar at point.

Travel_notes: Follow along river's edge 200m
Location_desc: Next to the river's edge, surrounded by large western red cedars.

Travel_notes: Follow along rivers edge and go around river eddy.
Location_desc: Point on edge just before terrain drops steeply down to river. On the other side of the river, there is a large rock wall with a horizontal crack running across it 2/3 of the way up. Boulders surrounding point.

Travel_notes: Go around rock face on the right hand side.
Location_desc: Surrounded by dense habitat of vine maple, dogwood, and red alder. Point is on washing machine sized boulder surrounded by hazelnut, willow and vine maple shrub

Travel_notes: Travel through thick vine maple until second boulder field, then habitat is more open.
Location_desc: Point located on West side of creek bad on a moss/lichen covered rock slope. Surrounded by hazelnut, douglas mapel, willow and doug fir. The point is perched up above the creeks gulch.

Travel_notes: Hike or crawl or swim through thick maple understory and across a few small drainages until you reach a DOFI grove which also unfortunately has a thick maple vine understory.
Location_desc: Point is in DOFI grove with thick vine maple understory.

Travel_notes: Walk 2 miles on Little Beaver Creek trail, it takes about 1 hr from Little Beaver campground. Be prepared for some intense vine maple on NN arm. Did this transect as part of Big Beaver trip in 2015. Either do that or arrange a ride with Hozomeen rangers or with the Resources boat. Aren't shrubby transects supposed to be birdy??
Location_desc: On trail next to western red cedar 100 cm dbh with a bulbous base.

Travel_notes: Due S from TO through thick douglas fir deciduous forest. Cross one stream, then head into open douglas fir, pondorosa pine forest
Location_desc: Point is just south of trail in open Douglas fir/Ponderosa pine forest.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is in open douglas fir/Ponderosa pine forest next to trail. Stehekin river and road are to the S. Point is on large pile of wood debris with a cut log at east end nearly hanging over the trail.

Travel_notes: First part in open douglas fir/ponderosa pine forest, second part through thick marshy creek vegetation. (Might be mostly easly accessed by road. Then cutting into thick vegetation).
Location_desc: Point is in the middle of a boggy, marshy creek,on a log crossing it.

Travel_notes: Take the road E until it passes the creek and curves away from the river. Then cut up into open Doug-fir forest to point.
Location_desc: Point is in flat open area of Douglas fir forest. Large rocks are scattered around forest floor. Stehekin River is visible at about 180 degrees.

Travel_notes: Walk on trail for ~200m until you reach a large boulder on S side of trail (just before sign). When you're near boulder, veer off-trail N for ~50m to point.
Location_desc: Point is ~3.5m S of a ~8' tall boulder. There are many other boulders in the area. Low shrub right at point and taller shrub ~10m to the S. There is an oceanspray shrub immediately to the E of point.

Travel_notes: Pretty easy travel through open Doug-fir forest, passing several huge boulders immediately after leaving SS05.
Location_desc: Point is at a ~70cm DBH Doug-fir that has been cut at about hip-height. Moderate (but low) shrub right at point, more than in much of the immediately surrounding area. It is ~4m upslope of a large downed tree.

Travel_notes: Travel through moderate to thick shrub the entire way. Not as slow as it could be.
Location_desc: Point is on a bunch of rocks with a lot of Bigleaf maple surrounding it. It is a less dense area than most areas immediately surrounding point.

Travel_notes: Travel through moderate shrub most of the way. Staying slightly S of bearing will help avoid the worst of it. At ~170m, you will cross a creek. Climb up W bank and walk ~23m uphill from there to point.
Location_desc: Point is located in an area with Bigleaf maple saplings, much less dense (and much shorter) than surrounding older Bigleaf maples. About 2m S of point is a row of large rocks. The point is ~23m E of creek.

Travel_notes: TO is 15 min from Bullion CG. Travel over 3 creeks with little fall. It's 180m from last creek crossing. SS arm through marshy creek, birdy! Trail showed on map not representative of reality. TO is 50m south of planned location. We camped at Bullion CG which can be accessed from the road about 1mile before High bridge RS. However the CG is not well marked from road. If being dropped at High Bridge RS hike the trail to Coon Lake. Take a turn on Cascade Corral Trail, follow it until you reach sign for Bullion CG. Coming from Harlequin drive 15 min uproad. There is a dirt 2 track on the N side of the road with a small wooden  "loop" sign. Hike up trail ~290m and bushwack the 100m to the Northern trail where the TO is located
travel on trail
Location_desc: Point on trail at the end of a relatively flat section, just before going down.

Travel_notes: Travel 235m on trail
Location_desc: Point is next to a root ball with little boulders stuck in it. Just before the creek that flows on the trail. Point is 2m before the creek turns and leaves the trail.

Travel_notes: Walk on trail 215m and keep right at the fork. You'll reach a 3.5m tall 90cm dbh clean cut doug fir stump on the N side of the trail. When you get there, the marker tree is ~30m away at 170 deg
Location_desc: Point is in burned douglas fir forest with lots of downed trees surrounding the point

Travel_notes: walk on trail 200m and then go down boulderfield for 20m. Be wary of loose rocks!
Location_desc: Point is at the beginning of talus slope

Travel_notes: travel on trail 220m and then go down rock field. The dead conifer feature is conspicous from the trail
Location_desc: On talus slope. Rock wall at N and the river can be heard from the bottom of slope.

Travel_notes: scurry back up boulder field to trail and walk 225m. Pine snag feature is easy to spot from trail
Location_desc: located 10m NE of trail on mossy rock slab, multiple doug fir snags to the N. Point is just after the trail curves to the right and before it goes into the forest

Travel_notes: traverse through fairly open doug fir forest acrros moderate slope. After 170m you'll pass through some shrub (mostly rose and oceanspray).
Location_desc: point is in doug fir forest just after shrub ends. Slope leads steeply to dry drainage to the SW. You can just barely see the river to the South

Travel_notes: first 80m are down and then up dry drainage, through doug fir. After passing the trail you'll drop into a small boulder field with a cliff to the N. The point is just past this boulderfield
Location_desc: point is just past larger boulders at the W edge of boulderfield. Lichen-studded doug firs and some ponderosa pine around. To the South is a large open flat spot (good for handstands) and further West the terrain goes downhill again

Travel_notes: Go downslope toward river from WW08 and hit McGregor Peak trail; hike down trail to High Bridge guard station. Cross the bridge and at first road curve after bridge, take social trail up to the edge of the high bridge camp. Point is on social trail.
Location_desc: Point is on social trail that goes from high bridge camp down to river; it is in sight of the main road, at the edge of High Bridge camp in open DOFI forest. High Bridge campground visible 8 m away.

Travel_notes: Pace 100 m down trail.
Location_desc: On trail before stream crossing.

Travel_notes: Head uphill away from trail. Cross a flat open spot and descend to point 02. Point is just as you exit the forest and come to a clearing.
Location_desc: At edge of clearing with view of mountains (if clear). Look for marker on a subalpine fir at opposite edge of clearing from point, but not far away.

Travel_notes: Travel downhill towards point 03, at times rather steep. Descend across a couple rocky outcrops to a stream. Head up bank and down hill to point 03, at the far end of a very small avalanche chute.
Location_desc: On far edge of area where soil has slid down to bottom (avalanche chute). Next to point are many old snags running up and down the slope.

Travel_notes: Travel across slope, mostly through dense spruce. Point 04 is on the far side of a slightly wet open area with many corn lillies.
Location_desc: On the edge of an open wet area, with downed logs described in features running across slope through open spot. Lots of snags near boundary between forest to NW and open area behind it.

Travel_notes: Head across slope, pass the rocky outcrop and head back into spruce forest to point 05.
Location_desc: On hillside in Engelmann spruce forest. Just past a patch of Salix sp (willow). Features hard but view of point helpful.

Travel_notes: Walk down and across steep slope through somewhat dense spruce forest
Location_desc: in fairly open subalpine fir forest, just past the dry drainage. Point is right next to a small bushy white pine 1m tall.

Travel_notes: travel up and across moderate slope through fir/spruce forest. Halfway you begin going downhill and across fairly steep/slick terrain
Location_desc: point is on small rock in open mountain hemlock forest. Slope goes steeply to west. A downed barkless tree runs downhill 1m south. Many snags in area.

Travel_notes: Pace more than 100m on trail. Point is 14m after large flat rock in trail.
Location_desc: Point is right at hollowed out root ball of uprooted pine tree bent over downhill. Small pine branches still survive and two subalpine firs grow between fallen trees (featured). Clump of subalpine firs above trail.

Travel_notes: Travel more than 200m on trail.
Location_desc: Point is at a large flat rock in trail that spans whole width of trail. It is just before some rock steps down trail. Many subalpine firs just downhill of trail. Large rocks uphill of trail (featured) surrounded by Vaccinium.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: Point is on trail at small curve before trail continues to S-curve downhill to McAlester trail junction. Lots of downed subalpine fir around, including two downed snags (both DBH ~50cm). One is pointed right to point and one pointing at trail above point (feature).

Travel_notes: Leave trail heading SE. First 70m through mostly open meadow. Cross stream and travel through denser subalpine fir. Point is about 20m after crossing South Pass trail, across creek at edge of large meadow.
Location_desc: Point is just to SE of stream at beginning of large meadow. There are three small dead subalpine fir trees on ground at point. Lots of rocks around. Marker tree should be visible from approach on bearing.

Travel_notes: Continue SE across meadow, crossing a few more streams. Head upslope through subalpine fir. Look for two spindly dead branchless subalpine fir tops together, leaning slightly to right. This tree is NE of point.
Location_desc: Point is in a nondescript location on slope. It is next to a small (DBH 5cm) subalpine fir that is uprooted upslope, broken and pointing downhill. Lots of small subalpine firs in area: vaccinium below. Just to north and down below point, larger mostly decomposed logs are visible. Open area to NE (right now covered in snow).

Travel_notes: Climb up to trail, then walk the rest of the way to point. Point is ~20m from trail.
Location_desc: Point is on NW edge of meadow, on the edge of a bunch of heather. Immediately to the SE is a more herbaceous meadow. To the NW is Subalpine fir.

Travel_notes: Walk up to trail, then walk to ~50m (NE) of point on trail (use GPS). You could go off-trail, but less meadow trampling if you stay on.
Location_desc: Point is in between 2 lines of Subalpine firs, one upslope and one downslope of point. The one upslope just consists of 3 trees. Aside from those 3 uphill, it is all meadow upslope and to the NW.

Travel_notes: You can walk up trail for much of it. Walk up to trail through meadow, then walk on trail until you're almost at point (~8m away).
Location_desc: Point is ~7-8m upslope of trail in meadow. There are no Subalpine firs immediately surrounding point. Thicker Subalpine fir to the SE.

Travel_notes: We camped at High Camp, an 8-mile hike from Bridge Creek trailhead. From High Camp, TO is a 10-minute walk. Look for larch on right side of trail. Bring a headnet- mosquitoes are awful here, one of the worst areas in the park.
Location_desc: On trail in Engelmann spruce and subalpine fir. On west side of trail next to TO is a large (40cm DBH) Larch. Marker is behind this tree. On E side of trail is a clump of 6 subalpine firs

Travel_notes: easy travel through low salal and flat/slightly downhill terrain
Location_desc: At edge of flat area with short steep slope to the south.  Powerline road visible from point.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is on Hwy 20, 2 meter from north edge of road.

Travel_notes: Walk East on Hwy 20 205m, point is just past where large stream begins to parallel road. Point is 15m away from road on NW side, close to a tall Douglas fir with a yellow paint band.
Location_desc: Close to road in mixed forest.  Between 2 streams. Close to tall DOFI with fading yellow paint band. Sword fren in a flat area

Travel_notes: Walk along road 195m and then to point, at bottom of ditch on lefthand side.
Location_desc: At bottom of ditch right along lefthand (W) side of road.  Under powerlines.

Reason_for_change: very steep cliff if continue NE
Travel_notes: Walk out of ditch up to road, down road and back into woods to point.
Location_desc: Point is in open patch of salmonberry, surrounded by red alder and a few cedars.  Can hear road not far off.  Powerlines are also visible. Big red alder leans over point

Travel_notes: Go back onto road from the way you came and walk 200m East.
Location_desc: Point is located on N side of hwy 20 along a sheer rock face, 1m W of its corner. Located directly behind guardrail on riverside of road in some grass

Travel_notes: Continue East down road, at 120m you will see a break in the rockwall on the NW sideof the road, head straight up and across this seep slope of salal/ferns approx 25m then cut to bearing to stay above ravine. Ensure GPS tracks are on to ensure exiting the same place you entered. When exiting - look for a mossy boulder approx 25m up from the road and cut down the slope here.
Location_desc: At base of flat mossy 8ft rockwall. Between a 60dbh cedar snag and mossy minifridge sized mossy boulder. Rockwall continues East. Rockwall topped with salal and mini RERC. Powerline cut and towers visible through trees

Travel_notes: Coming W from Diablo, 1st road on right after mile marker 115.  Park at first turnoff and walk up road 130m to TO.  A 15-min drive from Diablo. park at first turnoff on left side(riverside)
Travel through mostly flat mossy forest, lots of downed trees
Location_desc: Flat spot, second growth western red cedar. To the North is a small hill with moderate to large boulders.

Travel_notes: First 150m fairly easy through mossy boulders, starts going up steep hill soon after. Be wary of cliff if approaching from SE. Many loose boulders under moss.
Location_desc: On very steep SE facing slope, in open area with Big Leaf maples, mossy boulders and abundant sword ferns. Many skinny snags directly E of point, mainly surrounded by Doug Firs.

Travel_notes: Travel downhill ~140m over mossy boulder field, watch for pitfalls! Walk on road for another 40m or so and then head towards river.
Location_desc: Point is located 5.5 m N of river in a small clearing bordered by sword fern, salmonberry, vine maple, and dogwood. Point is E of a mossy downed log 55cm dbh.

Travel_notes: Easiest travel if you walk straight back to road from WW03 and continue on road to WW04.
Location_desc: Point is on N side of road at base of large cliff face

Travel_notes: Walk along road 200m.
Location_desc: Point is on W side of road

Travel_notes: Walk along road 132m, until you reach gravel road on right hand side.  Walk up gravel road until you reach pulloff.
Location_desc: Edge of road, at junction with reach pulloff and gravel road. On N side of gravel road.

Travel_notes: Continue up gravel road. When you read fork, stay right and continue u proad going through the opening with overhead powerlines.
Location_desc: Point is located on the road on the W side of the powerlines just after 180 degree bend in the road going uphill. the point is on the E side of the road.

Travel_notes: From point 07, walk back to fork in gravel road and take the path to the SW. Follow this up to its end before walking offtrail to point.
Location_desc: Point in flat mossy area with open understory in between grown-over old road and cliff above highway 20

Travel_notes: Travel 100m N on trail from TO
Location_desc: point in closed canopy of western hemlock forest. Ground entirely coverd by moss.

Travel_notes: Travel 200m North on trail
Location_desc: Point is on trail in closed canopy western hemlock forest. 2 hemlocks (65cm and 55cm dbh) straddle the trail at point.

Travel_notes: Proceed through nearly impenetrable western hemlock and western red cedar saplings to point on very steep slope. Steep grade begins at 130m.
Location_desc: Point is in douglas fir/ western red cedar forest on steep slope. Point under a vine maple and inbetween 2 downed logs forming a V.

Travel_notes: Travel (traverse) across steep slope through older, slightly more open forest with many downed log.
Location_desc: Point is in flat area of western hemlock and some western red cedar forest (young). The edge of steep slope to W is about 5m away

Travel_notes: continue through fairly flat and open hemlock forest with scatterd downed trees. If you stay on the bearing you'll cross the trail after 90m, but you could also go straight for the trail from ne04 and just take that
Location_desc: Point is just west of 5+ tree/log pile with feature rootball on one end. Open western hemlock forest with mossy ground and lots of oregon grape. Photo of rootwad is from approaching side, not point side

Travel_notes: easy travel through open western hemlock and doug fir forest, mossy ground
Location_desc: point in open hemlock forest with scatterd doug firs, very mossy/comfortable ground. A few small vine maples just NE of point

Reason_for_change: Lightning creek impassable along original bearing
Travel_notes: Go down steep slope from NE06 and go through old growth cedar forest with open vine maple understory.
Go up steep slope and hop back on the trail for the quickest travel; cross small wooden bridge and cut off west into the forest.
Location_desc: Point is in semi-open WEHE/DOFI forest with lots of WEHE saplings on top of a ridge.

Travel_notes: Hop back on trail and go ~200 m down it, crossing small bridge. Cut off the trail and walk through a WEHE sapling forest to the edge of a clearing.
Really hard travel in impenetrable western hemlock sapling forest.
Location_desc: Point is about 10m away from one arm of Lightning ck, next to a down log that goes across the water

Travel_notes: Lots of down western red cedar to go above/under. Very slippery. The transect follows an arm of lightning ck, they both meet at 130m (a lot louder!)
Location_desc: Point just SW of Deerlick CG
