Travel_notes: First part of travel in forest, then entered a clearing with aspen, devil club and a lots of downed tree cover with debris.
Location_desc: Point is in western red cedar forest and young western hemlock. Point is on 85cm dbh log in myriad hatchwork of downed trees surrounded by devils club. Lots of western hemlock saplings to the south

Travel_notes: Go through the forest for 60m. When you reach the trail stay on it (it will save you time and you deserve it!). Cross the bridge, pass the shelter. When you reach the double western red cedar (just before switch back) go 159 degrees for 15m
Location_desc: Point is between 2 <1m dbh western red cedar and one <1m douglas fir

Travel_notes: travel on trail ~200m, turn left when you reach a 170cm dbh doug fir on the W side of trail
Location_desc: Point is 5m E of trail in open hemlock forest with scattered downed trees on moderate slope

Travel_notes: travel on trail ~200m. Feature snag/stump is on E edge of trail
Location_desc: point is 7m West of trial in open hemlock/cedar forest with many downed trees, fairly flat.

Travel_notes: travel about 200m on trail. Turn of trail right before trail starts going up after a 28m flat section
Location_desc: point is on moderate slop 7m SW of trail in hemlock forest. The feature pine is the only pine in the area and leaves large cones on the ground nearby

Travel_notes: Walk approximatly 250m north on trail from Deerlick CG (until you reach a small opening). TO is 5-10min walk from Deerlick CG. Both arms go through thick, young western hemlock. Travel is  slow and difficult. Takes about 2 hours to reach CG from Lightning Creek Trailhead.
Location_desc: TO is in slightly more open forest over the trail (less canopy cover), on a mild wide bend in the trail. Across from the TO, there is a .5 m tall decaying mound (old stump) with one remaining 1.5 m tall wooden shard sticking up out of it.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: The point is about 18 m past (NE of) where slope levels off a little. Lots of downed wood in area. If continuing NE from point, it becomes less grassy right after point.

Travel_notes: Walk uphill through open forest with low shrub understory. Just over halfway (maybe 120m? sorry I lost track of pacing), you will enter a more meadowy habitat.
Location_desc: Point is just (~3 m) below small rock outcrop in low shrub/herbaceous vegetation. There are some large Ponderosa Pines within 10 m to the E.

Travel_notes: Go uphill across slope over many downed trees. When you are ~50-55 m from the end, you will have to go slightly more E to avoid rocky outcrop.
Location_desc: In the middle of a small meadow with a great view of mtns. There is a flat, bight green field next to the Stehekin River visible from point.

Travel_notes: A countour through open burned forest. Easy walking, going below a talus field for first part.
Location_desc: It is ~55 m E of talus (end of large rock section) and ~13 m N of where slope drops off more steeply. In burned forest with mainly ceanothus and fireweed understory.

Travel_notes: Transect is mostly a countour here with a great viewpoint ~68 m into route. After crossing this, it drops down slightly and mainly contours through Doug-fir forest until you reach a meadow (point is ~3 m after leaving forest).
Location_desc: Point is about 3m W of small Doug-firs leading into forest. View of Lake Chelan. Point is right at a low-to-the-ground, small boulder with manzanita on top.

Travel_notes: Walk down open meadow habitat, becoming gradually more forested as you get near NE06. After crossing trail, you climb down a rocky area, then descend gradually through burned Doug-fir forest to point.
Location_desc: Point is in burnt forest about 26m NW of closest point on trail, about 50 m N of where it drops off, ~ 80 m SE of grassy area.

Travel_notes: Easiest way to get to NE07 is to travel on the trail the whole way; point is ~4m downslope of trail (6 switchbacks).
Location_desc: Point is ~4m downslope of trail, almost directly upslope from blackened Doug-fir snag (feature). It is just below a ceanothus bush. Beautiful view of Rainbow Creek drainage (and trail on other side), and mountains.

Travel_notes: For 190 meters, pace heading NW down the trail toward a clearing point at the edge of the woods and clearing before switchbacks.
Location_desc: On trail at the edge of forest and clearing where switchbacks start.

Travel_notes: Pace 350 meters down switchbacks on the trail.
Location_desc: On trail down slope

Travel_notes: Pace for 200 meters down the trail to the point.
Location_desc: On the trail, down slope.

Travel_notes: Pace 200 meters. Easy and beautiful hike, dogwood present.
Location_desc: On the trail, at a bend and crown of a hill.

Travel_notes: Pace 95 meters; 18 meters off trail at 65 degrees from the boulder; Head up steep slope 55 meters then follow a well-defined game trail to the point.
Location_desc: On the game trail about 15 meters before a grassy patch. 2016 note: Game trail not seen, but did not look too hard for it.

Travel_notes: Travel up a steep slope, 80 meters to top of the hill through a small riparian area (15 meters).  Travel through the dense brushy riparian area, then approximately 20 meters up a steep slope to the point.
Location_desc: Point on a well-defined game trail with a downed log.

Travel_notes: Travel up a steep slope to a riparian area, cross a dried stream bed where huge Douglas-fir is located.  From there, 30 meters to the point.
Location_desc: Flat, large square boulder at point under a small Dougla-fir. Clearing with half brush cover.

Travel_notes: Travel through fairly dense shrub for most of the way, with some sections being steep and rocky, especially near the point.
Location_desc: Point is on a rocky ledge with a big lone Douglas fir (~1.5m DBH), It is steep; nothing crazy but do be careful. Big talus slope is visible to the NW.

Travel_notes: About a 50- minute hike from Harlequin Camp (about 40 minutes from where trail meets road). A beautiful NE arm with lots of birds. First 4 points on SW arm are on trail.  Off trail points on SW arm traverse steep slopes and drop down into a riparian gully filled with dense shrub.
Location_desc: Point on trail where trail direction is N and S, on the west side of trail, there are downed logs and a bunch of rounds. It is ~1m before reaching switchback

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point located in inconspicuous spot, dense Pacific Silver Fir and Western Hemlock.  Two downed Pacific Silver Firs make an obtuse angle at point.  Two large Douglas-firs close by as well as one Doug-fir snag.

Travel_notes: Travel upslope past a series of large mossy boulders and continue up through scree field.
Location_desc: Point is located on bottom edge of small scree field with understory plants surrounding the point.

Reason_for_change: looming cliffs to the NE and E
Travel_notes: Travel downslope through a lot of dense vine maple until reaching mossy boulder field.
Location_desc: Point is located in mossy boulder field filled with White Birch and Pacific Silver Fir. Point is right at two small Douglas-firs (6cm and 18 cm DBH).

Travel_notes: Traverse slope through boulder field, over old stream washes and through relatively clear understory until coming to a large scree field at 190 meters.
Location_desc: Point is located on the western edge of large scree slope, right next to a squared off black rock and a 30 cm DBH Douglas-fir.

Travel_notes: Traverse large scree slope, navigate through dense vine maple and travel halfway across another large scree field.
Location_desc: Point is located on the east side of large scree slope.  View of edge of Ross Lake and Pumpkin Mountain Campground through trees. Point is amongst 5 medium/large douglas firs (ave ~60cm DBH). [see photo; 5th largest douglad fir is upslope from photo].

Travel_notes: Traverse moderately steep slope across the rest of the scree field and then through Vine Maple/open understory.
Location_desc: The point is located in clearing on a slope, looking down on Ross Lake.  Very little ground cover, assorted grass and moss.  The best feature is a downed log, facing SW.  The point is equidistant between two Douglas-firs, both ~50cm DBH.

Travel_notes: Lots of blowdown with some shrub.
Location_desc: Point is in a clearing with a great view of the lake and Jack Mountain.

Travel_notes: From TO, walk back down trail and over bridge. Walk between 400 and 500m along creek off-trail. Hopefully the GPS will work somewhat. Allow ~30 minutes to get there from TO.
Location_desc: Point is ~2m SE of Big Beaver Creek. There are a bunch of yew saplings surrounding the point. Beyond those to the SE is much more open forest. There are some vine maple branches overhead.

Travel_notes: After initially walking up to higher ground, the remainder of the way is flat over many downed trees and through many saplings.
Location_desc: There are two very large Douglas-firs within 10 meters of point (to the S, approximately)).  Lots of Pacific Silver Fir saplings to the N/NE (A few to the S/SW).  Mostly free of saplings and shrub right at point, though.

Travel_notes: Flat, easy walking the whole way.
Location_desc: Point is in relatively open spot with mostly vaccinium understory. Lots of saplings in all directions- a small cedar sapling's branches extend to the point. Enclosed in a circle of downed trees (~7m radius).

Travel_notes: Travel is relatively flat for 1st ~100m, at which point it starts going up more steeply for the remainder.
Location_desc: Point is on a mossy downed tree running approximately N-S (between NE-SW and N-S). It is high enough so I am sitting on it without my feet touching the ground. There are many short Douglas-fir snags near point. It is in a slightly more level spot in otherwise upslope terrain.

Travel_notes: Walk up gradual slope initially. The last two ~50 m gets much steeper.  Transect goes along a small, dry drainage during the gradual slope part.
Location_desc: Point is between 2 diagonally-growing yews. There are about 20,000 mosquitoes around me right now.  Feature finding is rough.  It is about 1 meter upslope of a ~45 cm DBH Doug-fir.

Travel_notes: Walk up pretty steep, mossy slope the entire way to SW06. Right at the end, it gets slightly less steep.
Location_desc: Point is in a small opening in the forest, covered in moss. It is right next to a small Red Huckleberry bush and ~2m downslope of a ~80cm DBH Doug-fir.

Travel_notes: Easy travel, traversing along the slope for first ~100 m. Understory becomes dense for final ~90 m to point.
Location_desc: Point located on downed log, right next to stump, which stands at 1.5 m tall in 2016.

Travel_notes: TO is about a 10-minute walk up Big Beaver Trail from Pumpkin Mountain Camp.  Note that the SW arm starts on the opposite side of creek from TO (must cross bridge).  It is slightlty more than 100m between TO and SW01. A head net is HIGHLY RECOMMENDED due to extreme mosquito situation. Beware. Definitely camp at the awesome campsites down by the water if you can!
Location_desc: Located right before water bar on trail.

Travel_notes: Walk ~100m on trail to point.
Location_desc: On trail, just before steep snowfield (2016). If it seems too slick, we recommend going down and around this after this point.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On trail, in rockfield overlooking Rainbow Lake.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On trail, in open area overlooking Rainbow Lake.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Right after clearing/ snowfield.

Travel_notes: Off-trail, directions 227 degrees (SW) to get off-trail.
Location_desc: Close to Rainbow Lake in subalpine fir forest and slide alder, near a group of small mountain hemlocks.

Travel_notes: Travel through campground to get to the point.
Location_desc: Point is at a spot with an amazing view, near a rock face.

Travel_notes: Get back on trail, then jump off near point, and head upslope for about 20m.
Location_desc: Point is in a meadow.

Travel_notes: Get back on trail, then jump upslope when near point.
Location_desc: Point is in a meadow (not in the slide alder) 15m above trail.

Travel_notes: Get back on trail.
Location_desc: Point is on trail- only way to continue surveying due to steepness. Directly above switchback city.

Travel_notes: Only SE arm surveyable in 2016- too much steep snow/ice on NW arm (on a north-facing slope). Had to skirt 2 steep snowfields on way to TO, which delayed us by ~20 minutes. Could not reach TO.
Location_notes: The TO for this transect had to be offset (in 2016) by ~900m because the target TO (and anything N of there) could not be accessed. The TO was not established during this first visit, when the rest of the transect was established.

Travel_notes: Travel up steep, wet, mossy rocks and continue through open Douglas-fir/ Lodgepole Pine forest.
Location_desc: The point is right past marker, next to a rotting Douglas-fir stump, 1 meter high.  Many skinny Lodgepole Pines and Douglas-firs in surrounding area.  Open shrub-filled area 10 m directly east of point.

Travel_notes: Travel upslope from NE01 and traverse across flat, moss-covered bedrock with a good view.  Drop back into Lodgepole Pine forest and continue to point.
Location_desc: Point is nondescript.  In mixed Douglas-fir and Lodgepole Pine forest located in a small runoff area just after mossy groundcover ends.

Travel_notes: Continue travel through relatively clear understory.  Soon you will enter dark and gloomy dense Western Red Cedar forest. Do not despair as the travel is quick and soon opens up into a mixed Douglas-fir/Vine Maple forest.
Location_desc: Located on a fallen, barkless log on a crest of small hill.

Travel_notes: Travel NW, entering mossy talus at 65 meters.  Exit the talus among large boulders and continue on easy ground.
Location_desc: Point in open understory with spiky groundcover.  Many birches in the area.  Point is on the NE side of a level area, just where the rocky slope begins.  Beware of precarious snag right above the point.  May have fallen by next visit.

Travel_notes: Walk on level terrain. Traverse the steep slope, pass another ditch and arrive at the point.
Location_desc: Point located on a slope leading to lake, among vine maple and prickly groundcover.  Smaller silver firs and larger Douglas-firs.

Travel_notes: Travel at NW bearing, and hit the trail at approximately 50 meters.  Travel north down trail for approximately 150 meters.
Location_desc: Point located in an open, rocky area up and down slope of trail.   Smaller rock cluster on right side of trail just before entering denser forest again. Open view of Ross Lake to the west.

Travel_notes: Pace 200 meters N/NW along the trail.
Location_desc: Point located on trail between two trail drains, open to the NE side of the trail in a patch of smaller Douglas-fir snags.  Many fallen logs in the area.

Travel_notes: Continue on trail.
Location_desc: Next to a rocky clearing on the right and a 40 cm DBH Douglas fir on the left.

Travel_notes: Continue on trail.
Location_desc: Right where trail to the stock camp comes up, point is located next to the stock camp sign.

Travel_notes: On trail; cross bridge and keep right at Hozomeen sign.
From TO, walk down through dark forest. You will be just SE of a dry inlet for last ~25 m.
Location_desc: Point is in open Lodgepole Pine forest with lots of cedar saplings. It is ~15m S/SE of edge of bank dropping down to dry inlet. Look for marker - it is open here, but all of the trees look the same or similar.

Travel_notes: Travel flat until the last 10 meters. Walk between two sets of mossy boulders and over downed logs, 10 meters upslope.
Location_desc: Travel through dense lodgepole pine (surrounding SW01) and enter into thicker Douglas-fir and Western Red Cedar stand.  Travel is all flat, until last 10 meters it slopes up.  Point located 10 meters upslope from the forest floor overlooking mossy boulders.  Deciduous shrubs upslope from point.

Travel_notes: Walk through dark and dreary forest (contouring/going slightly uphill) for most of the way. The last ~25m opens up more for the remainder.
Location_desc: Point is in a more open canopy area - very green after exiting very dark, Blair Witch-esque forest. Lots of low shrub. There are about 5 snags (~15-25cm dbh) within 10m NW of point. There is a lot of mossy rock above point. It is on the SE side of a ~30cm dbh downed tree. It is ~10-12m below trail.

Travel_notes: Cross trail 3 times. Go upslope from SW04, cross trail and climb mossy boulders and enter dark, thick cedar forest at 100 meters.  Travel through and emerge into light again.  Cross the trail twice (on a bend) and just east of trail  (3 meters away).
Location_desc: Three meters off the trail under small Douglas-fir canopy.

Travel_notes: The best (and only safe way) is to walk on the trail until you cross creek on footbridge, then veer upslope ~90m to the point.
Location_desc: Point is less than a meter upslope of a willow-like shrub (and slightly to the NE). Mostly Lodgepole and Douglas-firs near point. It is on a fairly level spot (downslope and upslope are both at more of a slope).

Travel_notes: Continue to travel upslope from SW05 through relatively open Douglas-fir forest, crossing the clearing and re-entering the forest at 100 meters.  Continue upslope to point.
Location_desc: Point located on a moss-covered rock, on a moderate slope.  Fallen logs (2 Douglas-firs and a white birch) create 3 sides of a square around the point.  Douglas-fir forest with many white birches and scattered cedars.

Travel_notes: Walk gradually uphill the whole way. You will approach a small gully near the end - point is ~6m from bottom of this.
Location_desc: Point is on N side of a small gully, ~6m from bottom.  It is at the base (N side) of a ~75cm dbh Doug-fir. Oregon Grape is the dominant groundcover.

Travel_notes: Continue up gradual slope. Easiest to travel SW of vine maple stand and directly upslope to point once past stand.
Location_desc: Located in fairly open area, 1 meter upslope from ~70cm DBH Douglas Fir with ~7cm DBH birch next to it. Patch of vine maple to the west, young Oregon Grape mixed with Douglas Fir needles at point.

Travel_notes: About a 13-minute walk from Lodgepole Camp (no trail access from Dry Creek or Ponderosa). Lodgepole is about a 15-mile hike up the East Bank Trail. The TO is 27m after a 90 degree bend in the trail with large, moss-covered boulders.
Location_desc: Point is located right next to a small (18cm DBH) cedar growing out of a rock, 1m past a dry, rocky stream bed that comes downslope from the east and crosses the trail.  There are larger moss-covered rocks upslope, east of the point.

Travel_notes: Easy travel from TO along the road
Location_desc: Along the road directly in front of a small building with silver tin roof, before ranger residence and driveway.

Travel_notes: Travel along trail from trailhead near NE01 to the large, wet mossy rock by the point.
Location_desc: Point is by a large dead log that is about 10 meters E of the sharp trail switchback. Large, wet, mossy rock is obvious beside the point. Mid-sized Big-leaf maple is right beside it.

Reason_for_change: impassable rock face at NE bearing
Travel_notes: Follow NE02 until the correcet northing, then exit right from the trail.
Location_desc: Point is just E of the McGregor mountain trail by about 20 meters. At the base of a steep slope, lots of ferns and vine maple nearby. Note: I can't figure out what happened here (why observer went at a 6 degree bearing, etc.). Please verify that the bearing, directions, and coordinates are all correct next visit.

Travel_notes: Travel up steep slope across the rise of a meadow.
Location_desc: Point is on a large mound of dirt/stumps/rocks just a few meters E of the meadow.

Travel_notes: Short, but fairly steep slope about 40 m from NE04. Pretty level travel after that.
Location_desc: Point is located on eastern side of rocky meadow.  Snow-capped peaks visible on three sides.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is in open coniferous forest with low understory, many downed trees and branches around point

Travel_notes: Easy travel until it gets steeper as you drop down to the creek.
Location_desc: Point is just across the creek, next to a gurgling section. Lots of devil's club. It's at the end of a big downed log that crosses the creek. There's also a big root wad in the creek ~10m away.

Travel_notes: Travel is mostly through ferns and over a few logs.
Location_desc: Point is on a rock next to a ~60cm dbh douglas fir in open forest. Cliffs start rising up to the northeast.

Travel_notes: Easy travel through short understory.
Location_desc: Point is in open forest with douglas firs and smallish big-leaf maples. Camera died, sorry for lack of photos; they would have been helpful here.

Travel_notes: Walk W along Stehekin Valley Rd. until the correct northing, just before curve in the road to the right, exit road to right  (E) for about 12m point on E side of woodpile.
Location_desc: Point just to the E of stick and branches pile about 10 m off Stehekin Valley Rd. Very large Douglas-fir visible 12 m to the E. In moderate vine maple and dogwood.

Travel_notes: Climb very steep and thickly vegetated slope SW from the road. Travel slow and full of downed wood.
Location_desc: Point is on a steep slope in the middle of very dense dogwood and small mixed deciduous trees.

Travel_notes: Continue up steep, vegetated slope.  About 120 m along, you will hit the tall conifer forest, with less understory. Continue SW through this until you get to a clearing with dense shrub.
Location_desc: Point is in clearing containing dense shrub (mainly ceanothus), surrounded by conifers.  No real conspicuous features, but you will be standing in a shrub, about 5m out of the conifers you came from.

Travel_notes: Cross brush/shrub clearing and back into conifer forest. Continue SW through very dense alder shrub in sparse conifer forest. Come to the top of a steep downward slope about 160m in. Go across this slope to the SW until you reach the point.
Location_desc: Point is one a fallen conifer (hemlock?) with a large root wad upslope from point.  Downslope there is a large clump of rocks and roots visible from the point.  Point is in a mixed Douglas-fir/Hemlock forest with a lot of fallen trees in the area. Bigleaf maple branches extend over point from upslope. There is a cluster of several Bigleaf maples just upslope of rootwad feature.

Travel_notes: Travel through more dense shrub understory with lots of fallen trees, but less slope than before. It is ~275 meters from previous point. Cross trail at ~225 meters.
Location_desc: Point is a small gully, ~2.5 meters down slope from a downed tree.

Travel_notes: Walk back up to trail, then go up trail until you are close (use GPS.) Walk ~55 meters down from trail.
Location_desc: On a downed tree with cedar saplings and rose surrounding it. There is a lot of vine maple immediately upslope of point. Immediately "past" (upslope) end of downed tree point is on are four large-ish Doug-firs.

Travel_notes: Go back up to trail and walk up trail until you reach a ~90cm DBH Doug-fir on right (north) side of trail. Walk ~20 meters to point from there.
Location_desc: In between ceanothus and ocean spray bushes. About 4 meters to the northeast is an area that has less shrubby groundcover.

Travel_notes: Camped at High Bridge Campground, a 5 minute walk to the TO. Note that direction of travel for NE arm is not a semi-cardinal direction for several points.
Location_desc: along road, 7 meters before the bridge.

Travel_notes: Travel up slope toward forest edge.
Location_desc: Next to stream. Located on edge of Pacific silver fir forest and thick stand of slide alder.

Travel_notes: Cross stream and head up steep slope. It's a leg burner.
Location_desc: Point is on boulder / rock edge of forest, use GPS to find point. Great view.

Travel_notes: continue up slope
Location_desc: small clearing, no distinctive features can be seen, use GPS.

Travel_notes: continue up steep slope
Location_desc: no distinctive features, use GPS.

Travel_notes: Continue up slope to rocky clearing and continue for 100m
Location_desc: point is in a rocky clearing.

Travel_notes: Continue up slope through clearing. Once the ridge starts to become close, veer towards ridge.
Location_desc: On ridge between two clearings, use GPS to find exact point.

Travel_notes: Travel SW on easy downslope, many wet large logs to climb over. Wear rain pants.
Location_desc: On small, dead Pacific Silver Fir log (~15cm DBH), on the edge of a patch of Pacific Silver Fir saplings.

Travel_notes: cross small stream and continue to slight up slope ridge 3 m tall.
Location_desc: point on small 3m ridge.

Travel_notes: Hike south through swampy area to large 6 tree blow down and veer towards river.
Location_desc: At point large downed silver fir with the direction of W to E pointing at river. Point is on N side of downed log 2m to elevated end. QA note: the distance and bearing for the massive spruce may be incorrect. Please update if needed.

Travel_notes: Multiple stream crossings for first 50m.
Location_desc: On small hill with small clearing.

Travel_notes: Travel is up slope
Location_desc: none

Travel_notes: continue up slope
Location_desc: Point is at a 1m tall stump with a silver fir (dbh 75cm) to the W and one silver fir/ one spruce to the E whose DBHs are 25cm and 40cm, respectively. QA note: the distance for the big root wad feature might be incorrect. Update this next visit if needed.

Travel_notes: Continue 200m upslope.
Location_desc: Point is next to a small avalanche chute (~3m away), and at a 2m snag with the rest of the tree partially attached.

Travel_notes: Camped at McAlester Lake Camp (~35 min hike to TO). Trail is off on map (it seems like switchbacks have been added recently) so coordinates on TO establishment form are correct. NE arm very steep, lots of elevation gain. SW more mellow but tough travel when wet.
Location_desc: Point is 30 m on trail into the forest from the edge. Trails have been re-routed since the point was initially plotted so it seems that the easting and northing are not correct on the transect map.

Travel_notes: Walk up trail, passing 8 switchbacks from TO. NE01 is ~15m past 8th one, ~3m before reaching 9th.
Location_desc: Point is ~3m down trail from 9th switchback after leaving TO. The cluster of hemlock features is directly upslope of point. Very open- mostly heather and other low shrub.

Travel_notes: Walk up trail until you reach flat section of trail- use features and description from there.
Location_desc: Point is on relatively flat section of trail, between a ~1m tall bouldery spot on both sides of trail. There is a cluster of snags on the W side of the trail, right at the edge of dropoff.

Travel_notes: I forgot to count switchbacks, but there are many- steep uphill on trail.
Location_desc: Point is on a fairly straight (but not flat) section of trail- there are two hemlock saplings on "left" (W) side of trail right at point, and just below point, a bunch more hemlock saplings on opposite side of trail.

Travel_notes: Walk up trail until you reach lookout- obvious location.
Location_desc: Point is very close to the lookout- should be easy to find.

Travel_notes: Walk down trail to point. All open and it curves some, so you'll have to pace a bit more than 200m.
Location_desc: Point is ~6m after veering from Chilliwack side (where cluster of yellow cedars are). Beautiful point filled with pipits and very little else!

Travel_notes: Walk across/down a boulder field. With or without snow.
Location_desc: All open here- rock and snow. Steeper rock immediately to the N/NE and to the SE. Use GPS!

Reason_for_change: Steep snow with boulder field runout
Travel_notes: Walk across boulders of varying sizes, and snow.
Location_desc: In a steeper rock section- all open here. Difficult to describe- look for features.

Reason_for_change: steep snow with bad rocky runout
Travel_notes: Walk across huge boulders/snow the entire time- it's a bit steep at times.
Location_desc: You can just barely see the top of lookout from point. Very open- rock/snow. About 20m down from ridge.

Travel_notes: Head northwest from TO over rocky ground and low vegetation.
Location_desc: Point is on a small outcropping of rock in an open area.

Travel_notes: Looks too steep to go directly NW to point NW02 - head back to trail and continue downslope until terrain levels off, then go towards point.
Location_desc: Point is on the edge of an area that begins to slope steeply downward. 2m from a dry (2016) streambed, and 3m from a 1.5m tall pine.

Travel_notes: A bit difficult to reach. Head west over a hill over slippery heather, then south until you can more easily access the rocky valley below (this might not be possible in a heavy snow year, use discretion). Then head ~15 steeply upslope to point.
Location_desc: Point is on a steep slope at a cluster of rocks amoungst the heather, with mountain hemlocks growing on top. Lots of young mountain hemlocks around. Remnants of an old log 10m to the south.

Travel_notes: Return down to rocky "valley" and continue upslope, south, to point.
Location_desc: Point is on a moderately steep open hillside with mountain ash and mountain hemlocks. A small tarn is visible below (in 2016).

Travel_notes: Sideslope travel, mostly open as you contour around hill, heading SW to avoid trail.
Location_desc: Nice views from this point. Situated in an open meadow with forest and a rocky patch upslope.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is in an open area near a line of trees and a steep slope.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is on the SW edge of a heather meadow and is surrounded by young mountain hemlocks, ~2-6m tall.

Travel_notes: Fairly quick travel downslope with a couple of steeper, more thickly vegetated sections.
Location_desc: Point is amongst heather and near many mountain helock saplings. Difficult to find good features. The two subalpine firs are in a cluster with similarly-sized hemlocks. Yellow cedar seedling is amonst a group of 2-3m tall hemlocks with a taller 4m hemlock as well.

Travel_notes: About a 16-minute hike down trail from Lookout, where we stayed. If there is a lot of snow when visiting, you probably want trekking polesor an ice axe. Located after a series of switchbacks. Bring headnets.
Location_desc: TO is at an open, straight section of trail, 8.8m before a microwave-sized boulder on the right (upper) side of the trail.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On trail at massive charred Doug-fir (on south side of trail).

Travel_notes: Pace 200 m to rocky, grassy clearing and continue to pace about 35 m to point
Location_desc: Point is at turn of switchback with a large boulder

Travel_notes: Pace about 250-275 m from previous point
Location_desc: none

Travel_notes: Hike up trail past turn in switchback, pacing approximately 500 m
Location_desc: Point is on the North edge of exposed rock outcrop that covers 20 m of the trail

Travel_notes: Point is far up the trail (pace 400+ m and find point with GPS)
Location_desc: Point is under green forested area, less burned trees

Travel_notes: Pace 230 m on trail
Location_desc: Point is 20 m before rock creek bed crosses the trail

Travel_notes: Travel to turn in switchback. Head due North toward boulder field and travel across boulders for 50 m to point
Location_desc: Edge of boulder field and beginning of larches. Point is on one of the largest boulders at the edge.

Travel_notes: Go back to trail after leaving NE07, then walk up trail to NE08 (at a switchback).
Location_desc: Located at swithback with nice view of sparsely vegetated drainage below. A flat rock sits at the edge of the trail.

Travel_notes: Continue up trail toward Purple Pass.
Location_desc: Point is about 75m before reaching final swithchback to Purple Pass. Next to large boulder (2m x 3m) on the east side of trail. There are two whitebark pines joined at base ~5m up trail on east side of trail.

Travel_notes: Pace 215 m down switchbacks on trail
Location_desc: Point is before the second turn/switchback from T.O., next to Doug-fir with bright green lichen.

Travel_notes: Continue down switchback arm, SW02 is at the next turn
Location_desc: Located at the end of switchback with a large rock outcrop 2 m off the trail

Travel_notes: Continue down switchback past next turn, pacing about 600 m
Location_desc: To the west you can see a clear open hillside with burned snags

Travel_notes: Continue down trail, pacing 240 m
Location_desc: Point on section of trail heading East to West, vegetation is lower to the ground. Area is grassy and open

Travel_notes: Continue down trail pacing 450 m
Location_desc: Hazard Creek can be seen

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Trail runs East to West through a grassy opening with scattered rock

Travel_notes: Climb steep grassy slope to the crest, then contour the slope for 100 m. Travel for the last 20 m over rock outcrop
Location_desc: On top of rock outcrop, no marker installed but small rock cairn constructed

Travel_notes: Continue on trail.
Location_desc: Point is on trail next to a squat douglas fir that splits into three trunks 1m off the ground (trifurcated Douglas fir feature).

Travel_notes: Continue on trail.
Location_desc: Point is overlooking Lake Chelan, next to a 30cm dbh dead Douglas fir less than 1m downslope of trail.

Travel_notes: Coming down from Purple Pass, T.O. is on switchback headed downhill and north.  About a 50 minute hike down Purple Pass Trail from Juanita Lake.  SW01-06 and NE01-06 on trail. Terrain too steep and cliffy to attempt another off-trail point after NE07 (and SW07), so backtrack to trail, then do remaining points on trail.
from rainbow point campground, turn south and walk on trail.
Location_desc: point in stand of Doug Fir with understory of vine maple.  Several large snags 20-30m north of point.  Pair of rotting stumps right next to point on W side of trail.

Travel_notes: travel 200m down trail
Location_desc: point in a stand of moss-laden Doug fir with vine maple present.

Travel_notes: walk 200m on trail, the path will travel close to the waters edge for the last 80m
Location_desc: none

Travel_notes: Walk 200 m along trail.
Location_desc: large rootball just off west edge of trail at point.  Dominant stand of Doug-fir with vine maple understory.

Travel_notes: Walk 200 m along trail.
Location_desc: point located next to large DOFI on trail. There is a sharp drop off to the lake. The feature DOFI log is cut along the trail.

Travel_notes: Walk 200 m along trail.
Location_desc: several fallen red alders within 5m of point

Travel_notes: Walk 200 m along trail.
Location_desc: none

Travel_notes: walk 200m along trail, cross small stream at 80 m then walk upslope along exposed hillside.
Location_desc: On sloped trail surrounded by Doug-fir, hillside eroding onto trail.

Travel_notes: travel along trail 200m, path slopes downhill
Location_desc: point is in a stand of Doug Fir on the waters edge, good view of peaks from 220 to 230 degrees.

Travel_notes: walk 200m along trail. Large mass of driftwood on waters edge at 85 to 100 meters.
Location_desc: There is a conspicuous waterfall draining into ross lake on the west side at a bearing of 293.

Travel_notes: walk 200m along trail
Location_desc: there is a line of 5 red alders perpendicular to trail at 2 m from the point. Point just before entering area with dense canopy.

Travel_notes: walk along trail 200m amid lots of paper birch red alder and doug fir.
Location_desc: point is in a mixed stand of mostly doug fir and paper birch with an oregon grape understory

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: there is a 2.5cm wide piece of rebar in side of cliff exactly at the point.  Trail is almost at waters edge, <3m.

Travel_notes: travel 200m on trail alongside cliff face.  cliff overhangs over trail halfway.
Location_desc: point is about 10m from edge of water, there is a rockface to the east with a sprawling vine maple and a conspicuous doug fir 180cm dbh near the top of the rocky area.  Doug-fir is 10m away.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is in Doug-fir forest with bigleaf maple, vine maple mid story, oregon grape understory. IT is ~15m before trail bends to the "right" (SW).

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: point in Doug-fir forest, vine maple understory, with some paper birch.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: point in Doug-fir forest on trail, under vine maples.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: on trail in Doug-fir forest with vine maple mid-story. There is a vine maple on E side of trail that extends over point/trail

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: point is in flat area with Doug-fir/Cedar forest, ~30m beyond a small gully.  Vine maple mid story, oregon grape understory. To the South of point, there are mostly smaller Doug-fir trees and saplings. To the North, the Doug-firs are much larger.

Travel_notes: Rocky outcrop after 150m, travel is mostly uphill, some steep.
Location_desc: Point is near base of a slope after rocky outcrop in Doug-fir forest with sparse mid/understory.  Point is about 30m after last rock outcrop.

Travel_notes: Pretty easy walking. After crossing a gully, walk ~14m to point.
Location_desc: Point is ~14m E of a small gully (filled with vine maple). It is below the branches of a ~30cm DBH leaning Doug-fir (leaning out from a ~75cm DBH Doug-fir).

Travel_notes: Easy travel. Cross 2 small gullies. Point is ~6m past 2nd gully.
Location_desc: Point is ~6m NE of bottom of small gully. The cedar on the NE side of gully is fairly prominent if approaching from correct bearing, but beware- there are other, similar-sized cedars in area. This one is ~3m from bottom of gully.

Travel_notes: Map shows campground at the wrong spot, the TO is south of the campground about 200m away on the trail. TO is about a 4-minute walk from the Rainbow Point Campground. Rainbow Point is ~9 miles from the East Bank Trailhead, Sandals recommended for crossing Roland Creek. GPS seems iffy here; use features and pacing as much as possible.
Location_desc: The point is in a stand of Doug-fir with vine maple understory

Travel_notes: Travel NW from LaPush Rd., Third Beach trailhead parking lot on the west side.  Try to follow 348 degree bearing.
Location_desc: A large marshy area with lots of skunk cabbage. At top of large, decaying, mossy root wad in marshy area. There is a lot of Salal and False azalea just below root wad as well as many downed trees leading down from wad. Most of skunk cabbage is to SW of point. There is another root wad ~10m to the S. Go past small ditch with skunk cabbage and shrub to get to root wad point is on.

Travel_notes: The route goes through a primarily Western hemlock forest over many downed trees with thick salal understory throughout much of it.
Location_desc: There are a number of large trees (Sitka spruce, western hemlock). In relatively open Western hemlock/Sitka spruce forest. Point is about 2 m SW of big, high root system of 4 hemlocks. The 4 hemlocks are next to (N of) 2 Sitka spruces (~60cm and ~100cm DBH).

Travel_notes: The route is relatively flat, going through hemlock habitat with a lot of understory.
Location_desc: The point is in primarily hemlock forest. There is a stand of Red Alders toward the creek, which is just below (about 30 m). Skunk cabbage is visible ~15-20m to the N/NE.

Travel_notes: The route is undulating through shrub and Western hemlock forest.  After first muddy, marshy stream crossing, it is open and easy walking until about 150 m, at which point it gets shrubby and marshy for last 50 m or so.
Location_desc: The point is at the base of a mossy, decaying stump. There are a lot of ferns, roots, and shrubs (vaccinium and salal, in particular), surrounded by Western hemlock forest. 2012- There seems to be some sort of staked survey trail just N of point.

Travel_notes: Thick riparian shrubs for first 70-100 m, fading into Mixed conifer forest with shrubby understory.
Location_desc: In thick salal and sword fern among mistletoe damaged Western Hemlock, 10 m short of slope down to small creek (may be off from original). In edge of blow down area, slightly clearer but still shrubby. 2020-"side sprouting split leader hemlock" feature is now a snag w/ baby hemlock growing out of branch platform. The snag has many bracket fungus growths - still recognizable from the photo.

Travel_notes: At ~10m, transect goes down slope to skunk cabbagey, muddy area for ~25 m. It then goes up gradually and then the remaining ~150 m are pretty flat through hemlock and spruce forest with thick salal understory for much of it. At ~175m, there will be a large nurse stump with 2 hemlocks, a complex root system, and other wood mayhem. It is less densely vegetated if you walk to the left of this. From there, it is about 25 m to point.
Location_desc: Point is on a downed tree (not fully on the ground- at ~45 degree angle)- in fact, it may still be rooted in the ground- but I can't figure out what is going on with it (see photo). In sparse salal with a few skunk cabbage plants to the NE/E.

Travel_notes: Travel through thick salal and some salmonberry. Flat forest that becomes more open closer to NW07.
Location_desc: Point is in between two mid-to-small downed trees in relatively open area. If one continues too far following bearing, one would begin a steep descent into drainage. There are  many snags of varying heights but <20m around, and also a lot of blowdown on ground.

Travel_notes: Lots of shrubs, through salal and into false azalea. Look for a large Sitka spruce on the edge of a clearing. The point is on the east side of the clearing.
Location_desc: The point is in a patch of false azalea with lots of skunk cabbage. On the northern edge of a clearing created by fallen trees. 2008: Much of the false azalea previously mentioned is buried. The clearing is full of blowdown, bent alders, and salal.  Marker, however, is extant. Point is actually on the feature downed hemlock. 2014: The rootball in features is now so covered in salal, it is no longer identifiable as a root wad.

Travel_notes: Travel is easy between points.
Location_desc: The point is located just N of a creek that runs W-E. It is on on edge of a triangle of rotted out snags/stumps. The one listed as feature has a small hemlock growing from it. point is closest to the snag closest to the creek (2014).

Travel_notes: Cross the creek and the trail through a riparian area to a large Sitka spruce. Distance between SE02 and SE03 is closer to 250 m.
Location_desc: Large Sitka spruce tree growing out of mounds of debris. There are several Sitka spruces to the W and Western hemlock to the N and E. Large Sitka spruce growing from a mound of debris in a mostly Western hemlock forest. There is now a downed tree between the spruce and snag (with lots of branches on it still). There is a lot of salal to the N, not as much to the S (on the other side of the downed tree (2014)

Travel_notes: Cross Third Beach Trail down a riparian ditch up to some large stumps in Western hemlock forest. Cross another creek and travel 20 m to a large root wad. Distance from SE03 is 245 m.
Location_desc: Just beyond the drainage, up the hill, there is a large root wad. The point is just N of the root, between a large patch of salmonberry extending east and various rootballs and hemlocks on the slope.  Look for an awesomely curved Western hemlock (reaching like vine maple). 2018- Remove snag feature, mostly fallen now.

Travel_notes: Easy trail- nice walking through Western hemlock forest with Sword fern understory. Some vaccinium along the way too.
Location_desc: The point is located between 2 large Sitka spruce trees (~80-90cm DBH) that are right next to each other W-E about 3 m apart. Remove photo. There is a decayed snag on other side of the non-feature spruce of the 2 spruces (2014).

Travel_notes: Flat, not too bad travel until you reach drop (maybe ~90m in?)- at that point, good luck. Mostly a slog through salmonberry that has never before seen an elk. Look for spruce feature whenever you can see above your head- it is very obvious.
Location_desc: Point is surrounded by above-head-high salmonberry. There are a couple of downed trees nearby that you can stand on to try to see above it, but you're definitely in deep here. You can at least see the features because they are prominent.

Travel_notes: Backtrack north to top of slope, avoiding salmonberry. Proceed east until you reach small stream. Point is on west side of stream between stream and large root wad.
Location_desc: Point located between intermittent stream and large root wad with multiple hemlocks growing from it. It is on the west side of the stream above steep drop-off to stream (as of 2016). There is a large log crossing stream at 45 degrees, 8 meters from point.

Travel_notes:
Third Beach Trailhead, off of LaPush Rd.  It is about a 15-minute drive from Mora Campground.  If seeking a peaceful and quiet evening/night, you might want to go somewhere else. Our "neighbors" were still raging when we left this morning. Both arms are fairly marshy, boots are a good idea.

2015: Salal and vine maple are growing taller making travel more difficult
Location_desc: Located at the west end of the Third Beach parking lot. Distances/bearings to features are from S edge of parking lot. This transect is easier to follow if a bearing is taken from the map for each point (it doesn't seem to follow a direct bearing). The bearings of NW01-04 were corrected and in future, check bearings (and distances) on map to make sure same route is followed. An easy, flat transect assuming data sheets/field equipment/clothing aren't drenched.

Travel_notes: Travel east 200 meters from origin on the Hoh river trail.  There is a huge sitka spruce on the right at the point.
Location_desc: The point is on the trail where a sitka spruce is 1 meter south of the trail/point and a big leaf maple is just north of trail/point. There is a drainage ditch on the trail 8m up river from point.

Travel_notes: Travel about 165 m from TO on trail.
Location_desc: Point is on a short downhill stretch of trail, if heading E. There is a "border" on each side of trail at point. Point is about 35 m N of EE01 (trail was washed out and re-routed).

Travel_notes: Travel east on trail from pt EE02 for 200 meters.  At 190 meters the Hoh river will be very close and loud.  Start looking for a huge Doug Fir tree on the south side of the trail.
Location_desc: The path goes very near the Hoh River at this point.  The point is next to the Doug Fir tree in this 30 meter section of trail. It is about 15 m from river. It is about 20 m past huge cut log on both sides of the trail.

Travel_notes: Travel 200 meters east on hoh river trail.
Location_desc: The point is located about 15 m before the creek with no bridge.   It is on the trail right next to the huge (9 ft diameter) Sitka spruce.

Travel_notes: Travel 200 meters east on the Hoh river trail from point EE03.
Location_desc: Point is 5 meters East of "Mt. Tom Creek" sign and junction.

Travel_notes: Travel 200 meters east on trail from point EE04.
Location_desc: The point is in a forest that consists of smaller Sitka Spruce.  These spruces have very mossy limbs.  At this point, there are many roots in the trail and one very large Sitka Spruce just south of the trail. River is about 20 m to the S of point. There is a new channel of river ~4m from point. There is a snag on N side of trail right at point.

Travel_notes: Travel east on trail from point EE05 for 200 meters.
Location_desc: The trail slopes down then up in a 25 meter stretch.  The point is in the trough of the slope.  There is a drainage gap on the trail at the point. For 2 large hemlock feature: One on left has broken off and fallen.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: point is in open area with large salmonberry bushes all around. Point is at a drainage ditch along the trail.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is about 3 m past (E of) where trail begins to be "framed in."

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is on trail with large spruce on left and a fallen mossy log on right. A wooden beam crosses the trail here.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On trail, with a log cut on both sides of trail, and some rounds surrounding log on both sides of trail.

Travel_notes: Head due N from EE10.  Once you can see 2 very tall snags, aiming for right-hand one is helpful.  Some spots require heading off of the bearing to get through.  Stream can be crossed at area where there are many branches and the water is not deep. 2020: Not sure what is meant by "many branches", but I couldn't find any way to not get in at least ankle-deep water that didn't involve being suspended on a 20-ft. high root wad.
Location_desc: Point is in a moss covered area with an opening in the canopy.  Many large sitka spruces in area and vine maple is the understory.  Several downed logs all around.  You can still hear the stream you crossed behind you (~22m back). TO E of point, there is a downed Western hemlock log running S-N. To N of point, forest floor slopes slightly uphill. In a small clearing with not as much shrubby vegetation as in surrounding area. When looking at hemlock features from point, there is a very platey ~60cm DBH spruce ~2m beyond (upslope of hemlocks).

Travel_notes: Between 2 and 2.3 miles up Hoh River Trail. Camp at Hoh Campground, 1.4 mile camp, or Mt. Tom Creek Camp (about a 13-minute walk from there)- the other camps have washed out. This transect seems to change every year, so keep that in mind if nav. report doesn't make sense- it might need to be updated with current trail/river conditions. Takes about 50 minutes to hike up from campground without a pack. For WW arm: get those trail points done quickly to make-up for slow off-trail travel!
Location_desc: Right on the first step (bottom) of long set of large steps heading upslope.

Travel_notes: Walk along trail until it veers away from river (where new trail has been created). It is about 18 m from that point.
Location_desc: Point offset about 15 m because old point was washed out. It is on new trail now. It is changing every year! River is about 30 m from WW01 now.

Travel_notes: Stay on main trail that goes away from river (not blocked off old trail). Trail winds around, passing some massive spruces.
Location_desc: WW02 offset about 25 m to N because trail was re-routed away from river. On the S side of trail (about 8 m away) are 3 massive Sitka spruces- in between each is a large maple, the E of the 2 maple's foliage extends over trail/WW02. 2012- One of the tree spruces has fallen into river.

Travel_notes: There are a bunch of spruce rounds where new trail was cut just before the old trail/new trail merge.
Location_desc: The point is on the trail with the river to the south and dense forest to the north.

Reason_for_change: it wasn't as steep to go off-trail here (NW)
Travel_notes: The first 100 m or so is flatter and easier to walk through. Stay to left of the 3 big Sitka spruces. Then it gets denser and more uphill, then flattens out for the last ~25 m to point. Furthest SW of 3 spruces in features (furthest left) recently broke off (top 1/3 fell S) and pretty much flattened everything around- you can use the downed spruce to walk for a while toward slope that you must go up.
Location_desc: Point is in Sitka spruce forest in area where it flattens out after rising briefly (but steeply). It is ~25 m (at a 342 degree bearing) from this short, steep slope. Very mossy with lots of wood sorrel at and near point. Very mossy trees with mossy lower branches - look at pictures, I believe they are "seen from point" photos.

Travel_notes: The route to NW05 is up a steep slope, over a lot of moss, ferns, and decaying logs.  Traverse/travel slightly uphill over a steep slope. There are so many downed trees that pacing and keeping with bearing is difficult. Use GPS as much as possible.
Location_desc: Situated at intersection of 2 huge downed trees with ferns growing from them. There are several other downed trees very close to point (one huge tree fell on top of downed trees where point is located). There are also 3 huge (>122 cm DBH) Doug-firs within 20 m of point. Must go under tree to get on top of it for point.

Travel_notes: Lots of decayed downed trees on way to WW06. Difficult pacing. At about 160m, you reach the top of slope of trajectory you are walking. The remaining ~40 m are more of a side slope.
Location_desc: There are several very large trees nearby, especially cedars, mostly to the N and S. Point is essentially where you cannot walk any further at the 72 degree bearing due to cliffs leading down to creek. There are several large Doug-firs, mostly across creek, with one particularly large one between feature Doug-fir and creek, but feature Doug-fir is blocking it from view. Creek is visible from point over cliff (to SE). It is at the base of a snag with a hemlock (~30 cm DBH) and its roots wrapped around it.

Travel_notes: Climb up steep slope (keeping away from steep drainage initially) over a lot of downed trees most of the way. Slow travel.
Location_desc: Point is on the uphill side of a ~35cm DBH hemlock growing over a stump. There is a line of very large Doug-firs ~10m downslope of point (all <10m apart from each other). Point is on top of several downed trees (a lot immediately upslope, too).

Travel_notes: Climb up steep slope over a lot of downed trees. Travel is slow.
Location_desc: Point is in a small mossy area surrounded by hemlock saplings and Red huckleberry. To the W/SW (immediately) are dense hemlock saplings.

Travel_notes: Go downhill initially and eventually, it levels out. 2 streams/seeps are crossed along the way (one right away- within 10 m, the other ~70 m away).
Location_desc: at western edge of stand of large Mtn. hemlock. To E about 5 m is a sloping meadow with small stream and lots of downed logs.

Travel_notes: on trail, climbs up through forest/open with switchbacks
Location_desc: on trail at edge of V-shaped gully (on north side). Small Mtn. hemlock/SHRU

Travel_notes: on trail, climbs up with several switchbacks. Pacing is closer to 400 m than 200 m (I lost count). Go over 8 switchbacks (some minor ones I didn't count) to point.
Location_desc: on trail, 30 m E of flat, open, damp area with rock outcrops. 2 large snags to S. It is at the corner of a switchback, surrounded by lupine.

Travel_notes: on trail- 8 switchbacks (I think). Point SE04 located 25 m past the point where the ridgeline is attained.
Location_desc: on trail at ridgeline. Overlooks NE-facing cirque. Vaccinium/herbaceous/snags

Travel_notes: through rock and snow field
Location_desc: rock and snow field 50 m below ridgeline, some heather

Travel_notes: On trail from SE04.  SE05 from previous year was inacessible this visit due to snow.
Location_desc: Point might not be exaxctly on trail--covered in snow with patches of heather and rock.  It is downslope from the peak of ridge (end of line of burned snags to W).

Travel_notes: about 45 m from point SE05, a line of trees will be reached. Just beyond these trees is a 40 m wide stretch of steep loose slope. This can be skirted from above or below. After this, the transect runs at the base of a steep rock outcrop that parallels transect.
Location_desc: In middle of snowfield, 15 m N of a rock outcrop.

Travel_notes: On what  think is the trail, it is all snow-covered right now, sp pt. might not be exactly on trail.
Location_desc: It will likely look much different next visit-very snowy right now.  A beautiful point just below ridge at 2 degrees from pt., there is a low point in the ridge and the mountains can be seen through this.

Travel_notes:
Skyline Trail 2 km East of Kimta Peak. If you have an extra day, do the whole loop- it's amazing! We camped near Kimta Peak this year because it's beautiful, but there are far closer spots to camp off-trail (it took us about an hour and 15 minutes with full packs). Good camping spot near WW08, WW03, and between SE01 and SE02 (others as well). Recommended camping is between SE01 and SE02, for the proximity to TO and nice, level tent pads. SE05a and SE06 should be higher priority because they can be surveyed every year (even if SE05 and SE06 are snow-free/accessible, go to SE05a and SE06a first). Beautiful WW arm with great birds and views. Lots of bears up here (2015: three visible in valley belowfrom WW arm).
2018: There is a beautiful small tarn ~700m past (NE of) Promise Ck. Divide (basically SE04) that you can camp at, but it takes ~50min to get to TO, so if there is a lot of snow or it is cold (making snow hard), you probably want to camp closer to TO. Also, in a low snow year, it might be dried up!
Location_desc: In Shrub/Meadow habitat,about 5 m W of a small stream that is packed with downed wood. Some large hemlocks to the W.  Somewhat steep downhill from point (if coming from W). About 8-9 m after passing patch of slide alder very close to trail (on both sides, but SW side has patch closest to TO)

Travel_notes: Walk uphill from the origin on the trail.
Location_desc: The point is between a small stream and a dried-up stream bed, on the trail on rocky, dry substrate. There are many young Alaska yellow cedars and mountain hemlocks nearby.

Travel_notes: The trail passes over several small streams in the first 50 m. It is primarily uphill the whole way with a slight downhill in the last 20-25 m.
Location_desc: The point is surrounded by snags, herbaceous vegetation, downed wood, and some shrub. On either side of the point, the trail immediately ascends.

Travel_notes: The trail goes uphill for about 40 m, then downhill for the remainder of the way. It goes through a lot of snags (previously burned area) and is entirely open.
Location_desc: The point is on the trail in the middle of a burned area with some young mountain hemlocks around. There is a lot of downed wood.

Travel_notes: The route is mainly downhill through a burned area, surrounded by heather, herbaceous plants, some low shrubs (a lot of vaccinium), and downed wood.
Location_desc: The point is in the middle of a burned area, with many snags and herbaceous plant understory. There are streams (one very small) on either side of the point.

Travel_notes: The route is on the trail, going over several small streams, the end of a burned area, and mountain hemlock habitat.
Location_desc: The point is on the trail, surrounded by mountain hemlocks. It is on a flatter section of the trail, right before (E of) a sharp bend and right after (W of) a burned area.

Travel_notes: It is all on the trail, undulating through primarily Mtn. hemlock forest.
Location_desc: The point is on the trail, just E of a small dip in the trail and next to some mountain hemlocks. The point is on a large root of a mountain hemlock.

Travel_notes: The route is on the trail, undulating through Mtn. hemlock, Alaska yellow cedar, and Shrub.
Location_desc: The point is on the trail amidst a large patch of vaccinium. It is straight across the valley from the tallest hill around. Hill is visible through a gap between 2 cedar clusters. It is just NW (uphill) from a more forested part of the trail.

Travel_notes: the route is entirely on the trail, uphill through shrub (mostly vaccinium), heather, and occasional patches of various conifers.
Location_desc: The point is on the trail, next to a patch of small mountain hemlocks. It is ~10m NW of a small stream.

Travel_notes: Travel is way more than 200 m pacing on trail. Take care not to lose trail - trail crosses rock face. Point is up 3rd switchback- about 75 m from where trail switches sharply W.
Location_desc: There is a cluster of small yellow cedars below point. There are a few Mtn. hemlocks uphill of point on S of trail.Uphill of point, rock face visible of dry drainage. Lots of vaccinium on both sides of trail.

Travel_notes: Travel through mostly open meadow on trail. Cross over 1 small stream (may be more depending on amount of snowmelt)
Location_desc: On trail surrounded by open meadow and a few stands of hemlock. Point is at a right bend in the trail, just after the bend where the feature downed hemlock is located.

Travel_notes: Very easy walking through open Doug-fir forest.
Location_desc: Point is in open Doug-fir forest- very easy walking. There is a line of small, low cedars to the S. It is very open right at point. There are more saplings all around open area point is in .

Travel_notes: Travel is easy for 140 m. After creek, the slope becomes difficult.
Location_desc: The point is at the conjunction of several logs. Near conjunction, there are a couple of 2-4 m tall Alaka Yellow cedars. There is a live yellow cedar (dbh 40cm) that once pointed downhill and leaned over the logs, but is now just part of the mess.

Travel_notes: The best way to reach point EE03 from point EE02 is to follow the trail toward the road when you first hit it at 40 m. I did not do this, but it would be easier.
Location_desc: The point is on the trail where a creek is flowing through a large patch of Slide alder. The point is on the south side of the trail across from the center of the alder.

Travel_notes: Walk on path toward road until you reach correct easting. Walk north about 50 m through grass to reach correct northing. The trail is off on the map.
Location_desc: The point is N of the trail (~50 m) at 461551 easting on trail. The point is at the edge of a grass meadow/Subalpine Fir forest and the view of the mountains is spectacular.

Travel_notes: Travel E for 100 m through meadow, then Subalpine Fir forest until you cross the trail and reach a steep downslope. First 100 m stay S of Subalpine Fir line to walk through meadow (though slightly off bearing), then head up creek drainage and E to cross trail.
Location_desc: The point is where the slope is very steep 15 m from the top. Just upslope of 2 Subalpine Firs and a downed tree lying perpendicular to slope. Right below a bunch of huckleberry.

Travel_notes: Travel 100 m E through sparse Doug-fir and Subalpine fir.  First 60 m or so are very steep, leading down to a drainage. Traveling about 25 m to N going up other side of drainage is less steep and sketchy. After going up steeply, it is much flatter until last 15 m or so, where it drops very steeply (leading to another drainage). Watch out for boomer holes!
Location_desc: The point is at a downed log that runs N-S through a W-E clearing.  Point is on a very steep slope leading down to a drainage. It is about 2 m downhill from some small subalpine firs. There are some small cedars to the SW. In all other directions, it iis open, bare, or lightly vegetated with paintbrush and other herbaceous vegetation. There is some large rock about 1-2 m to the N and NW.

Travel_notes: Reach bottom of drainage after 25 meters.  Travel along bottom of drainage for 130 meters uphill.  Drainage follows a north bearing pretty well.  From the point at which the drainage dries up, both in water and water-loving vegetation, travel approximately 45 meters at 345 degrees.  Point is on a small game trail.
Location_desc: Point is located on a narrow game trail running east-west across slope not to be confused with another game trail closer to drainage.  Almost all trees around are subalpine fir.  There is a large subalpine fir snag, broken off at 4 meters high, 12 meters to the west.  At the base of this snag is a down tree over the game trail.

Travel_notes: To avoid trampling through highly visible from trail meadows, probably best to go up to trail from EE07, walk to trailhead, then walk on road (toward Hurricane Hill) for ~180m, until amost directly S of point. Walk ~25m N from there. Pretty clear shot from road to point- not many trees or understory.
Location_desc: Point is ~25m from road, in open subalpine fir forest. It's in an area with very little ground cover, compared to surrounding area (low to medium height shrub elsewhere).

Travel_notes: Near Top of Wolf Creek Trail, travel about 1 mile down Wolf Creek Trail. From the bend right after the giant yellow diamond-shaped sign that says "Snow Marker Course," it is ~100 m to point. WW arm steep, but mellow. Allow about 1 hour, 5-10 minutes from Port Angeles to TO.
Location_desc: Point is on the trail with a large stump on the east side of the trail. The forest here is Douglas-fir and there are several lupines on trail.  About a 25-minute walk down Wolf Creek Trail from Hurricane Ridge Rd.

Travel_notes: To get to the point, walk slightly downhill from the trail (origination point) through relatively open forest until you get to a meadow. The marker is facing the meadow.
Location_desc: Marker tree is at SE edge of a small meadow, surrounded by mostly Douglas-firs.

Travel_notes: The route travels downhill in varying degrees of steepness, primarily through Doug-fir forest. Walk until you reach transition between slight groundcover and debris to loose soil- stay E of Doug-fir that is essentially transition point. Walk almost the whole way on a ridge, becoming increasingly narrow as it nears WW02. Ridge is very narrow and steep at WW02.
Location_desc: There is a view of the mountains through a few Doug-firs. At the point, it is just loose soil, no herbaceous vegetation. Point is at base (E side- uphill) of a ~65 cm DBH Doug-fir- going beyond this tree could be harrowing. There is another slightly smaller Doug-fir about 3 m E (upslope) of point. On a small ridge.

Travel_notes: The first approximately 100 m are a traverse of a steep slope (very loose substrate), the remainder is down a not-as-steep slope. It is primarily through Doug-fir forest; there isn't much notable about it.
Location_desc: The point is on a slope with a large and long downed tree on it. There is some Oregon grape and a bit of vanilla leaf nearby. There is a large Doug-fir on W side of downed tree that is about 1 m downslope of feature hemlock/Doug-fir (see features).

Travel_notes: You can take the trail most of the way. For the first 40 m, walk off-trail downslope, then get on the trail. The point is about 145 m after the second obvious switchback.
Location_desc: The point is just north of the trail and south of the creek. It is on a steep bank leading down to the creek, next to a small Douglas maple.

Travel_notes: Go down trail about 25 m and go off-trail (S) from there. Go uphill/slightly contour initially and gradually shift into more full-on contouring through dark forest with little understory. It gradually shifts into less contouring and more downslope for the last ~40-50 m.
Location_desc: The point is on a relatively steep slope in a young Doug-fir forest. It is in a patch of Baldhip rose. There are several snags close to the point. There are 2 side by side snags about 7 m to the E (less than 2 m apart from each other).

Travel_notes: Travel is generally along the contour of the slope.  It is very steep both up and downhill of observer.  You will bisect areas of little or no vegetation because it so steep. You can follow deer trails for part of it.
Location_desc: Point is about 20 m up steep uphill in terrain.  it is on a grassy hillside (vanilla leaf) in a younger forest with some large Doug-firs surrounding point.  You can see mountains in the distance through the trees. Huge Doug-fir in features isn't that much larger than the 3 others within 15 m of it. I forgot to get a distance for the leaning Doug-fir feature. If you can figure it out next visit, please add!

Travel_notes: travel upslope (very steep!) for ~25 meter. Traverse gradually goes from slight elevation drop to a steep slope over the next 150 meters.  Large rock outcropping is obvious. Point 7 is ~15 meters below this.
Location_desc: large Doug-firs dominate the area. Rock outcropping to the N is a major feature.

Travel_notes: traverse steep slope (steadily losing elevation) until you reach base of small drainage (@ 150 meters). Then it is a short climb to small, open ridge. Point lies ~60 m further on the 90 degree bearing.
Location_desc: Point on very steep SE facing slope that leads down into a drainage. A number of old burnt stumps surround you in a Doug Fir forest

Travel_notes: Traverse on steep contour most of the way through sparse vegetation. If you stay directly on bearing, it will get a little cliffy right before getting to creek. Drop down to below the large downed tree near creek (feature), then climb up to point from there.
Location_desc: 2015: GPS jumping around area. GPS is off from features~15-20m- rely on features to hone in on pt. There is a massive 2m dbh downed Western hemlock right next to a loud creek. A steep rocky slope across the creek with Doug-firs is visible across creek. Also Douglas maples in the area. Point is ~10m W of creek. It is up against rock face amidst some Douglas maple branches.

Travel_notes: Start off in a wet meadow, then about halfway, it shifts into a drier meadow with lots of firs.
Location_desc: Dry meadowy area with beargrass and herbaceous vegetation. Smaller subalpine firs with several small Western White Pines and medium-large Douglas-firs.

Travel_notes: The first 55 m or so are a steep uphill, mostly through thick meadow. Then you reach the peak of uphill and the remainder of route is a traverse of a very steep slope.
Location_desc: steep slope with mixed Douglas-fir, Pacific silver fir, and Subalpine fir. Little shrubby/herbaceous cover. Point is just above a bunch of downed logs on bare steep slope. There are many rocks jutting out of slope to NW. There is a small root wad at point (downslope side) that you can lean your bag against so it won't plummet downhill.

Travel_notes: The first 25 m or so traverse a very steep slope, then it becomes more gradual and fairly easy walking.
Location_desc: Alaska yellow cedar dominates. Bordered to NW by a mast area with a trickle of running water.  The "trickle" of water is now several fast-flowing streams. About 8 m SE of seep; extensiveness of seep will vary immensely depending on current snowmelt. In the middle of a bunch of slide alder.

Travel_notes: Mostly a traverse through a lot of Vaccinium, Rhododendron, Beargrass, and more open areas.
Location_desc: Mainly Subalpine fir forest with some Pacific silver firs.   Shrubby understory with vaccinium and beargrass. A fair amount of downed wood and snags around the point. It is about 1 m NW of an intersection of several small downed trees.

Travel_notes: The first half is less shrubby, going through patches of beargrass and vaccinium mostly. The last 75 m is through dense White Rhododendron.
Location_desc: mixture of Pacific silver fir, Subalpine fir, Western hemlock. Dense white rhododendron cover. Several small to medium-sized snags.

Travel_notes: Travel through thick White Rhododendron at a 45 degree bearing. Occasional breaks in this shrubby understory.
Location_desc: Difficult point to describe. Homogeneous looking woods, dominated by White Rhododendron understory. The Subalpine fir snag feature is ~1m from a Subalpine fir with burly bark and many dead branches on it.

Travel_notes: first 50m through Rhododendron, then opens to flattish meadow area with Hemlocks. Changes back into uphill Rhododendron after ~100m and finally clears on a steep uphill gravel field with plethora of wildflowers
Location_desc: on a steep field with Lupine, Phlox, Columbine and Larkspur. A clearing surrounded by Subalpine Firs. A snowmelt stream runs E - W and is about 11m away. GPS might be a bit off here.

Travel_notes: Climb up steeply through meadowy area you're in, then subalpine fir forest, back into meadow, back into forest. At ~160m, you'll reach the final (and largest) meadow- point is in this.
Location_desc: Point is on the NW edge of a large meadow. There is a small downed tree between point and closest subalpine firs.

Travel_notes: To get to SE01, cut through the small meadow directly off the trail to avoid having to go through thick, difficult shrub.
Location_desc: The point is on a shrubby slope, also with a lot of herbaceous vegetation. There is a lot of downed wood nearby. It is on the intersection of 3 downed trees. Beware: there is another pair of large white snags ~25m to the N. The feature pair has 2 ~35cm dbh cedars to the SE of them. In between cedars and snags is a fallen cedar.

Travel_notes: A very difficult route. The first 60 m or so are downhill through shrub and a lot of downed trees. Then you cross a creek (slippery rocks and rapid water-be careful). After battling through shrub on both sides of creek, you go up and over a small, steep and forested ridge to point.
Location_desc: The point is just NW of (uphill from) a creek and thick shrubby area. (you can just barely see the creek because the shrub is hiding it). It is on a part of a downed log at the base of a ~45 cm dbh Doug-fir (uphill side). One of the 5 cedars is very small- they are mixed in with a <23 cm dbh Doug-fir.

Travel_notes: It is less steep going down to the creek (if you go due SE, it would be dangerous) if you go about 30 m E. After passing through a very thick shrub area, you go uphill until you hit a shrubby meadow at about 100 m. Go S about 20 m and you won't have to go through the thick shrub. Most of the rest of the way is uphill through meadow- the point is about 20 m in from the meadow. Watch out for boomer holes!
Location_desc: The point is on a slope, leading down to a meadow about 20 m away. It is surrounded by vanilla leaf, arnica, and shrub (mainly slide alder) to the N. It is on an old downed tree that runs E-W. The W end has lots of cedar saplings, the E end has vanilla leaf, slide alder, and pine, cedar, and sub. fir saplings.

Travel_notes: From SE03, you go uphill steeply for the first 100 m or so. Then it flattens out a bit, then you end up going downhill for the remainder.
Location_desc: The point is in Doug-fir forest on a steep slope. It is in a patch of vanilla leaf with some beargrass and Oregon grape nearby.

Travel_notes: For the first 70 meters, traverse a steep slope, then drop down steeply for the remaining 130m.
Location_desc: The point is located on a steep slope, surrounded by many downed trees and patches of bear grass.  It is about 30 m downslope of large rhododendron patch. It is ~1m uphill of a small leaning cedar and larger cedar with a Pacific silver fir (now a snag) inbetween. See photo.

Travel_notes: Begin traversing downhill through Doug-fir forest. At ~100 m the terrain gets steeper and rockier as you head more downhill. At ~150 m you will see cliffs that you pass below and pretty much parallel to point.
Location_desc: In open rocky slope, just S of a Douglas maple. There is another larger one downhill. There is a Oregon grape and lots of Doug-fir duff on ground. There are pieces of large fallen Doug-fir below pointy medium-sized boulders just E of pt. and large Doug-firs W of pt.

Travel_notes: Dosewallips, below Sunnybrook Meadows. Camped up trail from TO, but if not doing one of the rotating points near Constance Pass, you may want to camp off-trail below TO (difficult to find flat spot). But camping at Sunnybrook Meadows is worth the extra distance. TO is probably about 30 mins. from Sunnybrook Meadows. A tough day if coming from Dose Meadows transect. It is a surpisingly great night hike (Constance Pass Trail). A very shrubby, difficult 1st half of SE arm of transect- some seriously nasty traveling. NW arm: beautiful transect with views to the Cascades and southern Olympics on a clear day... some steep sections and also some sinister undergrowth around NW05 and NW06. You can also hike in at Upper Dungeness Trail (~11 miles) and camp at high point above Constance Pass - about a 48 minute walk down to TO from there. To exit NW arm and head back to TO - take ridgeline almost directly south of NW08. Easy walking. .
Location_desc: Point is on trail at edge of a wet meadow that runs SE-NW. Point is just N of a dense clump of 8-10 yellow cedars. About 70 m after switchback that goes into meadow (the 2nd meadow that you reach on trail (1st one is just before), if coming from down trail.

Travel_notes: To get to EE01, you go downhill from the trail (steeply at first) through meadow. Point is near a few mountain hemlocks.
Location_desc: The point is in a meadow surrounded by heather and mountain hemlock saplings. It is right on the edge of a small dropoff. The large boulder seen from point is just barely visible over trees.

Travel_notes: Traverse through meadow the entire way.
Location_desc: The point is in a steep meadow with a lot of False hellebore immediately surrounding it. The ground near the point is covered with small rocks.

Travel_notes: The route traverses a steep meadow for most of the way.
Location_desc: The point is next to a lot of heather, beargrass, shrub, and lupine. It is just E of a small gully. There are mountain hemlocks to the E and Subalpine firs to the N and S.

Reason_for_change: cliffs and very steep terrain, creek
Travel_notes: The route is downhill a steep slope. The last 30-40 m are through shrub. It is very steep at some points with many horizontal shrub branches- pacing is difficult because of this.
Location_desc: The point is in the middle  of a very shrubby area, surrounded by alder and salmonberry, primarily. It is on a slope leading down to a creek (the creek is very close (about 10 m away), but you can't see it from the point.).  It is slightly less shrubby to the E. Disregard "close subalpine fir" photo. There are several cedar saplings ~5m to the E. There is a line of Subalpine firs to the E. Point is a transition between all slide alder and more open area- it is mixed slide alder and salmonberry right at point.

Travel_notes: After leaving SS04, you immediately hit a creek that is impassable at due S bearing. Go about 20 m upslope (there's a small waterfall) and cross there. Definitely don't try to go downstream from the point, or you'll get trapped against the steep slope. Important note: there is another waterfall just down creek from waterfall in description. Travel below this is much too steep, so make sure you find the correct waterfall.
Location_desc: The point is on a slope in Mountain hemlock forest. At the point, there is a lot of beargrass, vaccinium, and rhododendron. In a very beargrassy spot.

Travel_notes: Traverse a steep slope through mostly open forest for 200 m. Much easier walking than previous points.
Location_desc: Point is in open forest on a steep slope. There is some sparse White rhododendron about 1 m to the N/NW. There is a larger patch of Rhododendron ~5m to the N/NE.

Travel_notes: Easy walking through open forest for ~120m, then you drop off ridge, getting increasingly steep as you get closer to point.
Location_desc: Point is about 2m downhill (and ~1m to the E) of a ~90cm DBH silver fir (feature). It is on top of a part of a short snag that is leaning over a downed tree so you can stand on top of it. There is a small clearing immediately NE of point.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: After climbing up to the ridgetop from the trail, the point is at the edge of where the other side begins to descend. A small stand of subalpine fir is just to the N

Travel_notes: Travel through slippery, steep talus field. At 175 m from point NW01, the transect crosses a low ridge. This ridge is easily skirted to the N to avoid the cliff on the backside.
Location_desc: Mixed talus and meadow habitat. At base of 20 m cliff, about 8 m W of large rounded rock.
