Location_desc: It's on a slight downhill section of trail if coming from the lake.  There are some boardwalk planks just up the trail- forgot to record how far up trail (toward lake) though- do this next visit, if possible.

Travel_notes: Pace 100 meters at 315 degrees.  Travel is upslope from TO.
Location_desc: Point is on the side of a medium slope forest consisting of mainly hemlocks, some doug-firs, with salal understory.

Travel_notes: Traverse across hillside for 200 meters at 315 degrees.
Location_desc: Point is located on the south side of a very small gully that runs NE-SW.  There are about equal numbers of mostly medium (60DBH) hemlocks and doug-firs in the vicinity.  Directly next to the point is a 30DBH barkless snag leaning over onto a nearby hemlock.

Travel_notes: Cross gully right after point NW02 and traverse across slope at 315 degrees for 200 meters.
Location_desc: Point is in an open blowdown area with lots of snags and down wood.  Almost all trees are hemlocks with a few doug-firs.  Point is located close to two rootwads (1m and 2m high) and a 60DBH doug-fir.

Travel_notes: Travel 200 meters at 315 degrees.  First half of travel is relatively flat, but second 100 meters starts to descend down the side of the hill.  The point is on an old abandoned road that cuts across the slope.
Location_desc: The point is on what seems to be an abandoned old logging road.  It is about 5m wide and runs roughly east-west.  There are a number of red alders grown up in the light gap that the road provided.  An open grassy patch with alders is visible 25 meters northwest of point.

Travel_notes: Travel downhill for 200 meters at 315 degrees.  There are two flat open spots with scattered larger alders within the first 50 meters of travel.  Then you get back into denser, smaller hemlock forest similar to the travel on the way to point NW04.
Location_desc: Point is in a dense stand of small western hemlocks (25-50DBH).  A small stream to the northwest is 50 meters past the point.  Lots of down wood.  Almost every tree around is a relatively uniform size hemlock except for a few alders that stand out.

Travel_notes: I only recommend following a direct bearing if you like falling down 10ft. drops every 20m. Otherwise follow the creek drainage - it takes you directly to point with less hassle.
Location_desc: Located on a flat mossy section of the creek drainage heard from previous point. Mostly Western Hemlock with some alder present. Very noisy creek makes from limited ability to hear birds.

Travel_notes: Leave drainage ASAP and follow direct bearing (315 degrees) for another 180m or so. Travel is through relatively open woods on gentle slope.
Location_desc: Located on gentle slope in open hemlock woods. Lots of uprooted stumps and downed wood around, as well as several small hillocks and some mossy boulders nearby. Creek still vaguely audible to the north.

Travel_notes: Walk downhill from NW07, passing bend in old road grade. At around 140m you cross the stream running through the last few points. In 2021 stream was dry here, but there is a jungle thicket if on bearing. Probably best to cross just above this.
Location_desc: Open secondary growth forest perched above stream. Low salal understory between many downed trees.

Travel_notes: Even though point ended up on trail, its easy walking off-trail, so I would just do that. Slightly uphill through open forest.
Location_desc: This point ended up being on the trail, unintentionally. The silver firs in features are somewhat blocked by a snag and a hemlock. Point is about 12 m after trail makes a near 90 degree bend. Two segments of a large downed tree (cut) are on SW side of trail right at point (lying parallel to trail).

Travel_notes: Pace the 1st ~80-85 m on trail (because trail goes generally SE too, even though it doesn't appear that way on map), then veer slightly off-trail for last ~120 m.
Location_desc: Point is in open forest with sparse salal groundcover, but very little else. The slope is still gradual here. There are 2 uniform-sized Doug-firs (~90 cm DBH) that form an almost equilateral triangle with point, slightly closer to the one further uphill (E/S).

Travel_notes: For the first 55-60 m, it is a gradual downhill, then it drops steeply into a bowl. The last ~50m are still steep, but transect contours it, rather than dropping further downhill.
Location_desc: Point is on a steep slope leading down into a bowl. There are 2 Red alders that I can see from point (both are features) and some vine maple scattered about.

Travel_notes: For the first ~15 m, transect is a sideslope of a steep slope, then the slope becomes less steep. At ~65 m, it stops sidesloping and begins going downhill.
Location_desc: Point is about 25 m before (NW of) abrupt change in slope (it gets much steeper) leading down to creek. It is also brighter and more deciduous starting after those 25 m. Very little groundcover right at point.

Travel_notes: After about 25 m, you will drop down pretty steeply to creek. After crossing it, the rest of the way is more gradual and mellow.
Location_desc: Point is about 15 m NW of relatively thick vine maple (where transect goes after leaving SE05). Thick salal groundcover. Sparse vine maple overhead.

Travel_notes: Becoming increasingly more gradual as it gets closer to point. Thick understory (mostly salal) for almost the whole way until about 10 m NW of point, at which point, there is much less groundcover to point.
Location_desc: Point is about 9 m E of a line of vine maples- not dense, though. Right at point itself, it is very open with little understory. It is about 30 m W of the start of a drop down to creek. Open Doug-fir forest with a bit of Oregon grape at point- not much else.

Travel_notes: Walk about 30m until you reach a steep descent to a drainage. It might be better to go slightly more S to avoid the steepest slope. After crossing drainage, climb back up to other side, walk across level terrain for a short stretch, then start dropping down to second drainage. SE07 is on slope down to that drainage.
Location_desc: Point is on a pile of splintered wood with mossy groundcover and a slight break in the dense salal. There is a vine maple that almost extends over point from the E. It is about 30m N of the bottom of drainage. It is on the E side of a ~75cm DBH hemlock.

Travel_notes: Drop down to cross stream from SE07, climbing out to wrap around ridge. Easy walking through open woods from here.
Location_desc: Point is on the edge of a young hemlock doghair zone. Very close to the base of a large hemlock at this border.

Travel_notes: About a 40-minute hike from Aurora Ridge trailhead. Trail is off on map, but intended coordinates for TO did put TO on the trail; it just doesn't seem like that from looking at the map. Because of that, SE01 ended up being on the trail. Note that the marker on SE arm is at SE02, rather than SE01. About 70m west of NW07 is an old logging road that connects to NW04 is somewhat roundabout but graded well and not too overgrown. Warrants some forethought (ie get NW05 & NW06 totally done, so you don't have to back track up that steep drainage). We camped at Fairholme Campground, about a 9-minute drive from trailhead. Otherwise, you can stay in PA, but it is probably a 45-minute drive (plus 40-minute hike). When returning to TH from NW08 you can attempt to travel back on the largest old road grade shown on map/GPS. This is nice for a few hundred meters before becoming salmonberry nonsense. From here though you can travel S through open woods speedily back to the trail.
Location_desc: Point is about 13 m before (W of) a major bend in trail. There is a Doug-fir (~95cm DBH) about 1 m from trail (N side) right where point is. There is a small gully that crosses trail right at the major bend.

Travel_notes: Head down trail from Anderson Pass.  Continue through open areas, and stop about 10 meters before trail leads into dense forest.
Location_desc: On trail down toward Honeymoon Meadows from Anderson Pass.  At open area in the trail (open to the right) and good view if clear.  Look for curvy hemlock on the right.  Skinny cedar leaning over the trail just ahead.

Travel_notes: Head down trail until it opens up into a large meadow.  Walk about 65 meters from the forest edge to point 02.
Location_desc: On trail uphill from a patch of salmonberry and mountain hemlock behind it.  Good view of LaCrosse Peak!

Travel_notes: Walk down trail until you get to the camping area.  Continue down trail to point 03.
Location_desc: On trail past camping area, in open meadow.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On trail in the middle of several switchbacks.  The switchback the point is on is particularly long. Point is in between 2 pieces of cut log (~70cm DBH) as forest opens to clearing with small Pacific silver firs and Mtn. hemlocks.

Travel_notes: Walk down trail until it reaches the river 10 meters below.  Turn left on the switchback and walk 6 meters.
Location_desc: On trail next to river.  Rapids visible. A young mountain hemlock (dbh=~10) curves out over the river.

Travel_notes: Walk down a couple switchbacks and continue paralleling the river.  Point 06 is just past a slight bend in the trail to the left, as trail starts to veer away from the water.
Location_desc: On trail next to two subalpine firs on the fight and one on the left that are still alive but the tops are broken off.  Visible down the trail on the left side is a fourth (a feature).  River is just barely visible.

Travel_notes: Walk down trail until it opens up and if clear you get a nice view.  Point is before sign to LaCrosse Pass.
Location_desc: On trail near river, open views and lots of exposed rock.

Travel_notes: Go on bearing at 45 degrees and cross river. If river is too high, it may be easiest to walk up trail toward Honeymoon Meadows. As soon as you can see the river on your right, and right before a stream crossing, is a social trail leading down to the river, 8 meters away.  Follow it a few meters, cross, and head upstream towards point. 2015: I was not able to find marker and so I established a new point in the same area.
Location_desc: On the western side of a large puddle 10cm deep and 8 meters across (featured) with a small stream 40cm wide flowing into it.  Small mountain hemlocks and some riparian vegetation present.  On the edge of an open area in forest.  Between point and river is much thicker. 2015: Look for marker, and if you find it, determine whether new features are in the same general vicinity and can be called the same point. If old description doesn't make sense, delete and use this: Point is on a large fallen log that stretches ~25m SW to NE (DBH ~1m). In Pacific silver fir forest with Mtn. hemlock saplings, ~25m from river.

Travel_notes: Pace about 130 m from TO on trail to NN01.
Location_desc: I'm not sure if point is exactly on the trail because of snow, but it's pretty close. It is where trail starts to flatten out a bit and turn to the W.

Travel_notes: Pace about 575 m up trail over 10 switchbacks. The first switchback is at ~70 m.
Location_desc: Point is at a switchback with a rocky outcrop (right at switchback) with vaccinium and Mountain ash on it (Mountain ash on top). There are 3 small clusters of small Mountain hemlocks within 5 m of point, all in a line with trail going between each one.

Travel_notes: Walk up trail over several switchbacks until you reach a ridge. At that point, drop into small basin/tarn and climb up trail on E side of tarn for about 30 m to point.
Location_desc: Point is on trail that is on the E side of tarn/small basin (couldn't find W trail because of snow). Starting at about 1 m down trail of point, there is a patch of heather on each side of trail. It is about 30 m from bottom of basin.

Reason_for_change: trail ended- could go off-trail anyway
Travel_notes: Walk to the end of the trail, then when you get to ridge (trail may continue, but I lost it with the snow), cut across and slightly uphill toward small tract of Mountain hemlock forest.
Location_desc: Point is on the edge of Mtn. hemlock forest. Totally open at point. Low shrub groundcover (most hasn't leafed out yet). A great view of White Mtn.

Travel_notes: Best to go about 90 m W first (easier to get down these boulders)- then cut across N/NW for the remainder. Use GPS.
Location_desc: A beautiful full-on view of Mt. Anderson. About 45 m upslope of where slope gets steeper leading down to lake.

Travel_notes: Walk downslope toward Anderson/lake. Be careful if it's hard snow. Use GPS.
Location_desc: Another hard point to describe. About 25 m from lake. Use GPS!

Travel_notes: Walk along lake for 200 m, gradually getting closer to it as you near NN07. It looks closer than it is (from NN06).
Location_desc: Point is about 15 m from edge of water- mostly frozen right now though. In snow right now- a beautiful view of Anderson and mountains to the S.

Travel_notes: Walk upslope/contour at 45 degree bearing. Aim to "left" of saddle.
Location_desc: Use GPS. Very hard to describe. On the flanks of Mt. Anderson- 100% snow-covered this visit. It is below a saddle.. better luck with features next time if there is no snow.

Reason_for_change: Going 360 degrees had very slippery upslope rockface; sketchy to climb
Travel_notes: Flat, easy travel
Location_desc: Right next to small stream. Flat, few boulders. Use GPS- not great features. Rocky orange rock face to N.

Travel_notes: Travel moderate, some rocks but overall flat.
Location_desc: Difficult to describe point. Use GPS! Flat ground, bare surroundings, few rocks.

Travel_notes: Rocks, sinking silt but overall moderate travel. At beginning 30m travel uphill, but evens out.
Location_desc: No good descriptions. GPS is best! Point is on a rocky upslope at bottom orange rocks.

Travel_notes: From Anderson Pass, head up trail to Anderson Glacier.  Trail switchbacks twice, then heads straight, and TO is at the point where the trail turns left again.  Would be possible to continue NE to add a 9th point on NE arm, possibly a 10th going N after that.  Fun transect with good views. An interesting and beautiful NN arm. Camp either at Anderson Pass (much closer to TO) or at tarn almost near end of trail (beautiful). Flypaper Pass is the low notch on Anderson connecting the Dose side to the Elwha/Hayden zone to the N (route on GPS). This is referenced as a feature.
Location_desc: At curve in switchback.  On the right side fo the trail is a clump of 3 mountain hemlocks.  Marker is on the far hemlock.

Travel_notes: At second switchback from TO.  Pace 230 meters on trail.
Location_desc: At a sharp switchback to the right.  Cliff wall to the southwest.  Rocky outcrop just west of the switchback.  Large patch of yellow cedar west of rocky outcrop.  Road visible. On switchback hairpin curve.

Travel_notes: Pace about 595 meters on trail.  Point is 75 meters past the trail junction.
Location_desc: Incredible view of valley, can see all the way to Mt. Baker.  No very conspicuous features at point.  Good GPS signal. Right next to a Subalpine fir with many branches low to the ground (like a carpet/blanket spread out), on left side of trail, <0.5m away.

Travel_notes: 2010: Trail completely obscured by a massive snowfield.  Used GPS to approximate how travel should go.
Location_desc: Totally open skree slope.  No conspicuous features.  Great GPS signal though.  There is a patch of krummholtz subalpine fir about 25 meters to the east.

Travel_notes: Pace 240 meters along trail.  Point is about 30 meters after you go through a narrow band of yellow cedar and subalpine fir that the trail intersects.
Location_desc: Running parallel to the trail 25 meters to the east is a band of small, prostrate yellow cedar.  There is also yellow cedar on the left (SW) side of the trail before the cliffs start.

Travel_notes: Pace 215 meters along trail.  Point is at end of straight section of trail, just before it starts switchbacking up to the ridgeline.  10 meters after point is a little gully.
Location_desc: To the NE is a massive cliff-face.  Area is totally open with only sparse herbs for vegetation.

Travel_notes: Go up 10 small switchbacks to reach saddle of ridgeline. (2010: After the saddle there was almost complete snow cover.  Trail not visible because of snow on NW side of ridge.)
Location_desc: There is a large clump of Alaska yellow cedar to the north 16 meters away.  Point may not be on the trail, there was too much snow to see where the trail was. On switchback curve on trail (hairpin). Two scraggly Subalpine firs are visible in the distance on a large cliff/rock face at 338 degrees, N/NW.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: There are lots of yellow cedar on both sides of the trail just past the point.  Probably less snow than the last point.

Travel_notes: Travel on trail.  Lots of snow patches make travel more difficult.
Location_desc: Point is on trail on the west side of a cliff-face.  The slope drops off very steeply on the other side of the trail.  There is a tall cliff-face 40 meters to the south.

Travel_notes: Travel on trail just about 200 meters.  Be careful of frozen-over snowfields covering trail.
Location_desc: There is a large pillar of rock 15 meters ot the south on the east side of the trail.  The Griff burn is visible to the SW.  The top of a rocky spire is seen to the NE.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Meadowy w/ fallen tree trunks on L side. Large cliff rock wall on R side of trail (NE). Sparse Subalpine fir on NE. Lots of lupine, thistle, cow parsnip meadow vegetation.

Travel_notes: Walk down somewhat steep, open section of trail before climbing gradually through subalpine fir and yellow cedar forest to point.
Location_desc: Point right after rock in trail before a small tunnel of cedars downhill and a tangle of bleached cedar roots uphill. Mostly meadow with a Subalpine fir before point and all Rock/sparsely vegetated ahead of point (no trees).

Travel_notes: Pace about 110 m down trail to SE01.
Location_desc: Point is in between Subalpine firs, just beyond a meadow. About 20 m before (up trail from) a switchback.

Travel_notes: Pace ~555 m down trail.
Location_desc: Point is in between Subalpine firs. On uphill side of trail, there is just a line of single-layered Subalpine firs between point and meadow. Point is where furthest SE (down trail) of firs are (in that line)

Travel_notes: Pace about 290 m down trail. When you reach trail junction, go toward Hurricane Ridge (instead of continuing down Switchback Trail).
Location_desc: There are a bunch of cedars growing over trail right at point, on top of a large reddish rock face. Right at point is where cedars start growing closer to trail on downhill side of trail (just for a few meters).

Travel_notes: Pace about 250 m on trail toward Hurricane Ridge.
Location_desc: Point is on trail, with a young cedar leaning almost over trail directly at point. There is an open, less forested area off-trail to the N.

Travel_notes: The first ~80-90 m are mostly forested, at which point you will reach a meadow, steep in parts. Much of remainder is through meadow or sparse forest. Be careful- it's steep.
Location_desc: Point is about 3 m upslope of a cluster of ~9 yellow cedars. It is on the W edge of a small clearing. Continuing S from here is all forested. It is on a downed tree running approximately NW-SE.

Travel_notes: A steepish downhill, mostly forested, to SE06. Lots of downed trees.
Location_desc: Point is less than 10 m from dropoff to road. Sparse understory right at point. Some cedar saplings just upslope of point (within 5 m). Road is visible from point.

Travel_notes: It might be easier to takl up the Ridge Rd., then cut down to point. I didn't do this and off-trail travel is rough in spots, but I have to collect flagging, so I can't go out that way. Next visit, you may want to access it by road (not sure how far it is, but it looks close on map). But if you do go off-trail, drop down about 10 m to road, cross road, drop down through meadow. When you reach thick swath of slide alder, go slightly W to avoid the worst of it.
Location_desc: Point is on the S side of some cedar saplings. There are 2 downed trees parallel and very close to each other, running SE-NW, about 2 m NE of point. Point is on a downed tree that goes under 2 downed trees.

Travel_notes: Note: it's easiest not to use road between 7 and 8.
Location_desc: Point is at a mossy patch downslope of several open dirt patches. The large Douglas fir is difficult to see through the brush/trees. Note: photos not taken exactly from point due to this.

Travel_notes: The TO is at the sixth switchback you hit after you reach the junction of the Switchback Trail and the trail from the Visitor Center.  About a 30-35 minute hike from the Switchback Trailhead, about a 30-minute drive from Port Angeles. Best to not do this transect on a weekend; it could get busy.
Location_desc: TO is at a sharp switchback to the right.  Just west of the switchback are four 60-80 DBH subalpine firs.  The marker is on the backside of the farthest one away from the trail.

Travel_notes: 100 meters from the road through sword fern understory and Sitka Spruce canopy.  Easy going.
Location_desc: In dense sword fern.

Travel_notes: Easy travel through sword fern.
Location_desc: The point is now located in a dense sword fern understory underneath a hemlock canopy.  Bigleaf Maples directly north of the point.

Travel_notes: NN02 and NN03 separated by  a large, impassable wetland.  Travel west from NN02 towards old gravel pit road.  Cross a wetland over remants of bridge (still a little wet) and navigate back west to NN03.
Location_desc: Point is in dense vine maple blowdown area, 50 meters north of wetland area/ephemeral lake/ lots of water. Right next to Sitka spruce (40 cm DBH) in dense vine maple.

Travel_notes: Travel north from point until reaching old road to the quarry.  Follow road to next point.
Location_desc: Point is on old quarry road in Western hemlock forest. Lots of old large stumps to be seen in forest. 3m rotten stump due East of point. 5.2 m before 1m high log across road.

Travel_notes: Travel 200 meters up the old quarry road.
Location_desc: Point is on old road towards the quarry. Small clearing due west with 2 snags.

Travel_notes: Travel up old road, lots of blowdown that requires some agile moves.
Location_desc: Point located on old road, 23 meters before quarry, in a patch of raspberry.

Travel_notes: Travel past old rock quarry and follow old road to next point.
Location_desc: Along road in salmonberry. Large clearing to the left.

Travel_notes: Follow the old road until it comes out at the river.  Take a bearing of 55 degrees before dropping down to the river and traverse the clearing through dense sword fern 75 meters until the point.
Location_desc: The point is located in a small clearing ~50 meters from gravel bar along the river.  We followed an old road past  gravel pit until it came out to the river. At the end of the road, take a bearing of 55 degrees through a flat fern covered clearing at the bottom of  a slope. Travel 75 meters towards a large Sitka Spruce in clearing.

Travel_notes: Walk 100m through flat, mellow forest to point.
Location_desc: Pt is in uniform alder forest. Difficult to come up with features. It is ~25m before dropping down slightly into stream.

Travel_notes: A walk through flat, mellow forest, crossing a stream along the way. After ~135m, it drops down into sandy/gravel bar, where it remains for the rest of way.
Location_desc: There is a very conical forested peak due SE from pt. Most of shrub and driftwood will likely be different next visit, so I wont use any as features.

Travel_notes: Walk through sparse shrub and sand, transitioning into gravel bar. At ~112m, climb up bank and walk the rest of the way to point in forest, not far from edge.
Location_desc: Point is ~20m N of where grassy flats drop down toward gravel bar. In open forest under the branches (the very end) of feature spruce.

Travel_notes: Easy walking for ~200m. So pleasant! So easy to pace!
Location_desc: It is right at the line dividing Red Alder forest and more conifer forest (mostly spruces, hemlocks, and cottonwoods (yes- I realize cottonwood is not a conifer)). Open understory at pt. - more ferns to the SW). Feature vine maple extends almost over point. There is a large downed Cottonwood ~10m to the SW. The 2 leaning alders (feature) are in an area with fewer alders, more conifers. The distance and bearing of 2 alders feature is to the alder closer to the river/point.

Travel_notes: Walk through flat forest, crossing a stream at ~100m. Shortly after, you will enter a meadow, where you will be the rest of the way.
Location_desc: Pt is in middle of field - see features. It is right on the E edge of some ferns. To the E, there are very few ferns.

Travel_notes: Walk 1st ~90m through field, go through forest briefly until crossing road at ~120m. The remainder is through wet, flat forest. A very nice walk.
Location_desc: Point is right where it starts go down a few feet (to the SE) into a wetter area (where root wad is). Mostly Oxalis right at point. Many ferns to the NW, but not right at point. It is right in some vine maple.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Pt is in muddy part of forest, in some skunk cabbage. In a slightly lower part of forest. There is a cluster of 4 Red Alders ~4m to the N/NE

Travel_notes: Easy walking through occasional muddy sections in open, mellow forest.
Location_desc: Pt is in open, fern-laden alder forest, surrounded by vine maple. It starts to drop down slightly about 10m to N. There is some vine maple to the W/NW that extends almost over point.

Travel_notes: About a 20-minute drive from Graves Creek Campground, or a 15-minute drive from North Fork Campground.. Drive past Bunch Field and look for end of pavement (see below). A few small stream crossings and muddy areas - rubber boots are recommended. A beautiful SS arm of transect! Travel on NN arm easy, very flat and not too much understory to contend with. Travel between NN02 and NN03 requires skirting around wetland area and following old gravel pit road.  Very wet.  You may want to bring rubber boots/canoe.  Travel after NN03 mostly along old road and very easy.
Location_desc: Point is ~95m SW (on road) of where road turns back to gravel after a brief paved stretch. It is ~95m NE of slightly wider spot in road (where we parked). Beautiful forest! South of road is a fairly non-vegetated area with few ferns or trees (aside from grass). Mostly Oxalis on N side of road.

Travel_notes: Walk uphill through dense salal to point. At ~75-80m, you will cross an old road bed.
Location_desc: In salal and Oregon grape. There are several very deeply furrowed Doug-firs near point (specifically there are 2 downslope, 8m and 14m from pt).

Travel_notes: A gradual uphill through pretty intense salal the whole way.
Location_desc: Pt. is in thick salal, about 4m from the edge of a small drop. Very indistinct forest. Really hard to find features. Look for the maple! It is at the base (N side) of a Doug-Fir (~45cm dbh)...I'm sure that's helpful!

Travel_notes: You will immediately drop down (not much) after leaving pt. Then it is pretty flat for ~70m, goes uphill briefly and flattens out at ~90m. It is undulating for the remainder with a slightly more noticeable gully at the end. After crossing that, pt. is ~1m from top. Pretty thick salal for most of it.
Location_desc: Pt is on a slight slope leading down to a small gully. It is ~1m from the top. Open forest. There are three alders within ~5m to the NW of pt. It is ~2m before (south of) reaching an old road bed.

Travel_notes: Pretty easy travel. I went off-bearing (accidentally) on my way back due to inadequate flagging and spacing out, so I can't wirte great details about travel except that it's pretty level with some small ups and downs. From the last high spot before dropping down to point, it is about 60m.
Location_desc: Point is at base of a large ~70m dbh cedar. There is a pond visible through the trees ~70m away. There isn't much vegetation right at point, just a few ferns nearby.

Travel_notes: Easy walking. Walk down toward pond (to the left) and walk on fairly level, slightly undulating terrain. At ~170m you will reach a seep. After crossing it, start to climb uphill. It is ~13m from there. After easy walking, immediarely cross an old road bed.
Location_desc: Poing is ~13m upslope of a seep. To the W ~5m is a large boulder, but is not visible from point (or at least, it cannot be IDed as a boulder). Point is at base (uphill side) of a ~70cm dbh mossy maple.

Travel_notes: Walk uphill through fairly substantial salal until it flattens and goes downhill briefly at ~110m. After this point it is uphill and less salal-rich to point.
Location_desc: Pt. is at base (uphill side) of a ~50cm dbh hemlock. The point forms a triangle with 2 ~150cm dbh Doug-firs, each about 14m away. There are cedar branches over point. In a spot with hardly any salal or other understory.

Travel_notes: Walk up moderate slope until it flattens out. It then levels off for ~55m, dropping down to point for the last ~35m.
Location_desc: Point is on slope leading down to gully. It is ~30m from the bottom of slope. It is almost equidistant with 2 giant Doug-firs that are burnt at base (point makes triangle with 2 Doug-firs). In some Oregon grape. Great hooting spot (not correct station, but try it once anyway!). It is underneath some branches of a ~35cm dbh cedar.

Travel_notes: Gradual downhill from NE07 with a few sections of thicker salal. Stop before you get to the bottom of gully that is filled with ferns. If you have reached dense fern area, you have gone too far.
Location_desc: Sparsely vegetated right at point. There are several large boulders to the southeast of point- all moss-covered, but the one mentioned in features is the largest. Pretty level ground right at point.

Travel_notes: Pace 100m up road to point, passing one telephone pole along the way.
Location_desc: Pt is ~12m before reaching the second telephone pole (both on lake-side of road).

Travel_notes: Pace ~205-210m on road to point.
Location_desc: Pt. is about 5m before reaching a telephone pole on the lake-side of road. Across the road is a Doug Fir (>150cm dbh) with several madrones and an electrical box in front of it.

Travel_notes: Pace ~225m down road until you reach a loud stream/creek. Walk ~18m past that.
Location_desc: Pt. is ~18m after passing a loud stream. It is under the branches of a cedar (if you remain off-road, which you should- crazy drivers on this road!)

Travel_notes: Pace ~220m down road.
Location_desc: Pt. is on a curve in the road, 9m past the second of two back-to-back telephone poles. There is a dirt driveway (?) across the road from point (a few meters past point).

Travel_notes: Pace ~200m down road until ~30m past driveway (see location description).
Location_desc: Pt. is ~30m past a driveway with a bunch of numbers on it (#1443, 1503...). It is ~1m past plastic post with reflector on it (only on backside of it if coming from NW04).

Travel_notes: Pace ~200-205m until you get to a driveway (#1603).
Location_desc: Pt is ~1m before driveway (#1603). You really can't miss it.

Travel_notes: Pace ~210m down road until you reach third telephone pole.
Location_desc: Pt. is right across road from large rock up against the hillside and 3m before telephone pole.

Travel_notes: Pace down road ~225m until you are ~17m shy of a telephone pole with #1893 placard on it (pole is just before driveway).
Location_desc: Pt is right across road from a large boulder. It is ~22m before reaching driveway (#1893)

Travel_notes: Pace ~215m down road. The road will drop down to the lake. Point is on part of road that is right on lake.
Location_desc: It is almost directly across from the first of the telephone poles that is on the non-lake side of the road. That should be enough of a description.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: At a small pullout on the road next to a douglas fir on the lake.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Point is directly across road from two electrical boxes on the ground.

Travel_notes: Park at East Beach on Lake Crescent (about 25-minute drive from Port Angeles). Point is about a 2-minute walk up road from East Beach. NE arm runs parallel to the park boundary the whole time. It is very close to it, but I never saw signs or evidence that I was out of the park at any point. If ever another point is established in the future, direction should be changed to west from NE07.
Location_desc: Pt. is ~110m from junction of East Beach turnoff and Lyre River/Joyce Piedmont Rd. It is ~6m past the only telephone pole on the lake-side of road between East Beach Junction and TO.

Travel_notes: Travel east for 100 meters.  Easy walking through clear understory.  Gradual downhill travel to point.
Location_desc: Point is in an area with quite a few western hemlocks around.  Looking north you pretty much just see bigger doug-firs, and looking south there are more hemlocks.

Travel_notes: Travel is flat and easy through open doug-fir and salal forest.
Location_desc: Point is in an open area with many small doug-firs and salal and sword fern understory.  There area a lot of rotting stumps visible.

Travel_notes: Walk east for 200 meters.  Travel is mildly downhill at first, becoming increasingly so as you approach the point.
Location_desc: Point is on a NE-facing slope just as the hill starts to get very steep.  There is a lot of down wood in the area.  Lake Mills is barely visible through the trees.

Travel_notes: Travel uphill for the first half of travel.  Then go down steep hillside, cross a small drainage and climb 60 meters up the next hillside to the point.
Location_desc: Point is on a fairly steep NE-facing slope.  Several larger doug-firs to the N, NE, E, and SE.  Moss-carpeted ground with short salal understory.

Travel_notes: Traverse moderately uphill along the hillslope.  Fairly uniform forest of small doug-firs.  Hill steep at first, but then slope becomes milder at 40-50 meters.
Location_desc: Point is just before the hill drops sharply downward.  Many small 20-50cm DBH doug-firs.  Just west of the point is a large 3m-wide boulder covered in moss with a 40DBH madrone growing at its southern end.

Travel_notes: Descend down steep hillside for 200 meters at 180 degrees.  Travel is open with doug-fir, some madrone, and a salal understory.  Point is just before the road.
Location_desc: The point is on a steep hillside about 25 meters north of the road.  Immediately to the west of the point are many twisted madrones (see picture).

Travel_notes: Travel along road. It is a steep drop to get to it, so you may need to walk parallel to the road until you find a safe spot to slide down.
Location_desc: Point is on the right side of the road as you go down. There are hemlock seedlings and a douglas maple very near the point. A big-leaf maple sapling is directly across the road.

Travel_notes: Travel downhill along road.
Location_desc: Point is on the right side of the road as you walk down.

Travel_notes: Hike 15 minutes from the trailhead up the Happy Lake Ridge Trail.  There is a sharp switchback to the right about 1/3-1/2 of the way.  After that is a long straightaway and then the trail eventually turns to the left.  After this is another sharp switchback to the right.  The TO is about 35-40 meters after the second switchback to the right. Allow about 30 minutes to trailhead from Port Angeles. WW arm is pretty mellow walking, mostly up and down gullies/ridges the whole time, but with agreeable understory.
Location_desc: Point is in open doug-fir forest with salal understory.  The marker tree is to the right side of the trail (to the south) on a doug-fir that is bigger than the other doug-firs around it.

Travel_notes: A sideslope for 100 m through open Doug-fir forest and thick salal understory. Starts to get slightly more open as you get closer to WW01.
Location_desc: There are some hemlock branches extending down to point from upslope. In a garden of salal, but underneath hemlock, there aren't very many. It is about 2 m W of a downed tree.

Travel_notes: Go uphill to ridge at about 75 m. It is gradual until about 135 m, at which point it drops steeply down to WW02.
Location_desc: Salal heaven! About 50 m east of a more level slope (slightly less than 50 m to the end of thick salal if looking W downslope).

Travel_notes: Downhill for ~50 m, then more or less level for about 75 m, and a steep uphill for most of the remainder.
Location_desc: Point is surrounded by manzanita. It is in an area with virtually no groundcover, but there is a circle of manzanita around it. It is in the middle of a broad ridge.

Travel_notes: Gradual travel for ~45 m, then it drops steeply, levels off a bit, then climbs back up at ~150 m.
Location_desc: Point is on steep slope of a ridge (~10 m W of top, if looking E-W). Very little groundcover right at point, but there are a bunch of Doug-fir saplings within 5 m in every direction except SW/W/NW.

Travel_notes: Go down steeply for about 40 m, then it is a gradual downhill/sideslope for the remainder. Point is at far (W) side of a ridge.
Location_desc: You can just barely see the mountains through the trees. On the N edge of a small mossy area with little salal or other groundcover. It is on the W side of a small ridge leading down to creek. Can see a Madrone cluster

Travel_notes: Downhill initially, then gradually shifting into more of a sideslope with changing aspect. Understory gets  more open around halfway to WW06.
Location_desc: Tough point to describe. There are some branches that extend to point from nearby Doug-fir saplings and a ~25 cm DBH hemlock to the E. Lots of salal.

Travel_notes: A sideslope/gradual downhill (through thick salal in parts) initially. At about 140 m, you reach a dropoff. It looks worse than it is. Start heading down at bearing and if it's a bit too steep, go farther S, which is more mellow. There are also pretty developed deer trails, which can help a lot. After crossing drainage, it is more mellow going up the ~25 m to point. Again though, go S if it's too steep (if it is, it's probably because you're N of bearing)
Location_desc: Point is on a steep slope leading down to drainage (not as steep as to the N though- keep that in mind when getting to point). It is about 25 m up from drainage bottom. It is about 0.5m S of a broken-top downed tree. Groundcover mostly bare (with some moss) right at point. It is right at a <10 cm DBH yew tree. If trying to add a point after WW07, go directly north. West and NW are bounded by a loud creek and steep cliff.

Travel_notes: Travel uphill from WW07. Pretty thick salal with occasional mossy open areas
Location_desc: Point is in a forest of mixed conifers with dense salal understory. point very close to a line of trees consisting of a tall barkless snag, a snag with bark on and a yew tree in between

Travel_notes: Continue travel uphill through somewhat thicker salal
Location_desc: Similar forest to WW08. Thick salal below doug-fir, hemlock, cedar and yew. Point right between a pair of 1.5m tall stumps, each 2m away. Just uphill from a small vine maple with a very mossy arching trunk

Travel_notes: Pace 105 meters on trail.
Location_desc: Point is on trail at the end of a large downed tree that you have to climb over where it lies on the trail.  Just past the base of this down tree on the left side of the trail are three patchy-bark snags.  Looking back, there are 2 barkless snags 15m behind you.  There are 2 small 50cm wide pointy stumps at the point on the right side of the trail. T

Travel_notes: Pace 230 meters on trail.
Location_desc: Point is very obvious.  Look for massive double-trunked doug-fir.

Travel_notes: Pace 220 meters on trail.
Location_desc: Point is on a narrow section of trail that traverses a steep mossy hillside.  Just downslope from point is a 50cm tall stump with moss on top.  River is very loud below.

Travel_notes: Pace 205 meters along trail.  Travel is flat for 50 meters, then goes down a small hill.
Location_desc: Point is on trail with many doug-firs around and lots of vanilla leaf understory.  Six meters before point on the right side of the trail is a pistol-butt doug-fir with moss on the curved first meter from ground.  Just past point are several mossy rocks on sides of trail and a 20cm DBH rotting 2 meter tall stump 9 meters past point left side of trail.

Travel_notes: Pace 230 meters on trail.  Point is 30 meters after you cross a stream near the beginning of an open meadow area.
Location_desc: Point is on trail in the middle of an avalanche chute.  There are no trees between the point and Cameron Creek.  Just to the south of the point is a stream bordered by sitka alder. Rocky feature now predominantly featured but picture is still useful. You can tell where the rocks were.

Travel_notes: Travel about 200 meters on trail.  Enter forest again after 50 meters.  Trail stays pretty straight.
Location_desc: Point is on trail just after snag with huge galls.  To the right of the trail at the point is some rotting wood.  The river can be heard below.

Travel_notes: Pace 210 meters on trail.  Trail traverses slope for a while and then starts to descend.  Cross two down logs over trail and then cross two small streams.  Point in low flat open area.
Location_desc: Point is in an open, flat, slightly wet area with doug-fir, silver fir, and a few spruces.  There are lots of snags and downed trees.  Just past point are a bunch of cut rounds of silver-fir on the left side of the trail.  On right side of trail are two tall silver-firs with protruding rootballs.

Travel_notes: Pace 230 meters on trail.
Location_desc: Point is on trail just after four cut logs, two on each side of trail.  Looking behind you (back towards NE07) you can see a large doug-fir that is forked halfway up.  Understory of vanilla leaf.

Travel_notes: Travel north 200 meters.  Travel is flat and easy at first.  It starts getting steeper in the second half of travel.
Location_desc: Point is on a fairly steep hillside.  You can hear the stream ahead of you.  Forest is mainly doug-fir and hemlock with some scattered silver fir.  Understory mossy and open with sparse salal.  Marker tree just downhill from point.

Reason_for_change: Very steep if cont. 360 degrees and creek crossing after NE09
Travel_notes: Going from NE09 a bit tricky because of huge valley steep dip. Consider going back to trail and then going to NE10; I think it will be easier/faster. I'm not sure what bearing to point is (possibly 45 degrees?). Please update this next visit.
Location_desc: Can see river and creek (behind you). Mossy ground cover w/ vanilla leaf and two hemlock samplings. Below toward river is Douglas maple (I think this is what it says). Can see Cameron Creek below and nearby stream up-trail. Mossy ground cover w/vanilla leaf and young hemlocks. Below trail there are Douglas Maple

Travel_notes: Cross over rocky, eroded, trailess edge alongside river. Travel predominantly follows river.
Location_desc: Right next to river, ~9m away. Behind you is eroded rocky trail. Doug-fir forest with huckleberry, Oregon grape, thimbleberry, Douglas maple- very diverse understory.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Snags all around. Predominantly Doug-fir forest. River close and audible. Western hemlock and Doug-fir saplings, rose plant, vanilla leaf and thimbleberry

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On right side of trail there is a Western hemlock w/ DBH 20cm and 3 trunks less than 0.5m up. Huge Doug-firs on both sides of trail. Huckleberry and fern understory. Further up trail, vegetation understory is sparse. River is audible.

Travel_notes: Walk upslope 100 m from trail. The closer you get to NW01, the more open the understory gets.
Location_desc: Point is at the base (upslope side) of a ~80cm DBH Doug-fir (marker tree) in open Doug-fir forest. Some Oregon grape groundcover between point and downed tree that is 1.5 m upslope from point.

Travel_notes: Traverse/climb steadily through mostly Doug-fir forest until ~165-170m, from which point you will be in an avalanche chute for the remainder.
Location_desc: Point is on SW edge of a meadowy avalanche chute. It is actually ~1m into the shrub from the meadow. Creek is very loud. The feature Doug-fir is the furthest upslope of the line of Doug-firs.

Travel_notes: Bushwack through shrub initially to get to creek. After crossing it, transect goes mostly through a meadowy avalanche chute (with occasional shrub and forest) to NW03.
Location_desc: On the S edge of tall willow in an open meadowy avalanche chute overlooking the creek (tallest willow in immediate vicinity). There is some smaller shrub within 10m to the S and SW. Note: Tallest Doug-fir feature distance is an estimate. My rangefinder isn't working for far distances. Correct this next visit.

Travel_notes: Walk downhill through meadowy avalanche chute for ~175m. From beginning of forest, point is about 25m farther.
Location_desc: Dense elderberry at point. There are a lot of downed trees between point and trail (about 15 m away). Surrounded by mostly Subalpine firs.

Travel_notes: Go about 10-15 m down to trail, then pace ~220m until you reach a large boulder (~6 ft. tall at its highest point). Go off-trail NW about 15 m from boulder to NW05.
Location_desc: Point is about 15 m S/SW of a thick band of slide alder, about 15 m NW of the trail. Vanilla leaf groundcover. It is on a rock.

Travel_notes: Drop back down to trail about 15 m and pace about 210 to 215 m up trail to NW06- point is on trail.
Location_desc: Point is actually on trail, right at intersection of a few cut logs. Salmonberry and vanilla leaf dominates understory.

Travel_notes: Pace about 180 m on trail until you reach a meadowy dried-up streambed on uphill side of trail. Go about 50 m NW off-trail up meadow from this point.
Location_desc: Point is in narrow open meadow with a view of a waterfall upslope. The feature Doug-firs are just upslope of some Douglas maple. The point is on a rock the size of a chair.

Travel_notes: About 9 miles from Deer Park to TO.  About 5 miles from junction of Three Forks, Cameron Creek, and Gray Wolf Trails.  Less than 200 meters past TO is former shelter with a flat spot to pitch a tent.  This is also where a large avalanche chute meadow begins.  Beautiful spot, a view of Mt. Cameron. A nice NW arm- lots of birds and pretty mellow walking. If snowpack is light next visit, you can try to access Dose points from here via Cameron and Lost Passes, but right now, Cameron Pass is way too snowy. Beware of salt-seeking deer- best to put everything inside your tent while surveying.
Location_desc: TO is 3 meters north of a log across trail that was cut for the trail portion.  Area southwest of TO is more open with large doug-firs.

Travel_notes: Transect parallels trail for most of 100 m. Easy walking.
Location_desc: In mixed Mtn. hemlock/Pacific silver fir forest. Vaccinium groundcover. About 23 m N of where transect starts to descend. Right at point where slope gets steeper (route to NN02).

Travel_notes: Walk down steep slope until you are within 40 m of open area (basin)- then start looking for features.
Location_desc: Very little understory right at point. There is a view of the small, open basin below through the trees.

Travel_notes: Walk slightly downhill for about 45 m until reaching small basin. It is level and mellow walking for about 90 m after this. After crossing streambed, it goes uphill for the remainder.
Location_desc: It is about 35 m upslope from a rocky streambed. There are 2 cedars E of point (the larger one (~45 cm DBH) is closer at about 5m, smaller (~30 cm DBH) farther one is at 8.5 m). Thick vaccinium. At the base (upslope side) of a ~65 cm DBH silver fir. Note: reddish, rotting stump feature is paler and very different looking when approaching from NN02. I just noticed this after leaving point.

Reason_for_change: too steep N, NE, W, NW
Travel_notes: It starts off as more of a traverse of a steep slope, gradually shifting into more of an uphill climb with an increasing density of vaccinium as you near NN04.
Location_desc: Point is on relatively steep slope in thick vaccinium. There are about 4 barkless, pale, similar-looking snags within 10 m downslope of point.

Travel_notes: Contour along and almost immediately reach a pool with standing water. Stay just to right (you'll be off-bearing, but if you go exactly SE, you will hit a steep (short) drainage that would be difficult to climb out of). After passing pool, go more S to correct bearing. Then continue; travel will be getting increasingly uphill (and steeper) as you near NN05.
Location_desc: About 9m to the SW of point, vegetation gets much thicker with saplings and vaccinium. Right at point, there is very little understory. A lot of rocks immediately surround point (mostly upslope of point). It is on the roots of a ~30cm DBH hemlock (upslope side of).

Travel_notes: The most obscure and roundabout way of getting to the trail. Very steep at times. Go slightly S to avoid cliffs. At ~165m, you will reach ridge. Then you'll drop down and cross trail. Point is about 20m down from trail. Be careful!
Location_desc: Point is on the uphill side of a ~45cm DBH silver fir. It is ~20m downslope of the trail. There are a few large boulders just upslope of point.

Travel_notes: Pace 100 meters at 180 degrees.  Open understory, easy travel.
Location_desc: Point is in open understory amid large hemlocks and silver-firs.  A large rotting down log lies east-west 10 meters past point.

Travel_notes: Travel is mellow for the first 50-75 meters, then becomes much steeper as you continue downhill.
Location_desc: Point is on a steep hillside just before (10 meters) a flat bench area.  There are a number of down rotting logs at point and west of point.  Point is just south of a huge (>122DBH) western hemlock, and there are several small (<30DBH) Pacific Silver-firs just to the west.

Travel_notes: Traverse for the first 50-60 meters.  Then travel down steep incline the rest of the way to the point.
Location_desc: Point is between a large (~100 DBH) 3 meter tall rotting stump and a hemlock that branches into two trunks at 4 meters high.  One of the trunks is dead and the other is still alive.  Hemlock is just uphill of point, stump just downhill.  Shrub understory.

Travel_notes: Traverse across steep slope for 200 meters at 270 degrees.  Slow going because of dense understory.  Point is just past a small drainage as you begin to go uphill once you cross it.
Location_desc: Point is right after you cross a drainage and start to climb up a NE-facing slope.  On the other side of the drainage, it is more open with just a few silver firs, and patches of green herbs.  Point is on rocky ground.

Travel_notes: Travel up steep slope for most of travel.  About 40-50 meters before point SS05, reach the top of hill and drop over the other side.  Last part of travel descend steep hill.
Location_desc: Point is on a steep hillside with silver fir, western hemlock, and huckleberry understory.  Top of ridge is visible to the north and northwest.  Point is right next to a 60cm DBH snag, burnt, with bark only on the lowest one meter.

Travel_notes: Travel uphill and across steep slope. Very thick vaccinium and young silver fir trees. Look for large Doug-fir when close to point.
Location_desc: Point is in a small open space close to two very large Doug-firs, of which there aren't many in the area. Thick young silver firs all around.

Travel_notes: Continue climbing up and across slope from SS06. Vegetation opens up somewhat when you get close to point.
Location_desc: Point in a relatively open area with many downed trees on the slope. Fairly close to the ridgeline, which is nice to travel on when returning to trail!

Travel_notes: Semi-established campsite just past TO on left side of trail, but there are several off-trail camping possibilities within 100 m of TO. Bring water- unreliable source near camp. Check snow conditions on Mink Lake Trail first. We encountered up to >10 ft. continuous snow between ~3500' and ~4100' on N-facing slope on the trail.  A steep, difficult to establish and run NN arm of transect. Very cliffy area, but many do not show up on map. About 6.5 miles in from Sol Duc on Mink Lake Trail. SS arm extremely steep and shrubby. Most of the travel was through very thick waist-high Pacific Silver-Fir saplings and vaccinium spp. Points SS02-05 were difficult to locate - features are decent but terrain is so steep and visibility so low they were difficult to spot unless you were practically on top of them. GPS drifting significantly on SS arm, with this and the steep travel the bearing is not the straightest between points. NN arm also very steep.
Location_desc: Point is in a fairly level area in mtn. hemlock forest. Vaccinium on both sides of trail (~2 m down trail (NW of) from where vaccinium gets thicker on SW side of trail.

Travel_notes: Pace 100m down trail to E. Travel is straight, going up and down some steep slopes.
Location_desc: Point is on flatter section of trail, just before a long steep drop to the E. There is a large white root on the N side of the trail that juts out exactly at point. Several large Doug-firs and small Western hemlocks surround point.

Travel_notes: Pace ~210m down trail to E. Trail goes steeply and then gradually downhill then flattens out before point.
Location_desc: Pt is in flat strip of trail just to the E of a tall broken-off Doug-fir stump with live branches on top. Dense salal covers ground around point.

Travel_notes: Pace 200m down trail to East. Pass through a forest with denser overstory about 50m before point.
Location_desc: Point is on flat stretch of trail, about 50m from the denser red-cedar forest to the W. In open forest past a large Doug-fir snag leaning downslop to W. Moss and Salal cover ground.

Travel_notes: Pace 200m down trail to the East. Cross into a more closed forest with a lot of moss and less salal. Terrain gets flatter to the S.
Location_desc: Pt. is just before a sharp uphill grade in slope and before it turns sharply to the West. Area is very mossy and damp. Lots of stumps surround point and small hemlocks are growing next to the redcedar sapling in the stump next to the trail. Terrain pretty flat in this area.

Travel_notes: Pace 250m on trail to E. Travel upslope for about 160m then trail flattens and goes downslope to point.
Location_desc: Pt. is on downhill slope from EE04, heading toward large stream. No understory except moss. Snag shaped like person is passed on way to EE05. Trail at point is along contour lining large stream.

Travel_notes: Pace 275m on trail to E. Cross two very small rocky creekbeds, and about 147m from EE05, cross large, rapid stream. Crossing is a log across to the N. Continue uphill for another 128m until you get to large clearing with lots of salal.
Location_desc: Pt. is on slope downward to E in middle of dense salal and open forest. There is also a skinny pole-like snag about 2m from point right off trail to the S. Downed tree crosses above trail just upslope of point. (Note: bearing to stump was recorded as 398 degrees. Check on this next visit.)

Travel_notes: Pace down trail 200m to the E. Trail becomes very overgrown at times. Travel through dense salal, mostly downhill.
Location_desc: Point is in open forest with dense salal undergrowth. Lots of stumps but the feature stump is directly across from pt. next to trail. Point is on flat ground where trail is hard to see.

Travel_notes: Pace 200m down trail to E. Trail becomes increasingly overgrown with salal and downed branches. Travel failry flat and indistinctive through open forest with salal undergrowth.
Location_desc: Point is in clearing with dense salal understory and large Doug-firs and Western hemlocks. Crazy tree is somewhat blocked by two conifers close to trail, but you'll know it when you see it. Pt. is on flat area, can't hear river as loud here. Look for very jagged stump on way to point as best indicator.

Travel_notes: Pace 200m on trail to the E. Travel through dense salal undergrowth and open forest for first 150m. Then drop into more closed forest nearing river.
Location_desc: Point is on flat, mossy area with a lot of downed logs. Some very old sawed-off logs are lying near point on the S side of the trail. Gall on small hemlock is round and black and perpendicular from point on trail. Kiss-shaped knob is uphill of point on S side of trail.

Travel_notes: Pace 200m down trail to the E. You will cross a large stream about 50m from EE09. Can either jump or cross on very large downed Doug-fir downstream. There is a faint trail to this log.
Location_desc: Point is on flat area before large river to the S. There are many large Doug-firs around and a lot of old sawed-off logs next to the trail. There is also a small redcedar on the right side of trail just before you reach the point.

Travel_notes: TO about one mile down Lillian River Trail from trail junction. Five mile hike total from Whiskey Bend Road trailhead to TO. Good opportunities to camp off-trail beginning ~500m past TO.
Location_desc: TO is at large Doug-fir snag burned at the base, with a 25cm dbh curved Bigleaf maple growing only a few inches away.

Travel_notes: Pace 100m from TO. Undulating travel.
Location_desc: Point just after passing mossy rock face on right but 15m before the large Doug-fir leaning over the trail. Lots of vine maple on both sides in the understory, especially uphill.

Travel_notes: Pace 210m down trail over undulating terrain.
Location_desc: Point where trail begins to go uphill right beside a huge mossy Doug-fir on left. Doug-fir forest, lots of Douglas maple and vanilla leaf close to point.

Travel_notes: Pace 220m down trail from second point. Mostly level travel, some gradual uphill.
Location_desc: Point on trail at snag on lower (W) end of  small (1m) mossy rock. Open Doug-fir and Western hemlock forest, varied groundcover including Oregon Grape, ferns and Vaccinium.

Travel_notes: Pace 210m down trail. Travel either flat or gradually downhill.
Location_desc: Surrounded by very open Doug-fir and Western hemlock forest (mid-aged) in which most trees are covered by lichen.

Travel_notes: Pace 210 down trail. Travel is mostly downhill.
Location_desc: Point in forest of lichen-covered Doug-fir. Downhill side of trail has groundcover of low salal, uphill side has more open ground. Several madrone trees beginning near trail ~10m past point.

Travel_notes: Pace 200m down trail. Travel downhill, trail winds gradually.
Location_desc: Point is at small opening in trees on left with steep open dirt/rock hill. Point is at the last of the madrona trees.

Travel_notes: Pace 220m down trail, mostly downhill. Trail winds back and forth.
Location_desc: small "clearing" on left, lots of salal and lichen-covered Doug-firs. Uphill mixed-age Doug-fir forest on right.

Travel_notes: Pace 210m down trail. Slightly downhill travel.
Location_desc: Point on trail between two large Doug-firs (one on each side of trail). Right side of trail slightly uphill and totally moss-covered with patchy salal. Left side of trail flat and moss-covered with patchy salal. Many small Doug-firs and Western hemlocks on left side of trail are either dead or only retaining their uppermost foliage.

Travel_notes: Continue traveling down trail for 140m until you reach the trail junction. Travel due W through young Western hemlock/Doug-fir forest with a groundcover of thick salal. Turn right at trail junction for 10m before heading due W.
Location_desc: Point is in very small mossy clearing amongst low but fairly thick salal and next to a 75cm dbh lichen-covered Doug-fir (largest tree in the immediate area).

Travel_notes: Slog through thick salal for first 110m before entering flat and open Doug-fir forest with lots of small downed trees and mossy groundcover. Travel relatively easy and flat.
Location_desc: Point is in very open Doug-fir forest by a stand of clustered large trees. Old burn scars on many of these larger trees. It is ~22m N/NE of edge of where slope drops steeply.

Travel_notes: Walk through pretty flat terrain. As you get closer to point, there is an increasing number of downed trees.
Location_desc: Point is on a very large downed tree. It is ~12m NE of where it starts to drop steeply (near forked maple feature). It is on the tallest down tree in the immediate vicinity. Mainly vanilla leaf and bleeding heart on both sides of downed tree right at point. There is a small blowdown area immediately to the NE of point.

Travel_notes: Head up trail toward Constance Pass.
Location_desc: Point is at the top of the first switchback, right before you head left up the trail.

Travel_notes: Head up the trail to Constance Pass.  When you can see Mt. Constance you are close.
Location_desc: on trail.

Travel_notes: Head up and over rise towards Constance Pass.  Head down a few small switchbacks and stop about 20 meters past last turn in trail as it heads straight down ridge.
Location_desc: on trail.  pretty sweet views.

Travel_notes: Head downhill as the trail winds its way through clumps of subalpine fir.  Point is at the last small clump of trees on the left side of the trail.
Location_desc: On trail next to two skinny subalpine firs, with a few shorter ones around them.  Right one taller, 2.5 meters tall and left one shorter.

Travel_notes: Head down trail and through lupine patches. Point is opposite middle clump of three large clumps of subalpine firs on the right.
Location_desc: On trail, lots of lupine to the right and cute little ground-dwelling subalpine fir scattered in front of the three major clumps described above.

Travel_notes: Head down trail until you reach the last clump of subalpine fir on the left.
Location_desc: On trail, relatively straight section.  Sweet flowers.

Travel_notes: Head down trail, through a small clump of various sizes of trees, and stop 15 meters before you get to a double misshapen subalpine fir right next to trail on right side.
Location_desc: On trail before it drops more steeply down to the pass.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Can see Home Lake from point and excellent view of mountains shaded by cluster of hemlock to the right and a cluster of Subalpine firs to the left on edge of trail. Point is in middle of trail between Subalpine fir and Mtn. hemlock. If in 5 years, the bent, broken snag is only a stump, it would be 2-2.5m tall.

Travel_notes: Follow a trickly stream.
Location_desc: Can see part of Home Lake, very open. Shrub to S and some vegetation to the N/NW

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On trail shady. Small ankle high shrub growing. Some grass but mostly rocky and Subalpine fir forest. In between large subalpine fir feature and ~20cm DBH subalpine fir on "right" side of trail.

Travel_notes: Rocky travel some large boulders. Some shrub and hardy moss/lichen. Can be slippery because of dead needles but easy travel. Come out of forest canopy to an open area on a rock facing a scree cliff face and that's where the point is.
Location_desc: Standing on a huge boulder looking at mountains and scree rock face ridge to E. There is an isolated patch of trees of short Whitebark Pine, triangular shaped, 326m away from point at 141 degrees. There are Subalpine firs where you came out of into the open (W/NW). Boulder the size of a semi-truck.

Travel_notes: Traverse slightly gaining elevation for 100 m at 360 degree bearing. All open, easy walking. Look for features.
Location_desc: In meadowy area, about 4 m SE of more sparsely vegetated area. Common juniper abundant right at point.

Travel_notes: Go up to ridge in the most northerly direction possible. From ridge, start walking up to high point from saddle. Point is about 45 m W of ridge.
Location_desc: Point is on a steep scree slope leading down to Sunnybrook Meadows. There is a line of Whitebark pines downslope (and slightly to N/NW) of point. It is exactly in line with point and Mt. Olympus. It is in a very slight dip in the terrain.

Travel_notes: Climb back up scree slope to ridge, then follow ridge up to high point along it. After that point, ridge will wrap around more to the NW. Point is about 50 m NE of ridge where it starts to change directions.
Location_desc: Snowy this visit. On gentle slope before it drops off more steeply to the N and NE.

Travel_notes: 100% snow this visit. Just go down slope at 360 degree bearing- use GPS and look for features.
Location_desc: Hard to describe point and come up with features because it is 100% snow-covered right now. Use GPS as much as possible- it's very open. About 10 m upslope of where slope increases. It is at the base of a rock outcrop. When it isn't snowy, it is on a steep scree slope.

Reason_for_change: too steep and snowy N and NE
Travel_notes: Route 100% snow-covered this visit, but basically just use rangefinder and compass to get approximate location and find easiest route based on that.
Location_desc: Point is on a rocky ridge leading steeply downslope. Common juniper and rock groundcover. Mt. Constance and Warrier visible beyond 3 ~15cm DBH subalpine firs (see features).

Travel_notes: Climb down steep scree slope (go a bit south if it's too steep), then carefully make your way down narrower scree slope (lined with a few subalpine firs) to saddle. From there, drop down scree slope (on side facing the fortress) ~45m to point.
Location_desc: Point is on a steep scree slope, ~45m down from saddle. There is some sparse vegetation just E of point, but otherwise just scree. Look for obvious Subalpine fir(s) in middle of scree- you can see it from miles away.

Travel_notes: Climb back up to saddle you were just at, then follow ridge NE(ish) to point.
Location_desc: Point is on a flat area on ridge. Immediately to the E, the slope increases. You can't see the lake below from point, but if you walk a few steps in any direction, you can. Heather and rock right at point.

Travel_notes: Hike up trail to Constance Pass.  From transect 3124, would take about an hour and a half to hike up to the top (the "fortress"), a camping spot near TO.  Awesome transect!!  Camped at the high spot on the map, called the fortress.  A 5-minute walk to the TO.  Sunset, stars, and sunrise all spectacular. Beautiful and snowy transect. Transect established differently than would have been otherwise due to extreme quantities of snow (see logistic notes).
Location_desc: On trail to Constance Pass, at the upper edge of a switchback that turns right immediately after.  About 250 meters from the top of a ridge leading down to Constance Pass.

Travel_notes: Walk up trail 100m.
Location_desc: Point is on trail (I think - it might be slightly off due to snow) with some fairly sizeable Mtn. Hemlocks on S side of trail. There are massive >10 foot deep snow drifts right now - it's difficult to assess steepness of trail here. Several snags up trail (within 10m on S side).

Travel_notes: Walk up trail 200m, passing Silver Snag Camp at ~150m. All snow-covered right now.
Location_desc: Not entirely sure I am exactly on trail (lots of snow), but I am close. Update next visit if bearings/distances need it. About 10m beyond point (E) on trail, it becomes more open on N side. Right at point are mostly subalpine firs on S side.

Travel_notes: Walk on trail the whole way - not sure exact pacing because I was probably not on trail for most part of it due to snow.
Location_desc: On N side of trail is all open, S side Subalpine fir and Mtn. Hemlock. There is a flat sloped rock on trail right at point, but there may be more - this is the only 5m stretch of trail in vincinity that isn't snow-covered.

Reason_for_change: could go off-trail and be far enough from other observer
Travel_notes: 200m downhill through snow.
Location_desc: Snow. What else to say??

Travel_notes: Another 100% snow-covered route - an easy downhill glissade.
Location_desc: Use GPS as much as possible - entirely open here. Snowy!

Travel_notes: A 200m glissade from EE05
Location_desc: A good view of Morganroth Lake from point. There is a rocky area (can't tell if it's a rocky outcrop with snow situation) starting about 6m to the W with some cedars (smaller) and larger mtn. hemlocks behind (W of) cedars.

Travel_notes: Go downhill on bearing, but if slope becomes too sleep, try to find a more gradual way down (I went farther E which was fine). At ~185m you will reach a creek. It is pretty easy to cross, even with snowmelt being rampant right now. You may need to go off-bearing slightly to find good crossing spot.
Location_desc: About 9m N of a loud creek/stream. In snow right now - probably heather underneath? It is open between point and creek, not so much anywhere else.

Travel_notes: Uphill the whole way through mostly open forest. There are a few potentially slick rocky areas, but you can easily get around them.
Location_desc: Less than 1m upslope of a cluster of Mtn. Hemlocks (and one subalpine fir). Upslope of point is mostly beargrass, heather, and huckleberry. There is some pale downed wood starting ~2m N/NE of point.

Travel_notes: Go downslope @360 degrees for 100m
Location_desc: Open meadow? Totally snow covered...

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Open area? Totally snow covered...

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Next to a few tiny hemlocks and firs near top of an exposed rock that slants downhill at ~15 degrees

Travel_notes: Go off transect at ~270 degrees to avoid dropping into steep gully with stream. Once past gully, head for small knoll with ~9 white snags and as many trees.
Location_desc: On moderate-steep slope in grove of small hemlocks. A somewhat flat area with some small exposed rocks to NE 25 degrees. ~7m away with good view of Mt. Appleton and lakes.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: On a knoll amidst Mountain Hemlock overlooking Morganroth Lake about 165m away.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Next to 3 small cedars on rocky slope of heather and huckleberry ~16m from edge of Moganroth Lake.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: In relatively open area above lake with 1 huge Mtn. Hemlock nearby and a large hemlock grove upslope to west.

Travel_notes: Head up moderate heather slopes into hemlock forest then to small saddle at ridgetop. Head down a steeper slope for ~50m to point.
Location_desc: On steep slope amidst Mtn. Hemlock with some Subalpine Fir and Yellow Cedar. Overlooking drainage into Long Lake. There is one Yellow Cedar (20cm dbh) 2m upslope next to a smaller fir surrounded by Mtn. Hemlock

Travel_notes: About a 5-minute (or less) walk from Silver Snag Camp on High Divide. Access via Heart Lake or Deer Lake (it's about halfway along Seven Lakes Basin loop). Access from Deer Lake is sketchier than Heart Lake if snowy. Bring sunglasses, sunscreen, light-colored clothing, whatever your preferred survival tactics employed under extremely bright conditions. Bring trekking poles if snowy, for the hike in and for the transect. If it isn't too snowy, this transect could be hellaciously buggy - plan for that, too.
Location_desc: TO is on saddle on High Divide. There are 2 large Mtn. Hemlocks (one has marker) on S side of trail at point. It is a very mellow slope N of trail leading into basin. Farther E and W, it is steeper.

Travel_notes: Walk off-trail 100 meters.  You will cross creek at ~60-70 meters.
Location_desc: Point is ~7 meters past thick slide alder thicket.  It continues upslope for ~10 meters to the east of the point.  Right at the base (uphill side) of a ~90cm DBH cedar. There is a ~15cm DBH pistol-gripped cedar <1 m upslope of point.

Travel_notes: Walk uphill over lots of downed trees, passing some massive yellow cedars. You will get increasingly close to a seep/stream as you near the point.
Location_desc: Point is ~6m NW of a small seep (and beginning of thick slide alder). Vanilla leaf at point, not much else.  There are a bunch of saplings to the NW (~10 meters).

Travel_notes: Travel is very steep from NE02. There is a major headwell almost directly on N bearing (slightly more NE), but even if going due N it is still sketchy in spots.  Stay low (well below steepest stuff) and go slightly to the W.  Once it isn't as steep, go straight up N and correct once you get to the ridge.
Location_desc: Point is on N sie of a small ridge (N side leading down to Black and White Lakes).  Beautiful view of mountains on both sides from here.  It is where ridge dips slightly before ascending steeply on east side, gradually on west side.  Some small mountain hemlocks and Subalpine Firs in line with point on ridge. Some may be buried under snow right at point?

Travel_notes: Drop down initially for ~20m, then gradually ascend (while traversing) slope to point.
Location_desc: Point is on slope above Black and White Lakes. 100% snow-covered right now, except for a few rock outcrops.  Just upslope from cedar/hemlock cluster (see features).

Travel_notes: Traverse snowy slope (this visit snowy), gradually gaining elevation the whole way. Point is on far edge of small rocky outcrop.
Location_desc: Right now, point is one of the only spots not covered in snow. It is on far (NE) edge of a small rocky outcrop. Heather and low shrub under/when there is no snow. There are a bunch of medium-sized boulders.  There are 2 small mountain hemlocks. Saplings ~1 meter upslope from point.

Travel_notes: Walk up ~40 meters to where it starts to get more forested (briefly).  At ~70 meters, it breaks out into open habitat and goes downhill for remainder (through blinding snow this visit).
Location_desc: Point is in open area - snow right now,but there is shrub/heather underneath.  Bring sunglasses if snowy!  To the NW and SE are mostly Mountain hemlocks, but not growing very densely.

Travel_notes: Walk downslope, using a wide drainage for part of the time for easy walking. Very mellow route.
Location_desc: Point is ~2m SW of small seep. It is ~6m up from where seep drops steeply down. Open here- primarily heather and low shrub groundcover.

Travel_notes: You will have to pick your way downslope (steep at times). You can initially walk down drainage that is slightly E of bearing, but then you'll have to go off-bearing a couple of times again to avoid steep dropoffs.
Location_desc: Point is right at point beyond which you cannot travel any farther without it being too steep. And if there is snow here, you might not want to go to this point. There is a nice view of Smith Lake. To the SE is a steep slope down to loud creek. There are a few large rocks right around point.

Travel_notes: pace 100 meters down the trail
Location_desc: On trail, descending but before a sharper descent.  About 5 meters after a few roots in the trail.

Travel_notes: Pace ~300 meters down trail from TO. Point is shortly after switchback to the right, after a huge cut Douglas-fir log.
Location_desc: On point in the trail, just past a log cut on either side of the trail.  Another, older cut log is upslope of the point. Several yew trees on either side of trail.

Travel_notes: Pace 200 meters down the trail.
Location_desc: On the slope with views of the creek. Many youn and old silver firs and vine maples just before reaching point.

Travel_notes: Pace ~400m down trail. Cross a creek (may be difficult) ~50 trail meters before the point. Point is one step after a sharp rock on the right side of the trail (watch your ankles!). If you get to the trail fork, you have gone too far.
Location_desc: Abundant ground cover around the trail. Alder, devil's club. Open view of creek. Level section of trail.  Small step with sharp rock to the right is just before point. A nice-looking campside can be seen down by the creek.

Travel_notes: Pace 200 meters down the trail.  After ~40 m, turn left onto Flapjack Trail.
Location_desc: Smaller diameter fallen Silver Fir, cut at either side of the trail. Abundant vanilla leaf ground cover. Several Pacific silver fir snags close by.

Travel_notes: Travel ~400m, paced on trail, turning left at the junction and heading towards Flapjack. After making a switchback to the right with a tall log-step, the point is right at the following hard switchback to the left, among rocks and roots.
Location_desc: At the hard-left switchback, described above, at the edge of a Pacific Silver Fir forest..

Travel_notes: Travel 200 meters down the trail.
Location_desc: Mossy cut log downslope, large rock next to the trail, upslope.  Silver fir with orange trail marker is right next to the point.  Downed log suspended 3 meters above trail just beyond point.

Travel_notes: Travel 200 meters SE up a wide gully through sparse vegetation and devil's club. Use GPS to reach the point on trail where you are ~100m away at ~120 degrees. You will have just passed a huge root wad [feature], and leave the trail at a tree on the right marked with an orange trail marker.
Location_desc: Open understory. Point upslope of a marked cedar, downslope of large fallen cedar that is suspended ~1 meter off ground.

Travel_notes: Follow 135 degree bearing up an initially steep slope that levels out. Pass a massive boulder on your right-hand side at ~150m.
Location_desc: On top of a fallen log, with many snags and young trees around. The log that the point is on intersects the trail to the NW.

Travel_notes: Cross trail and follow bearing to point, navigating boulder field. You have to leave bearing at times, so travel is a bit meandering.
Location_desc: Immediately NW of a smaller boulder, with many snags in area.

Travel_notes: Navigate a steepening boulder field that flattens out ~20m before point.
Location_desc: Point is on top of a relatively small boulder with a decomposed log on top. Massive boulder/cliff is to the west.

Travel_notes: About a 35-40 minute walk from Flapjack Lakes, depending on snow conditions.  2011:Black and White Lakes is a great camping spot, but too snowy right now- it wouldn't be too much difference in distance from camping at Flapjack.  NE arm is very steep between NE02 and NE03. Pay attention to the instructions in order to avoid headwall. Take it slow. Bring sunglasses for NE arm, especially if it's snowy. Hike down from Black and White lakes takes about ~30 minutes. Another option would be the sites by the creek at the Flapjack/Black and White Lakes junction.
Location_desc: Just after a very steep section of the trail, the trail levels out a bit before crossing a creek. Where the trail curves softly right, about 20 meters before reaching the creek. Just next to the featured leaning cedar.

Travel_notes: Walk down trail just over 100 m from TO.
Location_desc: Point is on trail, right where the south side of the trail (right) becomes more open. Point is right where that last subalpine fir is.  Lost Peak is straight ahead. There is a loudish stream just down trail.

Travel_notes: Walk down trail slightly more than  200m (hard to pace because of steep trail and snow).
Location_desc: Point is on trail, ~15m W of start of slope down to bottom of basin. It is in an open area, about 45 m after it breaks out of the trees.

Travel_notes: Best way is probably to go more N, skirting the west edge of trees. Once you are past the trees, veer E (and slightly N) to point.
Location_desc: Point is ~35 m N of area with more trees. Surrounded by avalanche lillies. There is a flat rectangular rock right at the point.

Travel_notes: Walk gradually uphill- it is entirely open the whole way.
Location_desc: Completely open here.  You can just barely see Mt. Olympus peaking out to the W down drainage. Lots of glacier and avalanche lilies where there isn't snow.
