Travel_notes: Walk across slope, gradually gaining elevation as you go.  The only thing of note is a line of trees that you walk through toward end.
Location_desc: Point is ~15-20m E of a faily big (for this area) line of trees.  You can see Mt. Anderson poking through behind the W slope up Lost Peak.  There is a small creek ~35-40m to the E.

Travel_notes: Walk gradually uphill the whole way. There was one snow-bridge-covered creek to cross this visit about 35m from EE05.
Location_desc: Point is in snow with a formidable view of Lost Peak. Look for features- otherwise hard to describe.

Travel_notes: Gradual uphill the whole way over snow.
Location_desc: Point is ~15m upslope of where slope gets steeper. I believe there is a stream right before slope gets steeper (if coming from EE06). There is a cluster of subalpine firs ~15m to the SW.

Travel_notes: I went a little further S than bearing initially, dropped below line of trees and then climbed up to basin where lake is.  Go around to far side of lake. 100% snow this visit.
Location_desc: Point is on W side of small lake that is mostly frozen right now, but I think point is ~15m away from it.  No idea what substrate surrounds lake- it's all snow now.

Travel_notes: Walk past the lake EE08 is on, and through very open habitat all the way to point.
Location_desc: There is a small snowmelt seep ~5m to the S of point- may be more or less obvious, depending on snowmelt. It is at the base of some steeper rock. Mt. Olympus is in view over the subalpine firs feature.

Travel_notes: Head down steep open slope, through some willows, more open ground and then a short bit of subalpine fir.
Location_desc: Small opening amidst subalpine fir groves. Open meadows to the East and the NE, dense forest to the W. Point is on the edge of forest.

Travel_notes: Head downslope at about 160 degrees into a riparian corridor and keep following this stream course through a meadow all the way to SS02.
Location_desc: On bare rocky slope above active stream channel. Point next to spring/seep that feeds into small stream that flows south (~200 degrees).

Travel_notes: Head downslope 30 m in slippery stream channel on steep terrain.  Go past cluster of 5 snags onto easier ground and enter a wet marsh of thick willow before ragaining subalpine fir forests below.
Location_desc: Attractive meadow surrounded by subalpine fir. Point is on edge of NW arm of meadow. Good views of (from E to SW) Lost Peak, Lost Pass, top of Mount Fromme, and Mt. Claywood. Relatively flat.

Travel_notes: Exit SS03 meadow towards Mt. Fromme and head downhill on bearing through some thick patches of fir and cedar and one wet open meadow.
Location_desc: In a small clearing with a seep, overlooking willow area below.

Reason_for_change: torrential creek with sketchy snow bridges
Travel_notes: Head towards gray snag, traversing down mellow slope for ~120m then starting to head down slightly steeper terrain past 2 distinct openings, the first of which is a good size meadow.
Location_desc: Open somewhat bare area on rocky slope surrounded by subalpine fir.  Small stream to west of point. Views of ridgeline across valley (Lost River).

Travel_notes: Head mostly downhill, contouring down valley first through subalpine fir, then mixed fir and cedar. Various small openings with small streams along the way.
Location_desc: In wet area with many small streams amidst Yellow Cedar groves. Relatively open canopy. Many white cedar snags in vicinity. Point is on a ~30cm DBH cedar that has a long horizontal taproot trunk above-ground.

Travel_notes: Start by crossing wet cedar grove, then go through to Pacific Silver Fir forest with occasional openings, half traversing, half downhill.  Many downed logs. Many snags.
Location_desc: Pacific Silver Fir forest with many downed logs nearby. Relatively open understory.

Travel_notes: We camped at Lost Pass because Lost Basin was full of snow. From Lost Pass, it took us about 45 minutes, but route was 90% snow-covered, so it may take less time next visit. Definitely scout this out the day before and if it's snowy, try to leave obvious tracks for the morning. For this panel, we surveyed all 4 Dose transects together, ending with this one. Beautiful! From Lost Pass, it takes about 30 minutes without snow.
Location_desc: On open steep meadowy slope 20 m past a stream crossing (if traveling toward Cameron Pass from Lost Pass). Overlooking Lost River headwaters to south and east. 20 m more on trail will bring you back into fir forest.

Travel_notes: Walk down road until you reach bend - see notes below.
Location_desc: Point is about 5 m N of the road - it is basically right off-road from the major bend (about 5m up from the end of bend).

Travel_notes: I tried to walk slightly S of bearing to stay in the open for longer, but I had to drop significantly N when I got closer to point. It worked though. I dropped down a narrow meadowy chute and cut E once I hit the correct Northing.
Location_desc: There is a cluster where several fallen trees intersect, creating a sort of doomy jungle feel. See above for specifics. There is actually another one of these intersections about 11 m to the SW, but with slightly larger trees (largest ~40cm dbh). Open forest, no understory, snow!

Reason_for_change: Too steep, didn't want to get trapped
Travel_notes: Walk for ~40 m through moderately thick forest. After ~40 m, it becomes more patchy forest and you can weave around some small stands or clusters. The last ~20 m is back to solid forest.
Location_desc: There is an open area ~20 m to the NW of point. Lots of snags near point. Very little understory or groundcover. Really hard to find features.

Travel_notes: Walk uphill through Subalpine fir forest for ~105 m, then it will open up (all snow now) for the remainder. The last ~95 m are a ridge walk.
Location_desc: Point is on N side of ridge. It is on the E edge of some Subalpine Fir layering and ~4 m below start of small rock outcrop. View of Olympics and Strait from here.

Travel_notes: Walk through open meadow the whole way, slightly downhill.
Location_desc: Point is in open meadow. To the SW (~2 m ) begins more substantial common juniper. GPS should work great here. There is a very small lodgepole sapling between point and feature white pine (which is larger).

Travel_notes: Walk SE down to trail. Walk ~ 165 m down trail. There will be 2 large Lodgepoles growing close together very close to trail on S side (at ~145 m ) - 20 m past that, go S off trail for ~30 m to point.
Location_desc: Point is on E edge of Subalpine fir / Lodgepole pine stand. The feature multi-trunked lodgepole is surrounded by common juniper and some saplings.

Travel_notes: Best way is to walk back up to trail from EE06 and walk down trail ~175 m until you are directly S of point. Then walk ~20 m N off-trail to point.
Location_desc: Point is ~ 20 m above trail - very little groundcover here. Mostly loose, fine rock. About 7 m to the N, there is a line of trees (pines, subalpine firs, Doug-firs).

Travel_notes: Walk NE across loose rocky slope (easy though) for 100m. Then enter subalpine fir forest and go uphill. Point is just over ridge.
Location_desc: Sparse subalpine fir forest on slope facing NW. Small clearling 10m to SE of point. No obvious features!

Travel_notes: About a 10-minute walk from Deer Park Campground, up Blue Mountain Rd. About 100m up road from end of major bend in road.
Location_desc: TO is right in line with the largest and closest to the road boulder along this stretch of road (on N side). There are some close-to-road boulders on S side of road (just to E of point), but they aren't as close as obvious one on N side.

Travel_notes: Walk through meadow, heading for rock outcrop. Stop when you reach the juniper.
Location_desc: Point is in meadow on E edge of common juniper that extends almost to rock outcrop to the W. Very open here - GPS should work well.

Travel_notes: I don't have a good description because thunderstorm was approaching and I bailed. Generally though, it is a mellow walk, mostly open through patches of Subalpine Fir, slightly downhill while contouring a slope.
Location_desc: Point is on N edge of Subalpine Fir cluster. To the N is mostly common juniper mixed in with some herbaceous veg. There is a cluster of subalpine fir directly upslope (16m) of point that has "layering" of Subalpine Fir downslope.

Travel_notes: Traverse slope initially, hitting an open area of loose soil that you will cross. After this, it goes through patchy Subalpine Fir and open areas, gradually becoming more of a downhill as you go.
Location_desc: Point is ~0.5m upslope from a large downed tree (significant because there aren't many around). Pt. itself is on loose soil but immediately surrounding it in all directions is common juniper. Road is just barely visible from pt. (~25m up from road). Several pines around point.

Travel_notes: Walk down very steeply to road (just go however looks safest/easiest). After crossing road, walk ~170m downhill (steeply at times) to WW04.
Location_desc: Point is in an open spot, the groundcover dominated by common juniper. There is a view of Grand Ridge. There is an old downed tree (or 2) less than a meter downslope from point. Mostly Subalpine Firs around pt. but look for feature pine. Note: photo has root wad in it too (see back right).

Travel_notes: Walk downhill the whole way. It gets a bit more densely vegetated at the end.
Location_desc: Point is in between the branches of 2 trees, threatening to poke your eye out at any second. The tree to the N is a ~75cm dbh Doug-fir and the one to the S is actually 2 Subalpine Firs connected at base (>70cm dbh). Little understory right at point.

Travel_notes: Walk downhill through forest with moderate-sized trees. At ~100m, there will be a wet meadow. Walk on N side of meadow for ~40m, then emerge into much darker forest, gradually getting darker and trees smaller and closer together as you near point.
Location_desc: In thick doghair forest. Hard to see very far from here, though it seems brighter to the N. There is a pile of large downed trees within ~7m to the S/SE.

Travel_notes: Walk through dense doghair for ~50m, then emerge into more open forest. From there, it is a mellow gradual downhill for the remainder.
Location_desc: Point is in open forest - difficult to find features. Very little understory, but lots of downed trees (small though). There is a cluster of hemlock saplings ~7m to the S/SE. There are other Doug-firs that look similar to ~30cm DBH Doug-fir with chunk missing feature- see photo.

Travel_notes: A pretty mellow (possibly wet) 100m from TO, slightly downhill for most of it.
Location_desc: Point is ~5m SW of stream. Snowy this year. It will probably be/feel thicker next visit if no snow and more is leafed-out. Marker is visible from relatively far away.

Travel_notes: Walk through woods until it opens up.  Aim for the rocky outcropping up against thick shrub. If nobody is camping in farthest up valley site at Honeymoon, access may be easier by way of that site.
Location_desc: The point is on the W edge of rock outcrop.  It is between rock outcrop and small stream/where thick shrubs begin to grow. A beautiful, unobstructed view of meadows and the flanks of Mt. Anderson.

Travel_notes: Go ~25m W to reach trail through camp. Best way is to walk to the end of the trail (on W side of river) and walk (roughly) N for ~50 m to point.
Location_desc: Point is on S edge of HUGE avalanche-caused blowdown (hundreds of meters). It is about 15 m W of river. There are piles upon piles of downed trees here. This could look very different next visit.

Travel_notes: Best way to go is to cross the river at the ford, walk to the privy, and walk ~100-110m NE (approximately) to point.
Location_desc: The point is in a fairly level spot with some huckleberry around. Not much else for groundcover.  Several Pacific Silver Firs surround the point.

Travel_notes: Walk through occasionally thickly vegetated, gradual uphill, dipping slightly (briefly) after about 40-50 m.
Location_desc: The point is about 1m upslope of a ~90cm dbh Pacific Silver Fir.  There is a young Pacific Silver Fir whose branches extend past the point. It is ~7m upslope of a large downed tree running more or less E-W.

Travel_notes: Walk through dense huckleberry up a moderate slope. Travel is slow, particularly when it's wet and slippery.
Location_desc: Point is <1m NE of a moderate-sized downed tree running upslope-downslope. Intersection of downed trees (feature) is just upslope- one of them is up against a ~65cm DBH silver fir. Dense huckleberry, but right at point, there is an old, decayed log, so not as many huckleberries are growing.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Fallen tree wedged between 2 Yellow Cedars at point.  Shrubby underbrush and saplings. The 2nd wedged tree is between a cedar and a fir.

Travel_notes: Go back to trail and continue southward.
Location_desc: LaCrosse Pass Trail is 5 meters away.

Travel_notes: Head off trail when trail turns sharply left.
Location_desc: In somewhat open area right before transect at 180 degrees drops into steep gorge with stream.

Reason_for_change: Steep snowy gorge with torrential stream
Travel_notes: 2016: found a game trail that parallels the creek, but is above gorge in shrubby area, helps travel a bit.
Location_desc: In mix of subalpine fir, Mountain hemlock and yellow cedar. Broken snag has fallen log uphill of it. Slope relatively mild.

Travel_notes: Last 80m gets quite steep. 50m from SS04 begins a wet open area that persists for ~40 more meters and is south of transect.
Location_desc: On a rather steep slope in dense mixed Yellow cedar, Mountain hemlock and slightly more dominant Pacific Silver- fir. There is another small cedar downslope, point is on its roots.

Travel_notes: Perhaps the fastest option is to head to the trail at ~52m, then head up trail, but it is a bit steep.
Location_desc: In Mountain hemlock grove on moderate slope with Pacific Silver fir abundant outside 20m. Small snag (18cm DBH) next to larger Mountain Hemlocks, with 2 similarly small shoots on downward slope, at point.

Travel_notes: Head east on trail, then jump off after ~100m.
Location_desc: Subalpine Fir and Mountain Hemlock forest with views of Mt. Lacrosse and Mt. Anderson through trees. Not far from Lacrosse Pass trail.

Travel_notes: About a 15-minute walk from Honeymoon Meadows, but allow for extra time to ford the knee-deep creek. Bring sandals for initial river crossing and for NN arm, be prepared to cross multiple times. You can also camp where the Lacrosse Pass trail intersects with the Dose/Anderson trail.
Location_desc: Point is ~(?)m after crossing through a wet meadowy area where there is a foot-log over part of it. There are some cedar branches extending over point from SE (right) side of trail. On left side (NW), it is open compared to before and after point.

Travel_notes: A mellow uphill through open forest to NE01.
Location_desc: Point is in open Subalpine fir forest with very little understory right at point (surrounding areas have more herbaceous vegetation). Lots of downed trees, downslope of point in particular.

Travel_notes: A mellow gradual uphill for most of the way. At about 170m, aspect changes and it is downhill for the remainder. There is a random human-constructed rock wall in gully that you will cross near end. Is this an old road bed?
Location_desc: Point is within 10 m (NW of) edge of open area/start of steep slope up to ridge. Snowy right now, but it is probably meadowy otherwise. Very little groundcover at point; just loose soil duff, and some rocks. There are other rock piles in area- look at photo.

Travel_notes: Best way is to backtrack slightly to attain ridge. Then walk up ridge until suddenly the road is in view and alarmingly close. At that point, it more or less parallels the road for the remaining ~30-40 m.
Location_desc: Point is about where it breaks out into meadow to the W (maybe ~7-8 m until there are no trees at all). Road is just barely visible from here. Lots of Subalpine fir saplings to the N.

Travel_notes: Traverse slope through meadow and small stands of Subalpine fir. Easy travel; parallels road the whole way.
Location_desc: Point is less than 1 m S of small rock outcrop with some Subalpine fir layering spreading over it. It is ~65 m NE of Obstruction Pt. Rd. Lots of comon juniper starting ~2-3 m NE of point.

Travel_notes: Traverse slope, gradually gaining elevation as you go. Most of it is meadow with some small stands of trees mixed in.
Location_desc: Point is in middle of meadow. Obstruction Point Rd. is visible from point. Beautiful view of Bailey Range- a great point! Use GPS- it is entirely open.

Travel_notes: Walk uphill through meadow, going slightly S of bearing to avoid trees. Once you reach the top of ridge, use GPS and walk downslope N-ish about 13 m to point
Location_desc: Point is on scree/meadow slope with view across valley to Klahhane Ridge. Very open- use GPS here. It is about 13 m down from ridge.

Reason_for_change: Too steep E, NE, and SE
Travel_notes: The best way is to go back up to high point just above NE06, then walk until you reach the ridge that runs generally N-S. Walk down the ridge until it levels off, then look for features.
Location_desc: Poine is on a relatively level part of the ridge. It is about 2 m W of edge of slope leaning down to bowl. To the W is all open, to the E is a Subalpine fir stand.

Travel_notes: Easy travel through meadow down to point. I stayed slightly more to the E/SE initially to avoid dense stands of subalpine fir.
Location_desc: Point is in meadow ~25m upslope from the road. There are 2 small subalpine firs ~11m upslope of point (and slightly to the N). Right at point is mainly herbaceous, but dense common juniper starts ~3m to the S.

Travel_notes: Pace 100 m from TO.
Location_desc: Even-aged Subalpine fir forest. Pace 100m from TO.

Travel_notes: Can use rangefinder to bend in road at ~160 m and then again to point ~40 m farther.
Location_desc: On west side of road, 40 m N of a bend.

Travel_notes: none
Location_desc: Open Subalpine fir forest with a moderate amount of downed trees.

Travel_notes: Gradual downhill through tangle of huckleberry, azalea, and Subalpine fir.
Location_desc: None. Note: please update next visit, adding features if you can find any.

Travel_notes: Gentle downhill for first 150m, then very steep through open meadows for the last 50m. Stop when you see the slide alder 20 m ahead.
Location_desc: N edge of cliff/clearing, just S of minor ridge between point and drainage. Single 50cm DBH Subalpine fir in meadow area at point, slide alder downslope. Lupine, paintbrush, and view to west.

Travel_notes: Cross ridge, then drop steeply to stream and climb out. Go east of bearing to avoid slide alder on N side of stream.
Location_desc: Dense Subalpine fir, numerous logs criss-cross point. Avalanche lily groundcover. Stream audible to south. Fairly level.

Travel_notes: Gradual uphill through open Subalpine fir, huckleberry understory.
Location_desc: none

Travel_notes: Pass through research plot with number tags on trees - dead only? Slightly uphill through open Subalpine fir forest.
Location_desc: none

Travel_notes: Through Subalpine fir forest to road, open understory, then into meadows above road. Climb and contour.
Location_desc: On the north side of juniper patch, open meadow to the north of point.

Travel_notes: Sidehill climb in open meadow, passing through a patch of subalpine fir, then opening up again with view into meadow where point is found.
Location_desc: Lovely. Middle of open meadow, just below lip where upper meadow drops into lower gravelly meadow, and above line of gravel patches seen in feature #1.

Travel_notes: After finishing NN08, I suggest continuing to road and hiking back on road to hoot points NN02 and NN04, as long as GPS, habitat, and direction updates for NN07, NN06, and NN05 were done on the hike in. Road is still closed at Waterhole, so from there it is about a 10-15 minute walk. I forgot to look if there were any closer spots to park if the gate were open though. About a 50-minute drive from Port Angeles. There is a small pullout ~160m down the road from TO (on uphill side of road), that you can park at if gate/road is open past Waterhole. Under 1 mile past Waterhole.
Location_desc: Point is on a slight bend in road. Just down road of point on SW side of road (~5m N/NW of marker tree) are several cut logs suspended diagonally.

Travel_notes: I don't think I was on actual trail for any part of travel between TO and SS01 because of snow- update this next time.
Location_desc: It is ~2m past a ~150 cm DBH Mountain hemlock that is very close to the trail (on W side). It is between 2 cut logs (on each side of trail, but with ~4m of trail (length-wise) between them.)

Travel_notes: I think it is more than 200m of pacing (due to switchbacks), but I lost trail and lost count due to snow.
Location_desc: Mostly Pacific Silver Fir with some Western and Mountain hemlocks, too.  At a bend in trail. It is is farther from creek than it seems/sounds.  It is ~9m past cut log on W side of trail  (and some smaller pieces of log on E side).

Travel_notes: Walk down the trail about 315m. Point is ~75 m after crossing creek. There is a small sign with spring labeled 'Wynochee Spring' a few meters after creek.
Location_desc: Point is in between a ~80 cm DBH Silver Fir snag and a cut log with a few small rocks next to it. Lots of large silver firs and hemlocks.

Travel_notes: Pace ~225 m down trail, crossing a small creek that you have to scale down small slope to get to (at least this year) at ~90m
Location_desc: Point is ~3 m past cut log on W side of the trail.

Travel_notes: Pace down 200m trail. Note: paper ripped where I wrote down coordinates and now I can't read the 5th digit of the Easting. Please update this next visit.
Location_desc: There are 2 young (similar-sized) Pacific Silver Firs just before point (farther S of 2 is ~2m before point on E side of trail). There are some cut logs on E side of trail right at point (~0.5m down trail).

Travel_notes: Pace ~200m down trail until you reach an open area ~15m before crossing creek.
Location_desc: Point is ~15m N (on trail) of small creek that crosses trail.  It is wet here with lots of low herbaceous vegetation. It is also open. Lots of snow right now, so maybe its wetter than usual.  It is between feature root wad and mountain hemlock.

Travel_notes: Head off-trail for 200m, going across streams and through huckleberry.
Location_desc: Point is at a 4m tall jagged half snag with a hollow inside. Lots of Alaska yellow cedars in the area, 4m from a huge downed yellow cedar.

Travel_notes: We camped at the end of the road/beginning of the trail, about 1.5 miles from TO, but if there is no snow, camping closer to TO would be a good option- some flat spots nearby. Check about road conditions. The road was washed out several miles before the trailhead in 2011. There is a great spot to camp off-trail just past the creek near TO. A pleasant surprise! This is a confusing and difficult trailhead to get to. Not suitable for Honda Civics, which was confirmed by a partially deflated tire when we got back to the car. This should be addressed next visit- can we borrow an NPS rig? Also, I'm not sure what the mileage difference is, but going through Montesano is far more straightforward than FS 23 (from Skokomish).
Location_desc: At point in the trail where trail levels out just before dropping to the creek at featured half-dead/ half-alive Silver Fir.

Travel_notes: Travel up moderate slope.
Location_desc: On slope ~20m SE of creek. Silver Fir, relatively open. Immediately to the N/NW is an area without as much huckleberry.

Travel_notes: Travel steeply up slope (snow) along slippery roots.
Location_desc: On moderate slope. Relatively open. On a decaying downed tree. There are several silver fir saplings immediately downslope of point. The large snag feature is up against a smaller silver fir.

Travel_notes: Travel steeply up (snow) to achieve relatively flat area.
Location_desc: On the edge of an opening right on the top of meltwater stream, next to large cedars. Pacific silver firs large and small. It is ~5m past small stream.

Travel_notes: Easiest to skirt cliffs and steep snow by staying on flats to the west.
Location_desc: Open snow, right next to Mtn. hemlock (?) tree.

Travel_notes: Travel NW, avoiding lakes and going ~50-60 m up the steep slope past the lake
Location_desc: On steep slope among sparse Pacific silver fir. Snow. Point is ~6m S of a boulder field/rock slide.

Travel_notes: Travel up steep slope until you get to a ridge. Stay a little to the NW- it's a little less steep (but avoid cliffs too far to the NW). Point is ~4m beyond (on W/NW side of) ridge.
Location_desc: Point is on the W/NW side of a narrow ridge, ~4m down from top. It is right below a steep rock face (leading down to point from ridge). More open right at point than any of surrounding area, which has a lot of saplings and huckleberry.

Travel_notes: Travel up road 100 m from origin.
Location_desc: Rocky on left, fairly open on right, but there are certainly still trees on right.  Ahead there is a doug fir growing right on the edge of the road.

Travel_notes: Pace 200 m.  Road winds back and forth.
Location_desc: Rocky outcropping on left w/ quite a bit of vegetation.  Large opening in trees to the right with vine maples below.

Travel_notes: Pace 200 m.  Road winds back and forth.
Location_desc: Rocky outcropping near point, after passing bare/loose soil.  Right side mostly Doug-fir.

Travel_notes: Road winds back and forth.  Only one obvious pull-out (several inconspicious ones).  Point not far after obvious one.
Location_desc: Mostly dirt hillside to left.  Many trees to the right.  A few stumps of smaller cut trees on left hillside. Point is about 15 m after passing end of small pullout.

Travel_notes: 2 curves in road.  2 small pulloffs on right side of road.  Point is not far after 2nd pulloff.
Location_desc: Point is about 20 m up road from the uphill-most point of a pull-off which is on the right side of the road at a bend.  Several small Doug-firs on both sides of road from point.

Travel_notes: 2 more obvious curves (but not that sharp).  Nothing too noteworthy.
Location_desc: Point right across from a pull off on right side of road.  Left side of road is mostly huge rock face.

Travel_notes: Road bends back and forth slightly.
Location_desc: Exposed rock on left. Maples on right.  Pretty open view to the right.

Travel_notes: Pace a little more than 200 m.  Road zig zags back and forth.  Pass lots of exposed rock.  One sharper turn to the right.  Point is ~25m after passing 2nd of 2 small pulloffs on right.
Location_desc: Point along relative straightaway.  Trees 3-4 thick on right before seeing through to views in background.  Moss, rocks & mostly dirt on left.

Travel_notes: Pace 300 m.  There's a very large curve in road that is also quite sharp.
Location_desc: Mostly dirt on left side of road.  2 large Doug-firs have roots exposed b/c of soil erosion.  2 hemlocks growing very close together right up on edge of right side of road.

Travel_notes: Pace 235m.  Road bends to the right then left.  You'll pass a pull out of sorts on the right.  Point is up road another 45 m.  After coming around turn, you'll see two stumps that were sawed about 6 in from ground on the left side of the road.
Location_desc: Open grassy hill on left.  Doug-firs on left.  Cedars and hemlocks on right.  No trees on the right have their bases right up by the road.

Travel_notes: Pace 225 m.  One sharper bend in road.
Location_desc: There is a fairly large (24 cm DBH) Subalpine fir on left side of road w/ its roots exposed b/c the soil washed away.  There are trees on the right hand side, though they aren't dense.  Looking down the road the way you came, you see a break in the trees and the mountains in the distance.  There are also 2 Doug-firs on the left side of the road that both seem to have lost their top halves but they're still alive.  One is up-road from Subalpine fir, other is down.

Travel_notes: Pace 225 m.  2 slight bends in road.
Location_desc: Point is after road curves to the right.

Travel_notes: Pace 240 m.  Travel a bend that curves right then a 2nd sharper turn that curves left.
Location_desc: Point is on a very slight curve.  You can see the bend starting in the road for the next curve.  Hillside on right is dirt.  most of the trees on left start about 8 m uphill but there's a clump of Subalpine firs closer to the road.  Dense trees on right side of road.

Travel_notes: Pace 240 m.  Travel uphill.  2 bends in the road.  After the 2nd bend, the point is where the trees on right get sparser.
Location_desc: The hillside on the left is dirt and rock and there is one large rock amongst many small ones.  One the horizon (if facing south) you can see (if not cloudy) the whitecaps of a mountain that you couldn't see until this point.  Mostly open on right side of road after having many trees on right side for much of the walk here.

Reason_for_change: couldn't go off-trail due to steepness
Travel_notes: Point is about 135-140 m down road from big curve/pullout (good parking spot). Pacing ends up being much longer than 100 m from TO due to big curve (ensuring that it is 200 m from NE01).
Location_desc: Point is on road with loose soil/rock on NE side and open Doug-fir forest on SW side. There is a lone cedar almost directly in line with point.

Travel_notes: Pace as if traveling 245 m down road. There are several curves between these points.
Location_desc: Point is on road. On SW side is a very dense forest of small trees. On the NE side is a steep rock face leading up to small trees. Finding features to describe here is difficult. Point is about 50 m down road from end of big curve.

Travel_notes: Pace as if traveling 275 m down road (compensated for curves) until small pullout is reached (not incredibly obvious).
Location_desc: Point is on a curve in the road where there seems to be a small pullout on SW side of road. The NE side is bordered by a rock face with some densely packed low shrub above it. Point is in center of pullout. [Photo shows rocky slope. Pine is hard to see - its below (toward road) of the Doug-fir seen.]

Travel_notes: Walk down road as if traveling 230 m (compensated for curves in road) until 2nd obvious curve is reached (after initial curve that NW03 is on)- point is on that curve (see features).
Location_desc: Point is on road where there is a big circular curve. Point is at SW corner of that curve. On the NE side of road, there is a rock face leading up to more vegetated substrate.

Travel_notes: Travel is down steep slope the whole way (off-trail), through mostly Douglas Fir forest.
Location_desc: Point is on a steep slope leading down to a drainage. It is covered in moss and there is a lot of Salal and Oregon Grape right at point. It is predominantly Douglas-fir forest. 2009 update - the downhill Douglas-fir of the "connected Doug-firs" is broken and the top half runs perpendicular into the hill above. You will see it when approaching point.

Travel_notes: The first 40 m drop steeply down to a drainage. The next 125 m traverse the side of a steep slope, much of it through thick salal. It drops at the end down to a drainage (where point is located).
Location_desc: Point is at the bottom of a drainage with lots of fallen trees over it. There are a few dense patches of Salal near point. Cedars are directly down creek of a decaying large hemlock snag (DBH 100cm).

Travel_notes: Mostly a traverse of a steep slope. It starts off through thick salal, then gradually becomes more bare. Relatively easy travel.
Location_desc: Point is on a steep slope that is sparsely vegetated. There are several large rocks near point. It is just (about 20 m) SW of a small, dry dip in terrain/gully.

Travel_notes: Traverse along slope, then cross drainage and go straight up steep slope. get rewarded w/ view at top. Point just down otherside of the ridge.
Location_desc: Point is in middle of large patch of manzanitas on a steep slope about 25 m down from ridge. It is sparsely vegetated aside from manzanita (and trees). It is relatively open at point with view of ridge across valley. Boulder featured has large pistol grip Doug-fir to E of it (only bottom part visible from point).

Travel_notes: Drop steeply from Point 8 for ~60 meters.  Traverse becomes less steep but there is still a steady elevation drop to Point 9.
Location_desc: Point is is in mostly doug fir and w. red cedar forest, though w/ small w. hemlocks scattered throughout). Salal dominates the understory. ~30 meters down a deer trail (heading W), a small opening can be seen from point. This opening has manzanita and salal growing in it.

Travel_notes: Travel downhill and across slope through taller salal than rest of transect within 30m of point there are 2 massive downed DOFI trees, point is 5m beyond the second one
Location_desc: Very close to large downed DOFI with huge branches. Dense salal understory in forest of relatively dense small conifers

Travel_notes: About 15-minute drive up from park boundary toward campground.  About a 40-45-minute drive from Port Angeles to TO.  TO is a 10-15 minute drive down from campground, right near a pullout that is often called "Water Barrel."
Location_desc: There's a rocky wall on left side of trail.  Point is at a stump that is comprised of one trunk that splits into 2 distinct trunks (you can only barely tell that it has 2 trunks now- most of it has fallen). The marker is not on this (in case it rots).  This tree is about 50 m up the road from a larger pull-off where you can park.  About a 15-minute drive up from park boundary on Deer Park Rd. Park at a big curve in road (very close to TO) where there is a pullout area.

Travel_notes: walk down Eagle Cove Rd. about 175 m. There is a small gate within dense shrub that leads you onto a trail. Point can be accessed from this (walk S from trail about 60 m).
Location_desc: The point is right on the NPS boundary, less than 50 m from Eagle Cove Rd. There is a cluster of Doug-firs to the SW and thick shrub to the W. The point itself is in thick grass.

Travel_notes: Point is off of Cattle Point Rd. As you stand near the sign for the visitor's center, set your compass to 267 degrees. This should take you across the road to a break in the line of trees - enter the forest/thicket here and proceed to 002. Do not enter by the Eagle Point Rd sign unless you want to bushwack rose.
Location_desc: Point is in an open area among the shrubs in a small grassy patch about 80 meters from road. It is 10m into the open rose thicket area - use "pair of doug fir" feature to guide you into the thicket. Dense thicket of wild rose along the entire NW side.  Doug firs to the west. Smaller trees to the south.

Travel_notes: Best reached from "Fire Camp" off of Cattle Point Rd. Pace about 300 m from there to the NW. We also ran across a trail en route to 003 (from Fire Camp), maybe the American Camp Trail that also goes to visitor center? It might be easier to go that (but it's already a very mellow walk directly from Fire Camp).
Location_desc: on edge of clearing (W side).

Travel_notes: Don't attempt to go straight through from point 001- a VERY bad idea. If going from 001, go on the small trail N of the point that connects to the larger trail from the visitor center. You will skirt the worst of the shrub to the N.
Location_desc: Point is situated next to (E of) very dense shrub. It is in a grassy area with a lot of ferns. There is the first of a few small "gullies" just to the E of point (about 3 m).

Travel_notes: easy travel
Location_desc: Point in middle of dense shrubs.  Many homes are visible to the SW.  Patch of mixed conifer and deciduous trees to the N and patch of deciduous trees to the S.

Travel_notes: Travel from 002.  Easy travel.  After crossing the road it is all open grassland.  During travel you can see the visitors center to the south. If coming from Fire Camp, walk on American Camp Trail toward visitor center. When trail makes a sharp bend, stay straight and go off-trail about 110m to point.
Location_desc: Point 280 m east of the main road in an open grassy area loosely surrounded by mostly Doug-firs.  Road runs between 002 and 006.

Travel_notes: If accessing from 003, first 100 m or so are open (through grassland), the next 200 m are through thicker shrub and other vegetation. The last 40+m open up. It may be easier to get to this point from Cattle Point Rd.
Location_desc: The point is on the eastern edge of a clearing in knee-high shrub. There are Doug-firs and Shore pines to the E. There is a flowering Hawthorn about 42 m away from point.

Travel_notes: Travel fairly easy from 004. Some shrubby sections, but you can go around the big patches
Location_desc: The point is mostly surrounded by shrub with a grassy section in middle (where point is). It is just downhill (S of) from the buildings of American Camp.

Travel_notes: Easy travel between 010 and 009.
Location_desc: Point in open grassland near Officer's quarters.

Travel_notes: When coming from 006, stay out in open (skirting Doug-firs to N) for as long as you can, then cut in as close to due N as possible. Travel is nasty if you cut in too early.
Location_desc: Point is in a very small open patch of gtrass within a stand of young Doug-firs. It is brighter at point than surrounding area because it's less enclosed by Doug-firs.

Travel_notes: Best accessed from Cattle Point Rd., as it is on Cattle Point Rd. Use GPS and point description.
Location_desc: Point is on S side of Cattle Point Rd. across from an open shrubby area that is surrounded by conifers on both sides.

Travel_notes: An easy walk from point 008, gradual uphill through occasional shrub/prickly vegetation. No problems assuming you aren't wearing Chacos...
Location_desc: The point is in some ferns, between sections of knee-waist high shrub. Beyond that and right at point is grassy.

Travel_notes: From point 012, easy walking gradually uphill through grassy, open vegetation with some shrubby parts. Watch out for Savannah sparrow nests!
Location_desc: The point is about 75 m S of dirt road from visitor center. It is in a grassy area with some ferns and other herbaceous vegetation.

Travel_notes: Best approached from road (from visitor center)- it is about 275 m N of it. If coming from point 013, a road will be reached at about 75 m.
Location_desc: Point is in a grassy area about 35 m SW of mostly Doug-fir forest. There is thick shrub to the N, but immediately surrounding point is grass/herbaceous vegetation.

Travel_notes: Best approached from Cattle Point Rd. From point 011, pace about 350 m E (or getting as close as possible). Walk about 35 m N of road through painful shrub (mostly rose). It is going to be tempting to try and keep going E on the road and try to find a more open entry/route, but it's rough going that way as well. It's probably best just to plow through the seemingly impenetrable wall of rose. It is actually slightly easier if you go in (N) a bit to the W on Cattle Point Rd.
Location_desc: Point is on northern edge of high (over head-height) shrub, surrounded by primarily Doug-firs and Shore pines and on southern side, Alder. It is about 35 m N of the road. It is now difficult to see anything from the point. I couldn't find the young Doug-fir feature, but everything is overgrown now. GPS works well here, though.

Travel_notes: Travel easy from point 017. Pace and use GPS through open, short vegetation.
Location_desc: In the middle of open grassland habitat amidst some dried-out looking ferns.

Travel_notes: Easily accessible from any surrounding point. Walk through rabbit warren for most of it.
Location_desc: In the middle of the dry, short grass rabbit warren sort of habitat, although not enclosed as the actual rabbit warren is. The point is about 75 m S of the road.

Travel_notes: If approaching from Cattle Point Rd., best way is to walk W about 175 m (after crossing road). Then veer N from there. I took a terrible, shrubby way so I shouldn't give details right to point. Try to walk as much as possible in grassland area before having to veer N to point.
Location_desc: Point is in middle of a cluster of salmonberry and near some giant Skunk cabbage. It is in Red alder forest with thick shrub understory.

Travel_notes: Accessed this point in worst imagineable way. Best access probably by road labeled "Horse Trailer Parking" off of Cattle Point Rd (Turn at road toward July 4th Beach). It is about 125 m W of this road when intended Northing is reached.
Location_desc: In small clearing surrounded by shrub. There is a view of the ocean to the NE.

Travel_notes: Travel on road from 024.
Location_desc: Point on gravel road in the second South Beach parking lot.

Travel_notes: Very easy walking from point 016 (or any direction, really). Pace 350 m through short grass and rabbit holes.
Location_desc: Point is in middle of rabbit warren. GPS should work well.

Travel_notes: Easy walking through rabbit warren from any direction.
Location_desc: Point is in middle of rabbit with views of both the bay and the ocean. It is approximately 60 m from (S of) the road from the visitor center. It is about 390 m from point 017.

Travel_notes: Best approached from Cattle Point Rd. Go in about 100 m E of road when you reach approximate northing (if traveling South on road, just when it opens up after dense shrub.)
Location_desc: Point is on southern edge of large grassland area, about 100 m E of road. Point is about 18 m from edge of Doug-fir tree line to the NW. Ocean is to the NE, about 300 m away.

Travel_notes: Start here- just E of South Beach parking lot.
Location_desc: Grassland right near beach on flat ground right before the hill to the N begins.

Travel_notes: Travel on road from 024- easy.
Location_desc: Point in grassy area behind sand gully.

Travel_notes: I rode my bike from the campsite to the Jakal Lagoon parking lot, about five minutes.
Location_desc: Point on S side of road across the street from Jakal's Lagoon parking lot.  Grassland habitat with view of Old Town Lagoon to the N.

Travel_notes: Take small, easy to miss trail from the recycling/trash bins at the parking lot down to the lagoon.
Location_desc: On N side of Old Town Lagoon. To the SE is Doug-fir forest, to the N is bay.

Travel_notes: From 024, travel over grassland, easy.
Location_desc: Point on sandy mound N of beach and 8 m south of the foot of the steep hill.

Travel_notes: From 026 travel on road entire time.
Location_desc: Point on side of road next to small Doug-fir.  Grassland habitat, view of ocean to S, and edge of Doug-fir forest to N.

Travel_notes: Walk in on the trail toward Jakles Lagoon/Mt. Finlayson about 200 m (not exact- messed up on pacing). Go off-trail to the S about 60 m to point.
Location_desc: Point is in Doug-fir forest, about 60 m S of trail at intended easting. The point is in a small area of relatively bare ground compared to its surroundings.

Travel_notes: From 029, travel on road entire way.
Location_desc: Point on S side of road, grassland habitat, view of ocean and Olympics to the S.

Travel_notes: Going from 030, walk SE on trail until it comes to split. Stay to the right at split and continue past the second trail junction for about 175 m, then veer off to the NE about 8.5 m.
Location_desc: Point is about 8.5 m NE of trail (see travel instructions). There are some rounds just below feature nurse cedar.

Travel_notes: Travel from 031 on road entire way, slightly downhill.
Location_desc: Point on S side of road, view of ocean and Olympics to S, grassland habitat.

Travel_notes: Point located on south fork of main trail running from Jackle lagoon to Mt. Finlayson
Location_desc: Point is just NE (on trail) of where trail starts to go uphill (or at base of downhill). It is 13.5m past (NE of) Douglas Maple on right side of trail. If coming from the East part of the park, the point is approx 120m SW of fork in trail.

Travel_notes: From 033 travel on road before walking downhill to point. In recent years the road was moved uphill, and some features are on the new road while some are on the now overgrown old road.
Location_desc: Point in open grassland just south of paved road, view of ocean and Olympics.

Travel_notes: A westerly bearing from point 038 works well  or the point can be accessed from the main trail.
Location_desc: Point on old logging road, being overgrown by deciduous saplings, ferns, and salal. Point directly beside deer-scraped alder. Uphill from small pond.

Travel_notes: From 035 easy travel up hill through open grassland.
Location_desc: Point in open grassland jst south of an unmapped dirt path. To N is a Doug-fir forest edge.

Travel_notes: Point is easily accessed from main trail in Mt. Finlayson forest. It may save time to drive over to E side of park and start there.
Location_desc: Point is in opening in understory, uphill from ferns and nettle patches. Some large stumps nearby.

Travel_notes: due S from pt. 2002 through grassland and shrub clumps.
Location_desc: grassy hillside overlooking ocean.  Indistinct shrub clumps to N, E and SE; house outside of park to W.  Point located on last distinct hill before slope down to ocean.

Travel_notes: open grassland
Location_desc: point located in grassland just E of park boundary, mid-way between line of pine trees growing to the N and ocean to the N.

Travel_notes: difficult, did not follow bearing due to head high Rosa and vaccinium thickets.
Location_desc: just inside of southern edge of tree/shrub habitat border with grassland.  Road to N ~45m; weather station to S ~50m.  Point centered in dense tangle of shrubs 1m high.

Travel_notes: travel alternates between open meadow and forested areas with thick shrub understory.  Difficult to travel.
Location_desc: pont approx 25m N of Cattle Point Rd. in dense ____ Pine/Doug Fir earl succesional forest with shrub/grassland understory.  No conspicuous features present.

Travel_notes: abrupt hab change at 40m. Relatively flat and nondescriptt except for dense veg beyond open meadow (then cuts through SE portion).
Location_desc: no really good conspicuous features present at this point. On S edge of a tall ___ Pine stand grading into mixed conifer and shrub understory.

Travel_notes: dense veg along entire route.  Large swamp ~50m across mid-way between pts. 6 and 7.
Location_desc: No conspic features present.  Ponit in very dense hard bark (?) forest (5m tall) with moss and forb understory.

Travel_notes: first point on transect/no notes.
Location_desc: no conspic features seen.  Point in doug fir forest opening up to very dense shrub undergrowth.  GPS coverage good.

Travel_notes: followed trail towards ocean and cut to point.
Location_desc: point faces ocean on small slope; surrounding geography varied.   Most conspicuous feature is point sticking out into ocean 75 m due south.

Travel_notes: walked out to trail and down to point.  Dense shrub (rosa, vaccininu) in off-trail path btwn points.
Location_desc: point on trail.  Large clump of sonspicuous shrubs 25 m in length, 30m to the SE. top of Am Camp flagpole seen in the distance almost due north.

Travel_notes: travel due S through grassland for 60m; use trail until rabbit fence is in view; go E over rabbit fence to point.
Location_desc: point is in grassland on eedge of dense patch of vaccinium.  Coniferous trees 100 m to NW, decid tree patch 200m to S.

Travel_notes: travel due S through grassland.  Skirt shrub hab to the left, see directions for next point (2010). From 2012 go through dense shrubs and follow treeline on right.
Location_desc: point due E of Am Camp bldgs at edge of open grassland just as fairly large Doug-fir trees begin to grow on grassland border.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: no conspic features visible; ____ in vaccinium shrubland with numerous conifers growing in southern half;  GPS coverage good.

Travel_notes: First point surveyed, no azimuth to point
Location_desc: open mixed conifer forest (Doug-fir and s--- pine) shrub understory, grass and ferns in openings.  Road only good feature 30m to S.

Travel_notes: the route is mostly throught very dense shrub and young trees (mostly Doug-firs)
Location_desc: the point is on the S side of the road, across the stree from an opne shrubby area

Travel_notes: to get to pt. 2015, go north from the white house and flagpole (continue going N past pt. 2016)
Location_desc: the point is in a grassy area in the middle of some young doug. Firs.  There isn't anything very conspicuous from the point.

Travel_notes: First point surveyed, no azimuth to point
Location_desc: it is on a slope, downhill from a road and next to a white fence.  It is in the middle of a small grassland area, surrounded by a young Doug-fir forest.

Travel_notes: for the last 60m, walk alongside white fence.  The point is at end of fence, about 20m to the E.
Location_desc: it is primarily grassland habitat with a view of a bunch f houses to the west and a white fence encircling a house and flagpole to the the NW.

Travel_notes: the easiest way is to get on the trail that is just to the E of point 2018, follow that until you get to point (it looks like it is becoming over grown though--if that is the case, just head N uphill east of the house).
Location_desc: you can see 2 white buildings and a flagpole that are north of the point.  The point is in the middle of a variety of shrub speices.

Travel_notes: there are no distinguishing features; it is just shrub/grassland habitat the entire 250m.
Location_desc: the point is on the edge of a cliff going down to the beach, just south of the trail.  The area is primarily grassland.

Travel_notes: the easiest way to get there is to follow the trail (in order to bypas cliffs) the entire way.  The point is about 7m to the south of the trail.
Location_desc: to the east, there are a lot of large (mostly flat) rocks partially covered by the surrounding grassland plat species.  The ocean lies just south.

Travel_notes: for the first 60m, follow the trail, then the trail veers more to the W so continue straight S.
Location_desc: it is completely grassland habitat overloking the ocean. There are a few medium-sized rocks within 15m of the point.

Travel_notes: follow a well-maintained trail the entire 250m between points 2022 and 2021.  other than that, there aren't any distinguishing features along the way.
Location_desc: completely grassland habitat, just to the west (within 5 m) of a well-maintained trail, just before a set of wooden stairs.

Travel_notes: for the last ~70m, you follow a well-maintained trail (to pt. 2022).
Location_desc: surrounded by mostly grassland with some young douglas firs.

Travel_notes: the route was primarily grassland the whole 250m.  There was nothing very notable about it.
Location_desc: the point is in the middle of grassland.

Travel_notes: walk on the roadthe entire way from 2014 to 2025
Location_desc: the point is right on the road (about 4 m away)

Travel_notes: walk on the road for the first 180m, then walk North off the road for the remainder.
Location_desc: the point is in the middle of a lot of shrub and mostly young doug firs.

Travel_notes: the route is primarily through dense shrub, on both sides of the road
Location_desc: the pointt is in the middle of a patch of stinging nettle surrounded by alders and shrub.  There is nothing else conspicuous that can be seen from the point.

Travel_notes: to get to the point, walk down the Redoubt road from either South Beach Rd or the visitor center, go North (downhill) to point 2028.
Location_desc: the point is on a slpe uphill from a forested area.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: open grassland W of rabbit warren.  View of mt Baker and the Olympic mtns.

Travel_notes: straight shot through grassland
Location_desc: in grassland approx 250 m W of rabbit warren at N edge of large black berrry patches, below bracen fern patches in grassland.

Travel_notes: down hill towards ocean through grassland.
Location_desc: point 175m (approx) from water line.  Rocky outcropping 100m downhill before dropping 75 m into water.

Travel_notes: the route is going slightly uphill through mainly rabbit warren and ferns.  In the distance (500+m), the fence runs parallel to the route.
Location_desc: the point is just north of the beach in grassland.

Travel_notes: the route goes uphill through rabbit warren, parallel to the South Beach Rd.
Location_desc: the point is in the middle of a bunch of ferns, surrounded by rabbit warren.

Travel_notes: walk uphill to the road, then down through rabbit warren to point 2034.
Location_desc: the point is in the middle of rabbit warren, just south of Redoubt Rd.

Travel_notes: it is possible to skirt the chapparal and walk down the hill to within 30 m of treeline then aproach the pt. from the N or downslope, and wade through the chapparal.
Location_desc: point falls on the toeslope of the hill below Redoubt Road, 10m from the N edge of a thick hedge of chapparal and 35m from the S edge of the rose thicket bordering the forest.

Travel_notes: enter forest at left/West end of rose thicket, to left and under branches of conifer. Walking on down trees makes travel easier!
Location_desc: point falls in a stand of stinging nettle under a dense Alder canopy.

Travel_notes: hellish thickets of thimbleberry, salmonberry and stinging nettle between points 36 and 37.  37 should be sampled by walking from the Fourth of July beach parking area.
Location_desc: point falls in a dense but traversable stand of pokey shrubs, next to a barrier formed by 5 young alders between 6 and 8 m tall (the tallest at a bearing of 309 degrees from point).

Travel_notes: from point 2048 walk N along beach to big rock outcrop obstructing beach.  Go up outcrop away from beach, continue N through least dense veg. to point.  Good GPS coverage.
Location_desc: point falls in young doug fir / shrub habitat 30m fro ocean.  E of the point is largely roses for 20m, no conifers; immediately W of the point is largely juve doug fir.

Travel_notes: I chose to use GPS to navigate and was able to cover ~200m on the road, then duck back into the forest for 40-50m of easy travel.
Location_desc: point falls in open alder forest with tall but open shrub understory, next to a denser stand of alder and shrub.  Herb layer is tall grass, some thistle and sword fern.

Travel_notes: from pt 2039 it is easy to walk back out to the road and follow it to the open grassland where the rose hedge ends.  Follow a 120 degree bearing from there to the point.
the route between 2042 and 2041 is just going slightly uphill thgough the rabbit warren; there is nothing very distinguishing along it.
Location_desc: it is in the middle of the rabbit fields, just south of Redoubt Rd.

Travel_notes: the route just goes uphill through the rabbit warren.  There is nothing conspicuous along the way.
Location_desc: the point is in the middle of the rabbit warren.

Travel_notes: stay north of the thick shrub patches. The point can be reached by staying in the grassland.
Location_desc: the point is right at the edge of a dense patch of shrub, just south of where the rabbits have stopped.  (but that could change).

Travel_notes: easy point to reach via car.  Drive to south side beach, just before the 1st lot on the right is a patch of willows.  The point is just on the NE corner of the willows.
Location_desc: NE of willow patch on W side of South beach rd--just N of the parking lot on the main road.

Travel_notes: the entire route is through the rabbit warren, parallel to the road.  There isn't anything else notable about it.
Location_desc: the point is next to the S. Beach Rd in the rabbit warren.

Travel_notes: easy pacing over sand dunes.  Be careful that paces aren't shortened by walking on sand and up hills.
Location_desc: point falls on sand dune amid thistle, a sticky yellow flowered succulent and a dry brown moss.  It is ~ 95m from the S. Beach Rd. and ~ 90m from Cattle Point Rd.

Travel_notes: there is a narrow trail cut through the shrub layer to point 2049.  follow this trail N until you can cut W through rose hedge.  Head for the big shrub hedge in the middle of the field.
Location_desc: point falls in sloping grassland btwn 2 islands of shrub.  Cattle Point Rd. runs ~70m to the S.  Great view of Mt Baker.  Great GPS coverage.

Travel_notes: easy walk through grassland.  There is no need to go through the hedge, walk around it to the South.
Location_desc: point falls on edge btwn marshy rush habiat and driftwood log-filled quagmire (lagoon), ~50m from ocean and 10m fromm aforementioned shrub hedge.

Travel_notes: from Jakk's lagoon, go 35 m downslope from sign to narrow trail cut through doug fir and brush; pace down it, confirm with GPS by balancing unit on doug fir branches for clear view of sky.
Location_desc: point falls on primitive trail in dense doug fir forest/shrub

Travel_notes: the route is parallel to the ____ in the rabbit warren the entire time.
Location_desc: the point is near the intersection of South Beach Rd and it is in the rabbit warren.

Travel_notes: easy travel over sand dunes
Location_desc: point falls on sand dune amid ferns and a buckwheat-looking plant with red racimes (10cm tall).  4 stands of shrub and 5 small conifers can be seen within a 70m radius.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point falls near edge of sand dune amid sparse thistle.  A border of fern and beach rose grow on the S edge of the dune.

Travel_notes: park in eastern South Side Beach lot and walk on beach to point.  It's within 300m of lot.
Location_desc: point is on beach near South Side beach eastern most parking lot.  It is at the southern edge of the driftwood across from the only patch of shrubs on the slope leading to the road.

Travel_notes: easy travel over driftwood and beach
Location_desc: the point is on the edge of the dritwood and grassy dune backshore.  It's south of where 2 paths cross up on the slope leading to the road.

Travel_notes: easy walking thru grassland and low thistle
Location_desc: point falls on hillside in vegetated rabbit warren.  Herb layer is grass, fern thistle, red-flowered buckwheat (all under 40cm).  Great view of the Olympics to the SW.

Travel_notes: mostly easy pacing through grassland
Location_desc: point falls on mown shoulder of Cattle Pt. Rd. surrounded by grassland.

Travel_notes: gradual uphill thru open forest
Location_desc: point falls in open Doug-fir forest on a moderately steep slope littered with down sticks and branches and moss-covered logs.

Travel_notes: ~40m from previous pt, hit trail, turn R, go ~18m to junction, turn L, follow trail to junction with post check coordinates.  Pt shoud be 4m down secondary trail.
Location_desc: point falls on trail descending toward ocean to NE.  Trail is 1.5 m wide, dirt with pine litter.

Travel_notes: all varieties of obstacles.  Difficult to follow a bearing thru this density of veg.  Travel time:  1 hour.
Location_desc: point falls under dense doug fir canopy surrounded by scarecely navigable stands of shrubs and saplings (doug fir, vine maple, red alder).  Next to huge Western red cedar.

Travel_notes: first point of day.  Park at scenic overlook on hill almost 500m S of South Beach Rd.  Walk 50m on a 8 degree bearing.
Location_desc: point is in grassland on the hill E of Cattle Pt Rd, apporx equidistant from the road and the forest's edge.

Travel_notes: walk from driftwood into backshore grass.  Walk 250m--the gap btwn steep hill and driftwood narrows.
Location_desc: the point is at the rock 20 m from the hill and 40 m from the driftwood I the backshore's grass.

Travel_notes: easy travel--250 m of grassland with a few himalayan blackberry bushes in between.  No real significant landmarks.
Location_desc: next to a patch of RUBARM S of the road and N of the cliff.

Travel_notes: park at vista lot on hill and walk up hill to the NE.  Follow path until you reach the coordinates.
Location_desc: point is at the edge of forest and grassland next to the main trail that runs adjacent to the forest edge.

Travel_notes: THE EASIEST WAY TO GET TO POINT IS TO TAKE TRAIL TOWARD WATER FROM THE MAIN MEADOW TRAIL.  IT HEADS TO THE WATER MIDWAY BETWEEN JACKLES RD AND VISTA ON THE HILL PARKING LOTS.
Location_desc: the point is in a patch of salal btwn the lagoon and the trail.  There is a large Doug-fir right next to lagoon (towering over it).

Travel_notes: travel from the main trail that runs near the water.  It is the widest trail I've seen in the forested area.
Location_desc: point is on a downslope almost to the trail to the West.

Travel_notes: nasty plants.  It's best to go directly out of forest, relocate yourself then proceed to point.  Follow the deer paths.  Beware stinging nettle everywhere.
Location_desc: near forest edge in a bouquet of yellow composite flowers.

Travel_notes: walk between road and cliff through grassland.  No significant travel features.
Location_desc: survey location is on a large (somewhat inconspicuous) rock just S of a large patch of Him. Blackberry.  The rock's dimensions are 1.5m x 2m x 0.75m high.  It's shaped like this:  ____

Reason_for_change: unable to go N due to cliff/ocean
Travel_notes: no real significant features--just grassland with Him. Blackberry and cross over road
Location_desc: pt. is near a small (3) patch of blackberry.  Survey pt is between these three patches.

Reason_for_change: no more unsurveyed points to east.
Travel_notes: walk at 67 degrees bearing east through greass, slightly uphill.  No real features, just grass.  Very accurate point.
Location_desc: in the grass field, south of the forest with a great view of the Olympics.  Beautiful!!

Travel_notes: head downslope from meadow into forest.  Follow a northern bearing until you reach cedar forest.
Location_desc: seven large <122 cm cedar trees surround the point.  It is on the steeper part of the slope.

Reason_for_change: b/c it was the most efficient way to go
Travel_notes: tough traveling thru the forest.  Lost of shrubs. Head W fro point 77 until you hit the trail. Get your bearings on the trail and travel accordingly.
Location_desc: on the SE edge of the bog, on the W side of the southerly trail.  In a patch of salmonberry (RUBSPE).

Travel_notes: head up the trail.  It travels S uphill and point is right after Red Alder forest on left.  Look for a downed tree with it's root facing the trail (1m off trail).  That is the point.
use trail for travel between points--much faster.
Location_desc: on the steep part of the slope N of the road.

Travel_notes: First point surveyed.
Location_desc: on top of the grass hill, near the E edge almost on the park's eastern border.  Great view!

Travel_notes: travel easily through grassN and more difficult through forest
Location_desc: point is on upper slope of forest with lots of herbaceous plants and shrubs.  4 snags in point area within 10 m of point.

Travel_notes: head downhill (N), cedar becomes more abundant and mixed into forest at this point on slope.  Understory less vegetated than higher on slope.
Location_desc: lots of downed trees-mixed conifer habitat. sparse understory vegetation

Travel_notes: These points grouped together well for 1 morning: 002, 001, 005, 004, 008, 009, 010 (and we had planned to do 006 but didn't get to it). We started from "Fire Camp" private NP campground at AMCA where we stayed. A good route: 033, 035, 037, 038, 036 (could probably go on to 034, but we were taking longer to go over each point count). An easy bike ride for this route from Fire Camp. Allow about 15 minutes to get to 033. Another good route: 003, 007, 011, 015, 019 (most likely will be able to continue on to more). Yet another good route: 022, 021, 024, 028, 031, 029, 025, 026. There was steep uphill climb between 028 and 031; this can be avoided by going up to road as soon as possible after 028. The last day, one crew just had 2 points left (027 and 023) to finish at AMCA. Could easily have done many more. An easy (5-minute) bike ride to Jackle's lagoon parking lot. Look at wind in forecast. If it's supposed to be windy, stick to British Camp or the forested points of American Camp.
Location_desc: All points out of (026, 029, 031, 033, 037) are on the road, except for 037.

Travel_notes: Access from Bell Point Trail (trail is reached by gravel "road" that 043 is almost on). It is about 50-55 m W of trail from intended Northing. Make sure you take a right for the eastern part of bell point trail loop, rather than continuing on toward the old buildings and Garrison Bay.
Location_desc: Point is on 2 moss-covered downed trees next to a Doug-fir bigger than most of the others around point. It is about 55 m W of Bell Point Trail. Update 2014: I couldn't find the moss covered downed trees

Travel_notes: Access from point 039. You can walk the entire way on the Bell Point Trail.
Location_desc: Point is about 10 m S of trail, looking out over the bay.  It is in Doug-fir forest, just as it is starting to go more steeply uphill. The actual point is in a patch of Oregon grape.

Travel_notes: Due west of BRCA parking road
Location_desc: Point located on edge of salal patch in transition zone between Doug-fir forest and Doug-fir/madrone mixed forest with grassy understory; exact point in inconspicuous grassy spot

Travel_notes: Pace about 35 m from parking lot until almost directly across from trail on W/NW side of road. Go about 5 m SE of road to point.
Location_desc: Point is just uphill (SW of) on road from parking lot. It is about 10 m SE of the road.

Travel_notes: From BRCA042, take the path across the road North past the parking lot until you get to a fork in the road. Take the left towards the white garage. Point is about 11 m from garage.
Location_desc: Point is NE of a clearing that leads to some housing. There is also a white garage just to the W of point. There are a few Doug-firs to the SW and a lot of Red alders in all other directions from point.

Travel_notes: From point 040, walk to the big curve in trail. When that trail curves, continue going straight onto a non-maintained trail. When that trail curves, go off-trail from there (up steep hill, then down steeply, the gradually to point).
Location_desc: The point is in Doug-fir forest with a line of horsetails to the SE, a patch of salal to the S, and a view of the bay to the NE (through trees).

Travel_notes: I started at this point, it is 50 m E of the road, N of the turn off for the parking lot.
Location_desc: Point in large open meadow surrounded by large (dbh 90 cm) snag and many smaller madrones and oaks.  Near road. (Photo of this point shows the oak grove near the point, although the photo file name IDs the trees as "madrones.")

Travel_notes: Easily accessed by Mitchell Bay Road; walking north, go 33m part yellow "Ped. X-ing" sign and go left/downhill (W) 20m to point.
Location_desc: 20m esat of Mitchell Bay Road; downhill off the road grade, the point is in a bracken, Oregon grape, and salal patch.

Travel_notes: Easiest access is from trail. Considerable salal thickets east of the point all the way to road.
Location_desc: Point located in grassy opening of Doug-fir/Madrone forest. The point is near an upturned root-ball in mossy patch with Oregon grape and small Rubus/rose-type shrub.

Travel_notes: If accessed from 044, it starts flat, then slightly uphill, through mostly Doug-fir forest.  At about 300 m, a small gully is reached. It may be easier to access from main road though.
Location_desc: Point is just SE of a large pile of recently downed trees/branches. There are smaller conifers to the NW and larger (mostly Doug-fir) to the SE. Hard to find good features. In small patch of rose.

Travel_notes: Travel (from 045) through grassland and uphill.  Gradual slope at beginning, becomes steeper closer to point.
Location_desc: Point in grassy area with a couple of Doug-firs, a Bigleaf maple, and a madrone clustered around it.  On steep slope with large portions of bedrock visible.  Puget sound visible to W.

Travel_notes: I headed N from 049.  It is open and grassy to the summit of Young Hill, not too steep, there I got on the main trail and headed downhill to the point.
Location_desc: Point is on the trail to Young Hill summit between hairpin turn and point where the trail splits.  In a patch of young Doug-fir with thick undergrowth, to the NW ther is a moare open grassy patch.

Travel_notes: easily accessed from Mitchell Bay Road before you reach the Maintenance building
Location_desc: Point is uphill from the road through downed timber and thickets. Look for cluster of large (~40cm DBH) madrones. Point located between old, rotten, mossy stumps.

Travel_notes: Point easily accessed by Mitchell Bay Road.
Location_desc: Just off Mitchell bay Road, 15 m due W of road. point is located on edge of dense salmonberry thicket, in low wash with small downed moss-covered logs. Road sign is a great landmark.

Travel_notes: Travel from 054.  I took a small game trail diverging from the main trail.  The game trail heads south toward 054.  I followed this trail along the side of the hill until I was at the correct northing and then bushwacked to the point.  It was pretty steep, this may not be the best way to go.
Location_desc: Point in a young Doug-fir forest with the steep slope to he NW begins to flatten out.  A few Big leaf maples are dispersed throughout, 4 small maple (dbh 20 cm) are just south of the point.

Travel_notes: Travel from 050.  Take trail to Young Hill summit, at summit take trail leading to the NW.  Follow this trail until near the point, the point is 20 m off the trail.
Location_desc: Point on a mossy slope surrounded by Doug-fir and Madrone, 20 m SE of trail. In the photo, the tree on the left side of "pistol grip Doug-fir" is actually behind it. Difficult to tell that in photo.

Travel_notes: just walk down the hill from the road throught the grass and at about 215 m (after a patch of ROSGYM) head S toward point.
Location_desc: there is shrub habitat all to the E, N and S with some GRAS mixed in.  To the W it is mostly grassland.

Travel_notes: (see directions for point 2101--it is just reversing that)
Location_desc: the point is located just W of the road next to the park boundary sign.  It is at the top of a hill.

Travel_notes: for the first 50m, you can take trail that starts right across road from point.  Also, there is a more-or-less maintained trail just N f the way you would want to go (for about 120m).
Location_desc: point is situated on a big hill, almost completely with shrubs.

Travel_notes: travel between the points is mostly through thick shrub.
Location_desc: the point is situated on a hill with moss-covered rocks.  There is a partial view of a cleared area (near the road) S, but it is somewhat obstructed by trees. It is completely open directly overhead.

Travel_notes: after ~80m, the rest of the way is primarily Doug-fir and GRAS.  Dontinue to follow uphill past large flat rocks surrounded by grass, until point is reached.
Location_desc: the point is on flat rock covered with moss, on the edge of a steep slope (cliff).  There is a clear view of th ocean, other bodies of water and everything else below.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point located on opne grassy hillside, a few trees of various types dispersed wildy (?).  The olympic mtns are to the S.  A large decaying snag is to the N.  Grassland continues to the E but not W.

Travel_notes: travel across road and into dense shrub.  Proceed through stinging nettle and salal.
Location_desc: point at edge of grassland and forest habitats.  Slope changes abruptly and goes to a stteper sloped forested habitat with abundant madrones and some Doug-fir.  Sparsely used trails at this margin.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: not many good features here for landmarks.  Plot is in even aged Doug-fir stand, right on the edge where undergrowth changes from dense Salal to a more diverse grass/shrub understory.

Travel_notes: to 2110:  cross road, proceed E through dense Salal undergrowth.
Location_desc: point 1m from (to the W) cross rail fence guarding the road down to British Camp parking area.  A large conspicuous Doug-fir present near point.   Ground covered in moss at point, not much >2m from point.

Travel_notes: travel across west side road up the small bank across the trail and then proceed through an open forest up a moderate slope.  Slope increases and vegeation densities towards 2111.
Location_desc: locate 15 m W of road in even aged Doug-fir forest with sparse salal understory.  A few madrones present.  Best landmark other than road is trailhead pullout 20m to the NNW.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point on steep slope (26 deg) just below a 8m high 15m wide rock outcrop. A large Doug-fir with charred bark grows at the base of the rock outcrop.  The ocean can be seen to the E thru trees.

Travel_notes: followed E bearing up hill to clearing then took trail the rest of the way to point 2112.  from clearing, due E above point 2111.
Location_desc: point just off trail and NE of largest hill on British Camp.  GPS coverage good.   Flat rock in clearing 23m S of point, just under a line of Doug-fir seperating 2 small openings.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point located on park boundary, park boundary sign nailed to doug fir tree 12 m, 257deg.  Otherwise indistinct.  Doug fir forest, sparse undergrowth, abundant downed wood.

Travel_notes: from 2015 (2115), road 150m from 2015 and to 2014 (2114).  Forest and slope changes distinctly across road.
Location_desc: Indistinct other than large rock outcrops 20 m at 163 deg; point is centered along the length of this rock.  Forest dense with doug fir, a few Western Red Cedar and Big leaf Maple.  Understory open ad varied.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: indistinct location, even-aged doug fir forest with madrone understory sparse.  West Side road 150 m at 107 deg.

Travel_notes: dense vegetation between 16 and 17.   use trail to parking lot and towards outhouse.  Go into marshy veg due N from the outhouse trail for 20m.
Location_desc: Point located 20m N of outhouse of the N edge of British Camp Parking lot. Habitat marshy with abundant salmonberry, vaccinium, equisetum.  Alder forest overstory.

Travel_notes: first point on transect.  Park at British Camp lot and go down the trail to the W towards camp buildings (historic).  Point is in grass field E of buildings (see below).
Location_desc: located in grassland W of historic British Camp buildings, approx 40m from NE corner of southern-most building.  Forest edge 15m at the closest on W side of plot.

Travel_notes: travel between ponts is fairly easy.  Downhill most of the way in Doug-fir habitat with a sparse understory.
Location_desc: there is a large (8x18m) moss covered rock.  The point lies on this rock.  There are madrone trees all around.  I've never seen so many in one spot.

Travel_notes: travel east through Doug-fir and alder until you hit the road
Location_desc: point is on the road.  There is a section on the south side of the road where the Red Alder grove is closer than other sections.  The alder is about 10m S of road at a bearing of 270.

Travel_notes: travel is through some tough vegetation.  There is a lot of salmonberry.  From pt 2119, go around the road until you see the alder, ente the alder East.
Location_desc: point is just after alder habitat.  It is in a grassy area 15 m N of the road.

Travel_notes: at point 2120 head W about 15m until you hit the road.  Then, walk NE up road for about 50m.  Get your coordinates and travel accordingly.  The Salal is tough to get through.
Location_desc: Western Hemlock/Doug Fir forest with lots of madrones.  There are 3 smaller (20cm dbh) ACEMAC trees N of point all within a 30m radius.

Travel_notes: all of travel is through head high salal.
Location_desc: survey point is in a large (40mx10m) salal-less area.  It's a patch of moss in the salal.  There are 3 madrone trees in the patch.

Travel_notes: first point of the day.  Follow service road W ~ 100m then navigate N to point.
Location_desc: point falls in alder stand of conifer-deciduous mixed forest.  The herbaceous layer is composed of tall grass, as well as equisedum.

Travel_notes: travel time from point 2130 was ~ 45 min.
Location_desc: point is 6m S of a traversable salmonberry hedge.  Herbaceous layer is dominated by waist-high ferns.

Travel_notes: I followed a 247 degree bearing from point 2126; arriving at what I thought should be point 2127 I found that I was 60 m short (E) and 100m too far south.
Location_desc: point is on boundary where an alder stand meets a coniferous forest, at the very foot of a small hill.

Travel_notes: fairly easy point to get to from service road that runs W from the ranger station.
Location_desc: point is next to a huge <122cm DBH madrone tree in a Doug-fir dominant forest.

Travel_notes: moderate dificulty.  Go uphill and through Doug-fir forest to point 2129 from 2128.
Location_desc: the point is midway up a large moss covered log.

Travel_notes: not bad, farily open.  Little to no ducking or crawling required!
Location_desc: point falls in open understory of closed canopy doug fir forest, encircled by salal except in the SE corner.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point is next to a lane, 2m salmonberry bush and under a leaning doug fir snag parallel to the ground and 2-3m above it; 10cm dbh.

Travel_notes: traverse along hillside traveling E park boundary; flagging and markers 10-20 m to the N for entire distance.
Location_desc: 60 m N of trail up Young Hill.  Located in SE corner of large, irregularly shaped open mossy patch.  Patch measures 30m long x 10m wide.  Madrones grow dense along N edge.

Travel_notes: None
Location_desc: point located down slope from trail approx 100m.  Sparse doug fir forest with grass understory.  Two large doug fir trees at 65 m almost due W.

Travel_notes: the travel between points went from FOFI to MICO with a gradual transition to shrub with MICO overstory.
Location_desc: point is at the base of a hill, surrounded by tall conifers.  There arent any distinguishing features from the point.

Travel_notes: there is a gradual increase in canopy cover from point 2104 to 2136.
Location_desc: the point is right on the park boundary, so there are markers on nearby trees. It is right next to a smal hill/mound of decomposed organic matter.

Travel_notes:
A good route: 042, 043, 039, 040, 044, 048. Another good route for a different set of points: 045, 049, 053, 054, 050. Another route: 041, 046, 047, 052, 051.
Access to pt 048 easy from EC service rd (NE of parking lot). 051, 052, 048, and 047 all easy to get to in that order. 
About a 25-minute drive from Fire Camp. British Camp main parking lot is ~15 minutes from Westcott Bay House, where you will likely camp in future.
Location_desc: Points 041, 046, 047, 051, and 052 made a good route--all very accessable from roads and trails. The other route was points 045, 049, 053, 054, and 050.
